soft\n|-\n|''Conviction ([[Anthem (video game)#Marketing and release|Anthem]])''|| February 14, 2019 || BioWare\n|-\n|''PUBG - The Worst Player in the World ([[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]])|| July 24, 2019 || [[Bluehole (company)|Bluehole]]\n|-\n|''The Division 2 - Warlords of New York'' || February 25, 2020\n|| [[Ubisoft]] \n|}\n\n==Documentaries on video games==\n\n===Theatrical releases===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! Title !! Release date !! Subject\n|-\n| ''8BIT'' || 2006 || The intersections of video games, art, and music\n|-\n| ''[[Chasing Ghosts: Beyond the Arcade]]'' || 2007 || The [[golden age of video arcade games]]\n|-\n| ''[[The King of Kong: A Fistful of Quarters]]'' || August 17, 2007 || The rivalry between [[Billy Mitchell (gamer)|Billy Mitchell]] and [[Steve Wiebe]] over the ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' record high score\n|-\n| ''Frag'' || 2008 || [[Electronic sports|Professional video gaming]]\n|-\n| ''[[Second Skin (2008 film)|Second Skin]]'' || March 7, 2008 || Follows seven people through the world of [[Massively multiplayer online role-playing game|MMORPGs]]\n|-\n| ''[[Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecstasyoforder.com/ |title=Film - Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters - |publisher=ecstasyoforder.com |date=August 11, 2011 |access-date=August 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815145941/http://ecstasyoforder.com/ |archive-date=August 15, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> || 2011 || A documentary following world-record holding [[Tetris]] players as they prepare for the 2010 [[Tetris]] Championships\n|-\n| ''[[Indie Game: The Movie]]'' || 2012 || Documentary about the struggles of independent game developers Edmund McMillen and Tommy Refenes during the development of Super Meat Boy, Phil Fish during the development of Fez, and also Jonathan Blow, who reflects on the success of Braid.\n|-\n| ''[[Thank You for Playing]]'' || 2015 || Follows the creation of the art-house video game [[That Dragon, Cancer]]\n|-\n| [https://moleman4.com ''Moleman 4 - Longplay'']\n|2017\n|A documentary which recounts the so far little-known story of the beginnings of video game development behind the Iron Curtain. Outfoxed Nintendo, surprised Commodore engineers, The Last Ninja story, a games software outfit that dodged the limelight and led the world.\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! Title !! Original air date(s) !! Network !! Subject\n|-\n| ''[[Thumb Candy]]'' || 2000 || [[Channel 4]] || History of video games\n|-\n| ''Games Odyssey'' || 2002 || [[3sat]] || German four-part documentary about the history of video games, simulations, digital adventures and video games as an art form\n|-\n| ''[[Icons (TV series)|Game Makers]]'' || 2002\u20132005 || [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4]] || Series on video game industry figures\n|-\n| ''Tetris: From Russia With Love'' || 2004 || BBC Four || History of the 1980s ''[[Tetris]]'' game phenomenon\n|-\n| ''Video Game Invasion: The History of a Global Obsession'' || 2004 || [[Game Show Network|GSN]] ||\n|-\n| ''The Video Game Revolution'' || 2004 || [[PBS]] ||\n|-\n| ''History of Video Games'' || No before than February 2005 || Discovery Asia ||\n|-\n| ''Game On!: The History of Videogames'' || 2006 || [[HLN (TV channel)|HLN]] || The [[Wii]] and [[PlayStation 3]] console launches\n|-\n| ''[[I, VIDEOGAME]]'' || 2007 || [[Discovery Channel|Discovery]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Rise of the Video Game]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/video-game/video-game.html |title=Rise of the Video Game |work=Discovery Channel |publisher=Discovery Communications |access-date=September 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903135836/http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/video-game/video-game.html |archivedate=September 3, 2010 }}</ref> || 2007 || Discovery ||\n|-\n| ''[[Charlie Brooker's Gameswipe]]'' || 2009 || [[BBC Four]] |