| 2006 || [[HLN (TV channel)|HLN]] || The [[Wii]] and [[PlayStation 3]] console launches\n|-\n| ''[[I, VIDEOGAME]]'' || 2007 || [[Discovery Channel|Discovery]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Rise of the Video Game]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/video-game/video-game.html |title=Rise of the Video Game |work=Discovery Channel |publisher=Discovery Communications |access-date=September 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903135836/http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/video-game/video-game.html |archivedate=September 3, 2010 }}</ref> || 2007 || Discovery ||\n|-\n| ''[[Charlie Brooker's Gameswipe]]'' || 2009 || [[BBC Four]] ||\n|-\n| ''Cyberdreams/Cyberdr\u00f8mme'' || 2011 || [[DK4 Denmark]] || Danish documentary about the national eSports team competing in World Cyber Games\n|-\n| ''[[How Videogames Changed the World]]'' || 2013 || [[Channel 4]] || Charlie Brooker explores the history of interactive entertainment and how it's changing how we work, communicate and play\n|-\n| ''[[The Gamechangers]]'' || 2015 || [[BBC Two]] ||  The story of the controversy caused by [[Grand Theft Auto]], a video game series by [[Rockstar Games]], as various attempts were made to halt the production of the games.\n|}\n\n===Other releases===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! Title !! Release date !! Subject\n|-\n| ''Game Over: Gender, Race & Violence in Video Games'' || 2000 ||\n|-\n| ''In the Game'' || 2007 || The game industry, technology, and the future of gaming\n|-\n| ''Once Upon Atari''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.onceuponatari.com/ |title=from Scott West Productions |publisher=Once Upon Atari |access-date=May 24, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201203534/http://onceuponatari.com/ |archive-date=February 1, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> || 2007 ||\n|-\n| ''FPS - Por dentro do virtual'' (Portuguese) || 2009 || Ethnographic research of an FPS gamers community\n|-\n| ''[[Get Lamp]]'' || 2010 || Documentary by historian [[Jason Scott Sadofsky|Jason Scott]] about [[interactive fiction]] (text adventures) and [[Infocom]]\n|-\n| ''[[Level Up (film)|Level Up]]'' - A story about gamers and the games they play''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.levelupdocumentary.com/ |title=Level Up Documentary |publisher=Purple Mouse Productions |access-date=August 6, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130516043949/http://www.levelupdocumentary.com/ |archive-date=May 16, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> || 2011 || Exploration of video gaming culture\n|-\n| ''[[Minecraft: The Story of Mojang]]'' || 2012 || Documentary about the history of the company Mojang and its creation, Minecraft.\n|-\n| ''[[Free to Play (film)|Free to Play]]'' || 2014 || Documentary by video game developer [[Valve Corporation|Valve]] about the lives of three players competing in a gaming tournament for [[Dota 2]]\n|-\n| ''Good Game'''<ref>{{imdb title|2141753|Good Game (2014)}}</ref>  || 2014 || Nine men pursue careers in competitive video games as members of the [[Evil Geniuses]]' [[Starcraft II: Wings of Liberty|Starcraft II]] division\n|-\n| ''[[Video Games: The Movie]]'' || 2014 || Documentary by Jeremy Snead<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/video_games_the_movie/|title=Video Games: The Movie|date=July 18, 2014|access-date=May 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423115629/https://rottentomatoes.com/m/video_games_the_movie|archive-date=April 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Atari: Game Over]]'' || 2014 || Documentary on the excavation of Atari video games.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n|-\n| ''[[Gaming in Color]]'' || 2014 || Documentary on the LGBTQ community in video games.\n|-\n| ''GameLoading - Rise of the Indies'' || 2015 || Follows several independent game developers.\n|-\n| ''Insert Coin || 2020 || History of [[Midway Games]] \n|}\n\n==Films with plots centered on video games==\n* ''[[Tron]]'' (1982) \u2013 Kevin Flynn, an [[arcade game]] designer, gets sucked into the video game world he created and has to fight his way back to the real world.\n* ''[[Nightmares (1983 film)|Nightmares]]'' (1983) \u2013 The segment \"Bishop of Battle\" stars [[Emilio Estevez]] as a video game wizard who breaks into the arcade at night to get to the 13th level, in doing so he becomes part of the game.\n* ''[[WarGames]]'' (1983) \u2013 Computer hacker breaks into military intelligence computer to play games, which almost starts a thermonuclear war.\n* ''[[Joysticks (film)|Joysticks]]'' (1983) \u2013 When a top local businessman and his two bumbling nephews try to shut down the town's only video arcade, arcade employees and patrons fight back.\n* ''[[Cloak & Dagger (1984 film)|Cloak & Dagger]]'' (1984) \u2013 A young boy has secret plans given to him in the form of a video game cartridge, which he must protect from spies.\n* ''[[The Last Starfighter]]'' (1984) \u2013 A boy, who is very good at a video game in his trailer park, finds himself recruited to be a pilot for an alien defense force just like the game he plays.\n* ''[[The Dungeonmaster]]'' (1985) \u2013 A computer whiz is drawn into a series of realistic simulations by a demonic wizard who considers him a worthy adversary. Armed with his wrist-mounted X-CaliBR8 computer, he must solve the puzzles and rescue his girlfriend.\n* ''[[Hollywood Zap]]'' (1986) \u2013 Tucker Downs tires of his boring job selling bras to fat ladies in Mississippi and heads for Hollywood to look for his long lost father. En route, Downs hooks up with wasted video game addict/hustler Ben Frank who is seeking a title match with \"The Zap,\" holder of the record score in [[Zaxxon]].\n* ''[[Kung Fu Master (film)|Kung Fu Master]]'' (1988) \u2013 A love story between a 40-year-old woman ([[Jane Birkin]]) and a 15-year-old boy addicted to the arcade game ''[[Kung-Fu Master (video game)|Kung-Fu Master]]''. Directed by [[Agn\u00e8s Varda]].<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=950DE2D7173BF930A15755C0A96F948260|title=Kung Fu Master (1987) Review/Film; She's 40. He's 15. Hmmm.|first=Caryn|last=James|date=June 23, 1989|access-date=January 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109121957/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=950DE2D7173BF930A15755C0A96F948260|archive-date=January 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Wizard (1989 film)|The Wizard]]'' (1989) \u2013 A boy with mental problems decides to run away to compete in a video game contest and his brother helps him hitchhike to the tournament. Features numerous [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]] video games, primarily ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' before its American release.\n* ''[[The Lawnmower Man (film)|The Lawnmower Man]]'' (1992) \u2013 A simple man is turned into a genius through the application of computer science and [[virtual reality]].\n* ''[[Arcade (film)|Arcade]]'' (1993) \u2013 A teenager has to battle inside of a deadly virtual reality video game, in order to save her friends.\n* ''[[Brainscan]]'' (1994) \u2013 A teenager is sent a mysterious computer game that uses hypnosis to make the game the most horrifying experience imaginable. He stops playing, only to find evidence that the murders depicted in the game actually happened.\n* ''[[Nirvana (film)|Nirvana]]'' (1997) \u2013 A computer game designer, finds that his latest video game has a virus which has given consciousness to the main character of the game, Solo.\n* ''[[eXistenZ]]'' (1999) \u2013 plot centered around a virtual reality game.\n* ''[[How to Make a Monster (2001 film)|How to Make a Monster]]'' (2001) \u2013 An evil video game comes to life and hunts the group of developers.\n* ''[[Avalon (2001 film)|Avalon]]'' (2001) \u2013 [[Science fiction]] film centered on a war-themed, virtual reality [[Massively multiplayer online game|MMO]] under the same title. Directed by [[Mamoru Oshii]].\n* ''[[Game Over (2003 film)|Game Over]]'' (2003) \u2013 Uses footage from five different [[Digital Pictures]] games.\n* ''[[Spy Kids 3-D: Game Over]]'' (2003) \u2013 Carmen Cortez is caught in a virtual reality game designed by their new nemesis, the Toymaker. Juni, her little brother, goes into the game to save her as well as beta players and the world.\n* ''[[GameBox 1.0]]'' (2004) \u2013 A video game tester must fight to escape from a video game that has become all too real.\n* ''[[Grandma's Boy (2006 film)|Grandma\u2019s Boy]]'' (2006) \u2013 A 35-year-old game tester develops a game in secret only to have someone at work try to steal it.\n* ''[[Stay Alive]]'' (2006) \u2013 Friends start dying just like they did in a video game they all played.\n* ''[[Ben X]]'' (2007) \u2013 The main character Ben is an autistic boy obsessed with an [[MMORPG]] called ''[[ArchLord]]''.  He plays the game to escape being bullied and has one online friend named Scarlite.  He considers suicide until he meets Scarlite in person.\n* ''[[Press Start (film)|Press Start]]'' (2007) \u2013 Average suburban youth Zack Nimbus is recruited by an ill-tempered ninja and a tough-as-nails space soldier to save the world from a tyrannical, but comically insecure, sorcerer. References to many classic video games.\n* ''[[WarGames: The Dead Code]]'' (2008) \u2013 is a sequel to the 1983 thriller film WarGames.\n* ''[[Gamer (2009 film)|Gamer]]'' (2009) \u2013 A man has to save humanity from being enslaved by an MMO.\n* ''[[Assault Girls]]'' (2009) \u2013 Three girls in an MMO team up to win a boss battle. Directed by [[Mamoru Oshii]].\n* ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'' (2010) \u2013 Action comedy film rife with video game references and plot [[conceit]] similar to [[fighting game]]s.\n* ''[[Tron: Legacy]]'' (2010) \u2013 Kevin Flynn's son Sam finds his missing father in a new version of the virtual game world and has a similar journey as his father did fighting to get back to reality.\n* ''[[l'autre monde|Black Heaven]]'' (2010) \u2013 An innocent young man becomes enamored with a mysterious girl. He is lured into \"Black Hole\" \u2013 a dark, obscure video game world of avatars with deadly serious intentions in the real world.\n* ''[[RPG: Metanoia]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Ra.One]]'' (2011) \u2013 Indian [[Bollywood]] [[superhero film]], where a [[video game developer]] creates an unstoppable villain for his son which becomes all too real.\n* ''[[.hack//The Movie]]'' (2012) \u2013 Japanese [[anime]] film based on ''[[.hack]]'', a franchise of anime, video games, [[novel]]s and [[manga]] that debuted in 2002, about a virtual reality MMORPG.\n* ''[[Wreck-It Ralph]]'' (2012) \u2013 An [[arcade game]] [[villain]] who dreams of being a hero decides to leave his game in order to become one. Features cameos by multiple licensed video game characters like [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic the Hedgehog]], [[Pac-Man (character)|Pac-Man]] & [[Ryu (Street Fighter)|Ryu]].\n* ''[[Angry Video Game Nerd: The Movie]]'' (2014) \u2013 Based on the web series of the same name.\n* ''[[Pixels (2015 film)|Pixels]]'' (2015) \u2013 When aliens misinterpret video-feeds of [[Golden age of arcade video games|classic arcade games]] as a declaration of war, they attack the Earth, using the games as models for their various assaults to fight aliens such as [[Donkey Kong]] and [[Galaga]] bugs.\n* ''[[Sword Art Online The Movie: Ordinal Scale]]'' (2017) \u2013 Japanese anime film based on ''[[Sword Art Online]]'', a novel, manga and anime franchise that debuted in 2002, about a virtual reality MMO, with ''Ordinal Scale'' being about an [[augmented reality]] MMO.\n* ''[[Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle]]'' (2017) \u2013  Teenagers find a vintage video game version of ''[[Jumanji]]'' and get sucked into its jungle setting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sonypicturespublicity.com/dom/secured/title/titleContainer.jsf?terrtitleId=1588|title=JUMANJI: WELCOME TO THE JUNGLE|work=[[Sony Pictures Entertainment]]|access-date=April 3, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818200210/https://sonypicturespublicity.com/dom/secured/title/titleContainer.jsf?terrtitleId=1588|archivedate=August 18, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]'' (2018) \u2013 Based on the 2011 [[Ready Player One|novel of the same name]], it is set in a [[dystopia]]n future and is about the search for an [[easter egg]] in a virtual reality game.\n* ''[[Ralph Breaks the Internet]]'' (2018) \u2013 Sequel to ''Wreck-It Ralph'', and part of the ''[[Wreck-It Ralph (franchise)|Wreck-It Ralph]]'' franchise.\n* ''[[Serenity (2019 film)|Serenity]]'' (2019) - Midway through the film, it is revealed that the story is occurring inside a virtual world.\n* ''The King's Avatar: For the Glory'' (2019) - anime film based on ''[[The King's Avatar (web series)|The King's Avatar]]'', a novel, manga and anime franchise. \n* ''[[Jumanji: The Next Level]]'' (2019) - Sequel to ''Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle''.\n* ''[[Free Guy]] (2020)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of anime based on video games]]\n* [[List of television programs based on video games]]\n* [[List of films based on television programs]]\n* [[List of video games based on films]]\n* [[Fictional games]]\n* [[Machinima]]\n{{Portal bar|Film|Video games}}\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=videogameadaptation.htm Video game adaptation comparison] at [[Box Office Mojo]]\n* [http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1851626_1851846,00.html Top 10 Worst Video Game Movies] on ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''\n* [https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/18-video-game-films-currently-in-production/2900-48/ 18 Video Game Films Currently In Production] (2015) on GameSpot\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Films Based On Video Games}}\n[[Category:Films based on video games|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of films based on works|Video games]]\n[[Category:Lists of works based on video games|Films]]\n", "name_user": "FilmLover72", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHollywood (live-action):i added sources to the recent additions to the list of films in development and i organised them in alphabetical order.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_films_based_on_video_games"}
{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage", "text_new": "{{short description|Effect of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:Closed library - Island Bay.jpg|alt=|thumb|350x350px|Announcement posted in the door of a [[public library]] in [[Island Bay, New Zealand]] that it is closed due to the pandemic, and will waive all [[Late fees|late return fees]].]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] had a sudden and substantial impact on the arts and cultural heritage ([[GLAM (industry sector)|GLAM]]) sectors. The global health crisis and the uncertainly resulting from it profoundly affected organisations' operations as well as individuals \u2013 both employed and independent \u2013 across the sector. Arts and culture sector organisations attempted to uphold their (often publicly funded) mission to provide access to cultural heritage to the community; maintain the safety of their employees, collections, and the public; while reacting to the unexpected change in their [[business model]] with an unknown end.\n\nBy March 2020, across the world most cultural institutions had been indefinitely closed (or at least with their services radically curtailed) exhibitions, events and performances cancelled or postponed. In response there were intensive efforts to provide alternative or additional services through digital platforms, to maintain essential activities with minimal resources, to document the events themselves through new acquisitions, and simultaneously an awareness that there would be many new [[creative works]] which had been inspired by the event.\n\nMany individuals across the sector would temporarily or permanently lose contracts or employment with varying degrees of warning and financial assistance available. Equally, [[financial stimulus]] from governments and charities for artists, would provide greatly differing levels of support depending on the sector and the country. The public demand for cultural activities was expected to return, but at an unknown time and with the assumption that different kinds of experiences would be popular.\n\n==Closures==\nThrough the first months of 2020, arts and culture sector organisations around the world progressively restricted their public activities and closed completely due to the coronavirus pandemic. Starting with China, and East Asia, by mid-to-late March most organisations worldwide had either closed voluntarily or by government mandate. This included libraries,<ref name=\"IFLA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ifla.org/covid-19-and-libraries|title=COVID-19 and the Global Library Field|publisher=[[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions|IFLA]]|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> museums,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/coronavirus-museum-closures-worldwide-1202680933/|title=See a List of Coronavirus-Related Closures at Museums Around the World|last=Solomon|first=Claire Selvin,Tessa|last2=Selvin|first2=Claire|date=2020-03-12|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26|last3=Solomon|first3=Tessa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LNCETkPjgcNdmybrwE5g2JEK4KpIfhKThnws1QqgjqE/mobilebasic|title=Museum Responses - COVID-19|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> theatre and stage productions,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2020/mar/13/coronavirus-culture-arts-films-gigs-festivals-cancellations|title=Coronavirus and culture \u2013 a list of major cancellations|date=2020-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> orchestras,<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|last=Kenyon|first=Nicholas|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/21/home-listening-classical-music-online-livestream-at-home-coronavirus|title=Classical music: let the Berlin Phil come to you|date=2020-03-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and arts festivals.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2020, dates for re-opening and expectations for when cultural organisation can fully \"return to normal\" are unknown for most of the world. Survey data from March in the USA indicated that, when museums were permitted to reopen, the public \"intent to visit\" metric for cultural activities should be unchanged overall from prior to the pandemic \u2013 but with a shifted preference for the ''kind'' of activity. Data indicated there would be a decreased willingness for attendance of activities in confined spaces, large immobile groups (such as cinemas), or tactile activities; with an increase in interest for activities outdoors or with large spaces (such as zoos and botanic gardens).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/25/how-is-covid-19-impacting-likelihood-to-attend-different-cultural-entities-data/|title=Post-Pandemic, Which Cultural Entity Types Are People More Likely to Revisit? (DATA)|date=2020-03-25|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/23/weekly-data-update-how-covid-19-is-impacting-intentions-to-visit-cultural-entities-march-23-2020/|title=DATA UPDATE: How COVID-19 is Impacting Intentions to Visit Cultural Entities - March 23, 2020|date=2020-03-23|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The most commonly cited reasons for the public to \"feel safe\" in returning would be: the availability of a [[COVID-19 vaccine|vaccine]], governments lifting [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel restrictions]], knowing that other people had visited, whether the activity/institution was outdoors, and the provision of [[hand sanitiser]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/04/01/what-will-make-people-feel-safe-attending-a-cultural-entity-again-data/|title=What Will Make People Feel Safe Attending a Cultural Entity Again? (DATA)|date=2020-04-01|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nBy early April at least one museum had announced its permanent closure, with more expected to follow.\n\n''The following is a list of notable closures, announcements and policies affecting the cultural sector.<br>For comprehensive lists:''\n{{See also|List of public venues and institutions closed during the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}} \n{{See also|List of events affected by the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n'''Africa'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Egypt}}. From 23 March until 31 March 2020, all museums and archaeological sites in Egypt were closed to the public for sterilisation and disinfection. During this period a programme to raise the awareness of the sites and museums\u2019 employees on ways of prevention and protection against the virus took place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cairoscene.com/Buzz/Egypt-to-Close-All-Museums-and-Archaeological-Sites|title= Egypt to close all museums and archaeological sites}}</ref>\n\n'''Asia'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flagicon|China}} [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]]. On 23 January 2020 all museums were closed throughout mainland China, As the first country for the virus to spread, China was also the first to close its GLAMs.<ref name=\":0\" /> By Mid-March Chinese institutions had slowly and cautiously begun to allow various public activities to be restored with the [[Shanghai Museum]] and the [[Power Station of Art]] (also in Shanghai) reopening on 13 March. Both had restricted visitor numbers and the latter noted that, \u201cWe have also prepared a temporary quarantine area on every floor in case of any emergencies. All visitors must have their temperature taken, as well as present their ID card and registered health code, before entering.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/china-japan-south-korea-museums-reopen-coronavirus-1202680994/|title=Museums in China, South Korea, Japan Begin to Reopen After Coronavirus Lockdown|last=Solomon|first=Tessa|last2=Solomon|first2=Tessa|date=2020-03-13|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Some other private galleries in China had begun to open, as had some institutions in South Korea and Japan with limited service (such as by private tour only). By the end of the month 40% of mainland China's tourism attractions had reopened yet most art venues remained closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/china-south-korea-and-japan-start-to-reopen-museums|title=China, South Korea and Japan start to reopen museums after strict coronavirus lockdown|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n:{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Hong Kong}}. Following the mainland, Hong Kong closed its museums five days later.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |India}}. The [[Kiran Nadar Museum of Art]] in Delhi closed on 14 March, two days before [[Shripad Naik]], minister for culture and tourism, ordered the closure of all \"monuments and museums protected by the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] across the country, including the Taj Mahal mausoleum in Agra.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Japan}}. On 28 February Japan announced all museums would be closed \"until 17 March\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in|Qatar}}. Qatar museums run by the state closed on 12 March. A forthcoming collaborative show on Picasso's Studio's due to be held by the [[Fire Station (gallery)|Fire Station]] and [[Mus\u00e9e Picasso]] has been indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |South Korea}}. On 23 February, one month after mainland China, South Korea closed all museums \"until further notice\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Europe'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts -->\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Austria}}. All federal public museums were closed by directors in response to government precautionary measures banning large events and arrivals from Italy. The [[Albertina Modern]] museum was supposed to open on 13 March but this opening was indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Belgium}}. All cultural activities regardless of size were banned by the government from 14 March, which involved the closure of the [[Jan van Eyck]] exhibition at the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Ghent]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |France}}. Weeks earlier than French government regulations required it, staff of [[The Louvre]] \"almost unanimously\" voted to force the closure of the museum on 1 March, due to concerns for their own health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51697644|title=Staff force Louvre closure over coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> It closed for three days, reopened,<ref>{{cite web|title=Coronavirus: Louvre museum in Paris reopens after staff walkout|url=https://www.thelocal.fr/20200301/frances-louvre-museum-closed-due-to-virus-fears|website=www.thelocal.fr|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> accepted only visitors with pre-booked tickets from the 9th,<ref name=\":0\" /> then closed definitively on 13 March by government mandate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200313-france-s-louvre-museum-and-versailles-palace-to-shut-over-coronavirus-crisis|title=Louvre, Versailles and Eiffel Tower close over coronavirus crisis|date=2020-03-13|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Reconstruction of the [[Notre-Dame de Paris|Notre-Dame cathedral]] following [[Notre-Dame de Paris fire|the 2019 fire]] was also halted because of worker security.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. On 16 March 2020, the German chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] announced in a press conference that the government and [[minister-president]]s had together agreed upon guidelines to limit social contacts in public spaces. Theatres, opera houses, concert halls, museums, exhibition spaces, cinemas, amusement parks and zoos needed to close.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/themen/coronavirus/leitlinien-bund-laender-1731000|title=Leitlinien gegen Ausbreitung des Coronavirus|date=2020-03-16|website=Die Bundesregierung|language=de|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. As the worst hit country in Europe during February and March, national closures were announced on 23 February with an initial reopening date of 1 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/la-cultura-chiusa-tempi-coronavirus-ACNKCpLB|title=La cultura chiusa ai tempi del coronavirus|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Museums outside the \"red zone\" of highly infected areas in the North were then permitted to re-open as long as visitors stayed 1 meter apart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/italian-museums-reopen-following-government-green-light|title=Coronavirus: Louvre closes while Italian museums reopen following government green light|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> this was later rescinded and all institution were closed until at least 3 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/rome-s-blockbuster-raphael-exhibition-closes|title=Coronavirus in Italy: Ai Weiwei criticised for 'insensitive' pasta meme and Raphael blockbuster closes|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The closure forced the indefinite postponement of the forthcoming \u201cmega-exhibition\u201d of [[Raphael]] to be held at the [[Scuderie del Quirinale]] in Rome. Originally timed to coincide with the 500th anniversary of the [[Renaissance art|Renaissance painter's]] death, it was to be the largest number of the artist's works ever displayed together.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n:{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Vatican City}}. The [[Vatican Museums]] closed in accordance with the policies of Italy.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Netherlands}}. On 12 March, Amsterdam's [[Rijksmuseum]] and [[Van Gogh Museum]] announced they would close until at least the end of that month.<ref name=\":0\" /> The following day, having previously announced the reading room and exhibition would remain open, the [[Nationaal Archief|National Archives]] announced their complete closure until 6 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaalarchief.nl/beleven/nieuws/studiezaal-en-tentoonstelling-nationaal-archief-tijdelijk-gesloten|title=Studiezaal en tentoonstelling Nationaal Archief tijdelijk gesloten|website=Nationaal Archief|language=nl|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On 30 March, the painting ''[[The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen]]'' (1884) by [[Vincent van Gogh]] was stolen from the [[Singer Laren|Singer Laren museum]] while the museum was closed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/i-m-absolutely-livid-van-gogh-painting-stolen-from-museum-during-pandemic-20200331-p54fgd.html|title='I'm absolutely livid': Van Gogh painting stolen from museum during pandemic|date=31 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Poland}}. On 11 March, a regional government \"recommendation\" was made that all cultural venues in the [[Tricity, Poland|tricity]] area be closed for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kultura.trojmiasto.pl/Teatry-odwolane-imprezy-spektakle-koronawirus-w-Trojmiescie-n143084.html|title=Teatry zamkni\u0119te przynajmniej na 2 tygodnie|date=2020-03-10|website=trojmiasto.pl|language=pl|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Museums, including the [[Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum]], and other cultural venues such as theatres and cinemas were then closed by the national government with an initial re-opening date of 25 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Russia}}. The [[Garage Museum of Contemporary Art]] was one of the first to announce its closure starting 14 March. Many [[Moscow]] museums announced closures in response to the mayor's ban on gatherings of 50 people or more on 17 March, and late that day the Russian culture ministry ordered the suspension of all public activities by federal and regional institutions, which resulted in many more closures from 18 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Spain}}. On 11 March, publicly owned museums in Madrid, including [[The Prado]], were closed indefinitely.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[Sagrada Fam\u00edlia]] indefinitely suspended construction works and closed the monument to visitors on 13 March and the [[Guggenheim Museum Bilbao]] closed on 14 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. On 18 March, the Swedish network and cooperation organisation for public museums of national interest, ''Centralmuseernas samarbetsr\u00e5d'', recommended all their 13 members to close their public venues if the risk for transmission of the virus was assessed as high in their respective regions. Only two of them stayed open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigesmuseer.se/nyheter/2020/03/cms-rekommenderar-stangning-av-centralmuseer-i-omraden-med-hog-smittspridning/|title=CMS rekommenderar st\u00e4ngning av centralmuseer i omr\u00e5den med h\u00f6g smittspridning|date=2020-03-18|website=Sveriges museer|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. The earliest closures of cultural institutions in the UK were announced from 13 March by [[Wellcome Collection]], [[South London Gallery]], the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]], [[The Photographers' Gallery]] and [[Amgueddfa Cymru \u2013 National Museum Wales|Amgueddfa Cymru]].<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|last=McGivern|first=Hannah|last2=Kenney|first2=Nancy|date=14 March 2020|website=The Art Newspaper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Many other organisations announced closures on the 17 and 18 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/london-museums-galleries-exhibitions-closed-coronavirus-a4389351.html|title=The London galleries and museums that are closed due to coronavirus|last=Paskett|first=Zoe|date=17 March 2020|website=Evening Standard|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51928526|title=Tate, V&A and Natural History Museum to close|date=2020-03-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] closed all ticketed properties by 20 March but aimed to keep gardens and parklands open, free of charge so that people could access the open space whilst social distancing.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe planned major exhibition at the [[National Gallery]] in London of [[Artemisia Gentileschi]], set to open on 4 April, was postponed for an indeterminate time due not only to the gallery's closure but also the inability of artworks on loan from Italy and America being unable to fly during the global shutdown in air traffic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jones|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/16/artemisia-gentileschi-national-gallery-exhibition-postponed-coronavirus|title=With coronavirus, the curse of Artemisia Gentileschi strikes again|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nIn literature events, the [[London Book Fair]],<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|last=Alter|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/books/london-book-fair-coronavirus.html|title=London Book Fair Canceled Over Coronavirus Fears|date=2020-03-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> AyeWrite Festival in Glasgow,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ayewrite.com/Pages/default.aspx|title=Glasgow's Book Festival - Coronovirus Latest Information|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and the [[Harrogate International Festivals]], were also cancelled<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://harrogateinternationalfestivals.com/news/statement-on-coronavirus/|title=Statement on Corfonvirus|last=Canavar|first=Sharon|date=|website=Harrogate International Festivals|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> while the [[Edinburgh International Book Festival|Edinburgh International Book Festival,]] scheduled for August, was postponed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edbookfest.co.uk/about-us/news/festival-2020-announcement|title=A message from Nick Barley, Director of the Edinburgh International Book Festival|last=Barley|first=Nick|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The [[Glasgow International]] 2020 arts festival was also postponed until 2021.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n'''North America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. A \"flurry\" of museums in New York, Boston and Washington all announced their closure on 12 March , led by the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] and coinciding with the New York Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] declaring a city wide emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/metropolitan-museum-of-art-to-shut-down-because-of-coronavirus|title=Led by Metropolitan Museum of Art, a flurry of US museums say they are shutting down because of coronavirus|last=Kenny|first=Nancy|date=2020-03-12|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> [[The Broadway League]] announced on the same day that all [[Broadway theatres]] would cease performances for at least a month, even though New York State governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] had at the time allowed them to continue at 50% capacity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/health/broadway-coronavirus-update/index.html|title=Broadway theaters to suspend all performances because of coronavirus|author1=Taylor Romine |author2=Eric Levenson |author3=Javi Morgado|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On March 17, two days before the [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|first State to declare a \"stay at home\" order]], the [[American Library Association]] \"strongly recommended\" that all academic, public, and school libraries close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/news/press-releases/2020/03/ala-executive-board-recommends-closing-libraries-public|title=ALA Executive Board recommends closing libraries to public|last=|first=|date=2020-03-17|website=|publisher=[[American Library Association]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n'''Oceania'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n[[File:Trading Status of Australian Businesses during COVID-19.gif|thumb|300px|The area of each segment represents the number of businesses per sector of the Australian economy; the figure represents the percentage still operating. By April, the Arts and Recreation sector (shown in red) was the worst hit.<ref name=\"ABS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Latestproducts/5676.0.55.003Main%20Features2Week%20Commencing%2030%20March%202020|title=5676.0.55.003 - Business Indicators, Business Impacts of COVID-19, Week Commencing 30 March 2020|date=2020-04-07|website=www.abs.gov.au|publisher=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>|alt=]]\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. Beginning from the second week of March Australian institutions began announcing reduced services, and then complete closures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wragge.github.io/closed-glams-covid19/|title=Australian GLAMs and COVID-19|website=closed-glams-covid19|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On the 13th, organisers of the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]] announced that the 2020 festival had been cancelled entirely.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Melbourne International Comedy Festival 2020 Has Been Cancelled |url=https://www.comedyfestival.com.au/2020/2020-statement |website=Melbourne International Comedy Festival |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> [[Opera Australia]] announced it would close on March 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://operawire.com/opera-australia-cancels-performances-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Opera Australia Cancels Performances Due to Coronavirus|date=2020-03-15|website=Opera Wire|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On March 24 the national closure of all cultural institutions was mandated, with subsequent restrictions on public gatherings. Consequently, many cultural events were also cancelled, including the [[Sydney Writers' Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.swf.org.au/|title=We have cancelled the 2020 Festival|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> According to the [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] by the beginning of April, \"Arts and Recreation services\" was the sector of the national economy with the smallest proportion of its business still in operation \u2013 at 47%.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|last=Anatolitis|first=Esther|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/08/as-we-crave-the-return-of-our-cultural-life-arts-workers-and-organisations-are-being-left-behind|title=Australia's arts have been hardest hit by coronavirus. So why aren't they getting support? {{!}} Esther Anatolitis|date=2020-04-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> (See also [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia#Arts]].)\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |New Zealand}}. New Zealand implemented a policy on March 23 that all institutions would be closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndf.org.nz/covid19-and-nz-glams|title=COVID-19 and NZ GLAMs|website=National Digital Forum|language=en-NZ|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]] closed from 6pm March 20.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Campbell|first=Georgina|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318548|title=Coronavirus: Te Papa museum to close for two weeks|date=20 March 2020|work=New Zealand Herald|access-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Auckland War Memorial Museum]] announced that it would close from March 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aucklandmuseum.com/service-pages/alerts/covid-19?utm_source=wordfly&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=TemporaryMuseumClosure&utm_content=version_A|title=Auckland Museum is temporarily closed}}</ref>\n\n'''South America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Argentina}}. All the museums, cultural activities and gatherings were cancelled in the city of Buenos Aires on 12 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/cultura/coronavirus-argentina-disponen-cierre-temporario-museos-ciudad_0_Hgfv9C32.html|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: disponen el cierre temporario de todos los museos de la Ciudad|last=|website=www.clarin.com|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> National libraries continue to offer means of contact through the main educational website of the Ministry of Education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.educ.ar/recursos/151053/bibliotecas-en-casa-en-seguimos-conectados?from=150858&fbclid=IwAR3S3KjeZavdRV6gjOCfJxVUz6Xu5L0Eqfep7SBTT5l1RrOOKvuHQDML0tY|title=#BibliotecasEnCasa en Seguimos Educando - Educ.ar|website=www.educ.ar|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Brazil}}. Museums which have closed{{when|date=March 2020}} in Brazil include the Museum of Art of S\u00e3o Paulo Assis Chateaubriand, the Pinacoteca, the Ita\u00fa Cultural, the Museum of Contemporary Art of the University of S\u00e3o Paulo, the Institute Tomie Ohtake, the Institute Moreira Salles, and the Museum of Tomorrow in Rio de Janeiro and the Instituto Inhotim contemporary art centre in Brumadinho.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===Permanent closure===\n{{Incomplete list|date=April 2020}}\n\n* [[Bauer Media Group|Bauer Media New Zealand]] announced to staff via [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] its immediate and permanent closure on 2 April. Management cited the financial strain due to lockdowns given that \"non-daily print media were not permitted to publish through the level four lockdown\". The NZ government contested that the company was closing of its own accord, as it had not sought access to financial assistance available to businesses during the crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/media/02-04-2020/publisher-of-nz-listener-womans-weekly-north-south-to-shut-down/|title=Publisher of NZ Listener, Woman's Weekly, North & South to shut down|date=2020-04-02|website=The Spinoff|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Bauer was the publisher of magazines including ''[[New Zealand Listener]]'', ''[[North & South (New Zealand magazine)|North & South]], [[New Zealand Woman's Weekly|New Zealand Woman\u2019s Weekly]],'' and Air New Zealand's inflight magazine ''[[Kia Ora (Inflight Magazine)|Kia Ora]].''\n* The first cultural institution to announced its permanent closure as a result of the pandemic was [[Indianapolis Contemporary]], a contemporary art museum founded in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/entertainment/arts/2020/04/03/indianapolis-contemporary-art-museum-shuts-down-coronavirus/5115668002/|title=Indianapolis Contemporary art museum shuts down, citing economic damage from coronavirus|last=Bongiovanni|first=Domenica|website=Indianapolis Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> An announcement from its board on 3 April, stated that \"We have concluded our operations are not sustainable. We are not alone as other arts institutions struggle in this crisis.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indcontemporary.org/press-release/ic-to-close|title=I/C Board Announces Plans To Close|website=Indianapolis Contemporary|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* On West End, ''[[Waitress (musical)|Waitress]]'' was scheduled to end on 4 July, but it closed on 16 March, as West End theatres shut down; the producers later announced the show will not re-open.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2020/coronavirus-waitress-confirms-it-will-not-reopen-after-theatre-closures |title= Coronavirus: Waitress confirms it will not reopen after theatre closures|publisher=The Stage|last=Snow|first=Georgia|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n[[File:Corona Graffiti.jpg|thumb|Coronavirus graffiti in Belgium]]\nFacing at least several weeks of closure of their buildings and publicly-accessible spaces, directors of [[GLAM (industry sector)|GLAMs]] noted several immediate trends emerging: A \"concern for staff wellbeing\" (ranging from [[Human factors and ergonomics|ergonomics]] to [[suicide]]), the expectation from many stakeholders to \"move fast, but with drastically reduced resources and not a lot of strategy\", \"plunging revenue\", probable [[layoffs]] \"starting with casual and part-time staff\", and a \"rush to get online\".<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nMany cultural sector organisations and individual artists turned to digital activities \u2013 from [[social media]] to [[virtual reality]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Feinstein|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2020/apr/08/art-virtual-reality-coronavirus-vr?CMP=Share_iOSApp_Other|title='Beginning of a new era': how culture went virtual in the face of crisis|date=9 April 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> \u2013 as a way to continue fulfilling their organisational mission and obtain or retain an audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@kajsahartig/museums-delivering-value-online-some-thoughts-during-the-covid-19-crisis-193fc0a58d22|title=Museums delivering value online \u2014 some thoughts during the Covid-19 crisis|last=Hartig|first=Kajsa|date=2020-03-29|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Farago|first=Jason|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/arts/design/coronavirus-digital-artists.html|title=The Merry-Go-Round Stopped. What Sort of Art Will Emerge?|date=2020-03-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> For example, the [[BBC]] launched a \"virtual festival of the arts\" called ''Culture in quarantine''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/culture-in-quarantine|title=BBC - BBC Arts announces new programmes for Culture In Quarantine - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Sydney Biennale]] became the first international [[arts festival]] to go entirely digital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/the-biennale-of-sydney-is-moving-online-1811871|title=Dawn of the Online Biennial Era? The Biennale of Sydney Becomes the First Major International Art Show to Go Virtual|last=Rea|first=Naomi|date=2020-03-23|website=[[Artnet]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Individual artists of all kinds offered [[impromptu]] performances via their personal accounts from their homes \u2013 singing [[Cover version|covers]], performing live book or [[poetry readings]], or creatively live-streaming themselves doing both normal and unusual activities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stubbins|first=Sinead|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/25/coronavirus-cabin-fever-the-best-celebrities-to-follow-from-robbie-williams-to-florence-pugh|title=Coronavirus cabin fever: the best celebrities to follow, from Robbie Williams to Florence Pugh|date=2020-03-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nCollecting institutions \u2013 libraries, archives, and museums of all sizes \u2013 initiated \"rapid response collecting\" programs in an effort to document and acquire artefacts associated with the period of time, and the many ways that society changed through of it.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Abend|first=Lisa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/arts/design/museums-coronavirus-pandemic-artifacts.html|title=Museums Scramble to Document the Pandemic, Even as It Unfolds|date=2020-03-31|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> For example, in the Netherlands, the national digital heritage sector organisation [[Netwerk Digitaal Erfgoed]] launched a campaign to ensure born-digital collections related to the pandemic, notably by [[web archiving]] but also including social media, and video, were archived.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.netwerkdigitaalerfgoed.nl/actueel/coronacollectie/|title=Coronacollectie|website=Netwerk Digitaal Erfgoed|language=nl-NL|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Crowdsourcing campaigns were also mounted. For example, an [[ephemera]] collection by libraries in Australia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/books/something-we-ll-never-see-again-museums-record-history-as-it-unfolds-20200403-p54gsy.html|title='Something we'll never see again': Museums record history as it unfolds|last=Dye|first=Josh|date=2020-04-05|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> a \"sound map\" of recordings of empty cities,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bakare|first=Lanre|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/art-project-captures-sound-of-cities-during-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Art project captures sound of cities during coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-31|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> an online oral history recording platform hosted by [[IUPUI]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/iu.edu/covid-19oralhistoryproject/|title=covid-19 oral history project|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> as well as an [[oral history]] project of the GLAM sector itself \u2013 which regularly interviewed directors of cultural sector organisations throughout the closure period.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=http://best-of-3.blogspot.com/2020/04/observations.html|title=Best of 3: Where are we at and how do we plan: museums as we look forward from the lock-down.|last=Johnston|first=Courtney|date=2020-04-06|website=Best of 3|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nHaving been the first country to enforce quarantine upon its population, museums in China were also the first to provide new digital services (primarily for a domestic audience, but to a lesser extent also internationally). In January the [[National Cultural Heritage Administration]] (NCHA) said they would \"encourage cultural heritage museums and institutions around the country to utilise existing digital resources and launch online exhibitions as appropriate, providing the public with safe and convenient online services.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/travel/news/chinas-museums-offer-online-exhibitions-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ar-BBZEOr6|title=China's museums offer online exhibitions amid coronavirus outbreak|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncha.gov.cn/art/2020/1/28/art_722_158541.html|title=\u5173\u4e8e\u5411\"\u535a\u7269\u9986\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5e73\u53f0\"\u63d0\u4f9b\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5185\u5bb9\u8d44\u6e90\u7684\u5021\u8bae\u4e66|website=www.ncha.gov.cn|publisher=[[National Cultural Heritage Administration]]|language=zh|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n\nVarious [[internet journalism]] and [[Industry association]]s published lists of new digitally-accessible arts and culture content for their country. Including Argentina,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buenosaires.gob.ar/culturaencasa|title=Cultura en casa|website=Buenos Aires Ciudad - Gobierno de la Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ozglam.info/s/updates/page/welcome|title=Australian GLAM updates|website=ozglam.info|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irishmuseums.org/text-pages/irishmuseumsonline-content-and-resources|title=#IrishMuseumsOnline: content and resources|website=Irish Museums Association|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Italy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalist.it/arti/2020/03/13/musei-chiusi-per-coronavirus-cosa-offrono-sul-web-e-social-mentre-iorestoacasa-2054444.html|title=Musei chiusi per Coronavirus: cosa offrono sul web e social mentre #iorestoacasa|website=Globalist|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2020/03/18/coronavirus-dal-louvre-agli-uffizi-i-musei-chiusi-ora-si-visitano-online-cineteche-teatri-e-biblioteche-cosi-la-cultura-arriva-direttamente-a-casa/5739782/|title=Coronavirus, dal Louvre agli Uffizi, i musei chiusi ora si visitano online. Cinema, teatri e biblioteche: cos\u00ec la cultura arriva direttamente a casa|date=2020-03-18|website=Il Fatto Quotidiano|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/it/article/n7jm97/nuovi-archivi-digitali|title=11 archivi digitali, immensi, gratuiti e meravigliosi|last=Davalli|first=Carolina|date=2020-03-25|website=i-D|language=it|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/19032020-how-digital-platforms-be-used-to-support-musems-during-covid-19-crisis|title=How can digital platforms help museums connect to audiences during Covid-19 emergency|publisher=[[Museums Association]]|website=www.museumsassociation.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kidsinmuseums.org.uk/2020/03/10-museum-activities-to-keep-children-entertained/|title=10 museum activities to keep children entertained|date=2020-03-23|website=Kids in Museums|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===By sector===\n====[[Public aquarium|Aquaria]] and [[zoo]]s====\nThe impact of the pandemic has been a uniquely serious crisis for some zoos \u2013 with reduced revenues for the operators but also reduced opportunities for [[stimulation]] for \"...the most intelligent and social animals \u2013 including [[gorillas]], [[kea]], [[otters]] and [[meerkats]]\".<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=Roy|first=Eleanor Ainge|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/02/new-zealand-zoos-strive-to-entertain-lonely-inhabitants-amid-lockdown|title=Animal tragic: New Zealand zoos strive to entertain lonely inhabitants amid lockdown|date=2020-04-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In order to maintain physical distancing but also still care for the animals, some [[zookeepers]] (classed as \"[[Essential worker|essential workers]]\") began living on-site at certain zoos.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mohdin|first=Aamna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/30/the-animals-arent-pleased-how-shut-uk-zoos-are-coping-under-coronavirus-lockdown|title='The animals aren't pleased': UK zoos under coronavirus lockdown|date=2020-03-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Animals who would normally have a regular scheduled public feeding, petting, or performance for zoo visitors were reported to be still \"keeping their appointments\" and noticing that \"something odd is upI\".<ref name=\":6\" /> In response to the absence of visitors, some institutions launched new [[webcams]] of their animal habitats as well as feeding sessions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/coronavirus-taronga-zoo-streams-to-homes-20200401-p54g78.html|title=Coronavirus: Taronga Zoo streams to homes|last=|first=|date=|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/travel/story/2020-03-20/virtual-touring|title=Watching animals helps. A lot. Here are the best webcams|date=2020-03-20|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> or took some animals (such as penguins<ref>{{Cite news|last=Padilla|first=Mariel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/us/coronavirus-zoos-webcams.html|title=Stuck at Home, You Can Still Explore the Zoo or Aquarium. Some Penguins Could, Too.|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|last2=Vigdor|first2=Neil|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and sloths<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.traveller.com.au/coronavirus-lockdown-and-animals-chico-the-sloth-meets-excited-dolphins-at-texas-aquarium-h1n72j|title=Chico the sloth's big day out sends dolphins into rapture|date=2020-04-07|website=Traveller|language=en-au|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>) to visit other animal enclosures. A pair of [[giant pandas]] at Hong Kong amusement park [[Ocean Park Hong Kong|Ocean Park]] mated for the first time in 10 years, after two months without tourists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/07/in-the-mood-for-love-hong-kongs-middle-aged-pandas-rediscover-their-mojo|title=Hong Kong's pandas mate for first time in decade in privacy of coronavirus lockdown|date=2020-04-07|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>  \n\nDue to the sudden collapse in international travel, the [[wildlife tourism]] sector risks the potential starvation of the animals. For example, as a consequence of the lack of tourists paying for food more than 1,000 [[elephants in Thailand]] risk starvation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hatton|first=Celia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52110551|title=Thai elephants face starvation as tourism plummets|date=2020-03-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Paddock|first=Richard C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/world/asia/coronavirus-thailand-elephants.html|title=As Tourism Plummets in Thailand, Elephants Are Out of Work, Too|date=2020-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-06|last2=Suhartono|first2=Muktita|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Dean|first3=Adam}}</ref> A \"brawl\" of hundreds of [[Long-tailed macaque]] broke out in the streets of [[Lopburi]], Thailand (known as \"monkey city\"), as the animals \u2013 normally sustained by scraps by tourists \u2013 fought for food.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ratcliffe|first=Rebecca|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/13/fighting-monkeys-highlight-effect-of-coronavirus-on-thailand-tourism|title=Mass monkey brawl highlights coronavirus effect on Thailand tourism|date=2020-03-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In countries wildlife tourism represents a significant portion of employment (such as Tanzania and Namibia), there is concern that a loss of jobs related to conservation will see a rise in [[poaching]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-lockdown-conservation/|title=The Coronavirus Lockdown Is a Threat for Many Animals, Not a Blessing|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\nNadia, a tiger at the [[Bronx Zoo]] in New York, tested positive for COVID-19 in the first week of April after developing a \"dry cough\" after having been infected via an asymptomatic zookeeper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/us/tiger-coronavirus-new-york-trnd/index.html|title=A tiger at the Bronx Zoo tests positive for coronavirus|first=Alaa |last=Elassar|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> This was the first known case of a wild animal having been infected via a human (two domestic dogs and a cat had previously been diagnosed).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/04/tiger-coronavirus-covid19-positive-test-bronx-zoo/|title=Tiger tests positive for coronavirus at Bronx Zoo, first known case in the world|date=2020-04-05|website=Animals|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n====[[Film industry|Cinema]], [[Television industry|television]] and [[radio]]====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|l1=Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television|l2=on television}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n\nThe production and release schedule of many films was suspended or delayed, with some awards ceremonies and festivals being cancelled entirely. March 2020 estimates were of approximately $5b losses for the industry,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shoard|first=Catherine|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/06/cinema-coronavirus-projected-5bn-loss|title=Cinema bullish in the face of coronavirus despite projected $5bn loss|date=2020-03-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> while April estimates were global losses of 40% (compared to 2019) of $20b.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-offices-best-case-scenario-down-40-percent-1289032|title=Box Office's Best Case Scenario? Down 40 Percent|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Examples of adaptations included the early [[Home video|home media]] release ([[Frozen II|''Frozen II'']]), [[Theatrical release|theatrical releases]] being cancelled entirely (''[[Lost in Russia]]''), and online premieres ([[Enter the Fat Dragon (2020 film)|''Enter the Fat Dragon'']]). The director of ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' also hosted a screening-party via his own [[Instagram]] account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/thor-ragnarok-screening-party-details-taika-waititi-instagram/|title=Taika Waititi Is Hosting an Instagram Live 'Thor: Ragnarok' Screening Party Today|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=2020-04-09|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Many film productions were suspended, including ''[[Avatar 2]],'' ''[[The Matrix 4]],'' and a film adaptation of ''[[Heptam\u00e9ron|The Heptameron]]'' in production in [[Florence]], Italy, based on the 14th century [[The Decameron|''Decameron'']] by [[Giovanni Boccaccio|Giovanni Boccacio]], set during the [[Black Death]] in Florence.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Marshall|first=Alex|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/world/europe/coronavirus-movie-italy-decameron.html|title=Making a Plague Movie, With Coronavirus on the Doorstep|date=1 March 2020|work=New York Times|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Wax|first=Eddy|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/life-mimics-art-plague-drama-coronavirus-hit-italy-veneto-british-film-crew/|title=Life mimics art for plague drama in coronavirus-hit Italy|date=26 February 2020|work=Politico|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The traditional cinema [[release schedule]] \u2013 whereby movie theatres enjoy a two-to-three-month period of exclusivity before a [[home video]] release \u2013 was also interrupted by the closure of theatres. Innovations because of this included \"high-priced rentals\". ''[[The Invisible Man (2020 film)|The Invisible Man]]'', ''[[The Hunt (2020 film)|The Hunt]]'', and ''[[Emma (2020 film)|Emma]]'' were almost immediately released on to digital streaming services, where viewers could rent \u2014 not buy \u2014 the film for $20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://onezero.medium.com/streaming-new-movie-releases-could-be-here-to-stay-463ba50df817|title=Streaming New Movie Releases Could Be Here to Stay|last=Ravenscraft|first=Eric|date=2020-04-03|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Cannes Film Festival]], originally scheduled to occur in mid-May, was postponed and potentially cancelled, and its venue converted to an emergency [[homeless shelter]] for the period of the national lockdown in France.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cannes opens its doors to homeless after coronavirus delays film festival |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-france-homeless-idUSKBN21B2U0 |website=Reuters |accessdate=6 April 2020|date=2020-03-24}}</ref> \n\nSimilarly, the [[television industry]] saw production halted on many [[Scripted television|scripted]] and unscripted shows. This included series which had been running uninterrupted for the proceeding several decades, including: ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]'' (season 34), ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' (season 34), ''[[Days of Our Lives]]'' (season 55), ''[[Home and Away]]'' (season 33), ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (season 45), and ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' (season 47). Some shows continue with production but without their normal [[studio audience]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-tv-shows-production-delayed-1202881997/|title=Coronavirus: TV Shows That Have Halted Or Delayed Production Amid Outbreak|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|last2=Pedersen|first2=Erik|date=2020-03-16|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Three national editions of the reality TV franchise ''[[Big Brother (franchise)|Big Brother]]'' were underway since before the pandemic began \u2013 with contestants being \"some of the last people in the world to find out about the rapid spread of Covid-19\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hern|first=Alex|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/no-news-is-good-news-big-brother-germany-cut-off-from-covid-19|title=No news is good news: Big Brother guests unaware of pandemic|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \u2013 leading to the \"ethical nightmare\" of how and whether to: inform participants; publicly broadcast their reactions; and continue production.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sampson|first=Issy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/mar/17/an-ethical-nightmare-how-coronavirus-turned-big-brother-into-a-house-of-horrors|title='An ethical nightmare': how coronavirus turned Big Brother into a house of horrors|date=2020-03-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/20/opinions/big-brother-coronavirus-reveal-ethics-thomas/index.html|title=The moral quagmire of coronavirus and 'Big Brother'|last=Thomas|first=Opinion by Holly|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\nIn parallel to the suspension of entertainment content production, there was a marked increase in the use of [[video streaming]] services for entertainment (as well as [[videoconferencing]] services such as [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] for work and education) due to the massive increase of people staying at home \u2013 causing unprecedented strain on global [[internet infrastructure]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/27/coronavirus-can-the-internet-handle-unprecedented-surge-in-traffic.html|title=The internet is under huge strain because of the coronavirus. Experts say it can cope \u2014 for now|last=Browne|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-27|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> In response, [[Netflix]] and [[YouTube]] both decreased the default video quality to [[standard definition]], [[Disney+]] delayed its launch in France, and [[Xbox]] requested developers to schedule software updates at times of lower network congestion.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kang|first=Cecilia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/business/coronavirus-internet-traffic-speed.html|title=Surging Traffic Is Slowing Down Our Internet|date=2020-03-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-03|last2=Alba|first2=Davey|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Satariano|first3=Adam}}</ref> \n\n[[HBO]] also released 500 hours of free programming, including full seasons of ''[[The Sopranos]]'', ''[[Veep]]'' and ''[[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/hbo-free-streaming-500-hours-sopranos-veep-wire-1234569585/|title=HBO Will Stream 500 Hours of Free Programming, Including Full Seasons of 'Veep,' 'The Sopranos,' 'Silicon Valley'|last=Spangler|first=Todd|publisher=Variety|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSatellite radio service [[SiriusXM]] offered free streaming of their subscription-based radio service from April 2 to May 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/siriusxm-offers-free-streaming-amid-social-distancing/|title=SiriusXM Offers Free Streaming Amid Social Distancing|website=Pitchfork|language=en|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In the USA, [[NPR]] continued to produce new episodes of its ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'' quiz [[panel show]], although it was no longer recorded in front of a live audience, and live tapings in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] and [[Atlanta]] were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.wbfo.org/post/message-npr-programming|title=A message from NPR on programming|last1=News|first1=N. P. R.|website=news.wbfo.org|language=en|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2020/03/17/taping-of-npr-wait-wait-quiz-show-at-sheas-postponed/|title=Taping of NPR's 'Wait, Wait' quiz show at Shea's postponed|date=17 March 2020|website=The Buffalo News|language=en-us|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/music/npr-cancels-thursday-live-taping-wait-wait-don-tell-the-fox-theatre/wb24HTGK9GaKFgd64XnK2O/|title=NPR cancels Thursday live taping of 'Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me' at the Fox Theatre|last1=Ruggieri|first1=Melissa|website=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|language=english|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDue to the global cancellation of [[professional sports]], the loss of advertising revenue and broadcast rights derived from the [[broadcasting of sports events]] is expected to threaten the financial viability of many competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/20/sports-broadcast-impact-coronavirus/|title=For the sports-entertainment business, coronavirus is taking a huge toll|last=Zeitchik|first=Steven|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n====[[Libraries]]====\nLibraries faced different situations, from maintaining a full service with some restrictions, through providing minimal services, to complete closure. Following recent medical journal publications, the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]] in the United States suggesting that the risk of coronavirus transmission from paper was low. In the light of this, the [[International Federation of Library Associations]] noted that some libraries had imposed a wait period before handling returned books, while others have made it clear that no-one is expected to return borrowed books until things return to normal.<ref name=\"IFLA\" /> Some libraries stopped programmes which would see people spend longer periods together. Others closed public reading rooms or only allow people to collect books on appointment, either inside or outside of the building \u2013 for example setting up tables, with a [[drive-through]], or book delivery service to especially vulnerable community groups.<ref name=\"IFLA\" />\n\nLibraries of different sizes and purposes around the world worked to provide access to collections and services remotely. For example, the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]] organised [[virtual exhibition]]s,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fantasy.bnf.fr/fr|title=Fantasy, retour aux sources|website=Fantasy, retour aux sources|language=fr|publisher=[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> the Granby library in [[Quebec City|Quebec]] highlighted content focused on learning new skills,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lavoixdelest.ca/actualites/covid-19/a-un-clic-de-1300-cours-en-ligne-23003711130c1556504efdc64b1422d2|title=\u00c0 un clic de 1300 cours en ligne|date=2020-03-28|website=La Voix de l\u2019Est|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> the [[National library of Israel]] announced it would provide free audiobooks,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/national-library-offers-free-audiobooks-amid-coronavirus-closures-621664|title=National Library offers free audiobooks amid coronavirus closures|website=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the library of the [[National Congress of Argentina]] announced it would record and share readings by prominent local authors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/cultura/2020/03/18/biblioteca-del-congreso-todas-las-actividades-online-durante-la-pandemia-del-coronavirus/|title=Biblioteca del Congreso: todas las actividades online durante la pandemia del coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=Infobae|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> There have also been major efforts to boost access to [[eBooks]]: by increasing the number of eBooks in the catalogue (the [[Digital Public Library of America]] announced its intention to double the collection to 12,000 titles),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dp.la/news/our-plans-for-the-next-90-days?|title=Our plans for the next 90 days|last=Bracken|first=John|date=2020-04-03|website=[[Digital Public Library of America]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> increasing the number that people can borrow at any given time, or by reassigning budgets to pay for electronic content.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/artery/2020/03/20/demand-e-books-rises-area-libraries|title=Demand For E-books Rises At Area Libraries|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"IFLA\" /> On March 24 the [[Internet Archive]] announced the creation of a \"National Emergency Library\" whereby it suspended the waitlists on 1.4m ebooks from their lending library \u2013 books that are not in the [[Public domain in the United States|Public domain in the USA]] \u2013 in order to ensure uninterrupted access to works books for educators and students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.archive.org/2020/03/24/announcing-a-national-emergency-library-to-provide-digitized-books-to-students-and-the-public/|title=Announcing a National Emergency Library to Provide Digitized Books to Students and the Public|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Internet Archive Blogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/03/internet-archive-offers-thousands-of-copyrighted-books-for-free-online/|title=Internet Archive offers 1.4 million copyrighted books for free online|last=Lee|first=Timothy B.|date=2020-03-28|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The announcement strongly criticised by the [[publishing industry]].<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n====[[Literature]] and [[publishing]]====\n{{Quote box\n| width = 22em\n| border = 1px\n| align = right\n| fontsize = 100%\n| salign = center\n| quote = \u201cI believe that books are essential. They make us kinder, more empathetic human beings. And they have the power to take us away \u2013 even momentarily \u2013 from feeling overwhelmed, anxious and scared.\u201d <br>Author, [[James Patterson]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Steger|first=Jason|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/books/deplorable-australia-council-stuns-literary-fold-with-funding-cuts-20200406-p54hny.html|title='Deplorable': Australia Council stuns literary fold with funding cuts|date=3 April 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=2020-04-13|url-status=live|language=en|}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| width = 22em\n| border = 1px\n| align = right\n| fontsize = 100%\n| salign = center\n| quote = \u201cIt is only now, physically separated from friends and colleagues, that I realise how much sustenance and inspiration I receive from their insights, their conversation and their argument. [[A Room of One's Own|A room of one\u2019s own]] is a necessity. It is not enough.\u201d <br>Author, [[Christos Tsiolkas]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Tsiolkas|first=Christos|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/books/were-so-many-of-us-wrong-christos-tsiolkas-on-the-new-uncertainty-20200331-p54fid.html|title=Why were so many of us wrong? Christos Tsiolkas on the new uncertainty|date=3 April 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|language=en||website=}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs a result of restrictions on gatherings of people, many [[Literary festival|literary festivals,]]<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|last=Alter|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/books/coronavirus-impact-publishing-industry-booksellers-authors.html|title=The World of Books Braces for a Newly Ominous Future|date=2020-03-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> commercial [[Trade fair|book fairs]]<ref name=\":13\" /> and book launches were cancelled or postponed, with bookshops such as [[Hatchards]] in London offering refunds on tickets already purchased.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.hatchards.co.uk/hatchards-calendar/fragile-borders-fragile-bodies-an-evening-with-miranda-gold/|title=Hatchards - this event has been cancelled|date=April 2020|work=Hatchards|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Such cancellations (as well as the closure of schools) had a significant impact on the ability of [[Publishing|publishers]] to bring new works to the public as well as on opportunities for [[Writer|writers]] to perform at paid speaking events. Many bookshops were forced to close their doors; others including [[Independent bookstore|independent bookshops]], closed their business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/books/story/2020-03-17/across-la-booksellers-are-scrambling-to-stay-afloat-amid-coronavirus-concerns|title=Across L.A., bookstores close, scramble to stay afloat amid coronavirus concerns|date=2020-03-17|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Booksellers adapted by providing free shipping and \"curbside pickup\" from closed shopfronts, giving book recommendations by video, and setting up partnerships with other businesses such as florists. While some bookshops continued to operate full phone, email, web order, mail order services and offered free delivery,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gleebooks.worldsecuresystems.com/|title=April 2020 - Covid19 Important Update|last=|first=|date=April 2020|website=Gleebooks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> others, such as [[Amazon (company)|Amazon.com]], de-prioritised book shipments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Partridge|first=Joanna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/17/amazon-to-suspend-all-non-essential-shipments-in-uk-and-us-until-april|title=Amazon to suspend non-essential shipments to UK and US warehouses|date=2020-03-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nLiterature on the subject of epidemics experienced a boom in sales, some becoming [[Bestseller|bestsellers]]. Titles that sold strongly include ''Decamerone'' by Giovanni Boccaccio, written about 1453;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spicer|first=Andr\u00e9|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/2020/03/coronavirus-survive-italy-wellbeing-stories-decameron|title=The Decameron \u2013 the 14th-century Italian book that shows us how to survive coronavirus|date=9 March 2020|work=New Statesman|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Vanamee|first=Norman|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/leisure/arts-and-culture/a31540805/decameron-sudden-popularity-coronavirus/|title=Decameron and Chill? Why a 14th-Century Italian Masterpiece Is on Everyone's Coronavirus Reading List|date=16 March 2020|work=Town & Country|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Plague|La Peste]]'' (The Plague) by [[Albert Camus]], published in 1947; [[The Stand|''The Stand'']] by [[Stephen King]], published in 1978; and [[The Eyes of Darkness|''The Eyes of Darkness'']] by [[Dean Koontz]], released in 1981.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Flood|first=Alison|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/mar/05/publishers-report-sales-boom-in-novels-about-fictional-epidemics-camus-the-plague-dean-koontz|title=Publishers report sales boom in novels about fictional epidemics|date=6 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Periodical]] publishers of news and magazines saw coronavirus related content published in late March represented just 1% of articles published, but accounted for about 13% of all article views.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://whatsnewinpublishing.com/coronavirus-leads-to-significant-surge-in-traffic-how-publishers-are-building-reader-loyalty-by-offering-free-content/|title=Coronavirus leads to surge in traffic: How publishers are building reader loyalty by offering free content|date=2020-03-19|website=What\u2019s New in Publishing {{!}} Digital Publishing News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Many [[paywalled]] news services removed that restriction in order to generate [[brand loyalty]] and greater public access to relevant information. [[Cond\u00e9 Nast|Cond\u00e9 Nast Italy]] made digital editions of all its magazines (such as [[Vogue Italia|''Vogue Italia'']]) free for three months, similarly [[Hearst Communications|Hearst Spain]] (publisher of ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'').<ref name=\":16\" /> Meanwhile, [[academic publishers]] made available \"more than 32,000 articles, chapters and other resources\" related to [[COVID-19]] under various degrees of [[open access]], in order to provide \"immediate access to accurate and validated articles and monographs that the public can trust.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stm-assoc.org/about-the-industry/coronavirus-2019-ncov/|title=Coronavirus (Covid-2019)|last=|first=|date=|website=STM|publisher=[[International Association of Scientific, Technical, and Medical Publishers]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nFor professional authors, many revenue streams were curtailed.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/apr/06/french-writers-corona-getaways-prompt-backlash-leila-slimani-marie-darrieussecq|title=French writers' coronavirus getaways prompt backlash|last=Flood|first=Alison|date=2020-04-06|website=the Guardian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[American Booksellers Association]] lobbied publishers to provide discounts to independent retailers.<ref name=\":14\" /> The [[Republic of Consciousness Prize]] for small publishers of fiction split its \u00a310,000 award of among the five shortlisted nominees.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Flood|first=Alison|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/mar/30/prize-shares-10000-between-publishers-amid-coronavirus-damage|title=Prize shares \u00a310,000 between publishers amid coronavirus damage|date=2020-03-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Audible (store)|Audible]] (owned by Amazon) announced it would make 300 [[audiobooks]] free with login, for the duration of school closures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/audible-offers-hundreds-of-free-audiobooks-for-homeschooling-due-to-coronavirus-school-closures|title=Free audiobooks offered by Audible for kids affected by coronavirus school closures|last=March 2020|first=Alex Whitelock 24|website=TechRadar|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/radio/2020-03-20/audible-just-made-hundreds-of-titles-completely-free-to-help-during-coronavirus-crisis/|title=Audible just made hundreds of titles completely free to help during coronavirus crisis|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n====[[Museums]]====\n{{Quote box\n|width     = 22em\n|border    = 1px\n|align     = right\n|fontsize  = 100%\n|salign    = center\n|quote     =\n\u201cThis year, the paint has more time to dry.\u201d<br> \nDirector of the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] announcing a delay to the [[Archibald Prize]] portraiture exhibition until after the health crisis, \"when art will be needed more than ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/paint-has-more-time-to-dry-archibald-prize-delayed-20200321-p54ck2.html|title='Paint has more time to dry': Archibald Prize delayed|date=21 March 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n}}\n\nMany websites were rapidly updated to focus on their \"virtual museum resources, e-learning, and online collections\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcn.edu/a-guide-to-virtual-museum-resources/|title=The Ultimate Guide to Virtual Museum Resources|date=2020-03-15|website=MCN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Institutions' efforts to engage with the public during the lockdown took many forms \u2013 including the provision of: humour; [[escapism]]; opportunities to express artistic creativity; education opportunities; social connection and collaboration; and \"a sense of calm\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mcn.edu/8-essential-things/|title=The 8 Essential Things Museums are Providing Right Now|date=2020-03-29|website=MCN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Lists also were published of fine-art museums with existing interactive services (notably those already \"partners\" of [[Google Arts & Culture]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/547919/2500-virtual-museum-tours-google-arts-culture/|title=2,500 Museums You Can Now Visit Virtually|date=2020-03-16|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n\nMany museums turned to their existing [[social media]] presences to engage their audience online. Quickly, the [[Twitter|Twitter hashtag]] #MuseumFromHome became particularly popular for museums sharing their content in innovative ways.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/museum-social-media-entertains-during-the-covid-19-crisis/|title=Museum Social Media Entertains During the COVID-19 Crisis|date=2020-03-19|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Various institutions were singled out for particular praise by industry analysts for their successful social media content strategy during the shutdown. These included: The [[J. Paul Getty Museum|Getty Museum]] for \"challenging\" the public to share their recreated version of its artworks;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Crace|first=John|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/apr/06/how-i-became-the-duke-of-urbino-getty-museum-recreate-masterpiece|title=Coronavirus art challenge: how a pan turned me into the Duke of Urbino|date=2020-04-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5812437/getty-museum-challenge/|title=Put These Artistic Masterpieces Re-created With Household Items in a Museum|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> the [[Shedd Aquarium]] in Chicago for filming their penguins visiting other animals;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/15/us/coronavirus-penguins-shedd-aquarium-trnd/index.html|title=With the aquarium closed to humans, penguins take opportunity to explore and visit other animals|first=Alicia |last=Lee|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> the [[Royal Academy]] in London for asking its followers to draw their own artworks;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Marshall|first=Alex|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/arts/design/museums-coronavirus-adam-koszary.html|title=Museum World\u2019s King of Memes Brings Humor to Lockdown|date=2020-03-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]] in Oklahoma for providing an authentic and unusual 'voice' to their social media - from their security guard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boredpanda.com/national-cowboy-museum-head-of-security-twitter/|title=Cowboy Museum Puts Their Head Of Security In Charge Of Their Twitter, And His Tweets Are Hilariously Wholesome|website=Bored Panda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Philbrook Museum of Art]]'s rapid relaunch their website in late-March \u2013 in order \"for us all to spend some time practicing social distancing and experiencing the #MuseumFromHome\" \u2013 was described as a model example of how an institution could \"Reorganise, Reuse and Rethink\" its activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/reorganise-reuse-get-creative-and-relaunch-lessons-from-philbrook/|title=Reorganise, Reuse, Rethink and Relaunch - Lessons from Philbrook|date=2020-03-21|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Other specific examples included [[Europeana]] publishing a digital gallery of images relating to the theme of [[handwashing]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.europeana.eu/en/galleries/washing-your-hands|title=Washing your hands|website=www.europeana.eu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|Museum of New Zealand]] publishing a \"little page of calm\" (in a reference to the 1997 bestselling book ''[[Little book of calm]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tepapa.govt.nz/discover-collections/read-watch-play/little-page-calm|title=The little page of calm|date=2020-03-16|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa, Wellington, NZ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n====[[Music]]====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the music industry}}\n{{Quote box\n|width     = 22em\n|border    = 1px\n|align     = right\n|fontsize  = 100%\n|salign    = center\n|quote     =\n\u201cIt is very hard financially and if you have lost the momentum you have built up over time,\" ... But this is also an ideal time for artists to do what it is they are supposed to be doing: create art.\"<br>Musician and performer, [[Tim Minchin]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cooper|first=Nathanael|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/for-musicians-collapse-of-touring-industry-opens-door-to-creativity-20200403-p54gpx.html|title=For musicians, collapse of touring industry opens door to creativity|date=5 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\nMany musicians delayed the releases of [[Album|albums]] due to the pandemic (including [[Lady Gaga]] and [[Willie Nelson]]),<ref name=\"rstone1\">{{cite web |last1=Leight |first1=Elias |title=They Were Going to Be Spring's Biggest Albums -- Until COVID-19 Hit |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/album-delays-caused-by-covid-19-973870/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> some moved up the release dates of their upcoming albums (including [[Dua Lipa]] and [[Sufjan Stevens]]),<ref name=\"sgum1\">{{cite web |last1=Rettig |first1=James |title=HAIM, Dua Lipa, Willie Nelson, & Sufjan Stevens Among Artists Moving Album Release Dates Amid Pandemic |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2077667/dua-lipa-willie-nelson-sufjan-stevens-among-artists-moving-album-release-dates-amid-pandemic/news/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> while others (including [[Nine Inch Nails]] and [[Phish]]) released new albums with little or no notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Farokhmanesh |first1=Megan |title=Nine Inch Nails just released two new albums for free |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/26/21195266/nine-inch-nails-new-albums-just-ghosts-v-vi-free-download |website=The Verge |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Phish to Debut New Album 'Sigma Oasis' During April 1st Livestream |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/phish-new-album-sigma-oasis-976437/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> In the middle of March, [[Bob Dylan]] released a single 17 minute new song called \"[[Murder Most Foul (song)|Murder Most Foul]]\", his first piece of original material in eight years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McFadyen|first=Matthew|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/murder-most-foul-bob-dylan-s-surprise-song-for-the-viral-age-20200330-p54f8z.html|title=Murder Most Foul: Bob Dylan's surprise song for the viral age|date=30 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|2020 Eurovision Song Contest]], set to take place in May in [[Rotterdam]], [[Netherlands]], was canceled, marking the first time the annual contest would not take place since its inauguration in 1956.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eurovision Song Contest Canceled Because of Coronavirus |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eurovision-song-contest-cancelled-because-coronavirus-1282660 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Official EBU statement & FAQ on Eurovision 2020 cancellation |url=https://eurovision.tv/official-ebu-statement-and-faq-eurovision-song-contest-2020-cancellation |website=Eurovision.tv |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral special remote-participation [[concerts]] were organised to provide entertainment to the public, and to raise awareness methods to combat the virus, notably [[physical distancing]].The [[iHeart Living Room Concert for America]] concert (hosted by [[Elton John]]) was broadcast on American TV and radio on March 29, while ''[[Together at Home]]'' was a \"virtual concert series\". It was then followed by the ''[[One World: Together at Home]]'' concert on April 18, organised by [[Lady Gaga]] as a [[benefit concert]] for the [[World Health Organization|World Health Organization\u2019s]] [[COVID-19 Solidarity Response Fund|COVID-19 solidarity response fund]], which would be broadcast on radio, tv, and many digital platforms simultaneously.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Snapes|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/06/lady-gaga-billie-eilish-and-paul-mccartney-to-play-coronavirus-benefit|title=Lady Gaga, Billie Eilish and Paul McCartney to play coronavirus benefit|date=2020-04-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-09|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The quickly organised \"Instagram Live Music Festival\" ''Isol Aid'' (a reference to [[Live Aid]]) of 72 Australian bands was broadcast on the weekend of 21\u201322 March. Each artist performed from wherever the were [[Isolation (health care)|self isolating]] and \"... play a 20-minute set streamed live on their Instagram accounts, and then tag-team the next artist to play\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/isol-aid-instagram-live-music-festival-coronavirus-covid-19/12072202|title=Isol-Aid is a stacked Aussie livestreaming music festival that's happening this weekend|last=Newstead|first=Al|date=2020-03-19|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://linktr.ee/isolaidfestival|title=@isolaidfestival|website=Linktree|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> On [[Easter Sunday]] 2020, which fell during the peak of the [[Flatten the curve|infection curve]] in many countries, Italian opera singer [[Andrea Bocelli]] performed in the empty [[Milan Cathedral|cathedral of Milan]] \u2013 capital of the worst-hit region of Italy \u2013 accompanied only by the [[Milan Cathedral|Cathedral]] organist and [[Streaming media|streamed live]] via YouTube.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lastampa.it/cultura/2020/04/07/news/bocelli-concerto-di-pasqua-nel-duomo-di-milano-1.38690201|title=Bocelli, concerto di Pasqua nel Duomo di Milano|date=2020-04-07|website=lastampa.it|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIndividually and collectively, [[musicians]] organised online performances, dubbed \"virtual concerts\", both of contemporary<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9335531/coronavirus-quarantine-music-events-online-streams|title=Coronavirus: Ongoing List of Virtual Concerts & Livestreams|date=2020-04-09|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and of classical music.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tilden|first=Imogen|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/15/bittersweet-symphony-the-best-lockdown-orchestras-and-choirs-online|title=Bittersweet symphony: the best lockdown orchestras and choirs online|date=2020-04-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Often these included musical sections referencing the fact of social isolation or home-quarantine, via their own social media platforms. Some were especially planned and prepared; some were impromptu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/live-streamed-gigs-coronavirus-yungblud-17955670|title=The best live streamed gigs to watch at home during coronavirus|last=Clements|first=Laura|date=2020-03-20|website=walesonline|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> For example, cellist [[Yo-Yo Ma|YoYo Ma]] performed \"Going Home\" by [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]], the [[West Australian Symphony Orchestra]] renamed themselves the \"West Australian Social Distancing Orchestra\" and played a re-arranged version of ''[[Bol\u00e9ro]]'' by [[Maurice Ravel]], and an amateur choir gathered the contributions of more than 1000 people from 18 countries to create a video performance of \u201cClose To You\u201d by [[The Carpenters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HezxInuN1YA|title=Couch Choir - (They Long To Be) Close To You|last=|first=|date=22 March 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Many musicians, singers and songwriters adapted to the crisis by turning to teaching online as there was both a sudden increase in people wanting to learn instruments, and a drop in paid public performance opportunities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lamond|first=Scott|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-26/coronavirus-cant-stop-the-music-as-online-lessons-in-demand/12089060|title=Coronavirus sees ARIA-winning musicians turn online teachers as students flock to lessons|date=26 March 2020|work=ABC News|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====[[Performing arts]]====\n{{main article|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the performing arts}}\nDue to physical distancing requirements many physical venues were closed, curtailing not only public performances but also rehearsals. In some cases, such as for the [[List of Edinburgh festivals|Edinburgh Festival]], launched after [[World War II]] as an effort to reconcile people through the performing arts, it was the first cancellation in more than sixty years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/theatre/edinburgh-festivals-cancelled-for-first-time-since-1947-20200402-p54gbo.html?btis|title=Edinburgh festivals cancelled for first time since 1947|date=2 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Many performing arts institutions attempted to adapt by offering new (or newly expanded) digital services. In particular this resulted in the free [[online streaming]] of previously recorded performances of many companies \u2013 especially [[Orchestral|orchestral performances]] and [[Play (theatre)|plays]] \u2013 lists of which were collated by crowdsourcing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://streams.culturaldigital.com/|title=Cultural Digital: Streams|last=Unitt|first=Chris|date=|website=streams.culturaldigital.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> and by journalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/theatre/best-streaming-theatre-shows-how-to-watch-online|title=The best theatre to watch online right now|website=Time Out Worldwide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Convery|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/20/livestreaming-schedule-music-art-literature-and-events-from-australia-and-beyond|title=Livestreaming schedule: music, art, literature and events from Australia and beyond|date=2020-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Rawson|first2=Sharnee|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/stage-shows-musicals-opera-free-stream-online_51198.html|title=Stage shows, musicals and opera you can watch online now for free {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>  For example: the [[Metropolitan Opera]] of New York broadcast a new opera each evening, including an entire [[Ring Cycle]] performed during the 2010\u201312 seasons;<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/in-wake-of-season-cancellation-metropolitan-opera-continues-free-streaming-series-with-a-week-of-wagner|title=In Wake of Season Cancellation, Metropolitan Opera Continues Free Streaming Series With a Week of Wagner|last=McPhee|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-23|website=[[Playbill]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> the [[Bolshoi Ballet]] company of Moscow made available six of their performances;<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/03/27/spend-an-evening-at-the-bolshoi-a69775|title=Spend an Evening at the Bolshoi|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=The Moscow Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-russia-bolshoi-idUSKBN21E35D|title=Russia's Bolshoi Theater goes online as coronavirus curbs public life|date=2020-03-27|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en}}</ref> [[Shakespeare's Globe]] published 40 of its filmed stage productions;<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/shakespeares-globe-free-stream-hamlet_51295.html|title=Shakespeare's Globe to release 40 free productions as part of new digital content offering {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> producer [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] published a filmed production of one of his stage [[Musical theatre|musicals]] each week.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/andrew-lloyd-webber-musicals-stream-free-online-joseph-jesus-a4404846.html|title=Andrew Lloyd Webber's musicals will be streamed for free online|date=2020-04-03|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIndividual actors, such as [[Patrick Stewart]] and [[Sam Neill]], entertained from isolation in order to \"...be in this together and that this has to take the form of being apart\", as Neill described his contribution of [[comedic relief]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Craven|first=Peter|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/movies/when-the-going-got-tough-sam-neill-got-out-his-ukulele-20200330-p54fd8.html|title=When the going got tough, Sam Neill got out his ukulele|date=1 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Stewart, a trained Shakespearian actor, broadcast himself reading one [[Shakespearean sonnet|sonnet]] each day via social media,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/books-and-poetry/patrick-stewart-is-treating-twitter-to-one-shakespearan-sonnet-a-day-during-lockdown|title=Patrick Stewart Is Treating Twitter To One Shakespeare Sonnet A Day During Lockdown|date=2020-03-25|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> readings described as \"more than light entertainment, they\u2019re moments of connection\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Marshall|first=Konrad|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/a-force-for-good-how-the-coronavirus-crisis-is-sweetening-our-collective-tune-20200227-p5452j.html|title=A force for good: how the coronavirus crisis is sweetening our collective tune|date=10 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=10 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Sydney Theatre Company]] commissioned actors to film themselves at home discussing, then performing, a monologue from one of the characters they had previously played on stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sydneytheatre.com.au/stc-virtual|title=STC Virtual|website=Sydney Theatre Company|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nMany ballet companies ran classes via [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] to their dancers which were also broadcast.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/arts/dance/ballet-class-coronavirus.html|title=Dancers Still Need Daily Class. No Barre? Just Grab a Chair.|work=New York Times|date=25 March 2020|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Ballet dancers, including [[principal dancer]] with the [[New York City Ballet]] [[Megan Fairchild]] and [[artistic director]] and a lead [[principal dancer]] of the [[English National Ballet]] [[Tamara Rojo]], offered live classes on social media.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/14/arts/dance/megan-fairchild-city-ballet-coping-at-home.html|title=A Dancer's Quarantine Diary: Coming Full Circle|work=New York times|last=Fairchild|first=Megan|date=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pointemagazine.com/online-ballet-class-2645499567.html?rebelltitem=14#rebelltitem14|title=Take Virtual Class From Your Kitchen Counter With These Pros|last=Lansky|first=Chava|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impacts==\n===Budgets and employment===\n{{see also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nDue to the closures, revenues for cultural organisations reliant on ticket sales were expected to cause devastating effects upon revenues, with consequent impacts upon organisational staffing, and on independent artists and professionals. This is due to the fact that the arts and culture is a sector of national economies characterised by particularly a high proportion of self-employment.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/arts-council-england-emergency-relief-fund-1814829|title=Arts Council England Has Launched a $190 Million Emergency Relief Package for Creative Organizations and Artists|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> For example, by the 20th of March the [[Cirque du Soleil]] had [[laid off]] 95% of its workforce and closed [[traveling circus]] performances operating in seven countries,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/cirque-de-soleil-canada-coronavirus-staff-fired-1493386|title=Cirque du Soleil lays off 95 percent of its workforce after coronavirus forces closure of all its shows globally|last=Cole|first=Brendan|date=2020-03-20|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The world commercial art market declined 5% in 2019 compared to the previous year, and is expected to decline further in 2020 \u2013 with six of the world's 10 largest auction houses operating exclusively in China. Major art fairs such as [[Hong Kong Arts Festival]] and [[Art Basel]] were cancelled, furthering a shift towards online purchases and the creation of VIP \"online viewing rooms\" rather than physical displaying at [[art auctions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/the-coronavirus-pandemic-corona-panic-is-shaking-up-worlds-global-art-market-starting-in-hong-kong/a-52651815|title=The coronavirus is shaking up the world's art market in unexpected ways|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|website=DW.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nVarious [[Celebrity|celebrities]] from different industries attempted to demonstrate [[empathy]] backfired for being tone-deaf to their privileged position. These included actor [[Gal Gadot]], musicians [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Pharrell Williams]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mahdawi|first=Arwa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/31/the-coronavirus-crisis-has-exposed-the-ugly-truth-about-celebrity-culture-and-capitalism|title=The coronavirus crisis has exposed the ugly truth about celebrity culture and capitalism|date=2020-03-31|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and French writers [[Le\u00efla Slimani]] and [[Marie Darrieussecq]] \u2013 who were ridiculed for their insensitivity as they described their \"bucolic isolation\" in countryside villas.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nArts and culture sector budgetary and employment reports from individual countries included:<br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. According to government figures, \"cultural and creative activity contributed to {{AUD|112}} billion (6.4% of [[GDP]]) to Australia's economy in 2016-17\".<ref name=docaapr9>{{cite web | title=COVID-19 update | website=Australian Government. [[Department of Communications and the Arts]] | date=9 April 2020 | url=https://www.arts.gov.au/covid-19-update | access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> By late March 2020, 255,000 cultural events had been cancelled with an estimated revenue loss of $A280 million, self reported through the crowdsourced website ILostMyGig.net.au.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-what-the-latest-stimulus-measures-mean-for-australian-artists-and-arts-organisations-134233|title=Coronavirus: what the latest stimulus measures mean for Australian artists and arts organisations|last=Caust|first=Jo|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> [[Opera Australia]] \u2013 the nation's largest [[performing arts]] company \u2013 temporarily stood down nearly all its staff<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/exit-stage-left-opera-australia-leads-arts-shutdown-20200325-p54dq1|title=Exit stage left: Opera Australia leads arts shutdown|date=2020-03-26|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> amid speculation it would also need to sell major assets in order to avoid [[bankruptcy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/opera-australia-looks-to-sell-offs-to-stay-afloat-20200316-p54ai2.html|title=Opera Australia looks to sell-offs to stay afloat|last=Galvin|first=Nick|date=2020-03-16|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> In mid-April, the [[Melbourne Symphony Orchestra]] fired all of its musicians \"rather than honouring an agreement that would have kept them on the books on half pay\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/culture/music/stood-down-musicians-blindsided-by-mso-decision-20200415-p54k3n.html|title=Stood-down musicians 'blindsided' by MSO decision|last=Miller|first=Nick|date=2020-04-15|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. In March, when many institutions closed for the first time since [[WWII]], the state-funded museum sector had been valued at \u20ac27 billion or 1.6% of national GDP \u2013 slightly smaller than the agriculture sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/coronavirus-l-impatto-negativo-chiusure-musei-che-valgono-l-16percento-pil-AC4pFCMB|title=Coronavirus, l'impatto negativo delle chiusure sui musei (che valgono l'1,6% del Pil)|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. As the pandemic spread and closures became the standard not the exception, institutions started publishing expected revenue shortfall calculations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AMTransparency/status/1242869675425443840|title=This will be a thread for tracking museum layoff news.|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|publisher=Art + Museum Transparency|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> For example, by the end of March: the [[Metropolitan opera]] expects to lose $60m in revenue;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Woolfe|first=Zachary|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/arts/music/metropolitan-opera-coronavirus.html|title=Metropolitan Opera Cancels Season Over Virus and Faces $60 Million Loss|date=2020-03-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the [[Metropolitan Museum]] expects to lose $100m<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/arts/design/met-museum-coronavirus-closure.html|title=Met Museum Prepares for $100 Million Loss and Closure Till July|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and [[SFMOMA]] predicted a 40% decrease in revenue.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13877653/sfmoma-to-lay-off-or-furlough-over-300-museum-staff|title=SFMOMA to Lay Off or Furlough Over 300 Museum Staff|last=Hotchkiss|first=Sarah|date=2020-03-27|website=[[KQED]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Matching this prediction, the American movie industry predicted a \"best case\" decreased of 40% (compared to 2019 figures) if cinemas were shut for only three months, the lowest figure since 2000.<ref name=\":19\" /> \n\nBy the end of March, many museums were announcing the [[Dismissal (employment)|dismissal]] of large portions of their staff with short short notice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/news/museums-across-the-us-lay-off-workers-as-covid-19-cases-rise-82588|title=Museums Across the US Lay Off Workers as COVID-19 Cases Rise|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Examples included: the [[Cleveland Museum of Art]] put all part-time staff on unpaid leave, \"temporarily\" [[Layoff|laid off]] unionised workers, and reduced the salaries of remaining staff; <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/arts/2020/03/cleveland-museum-of-art-announces-pay-cuts-furloughs-anticipating-5-million-revenue-loss-due-to-coronavirus-shutdown.html|title=Cleveland Museum of Art announces pay cuts, furloughs, anticipating $5 million revenue loss due to coronavirus shutdown|last=Litt|first=Steven|last2=Dealer|first2=The Plain|date=2020-03-26|website=cleveland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> [[SFMOMA]] put 300 employees on unpaid leave;<ref name=\":8\" />the [[Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art]] fired 73% of its staff;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/artery/2020/03/25/mass-moca-lays-off-majority-of-staff-as-coronavirus-closures-batter-cultural-institutions|title=Mass MoCA Lays Off Majority Of Staff As Coronavirus Closures Continue To Batter Cultural Institutions|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> ; [[Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh]] [[Furlough|furloughed]] 550 of its 1003 staff (75% of which were part-time);<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/ae/art-architecture/2020/03/24/Arts-groups-furlough-employees-reduce-pay/stories/202003240087|title=Carnegie Museums, Pittsburgh Glass Center furlough employees, reduce pay|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> the [[Science Museum of Minnesota]] \"temporarily\" laid off most of its staff in an announcement via a [[Google Hangouts]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/minnesota-science-museum-children-s-museum-lay-off-most-staff-in-wake-of-covid-19-outbreak/569063662/|title=Science Museum of Minnesota, Children's Museum temporarily lay off most staff in wake of COVID-19|website=Star Tribune|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> the [[Los Angeles Museum of Contemporary Art]] \u2013 which had recently received a gift of $10m from board president Carolyn Powers \u2013 fired all [[Part-time job|part-time]] staff;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/news/la-moca-lays-off-all-part-time-staffers-82559|title=LA MoCA Lays Off All Part-Time Staffers|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/wet-paint-moca-trump-backer-1755270|title=Wet Paint: MOCA Board President Revealed as Secret Trump Backer, Murakami Mix-Up at Paris Fashion Week, & More Juicy Art-World Gossip|date=2020-01-16|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and [[Museum of Modern Art|MOMA]] \u2013 an institution with a billion dollar [[Financial endowment|endowment]] \u2013 cancelled all educator contracts. Noting as it did so that when it reopens, \u201c...it will be months, if not years, before we anticipate returning to budget and operations levels to require educator services\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/551571/moma-educator-contracts/|title=MoMA Terminates All Museum Educator Contracts|date=2020-04-03|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\nIn parallel to museum sector layoffs, staff began to [[Labor unions in the United States|unionise]], even though \"[[Social distancing]] orders prevent the in-person meetings required to sign the cards required to file for union elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tinyletter.com/artandmuseumtransparency/letters/art-museum-transparency-newsletter-2-march-2020|title=Art + Museum Transparency Newsletter #2 -- March 2020|last=|first=|date=2020-03-26|website=artandmuseumtransparency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Meanwhile, on 18 March and in response to the rapid rise of online performances during the closures of performance spaces, the [[Actors' Equity Association]] \u2013 the union announced a new \"streaming media agreement\" available to productions in areas with physical distancing regulations in force, for \"select producers to capture and make a performance available online for one-time viewing to ticket buyers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.actorsequity.org/news/PR/March18/|title=ACTORS' EQUITY MAKES NEW, TEMPORARY STREAMING AGREEMENTS AVAILABLE TO PRODUCERS IN AREAS WITH LIMITS ON PUBLIC GATHERINGS&nbsp;\u00b7 Actors' Equity Association|website=www.actorsequity.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> A planned performance of ''[['Tis Pity She's a Whore]]'' via [[videoconferencing]] software was cancelled at the last minute due to a dispute between the theatre producers and the union. The AEA argued that during a time when almost everyone in the arts is going without a regular pay cheque and is worried about their health care, \"it's deeply sad to see that some employers will still ask Equity actors to work without the protections of a contract.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/red-bull-forced-to-cancel-live-stream-reading-following-dispute-with-actors-equity|title=Red Bull Cancels Scheduled Live Stream Reading Following Dispute With Actors' Equity|last=Clement|first=Olivia|date=2020-04-01|website=Playbill|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> The theatre producers argued that \"cyberspace\" is not within the AEA's jurisdiction nor \"...should free online-only experience, in which actors participate from the safety and comfort of their own home on teleconference, without rehearsal or admission price,\" be subject to the Off-Broadway agreement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbulltheater.com/live|title=Red Bull Theater Livestream|website=Red Bull Theater|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n===Financial aid===\n\nWith the extensive financial disruption across all areas of the economy, many governments announced [[Stimulus (economics)|fiscal stimulus]] and [[Bailout|economic bailout]] packages which included specific resources for the arts and cultural sectors. Equally, various [[charities]] and industry bodies raised funds to support their sector while companies in the creative industry announced their own donations. For example, author [[James Patterson]] donated $500,000 to independent bookstores<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lithub.com/friend-of-booksellers-james-patterson-will-donate-500000-to-indie-bookstores/|title=Friend of booksellers James Patterson will donate $500,000 to indie bookstores|last=Gaynor|first=Jessie|date=3 April 2020|website=Literary Hub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> and [[Sony International|Sony]] announced a fund which would help support [[Creative professional|creative professionals]] \"impacted by the cancellation or postponement of concerts and live events, or the shutting down of film and television productions\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/biz/asia/sony-coronavirus-relief-fund-1203552726/|title=Sony Unveils $100 Million Coronavirus Relief Fund|last=Frater|first=Patrick|last2=Frater|first2=Patrick|date=2020-04-02|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>  {{expand section|date=April 2020}}\nArts and culture sector financial stimulus packages from individual countries included: \n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Algeria}}. in April, Minister of Culture [[Malika Bendouda]] announced on her Facebook page that [[Office national des droits d'auteur et des droits voisins|ONDA]], the national [[copyright collective]], had been placed in charge with administering a financial aid package for artists whose work had been interrupted by the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dzvid.com/2020/04/04/coronavirus-en-algerie-des-aides-financieres-au-profit-des-artistes/|title=Coronavirus en Alg\u00e9rie : des aides financi\u00e8res au profit des artistes|last=|first=|date=2020-04-04|website=DzVID|language=fr-FR|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. In March, a petition of over 50 arts and culture organisations (including peak bodies from the music, dance, visual arts, museums, writers' and Indigenous arts groups) requested a financial aid package \"...to a value of 2% of the {{AUD|111.7}} billion [cultural and creative] industry\". Furthermore, it requested that the [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] \"...issue a public statement recognising the value of our industry to all Australians\" and noting that the industry had not yet recovered from the impact of the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://visualarts.net.au/news-opinion/2020/creative-industry-unites/|title=Creative industry unites to secure Australia's cultural life|website=NAVA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Separately, Live Performance Australia had requested {{AUD|850}} million for its sector, while the think tank [[The Australia Institute]] requested a package of {{AUD|750}} million for the performing arts in general.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farr|first=Malcolm|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/15/call-for-750m-rescue-package-for-coronavirus-hit-australian-arts|title=Call for $750m rescue package for coronavirus-hit Australian arts|date=2020-04-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nInstead of the {{AUD|2.2}} billion requested in the petition, in early April the [[Government of Australia|federal government]] announced a package of {{AUD|27}} million in specific arts funding \u2013 {{AUD|7}} million for the Indigenous Visual Arts Industry Support program, {{AUD|10}} million for [[Regional Arts Australia]]'s regional arts fund, and {{AUD|10}} million for Support Act, a charity providing financial support and counselling to people in the music industry in Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/27-million-for-arts-organisations-in-new-targeted-support-package-20200408-p54ic8.html|title=$27 million for arts organisations in new targeted support package|last=Cooper|first=Nathanael|date=2020-04-08|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> It also expanded unemployment assistance in response to the pandemic \u2013 dubbed ''JobKeeper''. However, the program specifically excluded \"freelancers and casuals on short-term contracts, or who have worked for a series of employers in the last year\" and, given arts sector's high reliance on short-term contracts, a large proportion of arts and cultural sector professionals were ineligible for the scheme \u2013 even though the arts sector had been demonstrated as the most adversely affected sector of the economy.<ref name=\":20\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/theatre/wrack-and-ruin-leading-actors-warn-industry-is-on-brink-of-collapse-20200407-p54hvl.html|title='Wrack and ruin': Leading actors warn industry is on brink of collapse|last=Miller|first=Nick|date=2020-04-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/apr/09/the-workers-shut-out-of-jobkeeper-ive-lost-100-of-my-business|title=The workers shut out of jobkeeper: 'I've lost 100% of my business'|date=2020-04-09|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nThe library professional association [[Australian Library and Information Association|ALIA]] announced a \"relief fund\" of payments up to {{AUD|500}} to cover the cost of essential expenses for its members experiencing loss in income.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alia.org.au/alia-covid-19-relief-fund|title=ALIA COVID-19 Relief Fund|last=|first=|date=2020-04-03|website=www.alia.org.au|publisher=Australian Library and Information Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Burkina Faso}}. The national [[copyright collective]], the [[Bureau Burkinab\u00e8 du Droit d'Auteur]] (BBDA) created a \"solidarity fund\" for artists.<ref name=\":21\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. In late March, the national copyright collective [[SIAE]] announced three measures: a \u20ac60 million \"extraordinary support fund\" for its members through 2020-21, a \u20ac50 million fund to offer [[loans]] to members at zero-interest, and 2500 food packages for members in especial immediate need.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.siae.it/it/iniziative-e-news/emergenza-covid-19-le-misure-adottate-dal-consiglio-di-gestione-siae-favore-degli|title=Emergenza Covid 19, le misure adottate dal Consiglio di Gestione SIAE per associati e utilizzatori {{!}} Societ\u00e0 Italiana degli Autori ed Editori|website=www.siae.it|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Cote D'Ivoire}}. On the first of April, the national copyright collective [[Bureau ivoirien du droit d\u2019auteur]] (Burida) announced a fund to support its members who fall ill with the coronavirus. Applicants must apply, with a medical certificate proving their illness, by the 10th of that month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fratmat.info/article/203419/Culture/bureau-ivoirien-du-droit-dauteur--une-commission-daide-aux-artistes-malades-instituee|title=Bureau ivoirien du droit d\u2019auteur : Une commission d\u2019aide aux artistes malades institu\u00e9e {{!}} FratMat|website=www.fratmat.info|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |France}}. The minister for culture [[Franck Riester]] announced that employees of cultural institutions currently receiving unemployment benefits calculated over 12 months will see the confinement period withdrawn from the calculation.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.francemusique.fr/actualite-musicale/coronavirus-le-gouvernement-annonce-des-mesures-pour-les-intermittents-du-spectacle-82453 |title=Coronavirus : le gouvernement annonce des mesures pour les intermittents du spectacle |language=fr|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The national copyright collectives for authors and for visual arts (respectively: The [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 fran\u00e7aise des int\u00e9r\u00eats des auteurs de l\u2019\u00e9crit]] [Sofia] and [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des auteurs dans les arts graphiques et plastiques]] [ADAGP]) announced they would not ask for grants they given for subsequently cancelled cultural festivals and events to be reimbursed, and requested that those grant recipients pay their originally contracted artists in full.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-sofia.org/action-culturelle-la-sofia-ne-demandera-pas-le-remboursement-des-aides-accordees-pour-2020/|title=ACTION CULTURELLE : LA SOFIA NE DEMANDERA PAS LE REMBOURSEMENT DES AIDES ACCORDEES POUR 2020|date=2020-03-18|website=Sofia|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adagp.fr/fr/actualites/l-adagp-mesures-exceptionnelles-liees-au-covid-19|title=A l'ADAGP : Mesures exceptionnelles li\u00e9es au COVID 19 {{!}} ADAGP|website=www.adagp.fr|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. The minister for culture [[Monika Gr\u00fctters]] declared that \"artists are not only indispensable, but also vital, especially now.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/german-bailout-50-billion-1815396|title=Germany Has Rolled Out a Staggering \u20ac50 Billion Aid Package For Small Businesses That Boosts Artists and Galleries\u2014and Puts Other Countries to Shame|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The statement was made while announcing a \u20ac50 billion stimulus package for small business and freelancers \u2013 explicitly including the creative sectors.\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |New Zealand}}. On March 24, [[Creative New Zealand]] announced a NZD$16 million \"Emergency Response Package\" for the first half of the year, noting the probability of a second tranche of funding for the latter half of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.creativenz.govt.nz/news/details-of-creative-new-zealand-s-first-phase-arts-sector-boost-ahead-of-14-april-opening|title=Details of Creative New Zealand's first phase arts sector boost, ahead of 14 April opening|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=creativenz.gov.nz|publisher=[[Creative New Zealand]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. The Swedish Minister of Culture [[Amanda Lind]] presented a 1 billion [[Swedish krona|SEK]] support package for sports and culture, where 500 million SEK was earmarked for culture (not including government agencies like the [[Royal Dramatic Theatre]] and [[Kungliga Operan]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=En miljard i akut st\u00f6d till kultur och idrott|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/coronaviruset/en-miljard-i-akut-stod-till-kultur-och-idrott/|publisher=Expressen|access-date=2020-03-25|language=Swedish}}</ref> The national copyright collective for visual arts [[Bildupphovsr\u00e4tt i Sverige]] (BUS) proposed a 25 million SEK \"crisis package\" of funds distributed to artists in their database whose works are already publicly displayed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://press.bildupphovsratt.se/posts/pressreleases/konstnarsorganisationer-foreslar-krispaket-fo|title=Konstn\u00e4rsorganisationer f\u00f6resl\u00e5r krispaket f\u00f6r drabbade bildskapare|website=press.bildupphovsratt.se|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. [[The Film and TV Charity]] created an emergency relief fund in order to \"provide emergency short-term relief to active workers and freelancers who have been directly affected by the closure of productions across the UK\", with an initial donation of \u00a31m from [[Netflix]] and by \u00a3500,000 from the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bfi-uk-film-and-tv-charity-set-up-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-with-1m-donation-from-netflix-1202890966/|title=BFI & UK Film And TV Charity Set Up Covid-19 Emergency Relief Fund With \u00a31M Donation From Netflix|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=2020-03-24|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bbc-donates-to-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-1202894127/|title=BBC Joins Netflix In Making $600,000 Donation To Coronavirus Emergency Relief Fund|last=Kanter|first=Jake|date=2020-03-27|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Museums Association]] called upon the UK government to divert \u00a3120m that was intended for the [[Festival of Britain|Festival of Britain 2022]] to bail out museums in financial distress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/17032020-museum-closures-coronavirus-covid-19|title=Museums and galleries close as coronavirus emergency intensifies|last=Kendall Adams|first=Geraldine|date=17 March 2020|website=Museums Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> [[Arts Council England]] announced \u00a3160 million would be made available for arts organisations, including \u00a350 million for organisations it does not usually fund and \u00a320 million for individual and freelance artists.<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[Paul Hamlyn Foundation]] announced that the usual competitive selection process for their \"Award for Artists\" program would be removed, and that instead of ten awards of \u00a360,000, each of the more than 100 previously nominated eligible applicants would automatically receive \u00a310,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phf.org.uk/news/1-million-awarded-to-visual-artists-and-composers-in-the-uk/|title=\u00a31 million awarded to visual artists and composers in the UK|date=2020-04-06|website=Paul Hamlyn Foundation|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The [[Society of Authors]] created an \"emergency fund\" for professional authors resident in the UK or British subjects, granting amounts up to \u00a32,000, \u201cdesigned to meet urgent need\u201d. Started initially with \u00a3330,000 from the SoA,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/mar/20/this-is-a-scary-time-coronavirus-emergency-fund-set-up-for-authors|title='This is a scary time': coronavirus emergency fund set up for authors|date=2020-03-20|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> [[Arts Council England]] later added \u00a3400,000 and other donors included the [[Authors' Licensing and Collecting Society]], [[Royal Literary Fund]], [[TS Eliot Foundation]], [[English PEN]], and [[Amazon UK]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alcs.co.uk/news/alcs-offers-additional-financial-support-to-writers-through-the-society-of-authors-330000-emergency-fund|title=ALCS {{!}} ALCS offers additional financial support to writers through the Society of Authors\u2019 Emergency Fund|website=www.alcs.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. A petition was begun by the [[American Alliance of Museums]] (AAM) to request that the museum sector was included in any future [[economic stimulus]] from the United States government,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congressweb.com/AAM/67|title=Tell Congress: Include Museums in COVID-19 Economic Relief|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> while the Metropolitan museum was more specific \u2013 requesting $4 billion for at-risk museums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/metropolitan-museum-of-art-congress-1813665|title=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Is Calling on the US Government to Bail Out At-Risk Museums With $4 Billion in Aid|date=2020-03-24|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> This request was met with resistance: A common argument raised the USA against the cultural sector receiving parts of the stimulus funding was that \"Arts groups may be 'nice,' but they\u2019re far from 'necessary.'\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn late March the United States federal government announced a $2 trillion economic stimulus package in the [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act]]. It included: \"$75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] and $75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], which can pass on the money to institutions that need it. Another $50 million was designated to the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]], which distributes funds to museums and libraries.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Jacobs|first=Julia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/arts/coronavirus-arts-bailout.html|title=Arts Groups, Facing Their Own Virus Crisis, Get a Piece of the Stimulus|date=2020-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Initial analysis of the bill by the AAM indicated several ways that aid could be applicable to the arts and culture sectors. These included: Emergency Small Business Loans, Economic Injury Disaster Loans, a Charitable Giving Incentive, and an Employee Retention Payroll Tax Credit. It was \"expected, but unclear\" whether charitable nonprofits qualified for the Industry Stabilisation Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aam-us.org/2020/03/27/museums-included-in-economic-relief-legislation/|title=Museums Included in Economic Relief Legislation|date=2020-03-27|website=American Alliance of Museums|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Press Photographers Association]] announced it was seeking donations to create a relief fund to support [[photojournalists]] who had lost work due to the economic impact of the crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nppf.org/nppa-covid-19-relief-fund/|title=\u00bb NPPA COVID-19 Relief Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n===Copyright===\n[[Ligue des Biblioth\u00e8ques Europ\u00e9ennes de Recherche|LIBER]] (the Association of European Research Libraries) called on the European Commission and national governments to allow libraries to provide remote access for the duration of their enforced closure and to ensure they can provide this service without fear of litigation; and called on publishers and authors to pledge to allow online delivery of normally 'onsite only' content (e.g. eBooks) and the use of copyrighted works in online educational activities (e.g. livestreamed reading of children's stories).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://libereurope.eu/blog/2020/04/14/copyright-coronavirus-statement/|title=Europe Must Take Urgent Copyright Law Action To Support Distance Learning & Research During the Coronavirus Pandemic|date=2020-04-14|website=LIBER|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The libraries of universities and of the [[National Research Council (Italy)|National Research Council]] in Italy petitioned [[academic publishers]] to provide temporary [[open access]] to publications in order to allow access for medical staff, scientific researchers, and the general public during the national emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centumcellae.it/cronaca/appello-per-il-diritto-di-accesso-alla-conoscenza-scientifica-in-stato-di-emergenza/|title=Appello Per Il Diritto Di Accesso Alla Conoscenza Scientifica In Stato Di Emergenza|last=|first=|date=2020-03-19|website=Centumcellae|language=it-IT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In early April letter signed by [[Communia]], [[Creative Commons]], the [[American Library Association]], the [[International Council on Archives]], the [[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions]], several [[List of Wikimedia chapters|Wikimedia affiliate organisations]] among many others \u2013 was sent a letter to [[Francis Gurry]] \u2013 Director General of the [[World Intellectual Property Organization]] \u2013 encouraging \"WIPO member states to take advantage of flexibilities in the international system...\", calling on \"rights holders to remove licensing restrictions that inhibit remote education, research...\", supporting a call by [[Costa Rica]] for a \"global pool of rights in COVID-19 related technology and data\" to be created by the [[World Health Organization]], and supporting the right of nations to use exceptions to intellectual property laws \"o achieve universal and equitable access to COVID-19 medicines and medical technologies as soon as reasonably possible.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.communia-association.org/2020/04/03/open-letter-wipo-intellectual-property-covid-19/|title=Open Letter to WIPO: Intellectual Property and COVID-19|last=Nobre|first=Teresa|date=2020-04-03|website=International Communia Association|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Federation of Reproduction Rights Organsisations]] (IFRRO) pointed to the various ways in which national rights management organisations had loosened licensing restrictions for online access due to the pandemic.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://us16.campaign-archive.com/?u=8353bb14837e4fc186bfea9cc&id=2dcdf36fd4&e=30bddf078d|title=IFRRO News - COVID19|website=us16.campaign-archive.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> These included: in Canada, the [[Association of Canadian Publishers]] permitting \"online story time\" reading of children's books by certain publishers for free;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accesscopyright.ca/read-aloud/|title=Read Aloud Canadian Books Program|website=Access Copyright|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> in the Czech Republic, university staff and students can obtain free online access to the digital collections of the National Library;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dilia.cz/index.php/component/k2/item/15453-dohoda-dilia-a-nk-%C4%8Dr-zp%C5%99%C3%ADstupn%C4%9Bn%C3%AD-d%C4%9Bl-pro-studenty-a-pedagogy|title=DILIA|website=www.dilia.cz|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> in Germany, churches were allowed to perform songs and lyrics to be displayed during the live streaming of church services;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg-musikedition.de/news/detail/news/information-fuer-kirchengemeinden-fuer-den-live-stream-von-gottesdiensten/|title=VG-Musikedition: Detail|website=www.vg-musikedition.de|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and in Norway, students can access for free digitised books in the National Library\u2019s online catalogue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kopinor.no/articles/covid-19-kopinor-keeps-the-wheels-turning|title=Covid-19: Kopinor keeps the wheels turning|last=Enonic|website=Kopinor|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nAcademic librarians in the United States made public statements on the applicability and importance of the role of the [[fair use]] copyright exception for \"Emergency Remote Teaching & Research\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/10baTITJbFRh7D6dHVVvfgiGP2zqaMvm0EHHZYf2cBRk/|title=Public Statement: Fair Use & Emergency Remote Teaching & Research|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Cornell University Library]] made the advice explicit, noting in a new official library policy recommending, \"...that faculty may scan course material in amounts that may exceed customary fair use limits under normal circumstances. Fair use provides flexibility to permit faculty scan broader amounts of course material than normal during these exigent circumstances.\" and noted that library staff were no longer allowed to work on-site and therefore not able to scan materials on behalf of teaching staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://copyright.cornell.edu/covid|title=COVID-19 & Copyright at Cornell {{!}} Copyright Information Center|website=copyright.cornell.edu|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> \n\nThe ''National Emergency Library'' of the Internet Archive \u2013 which suspended waitlists for access to digitised in-copyright books citing the justification of Fair Use during the pandemic \u2013 was criticised as \"piracy masquerading as public service\" and copyright infringement, especially by the [[Association of American Publishers]] and [[Authors Guild]]<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|last=Alter|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/books/internet-archive-emergency-library.html|title='Emergency' Online Library Draws Ire of Some Authors|date=2020-03-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> as well as drawing public critique from several noted authors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/04/internet-archive-national-emergency-library-controversy.html|title=The Internet Archive Started an \"Emergency\" Online Library. Authors Are Furious.|last=Hampton|first=Rachelle|date=2020-04-01|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The Internet Archive defended its program by emphasising that: the collection consisted primarily of older in-copyright works without digital surrogates; it is a temporary program; authors can choose to opt-out; and the works are chosen for the educational not commercial value.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.archive.org/2020/03/30/internet-archive-responds-why-we-released-the-national-emergency-library/|title=Internet Archive responds: Why we released the National Emergency Library|website=Internet Archive Blogs|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/controversy-surrounds-national-emergency-library-180974554/|title=Why the National Emergency Library Is So Controversial|last=Machemer|first=Theresa|website=Smithsonian Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n[[LeVar Burton]], host of ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'', announced his desire to perform live-streamed readings of books for his podcast ''LeVar Reads'' but that copyright law was unclear as to whether this was allowed. [[Neil Gaiman]] replied to Burton via Twitter, giving him permission to read any of his works.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/939vjv/please-dont-sue-levar-burton-for-reading-soothing-stories-to-scared-children|title=Please Don't Sue LeVar Burton for Reading Soothing Stories to Scared Children|last=Cole|first=Samantha|date=2020-03-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nVarious online training workshops were organised for cultural heritage to learn about relevant risks and [[Copyright exceptions|exceptions to copyright]] when providing online services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/open-glam/copyright-open-access-for-glams-in-the-age-of-covid-3a35e67f7a1|title=Copyright & Open Access for GLAMs in the age of COVID-19|last=|first=|date=2020-03-24|website=Medium|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Equally, [[digital strategy]] workshops<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usingdata.com/usingdata/2020/3/19/free-strategy-workshops-march-23-april-3|title=Free strategy workshops March 23 \u2013 April 3|website=Usingdata|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and live Q&A sessions with experts were organised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AAMers/status/1242798776655413249|title=What #COVID19 questions do you want to pose to the museum field? Comment below or DM us to include it in our #MuseumsDiscussCOVID19 Tweet chat! TODAY 3-4 pm|publisher=American Alliance of Museums|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===New creative works===\n{{Quote box\n| width = 22em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 100%\n| salign = center\n| quote = \"For writers, as the tentacles of the coronavirus unfurl each day, everything is copy. But what happens when every writer on the planet starts taking notes on the same subject? Will we all hand in our book reports simultaneously, a year from now? The nature of tragedy is that it takes more than it gives, but it\u2019s also produced some of our most iconic literature.\" <br>\nAuthor, [[Sloane Crosley]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Crosley|first=Sloane|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/books/review/sloane-crosley-pandemic-novel-coronavirus.html|title=Someday, We'll Look Back on All of This and Write a Novel|date=2020-03-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n| align = right\n}}\nEven during the crisis, there was the expectation of many and diverse cultural works would be created in the future which would reference, or were inspired by, the pandemic and its effects.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dye|first=Josh|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/perplexing-and-confusing-art-gallery-of-nsw-director-grapples-with-coronavirus-crisis-20200327-p54emd.html|title='Perplexing and confusing': Art Gallery of NSW director grapples with coronavirus crisis|date=28 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Many [[Internet meme|memes]] were created by, and shared among, the large numbers of amateur content creators isolated in their homes during the isolation period itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gpbnews.org/post/coronavirus-goes-viral-how-online-meme-culture-reflects-our-shared-experience-global-pandemic|title=Coronavirus Goes Viral: How Online Meme Culture Reflects Our Shared Experience Of A Global Pandemic|last=Prescott|first=Emilia Brock, Pria Mahadevan, Virginia|website=www.gpbnews.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/technology/online-life-explodes-with-covid-19-memes-and-hand-washing-tiktoks-20200318-p54bc7|title=Online life explodes with COVID-19 memes, and hand-washing TikToks|date=2020-03-20|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>  \n\nAside from vast amounts of scientific research published about the coronavirus, many professionally-produced [[Creative work|creative works]] which were created, adapted, inspired by, or published as a direct result of the pandemic, and/or feature it explicitly. \n\n{{Incomplete list|date=April 2020}}<!-- Do not include scientific/medical publications in this list. This is about [[creative works]] (of all kinds) not academic research. -->\n\n* Markus J Buehler at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] produced a [[Sheet music|musical score]] from a [[sonification]] algorithm and the structure of [[SARS-CoV-2|the virus]]' S (spike) protein. Beyond the aesthetic appeal of the outcome of the analysis, it may offer another method of finding potential binding sites for [[Biological target|therapeutic targets]] and thereby assist with treatment.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Taylor|first=Tegan|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/health/2020-04-06/coronavirus-music-scientists-translate-spike-proteins-melody/12124424|title=Scientists translate coronavirus spike protein into music, revealing more about its structure|date=6 April 2020|work=ABC News (Sydney)|access-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Venugopal |first1=Vineeth |title=Scientists have turned the structure of the coronavirus into music |journal=Science |date=3 April 2020 |doi=10.1126/science.abc0657 |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/04/scientists-have-turned-structure-coronavirus-music |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n*The novel ''[[Lockdown (book)|Lockdown]]'' by Scottish author [[Peter May (writer)|Peter May]]'','' written in 2005 and describing a global pandemic, was originally rejected for publication for being unrealistic. When requested by a fan to write something relating to the coronavirus pandemic, the author said he thought about it for a minute before he \"realised that I've kind of already done it.\" It will be published in April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/04/us/peter-may-lockdown-coronavirus-book-trnd/index.html|title=A pandemic thriller, once rejected by publishers for being unrealistic, is now getting a wide release|first=Alaa |last=Elassar|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n*Australian musicians [[Tim Minchin]] and [[Briggs (rapper)|Briggs]] produced the song ''[[HouseFyre]]'' \u2013 satirising Prime Minister's [[Scott Morrison|Scott Morrison's]] leadership during the preceeding months \u2013 whilst under isolation in their respective homes. The video clip was filmed from their mobile phones, with proceeds from the song's sale going towards a fundraiser for indigenous artists.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/apr/09/tim-minchin-and-briggs-release-isolation-track-satirising-scott-morrisons-leadership|title=Tim Minchin and Briggs release isolation track satirising Scott Morrison's leadership|date=2020-04-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*Horror and supernatural fiction author [[Stephen King]] chose to backdate the setting of a forthcoming novel from 2020 to 2019, so that the characters could plausibly congregate and go on a cruise ship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/08/829298135/stephen-king-is-sorry-you-feel-like-youre-stuck-in-a-stephen-king-novel|title=Stephen King Is Sorry You Feel Like You're Stuck In A Stephen King Novel|last=King|first=Stephen|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n| width = 22em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 100%\n| salign = center\n| quote = \"Books about the epidemic are needed now. They provide people with the cultural means to understand something that is uprooting their existence.\"<br>\nAuthor and virologist, [[Roberto Burioni]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Momigliano|first=Anna|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/books/italy-coronavirus-paolo-giordano-roberto-burioni.html|title=In Italy, Coronavirus Books Rush to Publication|date=9 April 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| align = right\n}}\n\n*[[Paolo Giordano]], Italian physicist and award-winning author of the [[Strega Prize|Premio Strega]], published his thoughts about the virus outbreak in an essay entitled ''How Contagion Works'' in March 2020. It was quickly translated into more than 20 languages.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Momigliano|first=Anna|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/books/italy-coronavirus-paolo-giordano-roberto-burioni.html|title=In Italy, Coronavirus Books Rush to Publication|date=9 April 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Italian [[Virology|virologist]] and author [[Roberto Burioni]] published an examination of how epidemics shape civilisations in March 2020, entitled ''Virus. La grande sfida [Virus. The Great Challenge].'' The author's proceeds were directed to research on the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consulenzeditoriali.it/books-fr/virus-the-great-challenge|title=Roberto Burioni - \"Virus. The Great Challenge\"|last=Carpinelli|first=Rosalia|date=2020|website=www.consulenzeditoriali.it/|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Italian publisher [[Garzanti]] published an anthology of 26 short stories and essays about quarantine, from a range of writers including children\u2019s author [[Elisabetta Gnone|Elisabetta Gnone,]] entitled ''Andr\u00e0 tutto bene [Everything will be fine].'' Profits from the sale of the e-book were directed to the [[Ospedale Papa Giovanni XXIII|Pope John XXIII Hospital]] in [[Bergamo|Bergamo.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.garzanti.it/libri/ritanna-armeni-andra-tutto-bene-9788811816331/|title=Andr\u00e0 tutto bene|last=|first=|date=|website=Garzanti.it|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Street artist [[Banksy]] published a new piece of his trademark wall art - this time located in his bathroom referencing the required [[Isolation (health care)|self-isolation]] - with coronavirus as the theme and \"stir-crazy rats\" as its subject. He published photographs of it online.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-17/banksy-bathroom-art-coronavirus-lockdown-united-kingdom/12156326|title=Banksy follows stay-at-home orders and makes bathroom art during coronavirus crisis|date=17 April 2020|work=ABC News|access-date=17 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n{{CC-notice|cc=by4|url=https://www.ifla.org/covid-19-and-libraries|author(s)=[[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions|IFLA]]}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage}}\n[[Category:2020 in arts]]\n[[Category:Cultural heritage]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|arts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Effect of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:Closed library - Island Bay.jpg|alt=|thumb|350x350px|Announcement posted in the door of a [[public library]] in [[Island Bay, New Zealand]] that it is closed due to the pandemic, and will waive all [[Late fees|late return fees]].]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] had a sudden and substantial impact on the arts and cultural heritage ([[GLAM (industry sector)|GLAM]]) sectors. The global health crisis and the uncertainly resulting from it profoundly affected organisations' operations as well as individuals \u2013 both employed and independent \u2013 across the sector. Arts and culture sector organisations attempted to uphold their (often publicly funded) mission to provide access to cultural heritage to the community; maintain the safety of their employees, collections, and the public; while reacting to the unexpected change in their [[business model]] with an unknown end.\n\nBy March 2020, across the world most cultural institutions had been indefinitely closed (or at least with their services radically curtailed) exhibitions, events and performances cancelled or postponed. In response there were intensive efforts to provide alternative or additional services through digital platforms, to maintain essential activities with minimal resources, to document the events themselves through new acquisitions, and simultaneously an awareness that there would be many new [[creative works]] which had been inspired by the event.\n\nMany individuals across the sector would temporarily or permanently lose contracts or employment with varying degrees of warning and financial assistance available. Equally, [[financial stimulus]] from governments and charities for artists, would provide greatly differing levels of support depending on the sector and the country. The public demand for cultural activities was expected to return, but at an unknown time and with the assumption that different kinds of experiences would be popular.\n\n==Closures==\nThrough the first months of 2020, arts and culture sector organisations around the world progressively restricted their public activities and closed completely due to the coronavirus pandemic. Starting with China, and East Asia, by mid-to-late March most organisations worldwide had either closed voluntarily or by government mandate. This included libraries,<ref name=\"IFLA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ifla.org/covid-19-and-libraries|title=COVID-19 and the Global Library Field|publisher=[[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions|IFLA]]|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> museums,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/coronavirus-museum-closures-worldwide-1202680933/|title=See a List of Coronavirus-Related Closures at Museums Around the World|last=Solomon|first=Claire Selvin,Tessa|last2=Selvin|first2=Claire|date=2020-03-12|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26|last3=Solomon|first3=Tessa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/1LNCETkPjgcNdmybrwE5g2JEK4KpIfhKThnws1QqgjqE/mobilebasic|title=Museum Responses - COVID-19|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> theatre and stage productions,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2020/mar/13/coronavirus-culture-arts-films-gigs-festivals-cancellations|title=Coronavirus and culture \u2013 a list of major cancellations|date=2020-03-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> orchestras,<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|last=Kenyon|first=Nicholas|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/21/home-listening-classical-music-online-livestream-at-home-coronavirus|title=Classical music: let the Berlin Phil come to you|date=2020-03-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and arts festivals.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2020, dates for re-opening and expectations for when cultural organisation can fully \"return to normal\" are unknown for most of the world. Survey data from March in the USA indicated that, when museums were permitted to reopen, the public \"intent to visit\" metric for cultural activities should be unchanged overall from prior to the pandemic \u2013 but with a shifted preference for the ''kind'' of activity. Data indicated there would be a decreased willingness for attendance of activities in confined spaces, large immobile groups (such as cinemas), or tactile activities; with an increase in interest for activities outdoors or with large spaces (such as zoos and botanic gardens).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/25/how-is-covid-19-impacting-likelihood-to-attend-different-cultural-entities-data/|title=Post-Pandemic, Which Cultural Entity Types Are People More Likely to Revisit? (DATA)|date=2020-03-25|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/03/23/weekly-data-update-how-covid-19-is-impacting-intentions-to-visit-cultural-entities-march-23-2020/|title=DATA UPDATE: How COVID-19 is Impacting Intentions to Visit Cultural Entities - March 23, 2020|date=2020-03-23|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The most commonly cited reasons for the public to \"feel safe\" in returning would be: the availability of a [[COVID-19 vaccine|vaccine]], governments lifting [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel restrictions]], knowing that other people had visited, whether the activity/institution was outdoors, and the provision of [[hand sanitiser]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colleendilen.com/2020/04/01/what-will-make-people-feel-safe-attending-a-cultural-entity-again-data/|title=What Will Make People Feel Safe Attending a Cultural Entity Again? (DATA)|date=2020-04-01|website=Colleen Dilenschneider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nBy early April at least one museum had announced its permanent closure, with more expected to follow.\n\n''The following is a list of notable closures, announcements and policies affecting the cultural sector.<br>For comprehensive lists:''\n{{See also|List of public venues and institutions closed during the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}} \n{{See also|List of events affected by the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n'''Africa'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Egypt}}. From 23 March until 31 March 2020, all museums and archaeological sites in Egypt were closed to the public for sterilisation and disinfection. During this period a programme to raise the awareness of the sites and museums\u2019 employees on ways of prevention and protection against the virus took place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cairoscene.com/Buzz/Egypt-to-Close-All-Museums-and-Archaeological-Sites|title= Egypt to close all museums and archaeological sites}}</ref>\n\n'''Asia'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flagicon|China}} [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]]. On 23 January 2020 all museums were closed throughout mainland China, As the first country for the virus to spread, China was also the first to close its GLAMs.<ref name=\":0\" /> By Mid-March Chinese institutions had slowly and cautiously begun to allow various public activities to be restored with the [[Shanghai Museum]] and the [[Power Station of Art]] (also in Shanghai) reopening on 13 March. Both had restricted visitor numbers and the latter noted that, \u201cWe have also prepared a temporary quarantine area on every floor in case of any emergencies. All visitors must have their temperature taken, as well as present their ID card and registered health code, before entering.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/china-japan-south-korea-museums-reopen-coronavirus-1202680994/|title=Museums in China, South Korea, Japan Begin to Reopen After Coronavirus Lockdown|last=Solomon|first=Tessa|last2=Solomon|first2=Tessa|date=2020-03-13|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Some other private galleries in China had begun to open, as had some institutions in South Korea and Japan with limited service (such as by private tour only). By the end of the month 40% of mainland China's tourism attractions had reopened yet most art venues remained closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/china-south-korea-and-japan-start-to-reopen-museums|title=China, South Korea and Japan start to reopen museums after strict coronavirus lockdown|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n:{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Hong Kong}}. Following the mainland, Hong Kong closed its museums five days later.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |India}}. The [[Kiran Nadar Museum of Art]] in Delhi closed on 14 March, two days before [[Shripad Naik]], minister for culture and tourism, ordered the closure of all \"monuments and museums protected by the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] across the country, including the Taj Mahal mausoleum in Agra.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Japan}}. On 28 February Japan announced all museums would be closed \"until 17 March\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in|Qatar}}. Qatar museums run by the state closed on 12 March. A forthcoming collaborative show on Picasso's Studio's due to be held by the [[Fire Station (gallery)|Fire Station]] and [[Mus\u00e9e Picasso]] has been indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |South Korea}}. On 23 February, one month after mainland China, South Korea closed all museums \"until further notice\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Europe'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts -->\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Austria}}. All federal public museums were closed by directors in response to government precautionary measures banning large events and arrivals from Italy. The [[Albertina Modern]] museum was supposed to open on 13 March but this opening was indefinitely postponed.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Belgium}}. All cultural activities regardless of size were banned by the government from 14 March, which involved the closure of the [[Jan van Eyck]] exhibition at the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Ghent]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |France}}. Weeks earlier than French government regulations required it, staff of [[The Louvre]] \"almost unanimously\" voted to force the closure of the museum on 1 March, due to concerns for their own health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51697644|title=Staff force Louvre closure over coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> It closed for three days, reopened,<ref>{{cite web|title=Coronavirus: Louvre museum in Paris reopens after staff walkout|url=https://www.thelocal.fr/20200301/frances-louvre-museum-closed-due-to-virus-fears|website=www.thelocal.fr|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> accepted only visitors with pre-booked tickets from the 9th,<ref name=\":0\" /> then closed definitively on 13 March by government mandate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200313-france-s-louvre-museum-and-versailles-palace-to-shut-over-coronavirus-crisis|title=Louvre, Versailles and Eiffel Tower close over coronavirus crisis|date=2020-03-13|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Reconstruction of the [[Notre-Dame de Paris|Notre-Dame cathedral]] following [[Notre-Dame de Paris fire|the 2019 fire]] was also halted because of worker security.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. On 16 March 2020, the German chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] announced in a press conference that the government and [[minister-president]]s had together agreed upon guidelines to limit social contacts in public spaces. Theatres, opera houses, concert halls, museums, exhibition spaces, cinemas, amusement parks and zoos needed to close.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesregierung.de/breg-de/themen/coronavirus/leitlinien-bund-laender-1731000|title=Leitlinien gegen Ausbreitung des Coronavirus|date=2020-03-16|website=Die Bundesregierung|language=de|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. As the worst hit country in Europe during February and March, national closures were announced on 23 February with an initial reopening date of 1 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/la-cultura-chiusa-tempi-coronavirus-ACNKCpLB|title=La cultura chiusa ai tempi del coronavirus|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Museums outside the \"red zone\" of highly infected areas in the North were then permitted to re-open as long as visitors stayed 1 meter apart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/italian-museums-reopen-following-government-green-light|title=Coronavirus: Louvre closes while Italian museums reopen following government green light|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> this was later rescinded and all institution were closed until at least 3 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/rome-s-blockbuster-raphael-exhibition-closes|title=Coronavirus in Italy: Ai Weiwei criticised for 'insensitive' pasta meme and Raphael blockbuster closes|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The closure forced the indefinite postponement of the forthcoming \u201cmega-exhibition\u201d of [[Raphael]] to be held at the [[Scuderie del Quirinale]] in Rome. Originally timed to coincide with the 500th anniversary of the [[Renaissance art|Renaissance painter's]] death, it was to be the largest number of the artist's works ever displayed together.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n:{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Vatican City}}. The [[Vatican Museums]] closed in accordance with the policies of Italy.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Netherlands}}. On 12 March, Amsterdam's [[Rijksmuseum]] and [[Van Gogh Museum]] announced they would close until at least the end of that month.<ref name=\":0\" /> The following day, having previously announced the reading room and exhibition would remain open, the [[Nationaal Archief|National Archives]] announced their complete closure until 6 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaalarchief.nl/beleven/nieuws/studiezaal-en-tentoonstelling-nationaal-archief-tijdelijk-gesloten|title=Studiezaal en tentoonstelling Nationaal Archief tijdelijk gesloten|website=Nationaal Archief|language=nl|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On 30 March, the painting ''[[The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen]]'' (1884) by [[Vincent van Gogh]] was stolen from the [[Singer Laren|Singer Laren museum]] while the museum was closed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/i-m-absolutely-livid-van-gogh-painting-stolen-from-museum-during-pandemic-20200331-p54fgd.html|title='I'm absolutely livid': Van Gogh painting stolen from museum during pandemic|date=31 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Poland}}. On 11 March, a regional government \"recommendation\" was made that all cultural venues in the [[Tricity, Poland|tricity]] area be closed for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kultura.trojmiasto.pl/Teatry-odwolane-imprezy-spektakle-koronawirus-w-Trojmiescie-n143084.html|title=Teatry zamkni\u0119te przynajmniej na 2 tygodnie|date=2020-03-10|website=trojmiasto.pl|language=pl|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Museums, including the [[Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum]], and other cultural venues such as theatres and cinemas were then closed by the national government with an initial re-opening date of 25 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Russia}}. The [[Garage Museum of Contemporary Art]] was one of the first to announce its closure starting 14 March. Many [[Moscow]] museums announced closures in response to the mayor's ban on gatherings of 50 people or more on 17 March, and late that day the Russian culture ministry ordered the suspension of all public activities by federal and regional institutions, which resulted in many more closures from 18 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Spain}}. On 11 March, publicly owned museums in Madrid, including [[The Prado]], were closed indefinitely.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[Sagrada Fam\u00edlia]] indefinitely suspended construction works and closed the monument to visitors on 13 March and the [[Guggenheim Museum Bilbao]] closed on 14 March.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. On 18 March, the Swedish network and cooperation organisation for public museums of national interest, ''Centralmuseernas samarbetsr\u00e5d'', recommended all their 13 members to close their public venues if the risk for transmission of the virus was assessed as high in their respective regions. Only two of them stayed open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigesmuseer.se/nyheter/2020/03/cms-rekommenderar-stangning-av-centralmuseer-i-omraden-med-hog-smittspridning/|title=CMS rekommenderar st\u00e4ngning av centralmuseer i omr\u00e5den med h\u00f6g smittspridning|date=2020-03-18|website=Sveriges museer|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. The earliest closures of cultural institutions in the UK were announced from 13 March by [[Wellcome Collection]], [[South London Gallery]], the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]], [[The Photographers' Gallery]] and [[Amgueddfa Cymru \u2013 National Museum Wales|Amgueddfa Cymru]].<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/here-are-the-museums-that-have-closed-due-to-coronavirus|title=Here are the museums that have closed (so far) due to coronavirus|last=McGivern|first=Hannah|last2=Kenney|first2=Nancy|date=14 March 2020|website=The Art Newspaper|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Many other organisations announced closures on the 17 and 18 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/london-museums-galleries-exhibitions-closed-coronavirus-a4389351.html|title=The London galleries and museums that are closed due to coronavirus|last=Paskett|first=Zoe|date=17 March 2020|website=Evening Standard|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51928526|title=Tate, V&A and Natural History Museum to close|date=2020-03-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] closed all ticketed properties by 20 March but aimed to keep gardens and parklands open, free of charge so that people could access the open space whilst social distancing.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe planned major exhibition at the [[National Gallery]] in London of [[Artemisia Gentileschi]], set to open on 4 April, was postponed for an indeterminate time due not only to the gallery's closure but also the inability of artworks on loan from Italy and America being unable to fly during the global shutdown in air traffic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jones|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/16/artemisia-gentileschi-national-gallery-exhibition-postponed-coronavirus|title=With coronavirus, the curse of Artemisia Gentileschi strikes again|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nIn literature events, the [[London Book Fair]],<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|last=Alter|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/books/london-book-fair-coronavirus.html|title=London Book Fair Canceled Over Coronavirus Fears|date=2020-03-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> AyeWrite Festival in Glasgow,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ayewrite.com/Pages/default.aspx|title=Glasgow's Book Festival - Coronovirus Latest Information|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and the [[Harrogate International Festivals]], were also cancelled<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://harrogateinternationalfestivals.com/news/statement-on-coronavirus/|title=Statement on Corfonvirus|last=Canavar|first=Sharon|date=|website=Harrogate International Festivals|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> while the [[Edinburgh International Book Festival|Edinburgh International Book Festival,]] scheduled for August, was postponed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edbookfest.co.uk/about-us/news/festival-2020-announcement|title=A message from Nick Barley, Director of the Edinburgh International Book Festival|last=Barley|first=Nick|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The [[Glasgow International]] 2020 arts festival was also postponed until 2021.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n'''North America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. A \"flurry\" of museums in New York, Boston and Washington all announced their closure on 12 March , led by the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] and coinciding with the New York Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] declaring a city wide emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/metropolitan-museum-of-art-to-shut-down-because-of-coronavirus|title=Led by Metropolitan Museum of Art, a flurry of US museums say they are shutting down because of coronavirus|last=Kenny|first=Nancy|date=2020-03-12|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> [[The Broadway League]] announced on the same day that all [[Broadway theatres]] would cease performances for at least a month, even though New York State governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] had at the time allowed them to continue at 50% capacity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/health/broadway-coronavirus-update/index.html|title=Broadway theaters to suspend all performances because of coronavirus|author1=Taylor Romine |author2=Eric Levenson |author3=Javi Morgado|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On March 17, two days before the [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|first State to declare a \"stay at home\" order]], the [[American Library Association]] \"strongly recommended\" that all academic, public, and school libraries close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/news/press-releases/2020/03/ala-executive-board-recommends-closing-libraries-public|title=ALA Executive Board recommends closing libraries to public|last=|first=|date=2020-03-17|website=|publisher=[[American Library Association]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n'''Oceania'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n[[File:Trading Status of Australian Businesses during COVID-19.gif|thumb|300px|The area of each segment represents the number of businesses per sector of the Australian economy; the figure represents the percentage still operating. By April, the Arts and Recreation sector (shown in red) was the worst hit.<ref name=\"ABS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Latestproducts/5676.0.55.003Main%20Features2Week%20Commencing%2030%20March%202020|title=5676.0.55.003 - Business Indicators, Business Impacts of COVID-19, Week Commencing 30 March 2020|date=2020-04-07|website=www.abs.gov.au|publisher=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>|alt=]]\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. Beginning from the second week of March Australian institutions began announcing reduced services, and then complete closures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wragge.github.io/closed-glams-covid19/|title=Australian GLAMs and COVID-19|website=closed-glams-covid19|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On the 13th, organisers of the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]] announced that the 2020 festival had been cancelled entirely.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Melbourne International Comedy Festival 2020 Has Been Cancelled |url=https://www.comedyfestival.com.au/2020/2020-statement |website=Melbourne International Comedy Festival |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> [[Opera Australia]] announced it would close on March 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://operawire.com/opera-australia-cancels-performances-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Opera Australia Cancels Performances Due to Coronavirus|date=2020-03-15|website=Opera Wire|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On March 24 the national closure of all cultural institutions was mandated, with subsequent restrictions on public gatherings. Consequently, many cultural events were also cancelled, including the [[Sydney Writers' Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.swf.org.au/|title=We have cancelled the 2020 Festival|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> According to the [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] by the beginning of April, \"Arts and Recreation services\" was the sector of the national economy with the smallest proportion of its business still in operation \u2013 at 47%.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|last=Anatolitis|first=Esther|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/08/as-we-crave-the-return-of-our-cultural-life-arts-workers-and-organisations-are-being-left-behind|title=Australia's arts have been hardest hit by coronavirus. So why aren't they getting support? {{!}} Esther Anatolitis|date=2020-04-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> (See also [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia#Arts]].)\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |New Zealand}}. New Zealand implemented a policy on March 23 that all institutions would be closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndf.org.nz/covid19-and-nz-glams|title=COVID-19 and NZ GLAMs|website=National Digital Forum|language=en-NZ|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]] closed from 6pm March 20.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Campbell|first=Georgina|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12318548|title=Coronavirus: Te Papa museum to close for two weeks|date=20 March 2020|work=New Zealand Herald|access-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Auckland War Memorial Museum]] announced that it would close from March 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aucklandmuseum.com/service-pages/alerts/covid-19?utm_source=wordfly&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=TemporaryMuseumClosure&utm_content=version_A|title=Auckland Museum is temporarily closed}}</ref>\n\n'''South America'''<!-- Note: Do not simply list every institution which closed. List important closure dates/rules, and any notable exceptions/firsts/lasts --><br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Argentina}}. All the museums, cultural activities and gatherings were cancelled in the city of Buenos Aires on 12 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/cultura/coronavirus-argentina-disponen-cierre-temporario-museos-ciudad_0_Hgfv9C32.html|title=Coronavirus en Argentina: disponen el cierre temporario de todos los museos de la Ciudad|last=|website=www.clarin.com|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> National libraries continue to offer means of contact through the main educational website of the Ministry of Education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.educ.ar/recursos/151053/bibliotecas-en-casa-en-seguimos-conectados?from=150858&fbclid=IwAR3S3KjeZavdRV6gjOCfJxVUz6Xu5L0Eqfep7SBTT5l1RrOOKvuHQDML0tY|title=#BibliotecasEnCasa en Seguimos Educando - Educ.ar|website=www.educ.ar|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Brazil}}. Museums which have closed{{when|date=March 2020}} in Brazil include the Museum of Art of S\u00e3o Paulo Assis Chateaubriand, the Pinacoteca, the Ita\u00fa Cultural, the Museum of Contemporary Art of the University of S\u00e3o Paulo, the Institute Tomie Ohtake, the Institute Moreira Salles, and the Museum of Tomorrow in Rio de Janeiro and the Instituto Inhotim contemporary art centre in Brumadinho.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===Permanent closure===\n{{Incomplete list|date=April 2020}}\n\n* [[Bauer Media Group|Bauer Media New Zealand]] announced to staff via [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] its immediate and permanent closure on 2 April. Management cited the financial strain due to lockdowns given that \"non-daily print media were not permitted to publish through the level four lockdown\". The NZ government contested that the company was closing of its own accord, as it had not sought access to financial assistance available to businesses during the crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/media/02-04-2020/publisher-of-nz-listener-womans-weekly-north-south-to-shut-down/|title=Publisher of NZ Listener, Woman's Weekly, North & South to shut down|date=2020-04-02|website=The Spinoff|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Bauer was the publisher of magazines including ''[[New Zealand Listener]]'', ''[[North & South (New Zealand magazine)|North & South]], [[New Zealand Woman's Weekly|New Zealand Woman\u2019s Weekly]],'' and Air New Zealand's inflight magazine ''[[Kia Ora (Inflight Magazine)|Kia Ora]].''\n* The first cultural institution to announced its permanent closure as a result of the pandemic was [[Indianapolis Contemporary]], a contemporary art museum founded in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/entertainment/arts/2020/04/03/indianapolis-contemporary-art-museum-shuts-down-coronavirus/5115668002/|title=Indianapolis Contemporary art museum shuts down, citing economic damage from coronavirus|last=Bongiovanni|first=Domenica|website=Indianapolis Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> An announcement from its board on 3 April, stated that \"We have concluded our operations are not sustainable. We are not alone as other arts institutions struggle in this crisis.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indcontemporary.org/press-release/ic-to-close|title=I/C Board Announces Plans To Close|website=Indianapolis Contemporary|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* On West End, ''[[Waitress (musical)|Waitress]]'' was scheduled to end on 4 July, but it closed on 16 March, as West End theatres shut down; the producers later announced the show will not re-open.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2020/coronavirus-waitress-confirms-it-will-not-reopen-after-theatre-closures |title= Coronavirus: Waitress confirms it will not reopen after theatre closures|publisher=The Stage|last=Snow|first=Georgia|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n[[File:Corona Graffiti.jpg|thumb|Coronavirus graffiti in Belgium]]\nFacing at least several weeks of closure of their buildings and publicly-accessible spaces, directors of [[GLAM (industry sector)|GLAMs]] noted several immediate trends emerging: A \"concern for staff wellbeing\" (ranging from [[Human factors and ergonomics|ergonomics]] to [[suicide]]), the expectation from many stakeholders to \"move fast, but with drastically reduced resources and not a lot of strategy\", \"plunging revenue\", probable [[layoffs]] \"starting with casual and part-time staff\", and a \"rush to get online\".<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nMany cultural sector organisations and individual artists turned to digital activities \u2013 from [[social media]] to [[virtual reality]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Feinstein|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2020/apr/08/art-virtual-reality-coronavirus-vr?CMP=Share_iOSApp_Other|title='Beginning of a new era': how culture went virtual in the face of crisis|date=9 April 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> \u2013 as a way to continue fulfilling their organisational mission and obtain or retain an audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@kajsahartig/museums-delivering-value-online-some-thoughts-during-the-covid-19-crisis-193fc0a58d22|title=Museums delivering value online \u2014 some thoughts during the Covid-19 crisis|last=Hartig|first=Kajsa|date=2020-03-29|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Farago|first=Jason|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/arts/design/coronavirus-digital-artists.html|title=The Merry-Go-Round Stopped. What Sort of Art Will Emerge?|date=2020-03-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> For example, the [[BBC]] launched a \"virtual festival of the arts\" called ''Culture in quarantine''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/culture-in-quarantine|title=BBC - BBC Arts announces new programmes for Culture In Quarantine - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Sydney Biennale]] became the first international [[arts festival]] to go entirely digital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/the-biennale-of-sydney-is-moving-online-1811871|title=Dawn of the Online Biennial Era? The Biennale of Sydney Becomes the First Major International Art Show to Go Virtual|last=Rea|first=Naomi|date=2020-03-23|website=[[Artnet]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Individual artists of all kinds offered [[impromptu]] performances via their personal accounts from their homes \u2013 singing [[Cover version|covers]], performing live book or [[poetry readings]], or creatively live-streaming themselves doing both normal and unusual activities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stubbins|first=Sinead|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/25/coronavirus-cabin-fever-the-best-celebrities-to-follow-from-robbie-williams-to-florence-pugh|title=Coronavirus cabin fever: the best celebrities to follow, from Robbie Williams to Florence Pugh|date=2020-03-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nCollecting institutions \u2013 libraries, archives, and museums of all sizes \u2013 initiated \"rapid response collecting\" programs in an effort to document and acquire artefacts associated with the period of time, and the many ways that society changed through of it.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Abend|first=Lisa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/arts/design/museums-coronavirus-pandemic-artifacts.html|title=Museums Scramble to Document the Pandemic, Even as It Unfolds|date=2020-03-31|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> For example, in the Netherlands, the national digital heritage sector organisation [[Netwerk Digitaal Erfgoed]] launched a campaign to ensure born-digital collections related to the pandemic, notably by [[web archiving]] but also including social media, and video, were archived.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.netwerkdigitaalerfgoed.nl/actueel/coronacollectie/|title=Coronacollectie|website=Netwerk Digitaal Erfgoed|language=nl-NL|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Crowdsourcing campaigns were also mounted. For example, an [[ephemera]] collection by libraries in Australia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/books/something-we-ll-never-see-again-museums-record-history-as-it-unfolds-20200403-p54gsy.html|title='Something we'll never see again': Museums record history as it unfolds|last=Dye|first=Josh|date=2020-04-05|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> a \"sound map\" of recordings of empty cities,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bakare|first=Lanre|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/art-project-captures-sound-of-cities-during-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Art project captures sound of cities during coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-31|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> an online oral history recording platform hosted by [[IUPUI]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/iu.edu/covid-19oralhistoryproject/|title=covid-19 oral history project|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> as well as an [[oral history]] project of the GLAM sector itself \u2013 which regularly interviewed directors of cultural sector organisations throughout the closure period.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=http://best-of-3.blogspot.com/2020/04/observations.html|title=Best of 3: Where are we at and how do we plan: museums as we look forward from the lock-down.|last=Johnston|first=Courtney|date=2020-04-06|website=Best of 3|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nHaving been the first country to enforce quarantine upon its population, museums in China were also the first to provide new digital services (primarily for a domestic audience, but to a lesser extent also internationally). In January the [[National Cultural Heritage Administration]] (NCHA) said they would \"encourage cultural heritage museums and institutions around the country to utilise existing digital resources and launch online exhibitions as appropriate, providing the public with safe and convenient online services.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/travel/news/chinas-museums-offer-online-exhibitions-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ar-BBZEOr6|title=China's museums offer online exhibitions amid coronavirus outbreak|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncha.gov.cn/art/2020/1/28/art_722_158541.html|title=\u5173\u4e8e\u5411\"\u535a\u7269\u9986\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5e73\u53f0\"\u63d0\u4f9b\u7f51\u4e0a\u5c55\u89c8\u5185\u5bb9\u8d44\u6e90\u7684\u5021\u8bae\u4e66|website=www.ncha.gov.cn|publisher=[[National Cultural Heritage Administration]]|language=zh|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n\nVarious [[internet journalism]] and [[Industry association]]s published lists of new digitally-accessible arts and culture content for their country. Including Argentina,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buenosaires.gob.ar/culturaencasa|title=Cultura en casa|website=Buenos Aires Ciudad - Gobierno de la Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ozglam.info/s/updates/page/welcome|title=Australian GLAM updates|website=ozglam.info|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irishmuseums.org/text-pages/irishmuseumsonline-content-and-resources|title=#IrishMuseumsOnline: content and resources|website=Irish Museums Association|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Italy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalist.it/arti/2020/03/13/musei-chiusi-per-coronavirus-cosa-offrono-sul-web-e-social-mentre-iorestoacasa-2054444.html|title=Musei chiusi per Coronavirus: cosa offrono sul web e social mentre #iorestoacasa|website=Globalist|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2020/03/18/coronavirus-dal-louvre-agli-uffizi-i-musei-chiusi-ora-si-visitano-online-cineteche-teatri-e-biblioteche-cosi-la-cultura-arriva-direttamente-a-casa/5739782/|title=Coronavirus, dal Louvre agli Uffizi, i musei chiusi ora si visitano online. Cinema, teatri e biblioteche: cos\u00ec la cultura arriva direttamente a casa|date=2020-03-18|website=Il Fatto Quotidiano|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/it/article/n7jm97/nuovi-archivi-digitali|title=11 archivi digitali, immensi, gratuiti e meravigliosi|last=Davalli|first=Carolina|date=2020-03-25|website=i-D|language=it|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/19032020-how-digital-platforms-be-used-to-support-musems-during-covid-19-crisis|title=How can digital platforms help museums connect to audiences during Covid-19 emergency|publisher=[[Museums Association]]|website=www.museumsassociation.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kidsinmuseums.org.uk/2020/03/10-museum-activities-to-keep-children-entertained/|title=10 museum activities to keep children entertained|date=2020-03-23|website=Kids in Museums|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===By sector===\n====[[Public aquarium|Aquaria]] and [[zoo]]s====\nThe impact of the pandemic has been a uniquely serious crisis for some zoos \u2013 with reduced revenues for the operators but also reduced opportunities for [[stimulation]] for \"...the most intelligent and social animals \u2013 including [[gorillas]], [[kea]], [[otters]] and [[meerkats]]\".<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last=Roy|first=Eleanor Ainge|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/02/new-zealand-zoos-strive-to-entertain-lonely-inhabitants-amid-lockdown|title=Animal tragic: New Zealand zoos strive to entertain lonely inhabitants amid lockdown|date=2020-04-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In order to maintain physical distancing but also still care for the animals, some [[zookeepers]] (classed as \"[[Essential worker|essential workers]]\") began living on-site at certain zoos.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mohdin|first=Aamna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/30/the-animals-arent-pleased-how-shut-uk-zoos-are-coping-under-coronavirus-lockdown|title='The animals aren't pleased': UK zoos under coronavirus lockdown|date=2020-03-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Animals who would normally have a regular scheduled public feeding, petting, or performance for zoo visitors were reported to be still \"keeping their appointments\" and noticing that \"something odd is upI\".<ref name=\":6\" /> In response to the absence of visitors, some institutions launched new [[webcams]] of their animal habitats as well as feeding sessions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/coronavirus-taronga-zoo-streams-to-homes-20200401-p54g78.html|title=Coronavirus: Taronga Zoo streams to homes|last=|first=|date=|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/travel/story/2020-03-20/virtual-touring|title=Watching animals helps. A lot. Here are the best webcams|date=2020-03-20|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> or took some animals (such as penguins<ref>{{Cite news|last=Padilla|first=Mariel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/us/coronavirus-zoos-webcams.html|title=Stuck at Home, You Can Still Explore the Zoo or Aquarium. Some Penguins Could, Too.|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|last2=Vigdor|first2=Neil|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and sloths<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.traveller.com.au/coronavirus-lockdown-and-animals-chico-the-sloth-meets-excited-dolphins-at-texas-aquarium-h1n72j|title=Chico the sloth's big day out sends dolphins into rapture|date=2020-04-07|website=Traveller|language=en-au|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>) to visit other animal enclosures. A pair of [[giant pandas]] at Hong Kong amusement park [[Ocean Park Hong Kong|Ocean Park]] mated for the first time in 10 years, after two months without tourists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/07/in-the-mood-for-love-hong-kongs-middle-aged-pandas-rediscover-their-mojo|title=Hong Kong's pandas mate for first time in decade in privacy of coronavirus lockdown|date=2020-04-07|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>  \n\nDue to the sudden collapse in international travel, the [[wildlife tourism]] sector risks the potential starvation of the animals. For example, as a consequence of the lack of tourists paying for food more than 1,000 [[elephants in Thailand]] risk starvation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hatton|first=Celia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52110551|title=Thai elephants face starvation as tourism plummets|date=2020-03-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Paddock|first=Richard C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/world/asia/coronavirus-thailand-elephants.html|title=As Tourism Plummets in Thailand, Elephants Are Out of Work, Too|date=2020-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-06|last2=Suhartono|first2=Muktita|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Dean|first3=Adam}}</ref> A \"brawl\" of hundreds of [[Long-tailed macaque]] broke out in the streets of [[Lopburi]], Thailand (known as \"monkey city\"), as the animals \u2013 normally sustained by scraps by tourists \u2013 fought for food.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ratcliffe|first=Rebecca|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/13/fighting-monkeys-highlight-effect-of-coronavirus-on-thailand-tourism|title=Mass monkey brawl highlights coronavirus effect on Thailand tourism|date=2020-03-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In countries wildlife tourism represents a significant portion of employment (such as Tanzania and Namibia), there is concern that a loss of jobs related to conservation will see a rise in [[poaching]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-lockdown-conservation/|title=The Coronavirus Lockdown Is a Threat for Many Animals, Not a Blessing|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\nNadia, a tiger at the [[Bronx Zoo]] in New York, tested positive for COVID-19 in the first week of April after developing a \"dry cough\" after having been infected via an asymptomatic zookeeper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/us/tiger-coronavirus-new-york-trnd/index.html|title=A tiger at the Bronx Zoo tests positive for coronavirus|first=Alaa |last=Elassar|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> This was the first known case of a wild animal having been infected via a human (two domestic dogs and a cat had previously been diagnosed).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/04/tiger-coronavirus-covid19-positive-test-bronx-zoo/|title=Tiger tests positive for coronavirus at Bronx Zoo, first known case in the world|date=2020-04-05|website=Animals|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n====[[Film industry|Cinema]], [[Television industry|television]] and [[radio]]====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|l1=Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television|l2=on television}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n\nThe production and release schedule of many films was suspended or delayed, with some awards ceremonies and festivals being cancelled entirely. March 2020 estimates were of approximately $5b losses for the industry,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shoard|first=Catherine|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/06/cinema-coronavirus-projected-5bn-loss|title=Cinema bullish in the face of coronavirus despite projected $5bn loss|date=2020-03-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> while April estimates were global losses of 40% (compared to 2019) of $20b.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-offices-best-case-scenario-down-40-percent-1289032|title=Box Office's Best Case Scenario? Down 40 Percent|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Examples of adaptations included the early [[Home video|home media]] release ([[Frozen II|''Frozen II'']]), [[Theatrical release|theatrical releases]] being cancelled entirely (''[[Lost in Russia]]''), and online premieres ([[Enter the Fat Dragon (2020 film)|''Enter the Fat Dragon'']]). The director of ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' also hosted a screening-party via his own [[Instagram]] account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/thor-ragnarok-screening-party-details-taika-waititi-instagram/|title=Taika Waititi Is Hosting an Instagram Live 'Thor: Ragnarok' Screening Party Today|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=2020-04-09|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Many film productions were suspended, including ''[[Avatar 2]],'' ''[[The Matrix 4]],'' and a film adaptation of ''[[Heptam\u00e9ron|The Heptameron]]'' in production in [[Florence]], Italy, based on the 14th century [[The Decameron|''Decameron'']] by [[Giovanni Boccaccio|Giovanni Boccacio]], set during the [[Black Death]] in Florence.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Marshall|first=Alex|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/world/europe/coronavirus-movie-italy-decameron.html|title=Making a Plague Movie, With Coronavirus on the Doorstep|date=1 March 2020|work=New York Times|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Wax|first=Eddy|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/life-mimics-art-plague-drama-coronavirus-hit-italy-veneto-british-film-crew/|title=Life mimics art for plague drama in coronavirus-hit Italy|date=26 February 2020|work=Politico|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The traditional cinema [[release schedule]] \u2013 whereby movie theatres enjoy a two-to-three-month period of exclusivity before a [[home video]] release \u2013 was also interrupted by the closure of theatres. Innovations because of this included \"high-priced rentals\". ''[[The Invisible Man (2020 film)|The Invisible Man]]'', ''[[The Hunt (2020 film)|The Hunt]]'', and ''[[Emma (2020 film)|Emma]]'' were almost immediately released on to digital streaming services, where viewers could rent \u2014 not buy \u2014 the film for $20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://onezero.medium.com/streaming-new-movie-releases-could-be-here-to-stay-463ba50df817|title=Streaming New Movie Releases Could Be Here to Stay|last=Ravenscraft|first=Eric|date=2020-04-03|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Cannes Film Festival]], originally scheduled to occur in mid-May, was postponed and potentially cancelled, and its venue converted to an emergency [[homeless shelter]] for the period of the national lockdown in France.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cannes opens its doors to homeless after coronavirus delays film festival |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-france-homeless-idUSKBN21B2U0 |website=Reuters |accessdate=6 April 2020|date=2020-03-24}}</ref> \n\nSimilarly, the [[television industry]] saw production halted on many [[Scripted television|scripted]] and unscripted shows. This included series which had been running uninterrupted for the proceeding several decades, including: ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]'' (season 34), ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' (season 34), ''[[Days of Our Lives]]'' (season 55), ''[[Home and Away]]'' (season 33), ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (season 45), and ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' (season 47). Some shows continue with production but without their normal [[studio audience]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-tv-shows-production-delayed-1202881997/|title=Coronavirus: TV Shows That Have Halted Or Delayed Production Amid Outbreak|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|last2=Pedersen|first2=Erik|date=2020-03-16|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Three national editions of the reality TV franchise ''[[Big Brother (franchise)|Big Brother]]'' were underway since before the pandemic began \u2013 with contestants being \"some of the last people in the world to find out about the rapid spread of Covid-19\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hern|first=Alex|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/no-news-is-good-news-big-brother-germany-cut-off-from-covid-19|title=No news is good news: Big Brother guests unaware of pandemic|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \u2013 leading to the \"ethical nightmare\" of how and whether to: inform participants; publicly broadcast their reactions; and continue production.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sampson|first=Issy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/mar/17/an-ethical-nightmare-how-coronavirus-turned-big-brother-into-a-house-of-horrors|title='An ethical nightmare': how coronavirus turned Big Brother into a house of horrors|date=2020-03-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/20/opinions/big-brother-coronavirus-reveal-ethics-thomas/index.html|title=The moral quagmire of coronavirus and 'Big Brother'|last=Thomas|first=Opinion by Holly|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\nIn parallel to the suspension of entertainment content production, there was a marked increase in the use of [[video streaming]] services for entertainment (as well as [[videoconferencing]] services such as [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] for work and education) due to the massive increase of people staying at home \u2013 causing unprecedented strain on global [[internet infrastructure]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/27/coronavirus-can-the-internet-handle-unprecedented-surge-in-traffic.html|title=The internet is under huge strain because of the coronavirus. Experts say it can cope \u2014 for now|last=Browne|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-27|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> In response, [[Netflix]] and [[YouTube]] both decreased the default video quality to [[standard definition]], [[Disney+]] delayed its launch in France, and [[Xbox]] requested developers to schedule software updates at times of lower network congestion.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kang|first=Cecilia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/business/coronavirus-internet-traffic-speed.html|title=Surging Traffic Is Slowing Down Our Internet|date=2020-03-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-03|last2=Alba|first2=Davey|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Satariano|first3=Adam}}</ref> \n\n[[HBO]] also released 500 hours of free programming, including full seasons of ''[[The Sopranos]]'', ''[[Veep]]'' and ''[[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/hbo-free-streaming-500-hours-sopranos-veep-wire-1234569585/|title=HBO Will Stream 500 Hours of Free Programming, Including Full Seasons of 'Veep,' 'The Sopranos,' 'Silicon Valley'|last=Spangler|first=Todd|publisher=Variety|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSatellite radio service [[SiriusXM]] offered free streaming of their subscription-based radio service from April 2 to May 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/siriusxm-offers-free-streaming-amid-social-distancing/|title=SiriusXM Offers Free Streaming Amid Social Distancing|website=Pitchfork|language=en|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In the USA, [[NPR]] continued to produce new episodes of its ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'' quiz [[panel show]], although it was no longer recorded in front of a live audience, and live tapings in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] and [[Atlanta]] were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.wbfo.org/post/message-npr-programming|title=A message from NPR on programming|last1=News|first1=N. P. R.|website=news.wbfo.org|language=en|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2020/03/17/taping-of-npr-wait-wait-quiz-show-at-sheas-postponed/|title=Taping of NPR's 'Wait, Wait' quiz show at Shea's postponed|date=17 March 2020|website=The Buffalo News|language=en-us|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/music/npr-cancels-thursday-live-taping-wait-wait-don-tell-the-fox-theatre/wb24HTGK9GaKFgd64XnK2O/|title=NPR cancels Thursday live taping of 'Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me' at the Fox Theatre|last1=Ruggieri|first1=Melissa|website=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|language=english|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDue to the global cancellation of [[professional sports]], the loss of advertising revenue and broadcast rights derived from the [[broadcasting of sports events]] is expected to threaten the financial viability of many competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/20/sports-broadcast-impact-coronavirus/|title=For the sports-entertainment business, coronavirus is taking a huge toll|last=Zeitchik|first=Steven|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n====[[Libraries]]====\nLibraries faced different situations, from maintaining a full service with some restrictions, through providing minimal services, to complete closure. Following recent medical journal publications, the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]] in the United States suggesting that the risk of coronavirus transmission from paper was low. In the light of this, the [[International Federation of Library Associations]] noted that some libraries had imposed a wait period before handling returned books, while others have made it clear that no-one is expected to return borrowed books until things return to normal.<ref name=\"IFLA\" /> Some libraries stopped programmes which would see people spend longer periods together. Others closed public reading rooms or only allow people to collect books on appointment, either inside or outside of the building \u2013 for example setting up tables, with a [[drive-through]], or book delivery service to especially vulnerable community groups.<ref name=\"IFLA\" />\n\nLibraries of different sizes and purposes around the world worked to provide access to collections and services remotely. For example, the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]] organised [[virtual exhibition]]s,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fantasy.bnf.fr/fr|title=Fantasy, retour aux sources|website=Fantasy, retour aux sources|language=fr|publisher=[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> the Granby library in [[Quebec City|Quebec]] highlighted content focused on learning new skills,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lavoixdelest.ca/actualites/covid-19/a-un-clic-de-1300-cours-en-ligne-23003711130c1556504efdc64b1422d2|title=\u00c0 un clic de 1300 cours en ligne|date=2020-03-28|website=La Voix de l\u2019Est|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> the [[National library of Israel]] announced it would provide free audiobooks,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/national-library-offers-free-audiobooks-amid-coronavirus-closures-621664|title=National Library offers free audiobooks amid coronavirus closures|website=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the library of the [[National Congress of Argentina]] announced it would record and share readings by prominent local authors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/cultura/2020/03/18/biblioteca-del-congreso-todas-las-actividades-online-durante-la-pandemia-del-coronavirus/|title=Biblioteca del Congreso: todas las actividades online durante la pandemia del coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=Infobae|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> There have also been major efforts to boost access to [[eBooks]]: by increasing the number of eBooks in the catalogue (the [[Digital Public Library of America]] announced its intention to double the collection to 12,000 titles),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dp.la/news/our-plans-for-the-next-90-days?|title=Our plans for the next 90 days|last=Bracken|first=John|date=2020-04-03|website=[[Digital Public Library of America]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> increasing the number that people can borrow at any given time, or by reassigning budgets to pay for electronic content.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/artery/2020/03/20/demand-e-books-rises-area-libraries|title=Demand For E-books Rises At Area Libraries|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"IFLA\" /> On March 24 the [[Internet Archive]] announced the creation of a \"National Emergency Library\" whereby it suspended the waitlists on 1.4m ebooks from their lending library \u2013 books that are not in the [[Public domain in the United States|Public domain in the USA]] \u2013 in order to ensure uninterrupted access to works books for educators and students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.archive.org/2020/03/24/announcing-a-national-emergency-library-to-provide-digitized-books-to-students-and-the-public/|title=Announcing a National Emergency Library to Provide Digitized Books to Students and the Public|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Internet Archive Blogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/03/internet-archive-offers-thousands-of-copyrighted-books-for-free-online/|title=Internet Archive offers 1.4 million copyrighted books for free online|last=Lee|first=Timothy B.|date=2020-03-28|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The announcement strongly criticised by the [[publishing industry]].<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n====[[Literature]] and [[publishing]]====\n{{Quote box\n| width = 22em\n| border = 1px\n| align = right\n| fontsize = 100%\n| salign = center\n| quote = \u201cI believe that books are essential. They make us kinder, more empathetic human beings. And they have the power to take us away \u2013 even momentarily \u2013 from feeling overwhelmed, anxious and scared.\u201d <br>Author, [[James Patterson]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Steger|first=Jason|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/books/deplorable-australia-council-stuns-literary-fold-with-funding-cuts-20200406-p54hny.html|title='Deplorable': Australia Council stuns literary fold with funding cuts|date=3 April 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=2020-04-13|url-status=live|language=en|}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| width = 22em\n| border = 1px\n| align = right\n| fontsize = 100%\n| salign = center\n| quote = \u201cIt is only now, physically separated from friends and colleagues, that I realise how much sustenance and inspiration I receive from their insights, their conversation and their argument. [[A Room of One's Own|A room of one\u2019s own]] is a necessity. It is not enough.\u201d <br>Author, [[Christos Tsiolkas]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Tsiolkas|first=Christos|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/books/were-so-many-of-us-wrong-christos-tsiolkas-on-the-new-uncertainty-20200331-p54fid.html|title=Why were so many of us wrong? Christos Tsiolkas on the new uncertainty|date=3 April 2020|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|language=en||website=}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs a result of restrictions on gatherings of people, many [[Literary festival|literary festivals,]]<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|last=Alter|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/books/coronavirus-impact-publishing-industry-booksellers-authors.html|title=The World of Books Braces for a Newly Ominous Future|date=2020-03-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> commercial [[Trade fair|book fairs]]<ref name=\":13\" /> and book launches were cancelled or postponed, with bookshops such as [[Hatchards]] in London offering refunds on tickets already purchased.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.hatchards.co.uk/hatchards-calendar/fragile-borders-fragile-bodies-an-evening-with-miranda-gold/|title=Hatchards - this event has been cancelled|date=April 2020|work=Hatchards|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Such cancellations (as well as the closure of schools) had a significant impact on the ability of [[Publishing|publishers]] to bring new works to the public as well as on opportunities for [[Writer|writers]] to perform at paid speaking events. Many bookshops were forced to close their doors; others including [[Independent bookstore|independent bookshops]], closed their business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/books/story/2020-03-17/across-la-booksellers-are-scrambling-to-stay-afloat-amid-coronavirus-concerns|title=Across L.A., bookstores close, scramble to stay afloat amid coronavirus concerns|date=2020-03-17|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Booksellers adapted by providing free shipping and \"curbside pickup\" from closed shopfronts, giving book recommendations by video, and setting up partnerships with other businesses such as florists. While some bookshops continued to operate full phone, email, web order, mail order services and offered free delivery,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gleebooks.worldsecuresystems.com/|title=April 2020 - Covid19 Important Update|last=|first=|date=April 2020|website=Gleebooks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> others, such as [[Amazon (company)|Amazon.com]], de-prioritised book shipments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Partridge|first=Joanna|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/17/amazon-to-suspend-all-non-essential-shipments-in-uk-and-us-until-april|title=Amazon to suspend non-essential shipments to UK and US warehouses|date=2020-03-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nLiterature on the subject of epidemics experienced a boom in sales, some becoming [[Bestseller|bestsellers]]. Titles that sold strongly include ''Decamerone'' by Giovanni Boccaccio, written about 1453;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spicer|first=Andr\u00e9|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/2020/03/coronavirus-survive-italy-wellbeing-stories-decameron|title=The Decameron \u2013 the 14th-century Italian book that shows us how to survive coronavirus|date=9 March 2020|work=New Statesman|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Vanamee|first=Norman|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/leisure/arts-and-culture/a31540805/decameron-sudden-popularity-coronavirus/|title=Decameron and Chill? Why a 14th-Century Italian Masterpiece Is on Everyone's Coronavirus Reading List|date=16 March 2020|work=Town & Country|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Plague|La Peste]]'' (The Plague) by [[Albert Camus]], published in 1947; [[The Stand|''The Stand'']] by [[Stephen King]], published in 1978; and [[The Eyes of Darkness|''The Eyes of Darkness'']] by [[Dean Koontz]], released in 1981.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Flood|first=Alison|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/mar/05/publishers-report-sales-boom-in-novels-about-fictional-epidemics-camus-the-plague-dean-koontz|title=Publishers report sales boom in novels about fictional epidemics|date=6 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Periodical]] publishers of news and magazines saw coronavirus related content published in late March represented just 1% of articles published, but accounted for about 13% of all article views.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://whatsnewinpublishing.com/coronavirus-leads-to-significant-surge-in-traffic-how-publishers-are-building-reader-loyalty-by-offering-free-content/|title=Coronavirus leads to surge in traffic: How publishers are building reader loyalty by offering free content|date=2020-03-19|website=What\u2019s New in Publishing {{!}} Digital Publishing News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Many [[paywalled]] news services removed that restriction in order to generate [[brand loyalty]] and greater public access to relevant information. [[Cond\u00e9 Nast|Cond\u00e9 Nast Italy]] made digital editions of all its magazines (such as [[Vogue Italia|''Vogue Italia'']]) free for three months, similarly [[Hearst Communications|Hearst Spain]] (publisher of ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'').<ref name=\":16\" /> Meanwhile, [[academic publishers]] made available \"more than 32,000 articles, chapters and other resources\" related to [[COVID-19]] under various degrees of [[open access]], in order to provide \"immediate access to accurate and validated articles and monographs that the public can trust.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stm-assoc.org/about-the-industry/coronavirus-2019-ncov/|title=Coronavirus (Covid-2019)|last=|first=|date=|website=STM|publisher=[[International Association of Scientific, Technical, and Medical Publishers]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nFor professional authors, many revenue streams were curtailed.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/apr/06/french-writers-corona-getaways-prompt-backlash-leila-slimani-marie-darrieussecq|title=French writers' coronavirus getaways prompt backlash|last=Flood|first=Alison|date=2020-04-06|website=the Guardian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[American Booksellers Association]] lobbied publishers to provide discounts to independent retailers.<ref name=\":14\" /> The [[Republic of Consciousness Prize]] for small publishers of fiction split its \u00a310,000 award of among the five shortlisted nominees.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Flood|first=Alison|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/mar/30/prize-shares-10000-between-publishers-amid-coronavirus-damage|title=Prize shares \u00a310,000 between publishers amid coronavirus damage|date=2020-03-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Audible (store)|Audible]] (owned by Amazon) announced it would make 300 [[audiobooks]] free with login, for the duration of school closures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/audible-offers-hundreds-of-free-audiobooks-for-homeschooling-due-to-coronavirus-school-closures|title=Free audiobooks offered by Audible for kids affected by coronavirus school closures|last=March 2020|first=Alex Whitelock 24|website=TechRadar|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/radio/2020-03-20/audible-just-made-hundreds-of-titles-completely-free-to-help-during-coronavirus-crisis/|title=Audible just made hundreds of titles completely free to help during coronavirus crisis|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n====[[Museums]]====\n{{Quote box\n|width     = 22em\n|border    = 1px\n|align     = right\n|fontsize  = 100%\n|salign    = center\n|quote     =\n\u201cThis year, the paint has more time to dry.\u201d<br> \nDirector of the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] announcing a delay to the [[Archibald Prize]] portraiture exhibition until after the health crisis, \"when art will be needed more than ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/paint-has-more-time-to-dry-archibald-prize-delayed-20200321-p54ck2.html|title='Paint has more time to dry': Archibald Prize delayed|date=21 March 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n}}\n\nMany websites were rapidly updated to focus on their \"virtual museum resources, e-learning, and online collections\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcn.edu/a-guide-to-virtual-museum-resources/|title=The Ultimate Guide to Virtual Museum Resources|date=2020-03-15|website=MCN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Institutions' efforts to engage with the public during the lockdown took many forms \u2013 including the provision of: humour; [[escapism]]; opportunities to express artistic creativity; education opportunities; social connection and collaboration; and \"a sense of calm\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mcn.edu/8-essential-things/|title=The 8 Essential Things Museums are Providing Right Now|date=2020-03-29|website=MCN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Lists also were published of fine-art museums with existing interactive services (notably those already \"partners\" of [[Google Arts & Culture]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/547919/2500-virtual-museum-tours-google-arts-culture/|title=2,500 Museums You Can Now Visit Virtually|date=2020-03-16|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n\nMany museums turned to their existing [[social media]] presences to engage their audience online. Quickly, the [[Twitter|Twitter hashtag]] #MuseumFromHome became particularly popular for museums sharing their content in innovative ways.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/museum-social-media-entertains-during-the-covid-19-crisis/|title=Museum Social Media Entertains During the COVID-19 Crisis|date=2020-03-19|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Various institutions were singled out for particular praise by industry analysts for their successful social media content strategy during the shutdown. These included: The [[J. Paul Getty Museum|Getty Museum]] for \"challenging\" the public to share their recreated version of its artworks;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Crace|first=John|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/apr/06/how-i-became-the-duke-of-urbino-getty-museum-recreate-masterpiece|title=Coronavirus art challenge: how a pan turned me into the Duke of Urbino|date=2020-04-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5812437/getty-museum-challenge/|title=Put These Artistic Masterpieces Re-created With Household Items in a Museum|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> the [[Shedd Aquarium]] in Chicago for filming their penguins visiting other animals;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/15/us/coronavirus-penguins-shedd-aquarium-trnd/index.html|title=With the aquarium closed to humans, penguins take opportunity to explore and visit other animals|first=Alicia |last=Lee|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> the [[Royal Academy]] in London for asking its followers to draw their own artworks;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Marshall|first=Alex|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/arts/design/museums-coronavirus-adam-koszary.html|title=Museum World\u2019s King of Memes Brings Humor to Lockdown|date=2020-03-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]] in Oklahoma for providing an authentic and unusual 'voice' to their social media - from their security guard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boredpanda.com/national-cowboy-museum-head-of-security-twitter/|title=Cowboy Museum Puts Their Head Of Security In Charge Of Their Twitter, And His Tweets Are Hilariously Wholesome|website=Bored Panda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Philbrook Museum of Art]]'s rapid relaunch their website in late-March \u2013 in order \"for us all to spend some time practicing social distancing and experiencing the #MuseumFromHome\" \u2013 was described as a model example of how an institution could \"Reorganise, Reuse and Rethink\" its activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumnext.com/article/reorganise-reuse-get-creative-and-relaunch-lessons-from-philbrook/|title=Reorganise, Reuse, Rethink and Relaunch - Lessons from Philbrook|date=2020-03-21|website=MuseumNext|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Other specific examples included [[Europeana]] publishing a digital gallery of images relating to the theme of [[handwashing]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.europeana.eu/en/galleries/washing-your-hands|title=Washing your hands|website=www.europeana.eu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|Museum of New Zealand]] publishing a \"little page of calm\" (in a reference to the 1997 bestselling book ''[[Little book of calm]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tepapa.govt.nz/discover-collections/read-watch-play/little-page-calm|title=The little page of calm|date=2020-03-16|website=Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa, Wellington, NZ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n====[[Music]]====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the music industry}}\n{{Quote box\n|width     = 22em\n|border    = 1px\n|align     = right\n|fontsize  = 100%\n|salign    = center\n|quote     =\n\u201cIt is very hard financially and if you have lost the momentum you have built up over time,\" ... But this is also an ideal time for artists to do what it is they are supposed to be doing: create art.\"<br>Musician and performer, [[Tim Minchin]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cooper|first=Nathanael|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/for-musicians-collapse-of-touring-industry-opens-door-to-creativity-20200403-p54gpx.html|title=For musicians, collapse of touring industry opens door to creativity|date=5 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\nMany musicians delayed the releases of [[Album|albums]] due to the pandemic (including [[Lady Gaga]] and [[Willie Nelson]]),<ref name=\"rstone1\">{{cite web |last1=Leight |first1=Elias |title=They Were Going to Be Spring's Biggest Albums -- Until COVID-19 Hit |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/album-delays-caused-by-covid-19-973870/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> some moved up the release dates of their upcoming albums (including [[Dua Lipa]] and [[Sufjan Stevens]]),<ref name=\"sgum1\">{{cite web |last1=Rettig |first1=James |title=HAIM, Dua Lipa, Willie Nelson, & Sufjan Stevens Among Artists Moving Album Release Dates Amid Pandemic |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2077667/dua-lipa-willie-nelson-sufjan-stevens-among-artists-moving-album-release-dates-amid-pandemic/news/ |website=Stereogum |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> while others (including [[Nine Inch Nails]] and [[Phish]]) released new albums with little or no notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Farokhmanesh |first1=Megan |title=Nine Inch Nails just released two new albums for free |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/26/21195266/nine-inch-nails-new-albums-just-ghosts-v-vi-free-download |website=The Verge |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Phish to Debut New Album 'Sigma Oasis' During April 1st Livestream |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/phish-new-album-sigma-oasis-976437/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> In the middle of March, [[Bob Dylan]] released a single 17 minute new song called \"[[Murder Most Foul (song)|Murder Most Foul]]\", his first piece of original material in eight years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=McFadyen|first=Matthew|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/murder-most-foul-bob-dylan-s-surprise-song-for-the-viral-age-20200330-p54f8z.html|title=Murder Most Foul: Bob Dylan's surprise song for the viral age|date=30 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|2020 Eurovision Song Contest]], set to take place in May in [[Rotterdam]], [[Netherlands]], was canceled, marking the first time the annual contest would not take place since its inauguration in 1956.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eurovision Song Contest Canceled Because of Coronavirus |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/eurovision-song-contest-cancelled-because-coronavirus-1282660 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Official EBU statement & FAQ on Eurovision 2020 cancellation |url=https://eurovision.tv/official-ebu-statement-and-faq-eurovision-song-contest-2020-cancellation |website=Eurovision.tv |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral special remote-participation [[concerts]] were organised to provide entertainment to the public, and to raise awareness methods to combat the virus, notably [[physical distancing]].The [[iHeart Living Room Concert for America]] concert (hosted by [[Elton John]]) was broadcast on American TV and radio on March 29, while ''[[Together at Home]]'' was a \"virtual concert series\". It was then followed by the ''[[One World: Together at Home]]'' concert on April 18, organised by [[Lady Gaga]] as a [[benefit concert]] for the [[World Health Organization|World Health Organization\u2019s]] [[COVID-19 Solidarity Response Fund|COVID-19 solidarity response fund]], which would be broadcast on radio, tv, and many digital platforms simultaneously.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Snapes|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/06/lady-gaga-billie-eilish-and-paul-mccartney-to-play-coronavirus-benefit|title=Lady Gaga, Billie Eilish and Paul McCartney to play coronavirus benefit|date=2020-04-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-09|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The quickly organised \"Instagram Live Music Festival\" ''Isol Aid'' (a reference to [[Live Aid]]) of 72 Australian bands was broadcast on the weekend of 21\u201322 March. Each artist performed from wherever the were [[Isolation (health care)|self isolating]] and \"... play a 20-minute set streamed live on their Instagram accounts, and then tag-team the next artist to play\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/isol-aid-instagram-live-music-festival-coronavirus-covid-19/12072202|title=Isol-Aid is a stacked Aussie livestreaming music festival that's happening this weekend|last=Newstead|first=Al|date=2020-03-19|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://linktr.ee/isolaidfestival|title=@isolaidfestival|website=Linktree|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> On [[Easter Sunday]] 2020, which fell during the peak of the [[Flatten the curve|infection curve]] in many countries, Italian opera singer [[Andrea Bocelli]] performed in the empty [[Milan Cathedral|cathedral of Milan]] \u2013 capital of the worst-hit region of Italy \u2013 accompanied only by the [[Milan Cathedral|Cathedral]] organist and [[Streaming media|streamed live]] via YouTube.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lastampa.it/cultura/2020/04/07/news/bocelli-concerto-di-pasqua-nel-duomo-di-milano-1.38690201|title=Bocelli, concerto di Pasqua nel Duomo di Milano|date=2020-04-07|website=lastampa.it|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIndividually and collectively, [[musicians]] organised online performances, dubbed \"virtual concerts\", both of contemporary<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9335531/coronavirus-quarantine-music-events-online-streams|title=Coronavirus: Ongoing List of Virtual Concerts & Livestreams|date=2020-04-09|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and of classical music.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tilden|first=Imogen|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/15/bittersweet-symphony-the-best-lockdown-orchestras-and-choirs-online|title=Bittersweet symphony: the best lockdown orchestras and choirs online|date=2020-04-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Often these included musical sections referencing the fact of social isolation or home-quarantine, via their own social media platforms. Some were especially planned and prepared; some were impromptu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/live-streamed-gigs-coronavirus-yungblud-17955670|title=The best live streamed gigs to watch at home during coronavirus|last=Clements|first=Laura|date=2020-03-20|website=walesonline|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> For example, cellist [[Yo-Yo Ma|YoYo Ma]] performed \"Going Home\" by [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]], the [[West Australian Symphony Orchestra]] renamed themselves the \"West Australian Social Distancing Orchestra\" and played a re-arranged version of ''[[Bol\u00e9ro]]'' by [[Maurice Ravel]], and an amateur choir gathered the contributions of more than 1000 people from 18 countries to create a video performance of \u201cClose To You\u201d by [[The Carpenters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HezxInuN1YA|title=Couch Choir - (They Long To Be) Close To You|last=|first=|date=22 March 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Many musicians, singers and songwriters adapted to the crisis by turning to teaching online as there was both a sudden increase in people wanting to learn instruments, and a drop in paid public performance opportunities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lamond|first=Scott|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-26/coronavirus-cant-stop-the-music-as-online-lessons-in-demand/12089060|title=Coronavirus sees ARIA-winning musicians turn online teachers as students flock to lessons|date=26 March 2020|work=ABC News|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====[[Performing arts]]====\n{{main article|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the performing arts}}\nDue to physical distancing requirements many physical venues were closed, curtailing not only public performances but also rehearsals. In some cases, such as for the [[List of Edinburgh festivals|Edinburgh Festival]], launched after [[World War II]] as an effort to reconcile people through the performing arts, it was the first cancellation in more than sixty years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/theatre/edinburgh-festivals-cancelled-for-first-time-since-1947-20200402-p54gbo.html?btis|title=Edinburgh festivals cancelled for first time since 1947|date=2 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> Many performing arts institutions attempted to adapt by offering new (or newly expanded) digital services. In particular this resulted in the free [[online streaming]] of previously recorded performances of many companies \u2013 especially [[Orchestral|orchestral performances]] and [[Play (theatre)|plays]] \u2013 lists of which were collated by crowdsourcing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://streams.culturaldigital.com/|title=Cultural Digital: Streams|last=Unitt|first=Chris|date=|website=streams.culturaldigital.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> and by journalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/theatre/best-streaming-theatre-shows-how-to-watch-online|title=The best theatre to watch online right now|website=Time Out Worldwide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Convery|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/20/livestreaming-schedule-music-art-literature-and-events-from-australia-and-beyond|title=Livestreaming schedule: music, art, literature and events from Australia and beyond|date=2020-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Rawson|first2=Sharnee|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/stage-shows-musicals-opera-free-stream-online_51198.html|title=Stage shows, musicals and opera you can watch online now for free {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>  For example: the [[Metropolitan Opera]] of New York broadcast a new opera each evening, including an entire [[Ring Cycle]] performed during the 2010\u201312 seasons;<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/in-wake-of-season-cancellation-metropolitan-opera-continues-free-streaming-series-with-a-week-of-wagner|title=In Wake of Season Cancellation, Metropolitan Opera Continues Free Streaming Series With a Week of Wagner|last=McPhee|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-23|website=[[Playbill]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> the [[Bolshoi Ballet]] company of Moscow made available six of their performances;<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/03/27/spend-an-evening-at-the-bolshoi-a69775|title=Spend an Evening at the Bolshoi|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=The Moscow Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-russia-bolshoi-idUSKBN21E35D|title=Russia's Bolshoi Theater goes online as coronavirus curbs public life|date=2020-03-27|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en}}</ref> [[Shakespeare's Globe]] published 40 of its filmed stage productions;<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/shakespeares-globe-free-stream-hamlet_51295.html|title=Shakespeare's Globe to release 40 free productions as part of new digital content offering {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> producer [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] published a filmed production of one of his stage [[Musical theatre|musicals]] each week.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/andrew-lloyd-webber-musicals-stream-free-online-joseph-jesus-a4404846.html|title=Andrew Lloyd Webber's musicals will be streamed for free online|date=2020-04-03|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIndividual actors, such as [[Patrick Stewart]] and [[Sam Neill]], entertained from isolation in order to \"...be in this together and that this has to take the form of being apart\", as Neill described his contribution of [[comedic relief]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Craven|first=Peter|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/movies/when-the-going-got-tough-sam-neill-got-out-his-ukulele-20200330-p54fd8.html|title=When the going got tough, Sam Neill got out his ukulele|date=1 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Stewart, a trained Shakespearian actor, broadcast himself reading one [[Shakespearean sonnet|sonnet]] each day via social media,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/books-and-poetry/patrick-stewart-is-treating-twitter-to-one-shakespearan-sonnet-a-day-during-lockdown|title=Patrick Stewart Is Treating Twitter To One Shakespeare Sonnet A Day During Lockdown|date=2020-03-25|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> readings described as \"more than light entertainment, they\u2019re moments of connection\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Marshall|first=Konrad|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/a-force-for-good-how-the-coronavirus-crisis-is-sweetening-our-collective-tune-20200227-p5452j.html|title=A force for good: how the coronavirus crisis is sweetening our collective tune|date=10 April 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=10 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Sydney Theatre Company]] commissioned actors to film themselves at home discussing, then performing, a monologue from one of the characters they had previously played on stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sydneytheatre.com.au/stc-virtual|title=STC Virtual|website=Sydney Theatre Company|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nMany ballet companies ran classes via [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] to their dancers which were also broadcast.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/arts/dance/ballet-class-coronavirus.html|title=Dancers Still Need Daily Class. No Barre? Just Grab a Chair.|work=New York Times|date=25 March 2020|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Ballet dancers, including [[principal dancer]] with the [[New York City Ballet]] [[Megan Fairchild]] and [[artistic director]] and a lead [[principal dancer]] of the [[English National Ballet]] [[Tamara Rojo]], offered live classes on social media.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/14/arts/dance/megan-fairchild-city-ballet-coping-at-home.html|title=A Dancer's Quarantine Diary: Coming Full Circle|work=New York times|last=Fairchild|first=Megan|date=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pointemagazine.com/online-ballet-class-2645499567.html?rebelltitem=14#rebelltitem14|title=Take Virtual Class From Your Kitchen Counter With These Pros|last=Lansky|first=Chava|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impacts==\n===Budgets and employment===\n{{see also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nDue to the closures, revenues for cultural organisations reliant on ticket sales were expected to cause devastating effects upon revenues, with consequent impacts upon organisational staffing, and on independent artists and professionals. This is due to the fact that the arts and culture is a sector of national economies characterised by particularly a high proportion of self-employment.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/arts-council-england-emergency-relief-fund-1814829|title=Arts Council England Has Launched a $190 Million Emergency Relief Package for Creative Organizations and Artists|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> For example, by the 20th of March the [[Cirque du Soleil]] had [[laid off]] 95% of its workforce and closed [[traveling circus]] performances operating in seven countries,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/cirque-de-soleil-canada-coronavirus-staff-fired-1493386|title=Cirque du Soleil lays off 95 percent of its workforce after coronavirus forces closure of all its shows globally|last=Cole|first=Brendan|date=2020-03-20|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The world commercial art market declined 5% in 2019 compared to the previous year, and is expected to decline further in 2020 \u2013 with six of the world's 10 largest auction houses operating exclusively in China. Major art fairs such as [[Hong Kong Arts Festival]] and [[Art Basel]] were cancelled, furthering a shift towards online purchases and the creation of VIP \"online viewing rooms\" rather than physical displaying at [[art auctions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/the-coronavirus-pandemic-corona-panic-is-shaking-up-worlds-global-art-market-starting-in-hong-kong/a-52651815|title=The coronavirus is shaking up the world's art market in unexpected ways|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|website=DW.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nVarious [[Celebrity|celebrities]] from different industries attempted to demonstrate [[empathy]] backfired for being tone-deaf to their privileged position. These included actor [[Gal Gadot]], musicians [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Pharrell Williams]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mahdawi|first=Arwa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/31/the-coronavirus-crisis-has-exposed-the-ugly-truth-about-celebrity-culture-and-capitalism|title=The coronavirus crisis has exposed the ugly truth about celebrity culture and capitalism|date=2020-03-31|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and French writers [[Le\u00efla Slimani]] and [[Marie Darrieussecq]] \u2013 who were ridiculed for their insensitivity as they described their \"bucolic isolation\" in countryside villas.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nArts and culture sector budgetary and employment reports from individual countries included:<br>\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. According to government figures, \"cultural and creative activity contributed to {{AUD|112}} billion (6.4% of [[GDP]]) to Australia's economy in 2016-17\".<ref name=docaapr9>{{cite web | title=COVID-19 update | website=Australian Government. [[Department of Communications and the Arts]] | date=9 April 2020 | url=https://www.arts.gov.au/covid-19-update | access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> By late March 2020, 255,000 cultural events had been cancelled with an estimated revenue loss of $A280 million, self reported through the crowdsourced website ILostMyGig.net.au.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-what-the-latest-stimulus-measures-mean-for-australian-artists-and-arts-organisations-134233|title=Coronavirus: what the latest stimulus measures mean for Australian artists and arts organisations|last=Caust|first=Jo|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> [[Opera Australia]] \u2013 the nation's largest [[performing arts]] company \u2013 temporarily stood down nearly all its staff<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/exit-stage-left-opera-australia-leads-arts-shutdown-20200325-p54dq1|title=Exit stage left: Opera Australia leads arts shutdown|date=2020-03-26|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> amid speculation it would also need to sell major assets in order to avoid [[bankruptcy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/opera-australia-looks-to-sell-offs-to-stay-afloat-20200316-p54ai2.html|title=Opera Australia looks to sell-offs to stay afloat|last=Galvin|first=Nick|date=2020-03-16|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> In mid-April, the [[Melbourne Symphony Orchestra]] fired all of its musicians \"rather than honouring an agreement that would have kept them on the books on half pay\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/culture/music/stood-down-musicians-blindsided-by-mso-decision-20200415-p54k3n.html|title=Stood-down musicians 'blindsided' by MSO decision|last=Miller|first=Nick|date=2020-04-15|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. In March, when many institutions closed for the first time since [[WWII]], the state-funded museum sector had been valued at \u20ac27 billion or 1.6% of national GDP \u2013 slightly smaller than the agriculture sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/coronavirus-l-impatto-negativo-chiusure-musei-che-valgono-l-16percento-pil-AC4pFCMB|title=Coronavirus, l'impatto negativo delle chiusure sui musei (che valgono l'1,6% del Pil)|website=Il Sole 24 ORE|language=it|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. As the pandemic spread and closures became the standard not the exception, institutions started publishing expected revenue shortfall calculations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AMTransparency/status/1242869675425443840|title=This will be a thread for tracking museum layoff news.|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|publisher=Art + Museum Transparency|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> For example, by the end of March: the [[Metropolitan opera]] expects to lose $60m in revenue;<ref>{{Cite news|last=Woolfe|first=Zachary|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/arts/music/metropolitan-opera-coronavirus.html|title=Metropolitan Opera Cancels Season Over Virus and Faces $60 Million Loss|date=2020-03-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the [[Metropolitan Museum]] expects to lose $100m<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/arts/design/met-museum-coronavirus-closure.html|title=Met Museum Prepares for $100 Million Loss and Closure Till July|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and [[SFMOMA]] predicted a 40% decrease in revenue.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13877653/sfmoma-to-lay-off-or-furlough-over-300-museum-staff|title=SFMOMA to Lay Off or Furlough Over 300 Museum Staff|last=Hotchkiss|first=Sarah|date=2020-03-27|website=[[KQED]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Matching this prediction, the American movie industry predicted a \"best case\" decreased of 40% (compared to 2019 figures) if cinemas were shut for only three months, the lowest figure since 2000.<ref name=\":19\" /> \n\nBy the end of March, many museums were announcing the [[Dismissal (employment)|dismissal]] of large portions of their staff with short short notice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/news/museums-across-the-us-lay-off-workers-as-covid-19-cases-rise-82588|title=Museums Across the US Lay Off Workers as COVID-19 Cases Rise|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Examples included: the [[Cleveland Museum of Art]] put all part-time staff on unpaid leave, \"temporarily\" [[Layoff|laid off]] unionised workers, and reduced the salaries of remaining staff; <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/arts/2020/03/cleveland-museum-of-art-announces-pay-cuts-furloughs-anticipating-5-million-revenue-loss-due-to-coronavirus-shutdown.html|title=Cleveland Museum of Art announces pay cuts, furloughs, anticipating $5 million revenue loss due to coronavirus shutdown|last=Litt|first=Steven|last2=Dealer|first2=The Plain|date=2020-03-26|website=cleveland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> [[SFMOMA]] put 300 employees on unpaid leave;<ref name=\":8\" />the [[Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art]] fired 73% of its staff;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/artery/2020/03/25/mass-moca-lays-off-majority-of-staff-as-coronavirus-closures-batter-cultural-institutions|title=Mass MoCA Lays Off Majority Of Staff As Coronavirus Closures Continue To Batter Cultural Institutions|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> ; [[Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh]] [[Furlough|furloughed]] 550 of its 1003 staff (75% of which were part-time);<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/ae/art-architecture/2020/03/24/Arts-groups-furlough-employees-reduce-pay/stories/202003240087|title=Carnegie Museums, Pittsburgh Glass Center furlough employees, reduce pay|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> the [[Science Museum of Minnesota]] \"temporarily\" laid off most of its staff in an announcement via a [[Google Hangouts]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/minnesota-science-museum-children-s-museum-lay-off-most-staff-in-wake-of-covid-19-outbreak/569063662/|title=Science Museum of Minnesota, Children's Museum temporarily lay off most staff in wake of COVID-19|website=Star Tribune|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> the [[Los Angeles Museum of Contemporary Art]] \u2013 which had recently received a gift of $10m from board president Carolyn Powers \u2013 fired all [[Part-time job|part-time]] staff;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/news/la-moca-lays-off-all-part-time-staffers-82559|title=LA MoCA Lays Off All Part-Time Staffers|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/wet-paint-moca-trump-backer-1755270|title=Wet Paint: MOCA Board President Revealed as Secret Trump Backer, Murakami Mix-Up at Paris Fashion Week, & More Juicy Art-World Gossip|date=2020-01-16|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and [[Museum of Modern Art|MOMA]] \u2013 an institution with a billion dollar [[Financial endowment|endowment]] \u2013 cancelled all educator contracts. Noting as it did so that when it reopens, \u201c...it will be months, if not years, before we anticipate returning to budget and operations levels to require educator services\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/551571/moma-educator-contracts/|title=MoMA Terminates All Museum Educator Contracts|date=2020-04-03|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\nIn parallel to museum sector layoffs, staff began to [[Labor unions in the United States|unionise]], even though \"[[Social distancing]] orders prevent the in-person meetings required to sign the cards required to file for union elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tinyletter.com/artandmuseumtransparency/letters/art-museum-transparency-newsletter-2-march-2020|title=Art + Museum Transparency Newsletter #2 -- March 2020|last=|first=|date=2020-03-26|website=artandmuseumtransparency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Meanwhile, on 18 March and in response to the rapid rise of online performances during the closures of performance spaces, the [[Actors' Equity Association]] \u2013 the union announced a new \"streaming media agreement\" available to productions in areas with physical distancing regulations in force, for \"select producers to capture and make a performance available online for one-time viewing to ticket buyers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.actorsequity.org/news/PR/March18/|title=ACTORS' EQUITY MAKES NEW, TEMPORARY STREAMING AGREEMENTS AVAILABLE TO PRODUCERS IN AREAS WITH LIMITS ON PUBLIC GATHERINGS&nbsp;\u00b7 Actors' Equity Association|website=www.actorsequity.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> A planned performance of ''[['Tis Pity She's a Whore]]'' via [[videoconferencing]] software was cancelled at the last minute due to a dispute between the theatre producers and the union. The AEA argued that during a time when almost everyone in the arts is going without a regular pay cheque and is worried about their health care, \"it's deeply sad to see that some employers will still ask Equity actors to work without the protections of a contract.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/red-bull-forced-to-cancel-live-stream-reading-following-dispute-with-actors-equity|title=Red Bull Cancels Scheduled Live Stream Reading Following Dispute With Actors' Equity|last=Clement|first=Olivia|date=2020-04-01|website=Playbill|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> The theatre producers argued that \"cyberspace\" is not within the AEA's jurisdiction nor \"...should free online-only experience, in which actors participate from the safety and comfort of their own home on teleconference, without rehearsal or admission price,\" be subject to the Off-Broadway agreement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbulltheater.com/live|title=Red Bull Theater Livestream|website=Red Bull Theater|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n===Financial aid===\n\nWith the extensive financial disruption across all areas of the economy, many governments announced [[Stimulus (economics)|fiscal stimulus]] and [[Bailout|economic bailout]] packages which included specific resources for the arts and cultural sectors. Equally, various [[charities]] and industry bodies raised funds to support their sector while companies in the creative industry announced their own donations. For example, author [[James Patterson]] donated $500,000 to independent bookstores<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lithub.com/friend-of-booksellers-james-patterson-will-donate-500000-to-indie-bookstores/|title=Friend of booksellers James Patterson will donate $500,000 to indie bookstores|last=Gaynor|first=Jessie|date=3 April 2020|website=Literary Hub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> and [[Sony International|Sony]] announced a fund which would help support [[Creative professional|creative professionals]] \"impacted by the cancellation or postponement of concerts and live events, or the shutting down of film and television productions\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/biz/asia/sony-coronavirus-relief-fund-1203552726/|title=Sony Unveils $100 Million Coronavirus Relief Fund|last=Frater|first=Patrick|last2=Frater|first2=Patrick|date=2020-04-02|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>  {{expand section|date=April 2020}}\nArts and culture sector financial stimulus packages from individual countries included: \n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Algeria}}. in April, Minister of Culture [[Malika Bendouda]] announced on her Facebook page that [[Office national des droits d'auteur et des droits voisins|ONDA]], the national [[copyright collective]], had been placed in charge with administering a financial aid package for artists whose work had been interrupted by the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dzvid.com/2020/04/04/coronavirus-en-algerie-des-aides-financieres-au-profit-des-artistes/|title=Coronavirus en Alg\u00e9rie : des aides financi\u00e8res au profit des artistes|last=|first=|date=2020-04-04|website=DzVID|language=fr-FR|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Australia}}. In March, a petition of over 50 arts and culture organisations (including peak bodies from the music, dance, visual arts, museums, writers' and Indigenous arts groups) requested a financial aid package \"...to a value of 2% of the {{AUD|111.7}} billion [cultural and creative] industry\". Furthermore, it requested that the [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] \"...issue a public statement recognising the value of our industry to all Australians\" and noting that the industry had not yet recovered from the impact of the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://visualarts.net.au/news-opinion/2020/creative-industry-unites/|title=Creative industry unites to secure Australia's cultural life|website=NAVA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Separately, Live Performance Australia had requested {{AUD|850}} million for its sector, while the think tank [[The Australia Institute]] requested a package of {{AUD|750}} million for the performing arts in general.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farr|first=Malcolm|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/15/call-for-750m-rescue-package-for-coronavirus-hit-australian-arts|title=Call for $750m rescue package for coronavirus-hit Australian arts|date=2020-04-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nInstead of the {{AUD|2.2}} billion requested in the petition, in early April the [[Government of Australia|federal government]] announced a package of {{AUD|27}} million in specific arts funding \u2013 {{AUD|7}} million for the Indigenous Visual Arts Industry Support program, {{AUD|10}} million for [[Regional Arts Australia]]'s regional arts fund, and {{AUD|10}} million for Support Act, a charity providing financial support and counselling to people in the music industry in Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/27-million-for-arts-organisations-in-new-targeted-support-package-20200408-p54ic8.html|title=$27 million for arts organisations in new targeted support package|last=Cooper|first=Nathanael|date=2020-04-08|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> It also expanded unemployment assistance in response to the pandemic \u2013 dubbed ''JobKeeper''. However, the program specifically excluded \"freelancers and casuals on short-term contracts, or who have worked for a series of employers in the last year\" and, given arts sector's high reliance on short-term contracts, a large proportion of arts and cultural sector professionals were ineligible for the scheme \u2013 even though the arts sector had been demonstrated as the most adversely affected sector of the economy.<ref name=\":20\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/theatre/wrack-and-ruin-leading-actors-warn-industry-is-on-brink-of-collapse-20200407-p54hvl.html|title='Wrack and ruin': Leading actors warn industry is on brink of collapse|last=Miller|first=Nick|date=2020-04-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/apr/09/the-workers-shut-out-of-jobkeeper-ive-lost-100-of-my-business|title=The workers shut out of jobkeeper: 'I've lost 100% of my business'|date=2020-04-09|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nThe library professional association [[Australian Library and Information Association|ALIA]] announced a \"relief fund\" of payments up to {{AUD|500}} to cover the cost of essential expenses for its members experiencing loss in income.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alia.org.au/alia-covid-19-relief-fund|title=ALIA COVID-19 Relief Fund|last=|first=|date=2020-04-03|website=www.alia.org.au|publisher=Australian Library and Information Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Burkina Faso}}. The national [[copyright collective]], the [[Bureau Burkinab\u00e8 du Droit d'Auteur]] (BBDA) created a \"solidarity fund\" for artists.<ref name=\":21\" />\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Italy}}. In late March, the national copyright collective [[SIAE]] announced three measures: a \u20ac60 million \"extraordinary support fund\" for its members through 2020-21, a \u20ac50 million fund to offer [[loans]] to members at zero-interest, and 2500 food packages for members in especial immediate need.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.siae.it/it/iniziative-e-news/emergenza-covid-19-le-misure-adottate-dal-consiglio-di-gestione-siae-favore-degli|title=Emergenza Covid 19, le misure adottate dal Consiglio di Gestione SIAE per associati e utilizzatori {{!}} Societ\u00e0 Italiana degli Autori ed Editori|website=www.siae.it|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Cote D'Ivoire}}. On the first of April, the national copyright collective [[Bureau ivoirien du droit d\u2019auteur]] (Burida) announced a fund to support its members who fall ill with the coronavirus. Applicants must apply, with a medical certificate proving their illness, by the 10th of that month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fratmat.info/article/203419/Culture/bureau-ivoirien-du-droit-dauteur--une-commission-daide-aux-artistes-malades-instituee|title=Bureau ivoirien du droit d\u2019auteur : Une commission d\u2019aide aux artistes malades institu\u00e9e {{!}} FratMat|website=www.fratmat.info|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |France}}. The minister for culture [[Franck Riester]] announced that employees of cultural institutions currently receiving unemployment benefits calculated over 12 months will see the confinement period withdrawn from the calculation.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.francemusique.fr/actualite-musicale/coronavirus-le-gouvernement-annonce-des-mesures-pour-les-intermittents-du-spectacle-82453 |title=Coronavirus : le gouvernement annonce des mesures pour les intermittents du spectacle |language=fr|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The national copyright collectives for authors and for visual arts (respectively: The [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 fran\u00e7aise des int\u00e9r\u00eats des auteurs de l\u2019\u00e9crit]] [Sofia] and [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des auteurs dans les arts graphiques et plastiques]] [ADAGP]) announced they would not ask for grants they given for subsequently cancelled cultural festivals and events to be reimbursed, and requested that those grant recipients pay their originally contracted artists in full.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-sofia.org/action-culturelle-la-sofia-ne-demandera-pas-le-remboursement-des-aides-accordees-pour-2020/|title=ACTION CULTURELLE : LA SOFIA NE DEMANDERA PAS LE REMBOURSEMENT DES AIDES ACCORDEES POUR 2020|date=2020-03-18|website=Sofia|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adagp.fr/fr/actualites/l-adagp-mesures-exceptionnelles-liees-au-covid-19|title=A l'ADAGP : Mesures exceptionnelles li\u00e9es au COVID 19 {{!}} ADAGP|website=www.adagp.fr|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Germany}}. The minister for culture [[Monika Gr\u00fctters]] declared that \"artists are not only indispensable, but also vital, especially now.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/german-bailout-50-billion-1815396|title=Germany Has Rolled Out a Staggering \u20ac50 Billion Aid Package For Small Businesses That Boosts Artists and Galleries\u2014and Puts Other Countries to Shame|date=2020-03-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The statement was made while announcing a \u20ac50 billion stimulus package for small business and freelancers \u2013 explicitly including the creative sectors.\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |New Zealand}}. On March 24, [[Creative New Zealand]] announced a NZD$16 million \"Emergency Response Package\" for the first half of the year, noting the probability of a second tranche of funding for the latter half of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.creativenz.govt.nz/news/details-of-creative-new-zealand-s-first-phase-arts-sector-boost-ahead-of-14-april-opening|title=Details of Creative New Zealand's first phase arts sector boost, ahead of 14 April opening|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=creativenz.gov.nz|publisher=[[Creative New Zealand]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |Sweden}}. The Swedish Minister of Culture [[Amanda Lind]] presented a 1 billion [[Swedish krona|SEK]] support package for sports and culture, where 500 million SEK was earmarked for culture (not including government agencies like the [[Royal Dramatic Theatre]] and [[Kungliga Operan]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=En miljard i akut st\u00f6d till kultur och idrott|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/coronaviruset/en-miljard-i-akut-stod-till-kultur-och-idrott/|publisher=Expressen|access-date=2020-03-25|language=Swedish}}</ref> The national copyright collective for visual arts [[Bildupphovsr\u00e4tt i Sverige]] (BUS) proposed a 25 million SEK \"crisis package\" of funds distributed to artists in their database whose works are already publicly displayed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://press.bildupphovsratt.se/posts/pressreleases/konstnarsorganisationer-foreslar-krispaket-fo|title=Konstn\u00e4rsorganisationer f\u00f6resl\u00e5r krispaket f\u00f6r drabbade bildskapare|website=press.bildupphovsratt.se|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |UK}}. [[The Film and TV Charity]] created an emergency relief fund in order to \"provide emergency short-term relief to active workers and freelancers who have been directly affected by the closure of productions across the UK\", with an initial donation of \u00a31m from [[Netflix]] and by \u00a3500,000 from the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bfi-uk-film-and-tv-charity-set-up-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-with-1m-donation-from-netflix-1202890966/|title=BFI & UK Film And TV Charity Set Up Covid-19 Emergency Relief Fund With \u00a31M Donation From Netflix|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=2020-03-24|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/bbc-donates-to-covid-19-emergency-relief-fund-1202894127/|title=BBC Joins Netflix In Making $600,000 Donation To Coronavirus Emergency Relief Fund|last=Kanter|first=Jake|date=2020-03-27|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Museums Association]] called upon the UK government to divert \u00a3120m that was intended for the [[Festival of Britain|Festival of Britain 2022]] to bail out museums in financial distress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/17032020-museum-closures-coronavirus-covid-19|title=Museums and galleries close as coronavirus emergency intensifies|last=Kendall Adams|first=Geraldine|date=17 March 2020|website=Museums Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> [[Arts Council England]] announced \u00a3160 million would be made available for arts organisations, including \u00a350 million for organisations it does not usually fund and \u00a320 million for individual and freelance artists.<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[Paul Hamlyn Foundation]] announced that the usual competitive selection process for their \"Award for Artists\" program would be removed, and that instead of ten awards of \u00a360,000, each of the more than 100 previously nominated eligible applicants would automatically receive \u00a310,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phf.org.uk/news/1-million-awarded-to-visual-artists-and-composers-in-the-uk/|title=\u00a31 million awarded to visual artists and composers in the UK|date=2020-04-06|website=Paul Hamlyn Foundation|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The [[Society of Authors]] created an \"emergency fund\" for professional authors resident in the UK or British subjects, granting amounts up to \u00a32,000, \u201cdesigned to meet urgent need\u201d. Started initially with \u00a3330,000 from the SoA,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/mar/20/this-is-a-scary-time-coronavirus-emergency-fund-set-up-for-authors|title='This is a scary time': coronavirus emergency fund set up for authors|date=2020-03-20|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> [[Arts Council England]] later added \u00a3400,000 and other donors included the [[Authors' Licensing and Collecting Society]], [[Royal Literary Fund]], [[TS Eliot Foundation]], [[English PEN]], and [[Amazon UK]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alcs.co.uk/news/alcs-offers-additional-financial-support-to-writers-through-the-society-of-authors-330000-emergency-fund|title=ALCS {{!}} ALCS offers additional financial support to writers through the Society of Authors\u2019 Emergency Fund|website=www.alcs.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n{{flag+link|2020 coronavirus pandemic in |USA}}. A petition was begun by the [[American Alliance of Museums]] (AAM) to request that the museum sector was included in any future [[economic stimulus]] from the United States government,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congressweb.com/AAM/67|title=Tell Congress: Include Museums in COVID-19 Economic Relief|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> while the Metropolitan museum was more specific \u2013 requesting $4 billion for at-risk museums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/metropolitan-museum-of-art-congress-1813665|title=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Is Calling on the US Government to Bail Out At-Risk Museums With $4 Billion in Aid|date=2020-03-24|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> This request was met with resistance: A common argument raised the USA against the cultural sector receiving parts of the stimulus funding was that \"Arts groups may be 'nice,' but they\u2019re far from 'necessary.'\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn late March the United States federal government announced a $2 trillion economic stimulus package in the [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act]]. It included: \"$75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] and $75 million for the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], which can pass on the money to institutions that need it. Another $50 million was designated to the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]], which distributes funds to museums and libraries.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Jacobs|first=Julia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/arts/coronavirus-arts-bailout.html|title=Arts Groups, Facing Their Own Virus Crisis, Get a Piece of the Stimulus|date=2020-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Initial analysis of the bill by the AAM indicated several ways that aid could be applicable to the arts and culture sectors. These included: Emergency Small Business Loans, Economic Injury Disaster Loans, a Charitable Giving Incentive, and an Employee Retention Payroll Tax Credit. It was \"expected, but unclear\" whether charitable nonprofits qualified for the Industry Stabilisation Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aam-us.org/2020/03/27/museums-included-in-economic-relief-legislation/|title=Museums Included in Economic Relief Legislation|date=2020-03-27|website=American Alliance of Museums|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Press Photographers Association]] announced it was seeking donations to create a relief fund to support [[photojournalists]] who had lost work due to the economic impact of the crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nppf.org/nppa-covid-19-relief-fund/|title=\u00bb NPPA COVID-19 Relief Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n===Copyright===\n[[Ligue des Biblioth\u00e8ques Europ\u00e9ennes de Recherche|LIBER]] (the Association of European Research Libraries) called on the European Commission and national governments to allow libraries to provide remote access for the duration of their enforced closure and to ensure they can provide this service without fear of litigation; and called on publishers and authors to pledge to allow online delivery of normally 'onsite only' content (e.g. eBooks) and the use of copyrighted works in online educational activities (e.g. livestreamed reading of children's stories).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://libereurope.eu/blog/2020/04/14/copyright-coronavirus-statement/|title=Europe Must Take Urgent Copyright Law Action To Support Distance Learning & Research During the Coronavirus Pandemic|date=2020-04-14|website=LIBER|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The libraries of universities and of the [[National Research Council (Italy)|National Research Council]] in Italy petitioned [[academic publishers]] to provide temporary [[open access]] to publications in order to allow access for medical staff, scientific researchers, and the general public during the national emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centumcellae.it/cronaca/appello-per-il-diritto-di-accesso-alla-conoscenza-scientifica-in-stato-di-emergenza/|title=Appello Per Il Diritto Di Accesso Alla Conoscenza Scientifica In Stato Di Emergenza|last=|first=|date=2020-03-19|website=Centumcellae|language=it-IT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In early April letter signed by [[Communia]], [[Creative Commons]], the [[American Library Association]], the [[International Council on Archives]], the [[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions]], several [[List of Wikimedia chapters|Wikimedia affiliate organisations]] among many others \u2013 was sent a letter to [[Francis Gurry]] \u2013 Director General of the [[World Intellectual Property Organization]] \u2013 encouraging \"WIPO member states to take advantage of flexibilities in the international system...\", calling on \"rights holders to remove licensing restrictions that inhibit remote education, research...\", supporting a call by [[Costa Rica]] for a \"global pool of rights in COVID-19 related technology and data\" to be created by the [[World Health Organization]], and supporting the right of nations to use exceptions to intellectual property laws \"o achieve universal and equitable access to COVID-19 medicines and medical technologies as soon as reasonably possible.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.communia-association.org/2020/04/03/open-letter-wipo-intellectual-property-covid-19/|title=Open Letter to WIPO: Intellectual Property and COVID-19|last=Nobre|first=Teresa|date=2020-04-03|website=International Communia Association|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Federation of Reproduction Rights Organsisations]] (IFRRO) pointed to the various ways in which national rights management organisations had loosened licensing restrictions for online access due to the pandemic.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://us16.campaign-archive.com/?u=8353bb14837e4fc186bfea9cc&id=2dcdf36fd4&e=30bddf078d|title=IFRRO News - COVID19|website=us16.campaign-archive.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> These included: in Canada, the [[Association of Canadian Publishers]] permitting \"online story time\" reading of children's books by certain publishers for free;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accesscopyright.ca/read-aloud/|title=Read Aloud Canadian Books Program|website=Access Copyright|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> in the Czech Republic, university staff and students can obtain free online access to the digital collections of the National Library;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dilia.cz/index.php/component/k2/item/15453-dohoda-dilia-a-nk-%C4%8Dr-zp%C5%99%C3%ADstupn%C4%9Bn%C3%AD-d%C4%9Bl-pro-studenty-a-pedagogy|title=DILIA|website=www.dilia.cz|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> in Germany, churches were allowed to perform songs and lyrics to be displayed during the live streaming of church services;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg-musikedition.de/news/detail/news/information-fuer-kirchengemeinden-fuer-den-live-stream-von-gottesdiensten/|title=VG-Musikedition: Detail|website=www.vg-musikedition.de|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and in Norway, students can access for free digitised books in the National Library\u2019s online catalogue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kopinor.no/articles/covid-19-kopinor-keeps-the-wheels-turning|title=Covid-19: Kopinor keeps the wheels turning|last=Enonic|website=Kopinor|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nAcademic librarians in the United States made public statements on the applicability and importance of the role of the [[fair use]] copyright exception for \"Emergency Remote Teaching & Research\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/10baTITJbFRh7D6dHVVvfgiGP2zqaMvm0EHHZYf2cBRk/|title=Public Statement: Fair Use & Emergency Remote Teaching & Research|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Cornell University Library]] made the advice explicit, noting in a new official library policy recommending, \"...that faculty may scan course material in amounts that may exceed customary fair use limits under normal circumstances. Fair use provides flexibility to permit faculty scan broader amounts of course material than normal during these exigent circumstances.\" and noted that library staff were no longer allowed to work on-site and therefore not able to scan materials on behalf of teaching staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://copyright.cornell.edu/covid|title=COVID-19 & Copyright at Cornell {{!}} Copyright Information Center|website=copyright.cornell.edu|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> \n\nThe ''National Emergency Library'' of the Internet Archive \u2013 which suspended waitlists for access to digitised in-copyright books citing the justification of Fair Use during the pandemic \u2013 was criticised as \"piracy masquerading as public service\" and copyright infringement, especially by the [[Association of American Publishers]] and [[Authors Guild]]<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|last=Alter|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/books/internet-archive-emergency-library.html|title='Emergency' Online Library Draws Ire of Some Authors|date=2020-03-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> as well as drawing public critique from several noted authors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/04/internet-archive-national-emergency-library-controversy.html|title=The Internet Archive Started an \"Emergency\" Online Library. Authors Are Furious.|last=Hampton|first=Rachelle|date=2020-04-01|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The Internet Archive defended its program by emphasising that: the collection consisted primarily of older in-copyright works without digital surrogates; it is a temporary program; authors can choose to opt-out; and the works are chosen for the educational not commercial value.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.archive.org/2020/03/30/internet-archive-responds-why-we-released-the-national-emergency-library/|title=Internet Archive responds: Why we released the National Emergency Library|website=Internet Archive Blogs|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/controversy-surrounds-national-emergency-library-180974554/|title=Why the National Emergency Library Is So Controversial|last=Machemer|first=Theresa|website=Smithsonian Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n[[LeVar Burton]], host of ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'', announced his desire to perform live-streamed readings of books for his podcast ''LeVar Reads'' but that copyright law was unclear as to whether this was allowed. [[Neil Gaiman]] replied to Burton via Twitter, giving him permission to read any of his works.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/939vjv/please-dont-sue-levar-burton-for-reading-soothing-stories-to-scared-children|title=Please Don't Sue LeVar Burton for Reading Soothing Stories to Scared Children|last=Cole|first=Samantha|date=2020-03-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nVarious online training workshops were organised for cultural heritage to learn about relevant risks and [[Copyright exceptions|exceptions to copyright]] when providing online services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/open-glam/copyright-open-access-for-glams-in-the-age-of-covid-3a35e67f7a1|title=Copyright & Open Access for GLAMs in the age of COVID-19|last=|first=|date=2020-03-24|website=Medium|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Equally, [[digital strategy]] workshops<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usingdata.com/usingdata/2020/3/19/free-strategy-workshops-march-23-april-3|title=Free strategy workshops March 23 \u2013 April 3|website=Usingdata|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> and live Q&A sessions with experts were organised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AAMers/status/1242798776655413249|title=What #COVID19 questions do you want to pose to the museum field? Comment below or DM us to include it in our #MuseumsDiscussCOVID19 Tweet chat! TODAY 3-4 pm|publisher=American Alliance of Museums|date=2020-03-25|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===New creative works===\n{{Quote box\n| width = 22em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 100%\n| salign = center\n| quote = \"For writers, as the tentacles of the coronavirus unfurl each day, everything is copy. But what happens when every writer on the planet starts taking notes on the same subject? Will we all hand in our book reports simultaneously, a year from now? The nature of tragedy is that it takes more than it gives, but it\u2019s also produced some of our most iconic literature.\" <br>\nAuthor, [[Sloane Crosley]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Crosley|first=Sloane|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/books/review/sloane-crosley-pandemic-novel-coronavirus.html|title=Someday, We'll Look Back on All of This and Write a Novel|date=2020-03-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n| align = right\n}}\nEven during the crisis, there was the expectation of many and diverse cultural works would be created in the future which would reference, or were inspired by, the pandemic and its effects.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dye|first=Josh|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/art-and-design/perplexing-and-confusing-art-gallery-of-nsw-director-grapples-with-coronavirus-crisis-20200327-p54emd.html|title='Perplexing and confusing': Art Gallery of NSW director grapples with coronavirus crisis|date=28 March 2020|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Many [[Internet meme|memes]] were created by, and shared among, the large numbers of amateur content creators isolated in their homes during the isolation period itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gpbnews.org/post/coronavirus-goes-viral-how-online-meme-culture-reflects-our-shared-experience-global-pandemic|title=Coronavirus Goes Viral: How Online Meme Culture Reflects Our Shared Experience Of A Global Pandemic|last=Prescott|first=Emilia Brock, Pria Mahadevan, Virginia|website=www.gpbnews.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/technology/online-life-explodes-with-covid-19-memes-and-hand-washing-tiktoks-20200318-p54bc7|title=Online life explodes with COVID-19 memes, and hand-washing TikToks|date=2020-03-20|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>  \n\nAside from vast amounts of scientific research published about the coronavirus, many professionally-produced [[Creative work|creative works]] which were created, adapted, inspired by, or published as a direct result of the pandemic, and/or feature it explicitly. \n\n{{Incomplete list|date=April 2020}}<!-- Do not include scientific/medical publications in this list. This is about [[creative works]] (of all kinds) not academic research. -->\n\n* Markus J Buehler at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] produced a [[Sheet music|musical score]] from a [[sonification]] algorithm and the structure of [[SARS-CoV-2|the virus]]' S (spike) protein. Beyond the aesthetic appeal of the outcome of the analysis, it may offer another method of finding potential binding sites for [[Biological target|therapeutic targets]] and thereby assist with treatment.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Taylor|first=Tegan|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/health/2020-04-06/coronavirus-music-scientists-translate-spike-proteins-melody/12124424|title=Scientists translate coronavirus spike protein into music, revealing more about its structure|date=6 April 2020|work=ABC News (Sydney)|access-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Venugopal |first1=Vineeth |title=Scientists have turned the structure of the coronavirus into music |journal=Science |date=3 April 2020 |doi=10.1126/science.abc0657 |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/04/scientists-have-turned-structure-coronavirus-music |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n*The novel ''[[Lockdown (book)|Lockdown]]'' by Scottish author [[Peter May (writer)|Peter May]]'','' written in 2005 and describing a global pandemic, was originally rejected for publication for being unrealistic. When requested by a fan to write something relating to the coronavirus pandemic, the author said he thought about it for a minute before he \"realised that I've kind of already done it.\" It will be published in April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/04/us/peter-may-lockdown-coronavirus-book-trnd/index.html|title=A pandemic thriller, once rejected by publishers for being unrealistic, is now getting a wide release|first=Alaa |last=Elassar|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n*Australian musicians [[Tim Minchin]] and [[Briggs (rapper)|Briggs]] produced the song ''[[HouseFyre]]'' \u2013 satirising Prime Minister's [[Scott Morrison|Scott Morrison's]] leadership during the preceeding months \u2013 whilst under isolation in their respective homes. The video clip was filmed from their mobile phones, with proceeds from the song's sale going towards a fundraiser for indigenous artists.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/apr/09/tim-minchin-and-briggs-release-isolation-track-satirising-scott-morrisons-leadership|title=Tim Minchin and Briggs release isolation track satirising Scott Morrison's leadership|date=2020-04-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*Horror and supernatural fiction author [[Stephen King]] chose to backdate the setting of a forthcoming novel from 2020 to 2019, so that the characters could plausibly congregate and go on a cruise ship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/08/829298135/stephen-king-is-sorry-you-feel-like-youre-stuck-in-a-stephen-king-novel|title=Stephen King Is Sorry You Feel Like You're Stuck In A Stephen King Novel|last=King|first=Stephen|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n| width = 22em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 100%\n| salign = center\n| quote = \"Books about the epidemic are needed now. They provide people with the cultural means to understand something that is uprooting their existence.\"<br>\nAuthor and virologist, [[Roberto Burioni]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Momigliano|first=Anna|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/books/italy-coronavirus-paolo-giordano-roberto-burioni.html|title=In Italy, Coronavirus Books Rush to Publication|date=9 April 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| align = right\n}}\n\n*[[Paolo Giordano]], Italian physicist and award-winning author of the [[Strega Prize|Premio Strega]], published his thoughts about the virus outbreak in an essay entitled ''How Contagion Works'' in March 2020. It was quickly translated into more than 20 languages.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Momigliano|first=Anna|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/books/italy-coronavirus-paolo-giordano-roberto-burioni.html|title=In Italy, Coronavirus Books Rush to Publication|date=9 April 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Italian [[Virology|virologist]] and author [[Roberto Burioni]] published an examination of how epidemics shape civilisations in March 2020, entitled ''Virus. La grande sfida [Virus. The Great Challenge].'' The author's proceeds were directed to research on the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.consulenzeditoriali.it/books-fr/virus-the-great-challenge|title=Roberto Burioni - \"Virus. The Great Challenge\"|last=Carpinelli|first=Rosalia|date=2020|website=www.consulenzeditoriali.it/|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Italian publisher [[Garzanti]] published an anthology of 26 short stories and essays about quarantine, from a range of writers including children\u2019s author [[Elisabetta Gnone|Elisabetta Gnone,]] entitled ''Andr\u00e0 tutto bene [Everything will be fine].'' Profits from the sale of the e-book were directed to the [[Ospedale Papa Giovanni XXIII|Pope John XXIII Hospital]] in [[Bergamo|Bergamo.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.garzanti.it/libri/ritanna-armeni-andra-tutto-bene-9788811816331/|title=Andr\u00e0 tutto bene|last=|first=|date=|website=Garzanti.it|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Street artist [[Banksy]] published a new piece of his trademark wall art - this time located in his bathroom referencing the required [[Isolation (health care)|self-isolation]] - with coronavirus as the theme and \"stir-crazy rats\" as its subject. He published photographs of it online.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-17/banksy-bathroom-art-coronavirus-lockdown-united-kingdom/12156326|title=Banksy follows stay-at-home orders and makes bathroom art during coronavirus crisis|date=17 April 2020|work=ABC News|access-date=17 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n{{CC-notice|cc=by4|url=https://www.ifla.org/covid-19-and-libraries|author(s)=[[International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions|IFLA]]}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage}}\n[[Category:2020 in arts]]\n[[Category:Cultural heritage]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|arts]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePerforming arts:Space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_the_arts_and_cultural_heritage"}
{"title_page": "Pencoyd (Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania)", "text_new": "[[File:Pencoyd restored Architectural Record April 1915 p.370.jpg|thumb|300px|\"Pencoyd\" in 1915, from the southwest. The {{circa}}1690 original 4-bay house is center. The 1913\u201315 Colonial Revival 4-bay extension is right.]]\n'''Pencoyd (Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania)''' was a historic house and farm in [[Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania|Bala Cynwyd]], [[Lower Merion Township, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]]. Located along the north side of what is now [[U.S. Route 1 in Pennsylvania|City Avenue]], the farm originally stretched from the [[Schuylkill River]] to [[Pennsylvania Route 23#Montgomery County|Conshohocken State Road]] (PA Route 23). Settled by John Roberts in 1683, his descendants owned the property for 280 years. The house was built {{circa}}1684\u20131690, and demolished in 1964.\n\n==Welsh Tract==\n[[File:Detail of Thomas Holme's 1687 survey.jpg|thumb|left|Detail of Thomas Holme's ''A Mapp of Ye Improved Part of Pensilvania in America,'' (1687). Pencoyd was part of the parcel marked \"Edward Jones and Compa~ 17 Families\" (center)]]\nWelsh [[Society of Friends|Quakers]] faced religious discrimination and harassment in their native land. A group of Welsh Quaker businessmen met with [[William Penn]] in [[London]] in late 1681, and secured a tract of {{convert|40,000|acres|mi2 km2|abbr=off|sp=us}} in his new [[Province of Pennsylvania|colony of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|26}} The [[Welsh Tract]] was to be contiguous and stretch northwestward along the Schuylkill River from the outskirts of Philadelphia to Valley Forge.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|26\u201327}} The understanding of the businessmen was that the Welsh Tract would be a separate county that they would control, and in which business would be conducted in their [[Welsh language|native language]]. The tract's boundaries significantly changed in [[Thomas Holme]]'s 1687 survey, with two large riverfront estates for Penn's children carved out of it, along with properties that Penn granted to his creditors. In addition to the intrusions by non-Welsh landowners, Thomas Holme's 1687 survey placed most of the Welsh Tract in Philadelphia County, with a significant section in [[Chester County, Pennsylvania|Chester County]] and miles from the Schuylkill River.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|45\u201348}}\n\nJohn Roberts, [[Malting process|maltster]], emigrated from [[Llanengan]] in North Wales. He joined a syndicate of Quaker families, the Edward Jones Company, that purchased 5,000 acres at the southeast corner of the Welsh Tract, prior to sailing to America.<ref name=\"LMHS\"/> On November 16, 1683, he arrived at Philadelphia aboard the ''Morning Star'',<ref name=\"LMHS\"/> with a servant,{{efn|It is unclear if John Roberts's servant was enslaved, indentured or free. Loth wrote: \"There is no record that any [slaves] were ever employed at Pencoyd.\" page 10.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>}} and possibly his siblings Richard and Anne.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|102}} On March 20, 1684, he married fellow passenger Gainor ap Robert, daughter of another member of the syndicate.<ref name=\"Glenn\">Thomas Allen Glenn, [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924010481723#page/n9/mode/2up ''Merion in the Welsh Tract'',] (Norristown, PA: Herald Press, 1896).</ref>{{rp|103}} Two of their four children, Robert and Elizabeth, lived to adulthood.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|104}} His original parcel of land seems to have been 100 acres, with the additional 50 acres extending it to the river the gift of his bride's family.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|14}} The combined 150-acre (60.7 hectare) parcel was the one closest to Philadelphia\u2014a rectangle that ran about a mile west from the river along the Blockley Township line, then north a quarter mile, then east to the river, then south to the starting place.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|21}} Downstream of the parcel, at the Falls of Schuylkill was Netopcum, a Native American seasonal settlement where [[Lenni Lenape]] came in spring to fish.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|21}} Family tradition holds that he began building the stone house on his property in 1684,{{efn|In 1912, Harold Donaldson Eberlein wrote: \"In the rear of the old house still remain marks of old mud plaster, and until fifty years ago there was a portion of the log cabin standing that doubtless served John Roberts as a temporary domicile while the house was a-building.\" page 150.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>}} although scholars date its earliest portion to {{circa}}1690.<ref name=\"Massey\">James C. Massey, [http://cdn.loc.gov/master/pnp/habshaer/pa/pa0600/pa0619/data/pa0619data.pdf ''\"Pencoyd Farm,\" The Roberts Estate, HABS No. PA-1087'',] (National Park Service, March 1964).</ref>{{rp|102}} Roberts and his servant cleared the wooded land to plant barley, for making [[Malt beer|malt]].<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|102}} He named the property \"Pencoid\"&mdash;Welsh for \"head of the woods.\"<ref name=\"LMHS\">[http://www.lowermerionhistory.org/texts/first300/part03.html \"John Roberts of Pencoyd,\"] Lower Merion Historical Society.</ref>\n\n==List of proprietors==\n[[File:GeorgeBrookeRoberts.jpg|thumb|George Brooke Roberts]]\nIn 1912, antiquarian Harold Donaldson Eberlein noted a rare distinction about Pencoyd: \"Since the date of the original grant Pencoyd has never been sold nor deeded, but has always passed by will from owner to owner.\"<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>{{rp|152}}\n*John Roberts (1648\u20131724) \u2014 married 20 March 1684, Gainor ap Robert (1653\u20131722) \u2014 4 children \u2014 proprietor 1683 to 1724<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|103\u201304}}\n**Served as justice of the peace for Merion Township,{{efn|Pencoyd Farm was in Merion Township, Philadelphia County, as shown on Thomas Holme's 1687 survey. The farm's southern property line formed part of the boundary with the \"Liberty Lands\" of Blockley Township, Philadelphia County. Merion Township was divided into two sections in 1713, and the farm became part of Lower Merion Township, Philadelphia County. When Montgomery County was carved out of the central portion of Philadelphia County in 1784, Lower Merion Township became part of the new county, and the farm's southern property line became part of the boundary between the counties. Philadelphia City remained about 2 square miles from 1682 to 1854, when the [[Act of Consolidation, 1854|Consolidation Act]] merged the city and Philadelphia County, resulting in a [[consolidated city-county]] of 141.7 square miles (367 k<sup>2</sup>). The farm's southern property line became part of the boundary between Montgomery County and the City of Philadelphia, and the road straddling the boundary became City Avenue.}} and was elected to the Pennsylvania Provincial Assembly. In addition to Pencoyd farm, he bequeathed to his son 750 acres in Goshen, Chester County. He and his wife were buried at Merion Meeting.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|103\u201304}}\n*Robert Roberts (1685\u20131768) \u2014 married 17 June 1709, Sidney Reese (1690\u20131764) \u2014 6 children \u2014 proprietor 1724 to 1768<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|105\u201306}}\n**Operated a ferry across the Schuylkill River.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|15}} Increased the size of Pencoyd farm to 180 acres. Raised cattle and pigs to be sold in Philadelphia market.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|15}} He and his wife were buried at Merion Meeting.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|106}}\n*John Roberts 2nd (1710\u20131776) \u2014 married 4 May 1733, Rebecca Jones (1710\u20131779) \u2014 12 children \u2014 proprietor 1768 to 1776<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|107\u201308}}\n**Farmer and land surveyor. Original shareholder (1731) in the [[Library Company of Philadelphia]].<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|17}} Established a subscription library at Merion Meeting.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|23}} He and his wife were buried at Merion Meeting.\n*Algernon Roberts (1751\u20131815) \u2014 married 18 January 1781, Tacy Warner (1761\u20131828) \u2014 11 children \u2014 proprietor 1776 to 1815<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|108\u201310}}\n**Served in the [[First Troop Philadelphia City Cavalry]] during the Revolutionary War.{{efn|He was \"dismissed\" but not \"disowned\" by Merion Meeting: \"The case of Algernon Roberts coming under Consideration and it appears he Persists in the Practice of Bearing arms. It is the sense and judgment of this Meeting that he hath Publickly Renounced our Peaceable Principles and cannot be deemed a Member of our Religious Society whilst Continuing in the Practice.\" page 27.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>}} He married (out of meeting) a daughter of his commanding officer, Col. Isaac Warner. Bought land on the opposite side of the Blockley Township line, increasing Pencoyd farm to 224 acres.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|30}} Scientific farmer. Built 1791 barn. He and his wife were buried at Merion Meeting.\n*Isaac Warner Roberts (1789\u20131859) \u2014 married (1st) 20 March 1817, Emily Thomas (1795\u20131825) \u2014 4 children; (2nd) 22 February 1827, Rosalinda Brooke (1800\u20131873) \u2014 2 children \u2014 proprietor 1815 to 1859\n**Expanded Pencoyd house. Divided Pencoyd farm in half, between his two sons. He was buried with his first wife at Merion Meeting. His second wife was buried with family members at Laurel Hill Cemetery.\n*[[George Brooke Roberts]] (1833\u20131897) \u2014 married (1st) 9 June 1868, Sarah Brinton (1846\u20131869) \u2014 1 child; (2nd) 14 October 1874, Miriam Pyle Williams (1846\u20131913) \u2014 5 children \u2014 proprietor 1859 to 1897\n**Civil engineer. He spent his career with the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]], and served as PRR's president (1880\u201396). Major expansion of Pencoyd house. Driving force behind Church of Saint Asaph. His first wife was buried at Laurel Hill Cemetery. He was first buried at Laurel Hill Cemetery, and later reinterred with his second wife at Saint Asaph Church Cemetery.\n*T. Williams \"T. Willy\" Roberts (1877\u20131962){{efn|T. Willy Roberts became proprietor of Pencoyd at age 20, after both his elder brothers declined the honor.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>}} \u2014 married 29 April 1915, Ellanor C. Thompson (1890\u20131938)<ref name=\"Twilly obit\">Obituary, ''The Princeton Alumni Weekly'', November 30, 1962, p. 16.</ref> \u2014 4 children \u2014 proprietor 1897 to 1962<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|1}}\n**Restored and expanded Pencoyd, 1913\u201315, in a Colonial Revival style. Worked in real estate development, and served as a Lower Merion Township commissioner.<ref name=\"Twilly obit\"/> Last proprietor of Pencoyd.\n\n==House==\n[[File:Pencoyd - GBR 1849 elevation rotated & cropped.jpg|thumb|left|1849 elevation by George Brooke Roberts, showing the c.1690 house and 1835 addition (right).]]\n[[File:Historic American Buildings Survey, Photocopy, RESTORED PLANS AND ELEVATIONS, 1962. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, Montgomery County, HABS PA,46-BALA,1-16.tif|thumb|left|Conjectural elevations and plans of the house as it looked in 1835, George B. Roberts, architect, 1962.]]\nAbout 1690, John Roberts built a two-story, four-bay, [[Gambrel|gambrel-roof]]ed house&mdash;exterior dimensions: {{convert|26|x|41|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Massey\"/>&mdash;with stone walls two feet thick.<ref name=\"Eberlein\">Harold Donaldson Eberlein and Horace Mather Lippincott, ''The Colonial Homes of Philadelphia and Its Neighbourhood'' (Philadelphia and London: J. B. Lippincott Company, 1912), pp. 150\u201352.</ref> It faced south (City Avenue), and had large stone chimneys at its east and west ends. Its first floor featured four rooms \u2014 an off-center entrance hall with front and back doors and a stair at the north end; a long room running the depth of the house with a large fireplace (kitchen?) to the west; a smaller room with a corner fireplace (parlor?) at the southeast corner; and another smaller room with a corner fireplace (bed chamber?) at the northeast corner.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|2}} A datestone&mdash;not original, added {{circa}}1913\u201315,<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|5}} and now in the collection of the Lower Merion Historical Society&mdash;reads \"J & G / R / 1683.\"<ref name=\"LMHS\"/>\n\nUnder Isaac Warner Roberts the first fire insurance survey was made of the house in 1827. It listed the dimensions of the original house, a one-and-a-half-story stone kitchen, and a \"new\" one-story stone wash house.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|3}} He probably built the hexagonal smokehouse with Gothic windows in the second quarter of the 19th century.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|3}} An 1835 insurance survey recorded his {{convert|19|x|27|ft|m|abbr=on}} two-story stone addition, a new kitchen with a bedroom above.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|3}} Fifteen-year-old [[:en:George Brooke Roberts|George Brooke Roberts]] drew an elevation of his parents' house in 1849, showing the 1835 addition.{{efn|Loth assumed that the two-story addition was new in 1849, when GBR drew the elevation. page 39.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>}} In his will, Roberts divided the farm in half (including the section in Blockley Township), bequeathing the western half (with Pencoyd house) to son George, and the eastern half (along the river) to son Algernon Sidney Roberts. In 1866, Rosalinda Roberts (widow of Isaac Warner Roberts) converted the 1835 kitchen into a dining room, built a new stone kitchen, and made other additions, including an entrance porch with ornamental cast-ironwork.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|3}} She added indoor plumbing and the house's first bathroom&mdash;an 8 x 8&nbsp;ft frame addition built atop posts and attached to the north wall. Access to the bathroom was from the stair landing between the first and second floors, with water supplied from a cedar cistern in the attic.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|3}}\n\nGeorge Brooke Roberts hired architect [[Allen Evans]], of [[Furness & Evans]], to modernize and expand the house, 1883\u201384. Evans designed a two-and-a-half-story, gambrel-roofed east wing&mdash;anchored by a massive \"upside down\" brick chimney&mdash;that extended the length of the front (south) fa\u00e7ade to {{convert|92|ft|m|abbr=off}}.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|6}} Evans also may have designed later additions, 1888\u201389,<ref>Mutual Assurance Company, Policy #4613, George Brooke Roberts, Resurvey May 29, 1890.</ref> and 1891\u201392.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|4}} \n<blockquote>The house was expanded and altered so greatly that it looked like a quite different sort of dwelling than before. George tore down the wing which his father had built and in its place erected an even larger extension, as tall as the original house but of a different style of architecture. In the course of time he also added in another direction [north] a new drawing room, dining room, morning room and sunporch, relocated the driveway and built various porches and balconies. Indoors the main part of the house was redecorated to conform to the fashions of the day.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|48}}</blockquote>\nRoberts also subdivided his half of the farm into generous lots, which he gave to his six children to build their own houses.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|55}}\n\nT. Williams Roberts inherited Pencoyd, and demolished or refaced his father's Victorian additions. He hired architect Louis Carter Baker, Jr., a fellow vestryman of St. Asaph's Church, to restore the house in a tasteful [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]] style, 1913\u201315.<ref>\"Portfolio of Current Architecture,\" ''The Architectural Record'', vol. 37, no. 4 (April 1915), pp. 370\u201373.[https://archive.org/stream/architecturalrec37newyuoft#page/370/mode/2up]</ref> This included a 4-bay, {{convert|34|ft|m|adj=on}} extension of the front fa\u00e7ade (replicating that of the original house),<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|6}} moving the house's main entrance to the east facade, and removing interior walls to make the original house's entire first floor an expansive livingroom. In 1937, Pencoyd stood on about {{convert|35|acre|ha|abbr=off}}, among other [[gentleman's farm]]s.<ref name=\"1937 atlas\">''Property Atlas of the Main Line, Penna.'' (Franklin Survey Company, 1937), plate 8.</ref> After World War II, he sold land at the northwest corner of City and Monument Avenues to the [[Philadelphia Evening Bulletin]] for [[WCAU|WCAU-TV]], the newspaper's local television station.{{efn|WCAU-TV was a [[CBS]] affiliate from 1948 to 1995. Since 1995 it has been an [[NBC]] affiliate.}} Architect [[George Howe (architect)|George Howe]] designed the [[International Style (architecture)|International Style]] television studio building (1951\u201352),<ref>[https://www.philadelphiabuildings.org/pab/app/pj_display.cfm/113870 WCAU-TV Station,] from Philadelphia Architects and Buildings.</ref> one of his final works.\n\nT. Williams Roberts died in 1962. His nephew, architect George B. Roberts, made measured drawings of Pencoyd. HABS photographer Cortlandt V. D. Hubbard photographed it in 1963, and architect James C. Massey completed his HABS survey of it in 1964. This activity was in expectation of the house's demolition and the property's development as a suburban office campus. The Estate of T. Williams Roberts sold the house in 1964,<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|5}} the same year it was demolished.\n\nA [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] department store now occupies the house's site.\n<gallery perrow=5>\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Photocopy, SOUTH (FRONT) ELEVATION, 1870. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, Montgomery County, PA HABS PA,46-BALA,1-2.tif|\"Pencoyd\" in 1870, from the south. The cast-iron entrance porch was added in 1866.\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, PHOTOCOPY OF c.1872 PHOTOGRAPH. - Pencoyd Farm, Smokehouse, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, Montgomery County, PA HABS PA,46-BALA,1A-1.tif|Smokehouse ({{circa}}1825-50) in a {{circa}}1872 photograph.\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Photocopy, SOUTH AND EAST SIDES, 1891. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, Montgomery County, PA HABS PA,46-BALA,1-3.tif|\"Pencoyd\" in the 1890s, from the southeast. Victorian additions by architect [[Allen Evans]].\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Photocopy, PLAN OF FIRST FLOOR BEFORE 1914 REMODELING. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, Montgomery HABS PA,46-BALA,1-13.tif|First floor plan (1913), prior to restoration, Louis Carter Baker, Jr., architect.\nFile:Architectural Record April 1915 p.372.jpg|Floor plans of restored house (1915), Louis Carter Baker, Jr., architect.\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Cortlandt V.D. Hubbard, Photographer, 1963 SOUTH AND EAST SIDES. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, HABS PA,46-BALA,1-5.tif|East fa\u00e7ade of restored house and new main entrance, in 1963.\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Cortlandt V.D. Hubbard, Photographer, 1963 LIVING ROOM, FIRST FLOOR, SOUTHWEST ROOM. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township HABS PA,46-BALA,1-7.tif|Living room in 1963.\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Cortlandt V.D. Hubbard, Photographer, 1963 DINING ROOM, FIRST FLOOR, NORTHEAST ROOM. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township HABS PA,46-BALA,1-8.tif|Dining room in 1963.\n</gallery>\n\n==Farm==\n[[File:Historic American Buildings Survey, Cortlandt V.D. Hubbard, Photographer, 1963 SOUTHEAST VIEW. - Pencoyd Farm, Barn, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, HABS PA,46-BALA,1B-1.tif|thumb|Algernon Roberts's 1791 stone barn, in 1963.]]\nAt the end of the 17th century, John Roberts's principal crop was barley (for making malt), but he also grew Indian corn (for livestock) and wheat.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|6}} His son, Richard, made wheat his principal crop (ground into flour), and provided beef, pork, eggs, fruits and vegetables, and butter to the growing Philadelphia marketplace.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|15}} By the time of John Roberts 2nd, the wonderfully fertile soil was becoming exhausted. He began mixing lime into the soil, and even built his own kiln for burning lime.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|26}} The farm's wooden barn was struck by lightning, September 3, 1760, burning it and other outbuildings. He wrote: \"all that had a farmer[']s store for man and beast were laid to ashes.\"<ref name=\"Loth\">David Loth, ''Pencoyd and the Roberts Family'' (New York: by the author, 1961).</ref>{{rp|22}} A new barn (probably wooden) was built, funded in part by donations from Quaker neighbors.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|17}}\n\nAlgernon Roberts concluded that there was more profit to be made in eggs and dairy products than meat.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|31}} He rented a market stall on Philadelphia's High Street, staffed on market days (Wednesdays and Saturdays) by his tenant farmer and wife.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|32}} One year, they sold 922 pounds of butter.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|32}} In 1791, he built a large stone barn at the north end of the farm.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|32}} The barn's size was considered so extreme that Merion Meeting censured him for \"excessive ostentation.\"<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|32}} In 1827, his son, Isaac Warner Roberts, insured the barn for more than the house. The insurance survey listed the barn's dimensions&mdash;{{convert|76|x|37|ft|m|abbr=on}}&mdash;and \"noted that there were 20 stalls [for cows] with earth floors, racks and mangers. The rest of the ground floor was taken up by 'fodder gangs, fodder rooms, etc.,' the floors of which were of rough oak planks. Upstairs was a threshing floor of oak boards two inches thick. The rest of the structure was devoted to hay mows. The barn was protected by two lightning rods.\"<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|37}}</blockquote> The \"back barn\" was still standing in 1963, when HABS photographed it.{{efn|Algernon Roberts's \"back barn\" was located on a rise of land north of the intersection of St. Asaph's Road and Decker Boulevard. It is now the site of the Bala Plaza office complex.}}\n\nIsaac Warner Roberts insured the stables and a carriage house (east of the main house) in 1827,<ref>Mutual Assurance Company, Policy #4614, Isaac Warner Roberts, Survey November 28, 1827.</ref> which were altered in 1863,<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|43}} and replaced in 1893.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|5}} He divided the farm in half between his two sons. On the eastern half, son Algernon Sidney Roberts (and his cousin) opened a specialty iron foundry, Pencoyd Iron Works, along the Schuylkill River. George Brooke Roberts turned the western half into a model dairy farm, with a herd of [[Guernsey cattle|Guernsey cows]].<ref name=\"LMHS\"/> He erected a new farmhouse, tool house and chicken house, and the eaves of the barn were extended into an \"over shot\" (shed roof) in 1886.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|4}} He demolished the old greenhouse in 1890, and replaced it with a new \"Iron and Wooden one.\"<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|20}} His farm also featured an ice pond and spring house.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|20}}\n\nA new bridge carrying City Avenue over the Schuylkill River was completed in May 1890.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|20}} City Avenue was paved and [[gaslight|gas]] streetlights were erected.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|20}} Farm Road, which separated the two halves of the farm, was renamed Monument Road, and paved in 1891.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|20}}\n\nSome of the farm buildings were converted into residences in the early 20th century.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|19}} By the time of T. Williams Roberts's death in 1962, the size of the farm was down to about {{convert|20|acre|ha|abbr=off}}.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|60}}\n\n==Church of Saint Asaph==\n[[File:St Asaph's Hotchkin Rural Pennsylvania 1897.jpg|thumb|Church of Saint Asaph, 1888 perspective drawing by architect Theophilus P. Chandler.]]\n[[File:Pennsylvania Route 23 eastern terminus.jpg|thumb|Entrance to St. Asaph's Church from Conshohocken State Road (left), in 2019]]\nGeorge Brooke Roberts had been born a Quaker, but became an Episcopalian prior to his 1868 marriage to Sarah Lapsley Brinton.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|45}} She died the following year, at age 23, after giving birth to their only child, George Brinton Roberts. He married Miriam Williams in 1874, and they had five children together. Roberts was the driving force behind building the Church of Saint Asaph.\n\nRoberts obtained permission to create a new Episcopal parish, organized its Board of Trustees, and hosted its first vestry meeting, at Pencoyd, on November 16, 1887.<ref name=\"JCR\">Joan Church Roberts, ''Our First One Hundred Years, 1888\u20131988: The Church of Saint Asaph'' (Church of Saint Asaph, 1992).</ref>{{rp|2\u20133}} At the second vestry meeting, December 12, 1887, several sites along City Avenue were discussed, and the name \"[[Saint Asaph]]\" was chosen.{{efn|Saint Asaph had been a 6th century Welsh bishop, but the name also had a Philadelphia connection: Dr. [[Jonathan Shipley]], Bishop of the Diocese of Saint Asaph, Wales, 1769\u201388, was a close friend of Benjamin Franklin. Franklin began writing his famous ''[[Autobiography of Benjamin Franklin|Autobiography]]'' while Shipley's houseguest. page 7.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>}} At the third vestry meeting, January 30, 1888, architect [[Theophilus P. Chandler, Jr.]] was an invited guest.{{efn|Chandler had designed investment properties for George Brooke Roberts.<ref name=\"JCR\"/> Chandler's presence at the vestry meeting with plans already in hand was no coincidence.}} He submitted a general plan for a church, which was accepted, and he was elected to the vestry that night.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|4}} At that same meeting, Roberts announced that he and his sisters wished to donate land at the west end of Pencoyd Farm, along Conshohocken State Road, as the site for the church, which the vestry also accepted.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|4}}\n\nChandler may have based his design on [[Saint Asaph Cathedral]], a small 14th-century cathedral in [[St. Asaph|Saint Asaph]], [[Denbighshire]], Wales.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|5}} Superficially, both churches share a squat, flat-roofed tower at the [[Crossing (architecture)|crossing]]. Excavation was to begin in mid-March, but was interrupted by the [[Great Blizzard of 1888]].<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|7}} The church's cornerstone was laid, May 8, 1888.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|8}} Chandler also designed the church's rectory, which Roberts donated in thanksgiving for the birth of his daughter Miriam that summer.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|10}} The opening service in the nearly-completed church was held on March 24, 1889.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|14}} The following Sunday, Chandler placed the signed bill for his services in the [[collection plate]], indicating that he regarded it as paid in full, along with a monetary contribution.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|4}}\n\nRoberts was the church's first rector's warden, serving until his death in 1897.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|109}} He was initially buried at [[Laurel Hill Cemetery]], but was later reinterred in the church's cemetery. His son, T. Williams Roberts, served as a vestryman for 42 years, and accounting warden for 29 years.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|109}} Architect Louis Carter Baker, Jr. designed alterations to the church and rectory, and served on the vestry from 1908 to his death in 1915.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|36\u201337}}\n\n==Pencoyd Iron Works==\nIn 1852, Algernon Sidney Roberts (who would later inherit the eastern half of Pencoyd farm) and his cousin Percival Roberts founded the A. & P. Roberts Company, a specialty iron foundry located along the Schuylkill River, opposite [[Manayunk, Philadelphia|Manayunk]].<ref name=\"PIW\"/> The company initially made railroad equipment, but soon began manufacturing iron bridge members.<ref name=\"PIW\">[http://www.pennrealestategroup.com/pencoyd_ironworks_history.htm The History of the Pencoyd Iron Works,] from Penn Real Estate Group.</ref> It won the contract to manufacture all the structural elements for the cast-iron-and-glass Main Exhibition Building and Machinery Hall at the [[1876 Centennial Exposition]]. The Main Exhibition Building was to be the largest building in the world. Designed by [[Wilson Brothers & Company]], it was {{convert|1,880|ft|m|abbr=on}} in length, {{convert|464|ft|m|abbr=on}} in width, and enclosed {{convert|21.5|acre|ha|abbr=off}} of space. Machinery Hall, also designed by the Wilson Brothers, was {{convert|1402|ft|m|abbr=on}} in length, {{convert|360|ft|m|abbr=on}} in width, and enclosed {{convert|12.8|acre|ha|abbr=off}}. After the World's Fair, the buildings were auctioned off, disassembled, and their structural elements were reused in other buildings.{{efn|The Main Exhibition Building sold at auction for $250,000.<ref>Sandy Hingston, [http://www.phillymag.com/news/2016/05/10/centennial-exhibition-history/ \"10 Things You Might Not Know About the 1876 Centennial Exhibition,\"] ''Philadelphia Magazine'', May 10, 2016.</ref>}}\n\nPencoyd Iron Works became a major bridge producer, manufacturing and constructing hundreds of bridges in the United States.<ref name=\"PIW\"/> The company built Pencoyd Village \u2013 a community of 70 worker houses,{{efn|Most of the worker houses, which once lined Righters Ferry Road,<ref name=\"1937 atlas\"/> have been demolished.}} a public school and a public library \u2013 all squeezed between Pencoyd Farm and [[West Laurel Hill Cemetery]].<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|43}} The company was purchased by [[J. P. Morgan]] in 1900, [[List of companies consolidated into American Bridge Company|one of 28 companies consolidated into the American Bridge Company]].<ref name=\"PIW\"/> The [[American Bridge Company]] became part of [[United States Steel]] in 1902.<ref name=\"PIW\"/> Pencoyd Iron Works closed in the 1940s, and most of the steel mill was demolished in the 1950s for construction of the [[Schuylkill Expressway]].<ref name=\"PIW\"/> \n\nThe \"Pencoyd Bridge over Schuylkill River,\" a two-span, 1899 iron [[Truss bridge#Parker (camelback) truss|Parker truss bridge]] that connected the foundry to Manayunk, is now part of the Pencoyd Trail and open to pedestrians and bikes. The Schuylkill Expressway's 1950s Pencoyd [[Viaduct]], between the Belmont Avenue and City Avenue exits, is also (inaccurately) called the \"Pencoyd Bridge.\"\n<gallery>\nFile:AmCyc Philadelphia - Main Exhibition Building.jpg|Main Exhibition Building, 1876 Centennial Exposition, Philadelphia\nFile:Construction of the Netherlands department in the main exhibition building of the Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia in 1876.jpg|Interior of Main Exhibition Building, 1876 Centennial Exposition, Philadelphia\nFile:Pencoyd Iron Works Port of Philadelphia 1914 p.58.jpg|Pencoyd Iron Works, in 1914, at background left. Pencoyd Bridge is visible in the background center.\nFile:Manayunk, Philadelphia (2015).jpg|Site of Pencoyd Iron Works, in 2015. Righters Ferry Road passes under the railroad line at bottom left.\nFile:View from Manayunk Bridge, October 2014.jpg|Schuylkill Expressway Pencoyd Viaduct, in 2014, at far right. Manayunk is left.\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n*[http://www.saintasaphs.org/ Church of Saint Asaph website]\n\n{{coord|40.006444|-75.216741|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-PA|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1690]]\n[[Category:Frank Furness buildings]]\n[[Category:Houses in Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Lower Merion Township, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Welsh-American culture in Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Pencoyd restored Architectural Record April 1915 p.370.jpg|thumb|300px|\"Pencoyd\" in 1915, from the southwest. The {{circa}}1690 original 4-bay house is center. The 1913\u201315 Colonial Revival 4-bay extension is right.]]\n'''Pencoyd (Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania)''' was a historic house and farm in [[Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania|Bala Cynwyd]], [[Lower Merion Township, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]]. Located along the north side of what is now [[U.S. Route 1 in Pennsylvania|City Avenue]], the farm originally stretched from the [[Schuylkill River]] to [[Pennsylvania Route 23#Montgomery County|Conshohocken State Road]] (PA Route 23). Settled by John Roberts in 1683, his descendants owned the property for 280 years. The house was built {{circa}}1684\u20131690, and demolished in 1964.\n\n==Welsh Tract==\n[[File:Detail of Thomas Holme's 1687 survey.jpg|thumb|left|Detail of Thomas Holme's ''A Mapp of Ye Improved Part of Pensilvania in America,'' (1687). Pencoyd was part of the parcel marked \"Edward Jones and Compa~ 17 Families\" (center)]]\nWelsh [[Society of Friends|Quakers]] faced religious discrimination and harassment in their native land. A group of Welsh Quaker businessmen met with [[William Penn]] in [[London]] in late 1681, and secured a tract of {{convert|40,000|acres|mi2 km2|abbr=off|sp=us}} in his new [[Province of Pennsylvania|colony of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|26}} The [[Welsh Tract]] was to be contiguous and stretch northwestward along the Schuylkill River from the outskirts of Philadelphia to Valley Forge.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|26\u201327}} The understanding of the businessmen was that the Welsh Tract would be a separate county that they would control, and in which business would be conducted in their [[Welsh language|native language]]. The tract's boundaries significantly changed in [[Thomas Holme]]'s 1687 survey, with two large riverfront estates for Penn's children carved out of it, along with properties that Penn granted to his creditors. In addition to the intrusions by non-Welsh landowners, Thomas Holme's 1687 survey placed most of the Welsh Tract in Philadelphia County, with a significant section in [[Chester County, Pennsylvania|Chester County]] and miles from the Schuylkill River.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|45\u201348}}\n\nJohn Roberts, [[Malting process|maltster]], emigrated from [[Llanengan]] in North Wales. He joined a syndicate of Quaker families, the Edward Jones Company, that purchased 5,000 acres at the southeast corner of the Welsh Tract, prior to sailing to America.<ref name=\"LMHS\"/> On November 16, 1683, he arrived at Philadelphia aboard the ''Morning Star'',<ref name=\"LMHS\"/> with a servant,{{efn|It is unclear if John Roberts's servant was enslaved, indentured or free. Loth wrote: \"There is no record that any [slaves] were ever employed at Pencoyd.\" page 10.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>}} and possibly his siblings Richard and Anne.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|102}} On March 20, 1684, he married fellow passenger Gainor ap Robert, daughter of another member of the syndicate.<ref name=\"Glenn\">Thomas Allen Glenn, [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924010481723#page/n9/mode/2up ''Merion in the Welsh Tract'',] (Norristown, PA: Herald Press, 1896).</ref>{{rp|103}} Two of their four children, Robert and Elizabeth, lived to adulthood.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|104}} His original parcel of land seems to have been 100 acres, with the additional 50 acres extending it to the river the gift of his bride's family.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|14}} The combined 150-acre (60.7 hectare) parcel was the one closest to Philadelphia\u2014a rectangle that ran about a mile west from the river along the Blockley Township line, then north a quarter mile, then east to the river, then south to the starting place.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|21}} Downstream of the parcel, at the Falls of Schuylkill was Netopcum, a Native American seasonal settlement where [[Lenni Lenape]] came in spring to fish.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|21}} Family tradition holds that he began building the stone house on his property in 1684,{{efn|In 1912, Harold Donaldson Eberlein wrote: \"In the rear of the old house still remain marks of old mud plaster, and until fifty years ago there was a portion of the log cabin standing that doubtless served John Roberts as a temporary domicile while the house was a-building.\" page 150.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>}} although scholars date its earliest portion to {{circa}}1690.<ref name=\"Massey\">James C. Massey, [http://cdn.loc.gov/master/pnp/habshaer/pa/pa0600/pa0619/data/pa0619data.pdf ''\"Pencoyd Farm,\" The Roberts Estate, HABS No. PA-1087'',] (National Park Service, March 1964).</ref>{{rp|102}} Roberts and his servant cleared the wooded land to plant barley, for making [[Malt beer|malt]].<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|102}} He named the property \"Pencoid\"&mdash;Welsh for \"head of the woods.\"<ref name=\"LMHS\">[http://www.lowermerionhistory.org/texts/first300/part03.html \"John Roberts of Pencoyd,\"] Lower Merion Historical Society.</ref>\n\n==List of proprietors==\n[[File:GeorgeBrookeRoberts.jpg|thumb|George Brooke Roberts]]\nIn 1912, antiquarian Harold Donaldson Eberlein noted a rare distinction about Pencoyd: \"Since the date of the original grant Pencoyd has never been sold nor deeded, but has always passed by will from owner to owner.\"<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>{{rp|152}}\n*John Roberts (1648\u20131724) \u2014 married 20 March 1684, Gainor ap Robert (1653\u20131722) \u2014 4 children \u2014 proprietor 1683 to 1724<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|103\u201304}}\n**Served as justice of the peace for Merion Township,{{efn|Pencoyd Farm was in Merion Township, Philadelphia County, as shown on Thomas Holme's 1687 survey. The farm's southern property line formed part of the boundary with the \"Liberty Lands\" of Blockley Township, Philadelphia County. Merion Township was divided into two sections in 1713, and the farm became part of Lower Merion Township, Philadelphia County. When Montgomery County was carved out of the central portion of Philadelphia County in 1784, Lower Merion Township became part of the new county, and the farm's southern property line became part of the boundary between the counties. Philadelphia City remained about 2 square miles from 1682 to 1854, when the [[Act of Consolidation, 1854|Consolidation Act]] merged the city and Philadelphia County, resulting in a [[consolidated city-county]] of 141.7 square miles (367 k<sup>2</sup>). The farm's southern property line became part of the boundary between Montgomery County and the City of Philadelphia, and the road straddling the boundary became City Avenue.}} and was elected to the Pennsylvania Provincial Assembly. In addition to Pencoyd farm, he bequeathed to his son 750 acres in Goshen, Chester County. He and his wife were buried at Merion Meeting.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|103\u201304}}\n*Robert Roberts (1685\u20131768) \u2014 married 17 June 1709, Sidney Reese (1690\u20131764) \u2014 6 children \u2014 proprietor 1724 to 1768<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|105\u201306}}\n**Operated a ferry across the Schuylkill River.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|15}} Increased the size of Pencoyd farm to 180 acres. Raised cattle and pigs to be sold in Philadelphia market.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|15}} He and his wife were buried at Merion Meeting.<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|106}}\n*John Roberts 2nd (1710\u20131776) \u2014 married 4 May 1733, Rebecca Jones (1710\u20131779) \u2014 12 children \u2014 proprietor 1768 to 1776<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|107\u201308}}\n**Farmer and land surveyor. Original shareholder (1731) in the [[Library Company of Philadelphia]].<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|17}} Established a subscription library at Merion Meeting.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|23}} He and his wife were buried at Merion Meeting.\n*Algernon Roberts (1751\u20131815) \u2014 married 18 January 1781, Tacy Warner (1761\u20131828) \u2014 11 children \u2014 proprietor 1776 to 1815<ref name=\"Glenn\"/>{{rp|108\u201310}}\n**Served in the [[First Troop Philadelphia City Cavalry]] during the Revolutionary War.{{efn|He was \"dismissed\" but not \"disowned\" by Merion Meeting: \"The case of Algernon Roberts coming under Consideration and it appears he Persists in the Practice of Bearing arms. It is the sense and judgment of this Meeting that he hath Publickly Renounced our Peaceable Principles and cannot be deemed a Member of our Religious Society whilst Continuing in the Practice.\" page 27.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>}} He married (out of meeting) a daughter of his commanding officer, Col. Isaac Warner. Bought land on the opposite side of the Blockley Township line, increasing Pencoyd farm to 224 acres.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|30}} Scientific farmer. Built 1791 barn. He and his wife were buried at Merion Meeting.\n*Isaac Warner Roberts (1789\u20131859) \u2014 married (1st) 20 March 1817, Emily Thomas (1795\u20131825) \u2014 4 children; (2nd) 22 February 1827, Rosalinda Brooke (1800\u20131873) \u2014 2 children \u2014 proprietor 1815 to 1859\n**Expanded Pencoyd house. Divided Pencoyd farm in half, between his two sons. He was buried with his first wife at Merion Meeting. His second wife was buried with family members at Laurel Hill Cemetery.\n*[[George Brooke Roberts]] (1833\u20131897) \u2014 married (1st) 9 June 1868, Sarah Brinton (1846\u20131869) \u2014 1 child; (2nd) 14 October 1874, Miriam Pyle Williams (1846\u20131913) \u2014 5 children \u2014 proprietor 1859 to 1897\n**Civil engineer. He spent his career with the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]], and served as PRR's president (1880\u201396). Major expansion of Pencoyd house. Driving force behind Church of Saint Asaph. His first wife was buried at Laurel Hill Cemetery. He was first buried at Laurel Hill Cemetery, and later reinterred with his second wife at Saint Asaph Church Cemetery.\n*T. Williams \"T. Willy\" Roberts (1877\u20131962){{efn|T. Willy Roberts became proprietor of Pencoyd at age 20, after both his elder brothers declined the honor.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>}} \u2014 married 29 April 1915, Ellanor C. Thompson (1890\u20131938)<ref name=\"Twilly obit\">Obituary, ''The Princeton Alumni Weekly'', November 30, 1962, p. 16.</ref> \u2014 4 children \u2014 proprietor 1897 to 1962<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|1}}\n**Restored and expanded Pencoyd, 1913\u201315, in a Colonial Revival style. Worked in real estate development, and served as a Lower Merion Township commissioner.<ref name=\"Twilly obit\"/> Last proprietor of Pencoyd.\n\n==House==\n[[File:Pencoyd - GBR 1849 elevation rotated & cropped.jpg|thumb|left|1849 elevation by George Brooke Roberts, showing the c.1690 house and 1835 addition (right).]]\n[[File:Historic American Buildings Survey, Photocopy, RESTORED PLANS AND ELEVATIONS, 1962. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, Montgomery County, HABS PA,46-BALA,1-16.tif|thumb|left|Conjectural elevations and plans of the house as it looked in 1835, George B. Roberts, architect, 1962.]]\nAbout 1690, John Roberts built a two-story, four-bay, [[Gambrel|gambrel-roof]]ed house&mdash;exterior dimensions: {{convert|26|x|41|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Massey\"/>&mdash;with stone walls two feet thick.<ref name=\"Eberlein\">Harold Donaldson Eberlein and Horace Mather Lippincott, ''The Colonial Homes of Philadelphia and Its Neighbourhood'' (Philadelphia and London: J. B. Lippincott Company, 1912), pp. 150\u201352.</ref> It faced south (City Avenue), and had large stone chimneys at its east and west ends. Its first floor featured four rooms \u2014 an off-center entrance hall with front and back doors and a stair at the north end; a long room running the depth of the house with a large fireplace (kitchen?) to the west; a smaller room with a corner fireplace (parlor?) at the southeast corner; and another smaller room with a corner fireplace (bed chamber?) at the northeast corner.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|2}} A datestone&mdash;not original, added {{circa}}1913\u201315,<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|5}} and now in the collection of the Lower Merion Historical Society&mdash;reads \"J & G / R / 1683.\"<ref name=\"LMHS\"/>\n\nUnder Isaac Warner Roberts the first fire insurance survey was made of the house in 1827. It listed the dimensions of the original house, a one-and-a-half-story stone kitchen, and a \"new\" one-story stone wash house.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|3}} He probably built the hexagonal smokehouse with Gothic windows in the second quarter of the 19th century.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|3}} An 1835 insurance survey recorded his {{convert|19|x|27|ft|m|abbr=on}} two-story stone addition, a new kitchen with a bedroom above.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|3}} Fifteen-year-old [[:en:George Brooke Roberts|George Brooke Roberts]] drew an elevation of his parents' house in 1849, showing the 1835 addition.{{efn|Loth assumed that the two-story addition was new in 1849, when GBR drew the elevation. page 39.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>}} In his will, Roberts divided the farm in half (including the section in Blockley Township), bequeathing the western half (with Pencoyd house) to son George, and the eastern half (along the river) to son Algernon Sidney Roberts. In 1866, Rosalinda Roberts (widow of Isaac Warner Roberts) converted the 1835 kitchen into a dining room, built a new stone kitchen, and made other additions, including an entrance porch with ornamental cast-ironwork.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|3}} She added indoor plumbing and the house's first bathroom&mdash;an 8 x 8&nbsp;ft frame addition built atop posts and attached to the north wall. Access to the bathroom was from the stair landing between the first and second floors, with water supplied from a cedar cistern in the attic.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|3}}\n\nGeorge Brooke Roberts hired architect [[Allen Evans]], of [[Furness & Evans]], to modernize and expand the house, 1883\u201384. Evans designed a two-and-a-half-story, gambrel-roofed east wing&mdash;anchored by a massive \"upside down\" brick chimney&mdash;that extended the length of the front (south) fa\u00e7ade to {{convert|92|ft|m|abbr=off}}.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|6}} Evans also may have designed later additions, 1888\u201389,<ref>Mutual Assurance Company, Policy #4613, George Brooke Roberts, Resurvey May 29, 1890.</ref> and 1891\u201392.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|4}} \n<blockquote>The house was expanded and altered so greatly that it looked like a quite different sort of dwelling than before. George tore down the wing which his father had built and in its place erected an even larger extension, as tall as the original house but of a different style of architecture. In the course of time he also added in another direction [north] a new drawing room, dining room, morning room and sunporch, relocated the driveway and built various porches and balconies. Indoors the main part of the house was redecorated to conform to the fashions of the day.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|48}}</blockquote>\nRoberts also subdivided his half of the farm into generous lots, which he gave to his six children to build their own houses.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|55}}\n\nT. Williams Roberts inherited Pencoyd, and demolished or refaced his father's Victorian additions. He hired architect Louis Carter Baker, Jr., a fellow vestryman of St. Asaph's Church, to restore the house in a tasteful [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]] style, 1913\u201315.<ref>\"Portfolio of Current Architecture,\" ''The Architectural Record'', vol. 37, no. 4 (April 1915), pp. 370\u201373.[https://archive.org/stream/architecturalrec37newyuoft#page/370/mode/2up]</ref> This included a 4-bay, {{convert|34|ft|m|adj=on}} extension of the front fa\u00e7ade (replicating that of the original house),<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|6}} moving the house's main entrance to the east facade, and removing interior walls to make the original house's entire first floor an expansive livingroom. In 1937, Pencoyd stood on about {{convert|35|acre|ha|abbr=off}}, among other [[gentleman's farm]]s.<ref name=\"1937 atlas\">''Property Atlas of the Main Line, Penna.'' (Franklin Survey Company, 1937), plate 8.</ref> After World War II, he sold land at the northwest corner of City and Monument Avenues to the [[Philadelphia Evening Bulletin]] for [[WCAU|WCAU-TV]], the newspaper's local television station.{{efn|WCAU-TV was a [[CBS]] affiliate from 1948 to 1995. Since 1995 it has been an [[NBC]] affiliate.}} Architect [[George Howe (architect)|George Howe]] designed the [[International Style (architecture)|International Style]] television studio building (1951\u201352),<ref>[https://www.philadelphiabuildings.org/pab/app/pj_display.cfm/113870 WCAU-TV Station,] from Philadelphia Architects and Buildings.</ref> one of his final works.\n\nT. Williams Roberts died in 1962. His nephew, architect George B. Roberts, made measured drawings of Pencoyd. HABS photographer Cortlandt V. D. Hubbard photographed it in 1963, and architect James C. Massey completed his HABS survey of it in 1964. This activity was in expectation of the house's demolition and the property's development as a suburban office campus. The Estate of T. Williams Roberts sold the house in 1964,<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|5}} the same year it was demolished.\n\nA [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] department store now occupies the house's site.\n<gallery perrow=5>\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Photocopy, SOUTH (FRONT) ELEVATION, 1870. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, Montgomery County, PA HABS PA,46-BALA,1-2.tif|\"Pencoyd\" in 1870, from the south. The cast-iron entrance porch was added in 1866.\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, PHOTOCOPY OF c.1872 PHOTOGRAPH. - Pencoyd Farm, Smokehouse, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, Montgomery County, PA HABS PA,46-BALA,1A-1.tif|Smokehouse ({{circa}}1825-50) in a {{circa}}1872 photograph.\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Photocopy, SOUTH AND EAST SIDES, 1891. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, Montgomery County, PA HABS PA,46-BALA,1-3.tif|\"Pencoyd\" in the 1890s, from the southeast. Victorian additions by architect [[Allen Evans]].\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Photocopy, PLAN OF FIRST FLOOR BEFORE 1914 REMODELING. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, Montgomery HABS PA,46-BALA,1-13.tif|First floor plan (1913), prior to restoration, Louis Carter Baker, Jr., architect.\nFile:Architectural Record April 1915 p.372.jpg|Floor plans of restored house (1915), Louis Carter Baker, Jr., architect.\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Cortlandt V.D. Hubbard, Photographer, 1963 SOUTH AND EAST SIDES. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, HABS PA,46-BALA,1-5.tif|East fa\u00e7ade of restored house and new main entrance, in 1963.\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Cortlandt V.D. Hubbard, Photographer, 1963 LIVING ROOM, FIRST FLOOR, SOUTHWEST ROOM. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township HABS PA,46-BALA,1-7.tif|Living room in 1963.\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Cortlandt V.D. Hubbard, Photographer, 1963 DINING ROOM, FIRST FLOOR, NORTHEAST ROOM. - Pencoyd Farm, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township HABS PA,46-BALA,1-8.tif|Dining room in 1963.\n</gallery>\n\n==Farm==\n[[File:Historic American Buildings Survey, Cortlandt V.D. Hubbard, Photographer, 1963 SOUTHEAST VIEW. - Pencoyd Farm, Barn, 355 East City Avenue (Lower Merion Township), Bala-Cynwyd, HABS PA,46-BALA,1B-1.tif|thumb|Algernon Roberts's 1791 stone barn, in 1963.]]\nAt the end of the 17th century, John Roberts's principal crop was barley (for making malt), but he also grew Indian corn (for livestock) and wheat.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|6}} His son, Richard, made wheat his principal crop (ground into flour), and provided beef, pork, eggs, fruits and vegetables, and butter to the growing Philadelphia marketplace.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|15}} By the time of John Roberts 2nd, the wonderfully fertile soil was becoming exhausted. He began mixing lime into the soil, and even built his own kiln for burning lime.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|26}} The farm's wooden barn was struck by lightning, September 3, 1760, burning it and other outbuildings. He wrote: \"all that had a farmer[']s store for man and beast were laid to ashes.\"<ref name=\"Loth\">David Loth, ''Pencoyd and the Roberts Family'' (New York: by the author, 1961).</ref>{{rp|22}} A new barn (probably wooden) was built, funded in part by donations from Quaker neighbors.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|17}}\n\nAlgernon Roberts concluded that there was more profit to be made in eggs and dairy products than meat.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|31}} He rented a market stall on Philadelphia's High Street, staffed on market days (Wednesdays and Saturdays) by his tenant farmer and wife.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|32}} One year, they sold 922 pounds of butter.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|32}} In 1791, he built a large stone barn at the north end of the farm.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|32}} The barn's size was considered so extreme that Merion Meeting censured him for \"excessive ostentation.\"<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|32}} In 1827, his son, Isaac Warner Roberts, insured the barn for more than the house. The insurance survey listed the barn's dimensions&mdash;{{convert|76|x|37|ft|m|abbr=on}}&mdash;and \"noted that there were 20 stalls [for cows] with earth floors, racks and mangers. The rest of the ground floor was taken up by 'fodder gangs, fodder rooms, etc.,' the floors of which were of rough oak planks. Upstairs was a threshing floor of oak boards two inches thick. The rest of the structure was devoted to hay mows. The barn was protected by two lightning rods.\"<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|37}}</blockquote> The \"back barn\" was still standing in 1963, when HABS photographed it.{{efn|Algernon Roberts's \"back barn\" was located on a rise of land north of the intersection of St. Asaph's Road and Decker Boulevard. It is now the site of the Bala Plaza office complex.}}\n\nIsaac Warner Roberts insured the stables and a carriage house (east of the main house) in 1827,<ref>Mutual Assurance Company, Policy #4614, Isaac Warner Roberts, Survey November 28, 1827.</ref> which were altered in 1863,<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|43}} and replaced in 1893.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|5}} He divided the farm in half between his two sons. On the eastern half, son Algernon Sidney Roberts (and his cousin) opened a specialty iron foundry, Pencoyd Iron Works, along the Schuylkill River. George Brooke Roberts turned the western half into a model dairy farm, with a herd of [[Guernsey cattle|Guernsey cows]].<ref name=\"LMHS\"/> He erected a new farmhouse, tool house and chicken house, and the eaves of the barn were extended into an \"over shot\" (shed roof) in 1886.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|4}} He demolished the old greenhouse in 1890, and replaced it with a new \"Iron and Wooden one.\"<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|20}} His farm also featured an ice pond and spring house.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|20}}\n\nA new bridge carrying City Avenue over the Schuylkill River was completed in May 1890.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|20}} City Avenue was paved and [[gaslight|gas]] streetlights were erected.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|20}} Farm Road, which separated the two halves of the farm, was renamed Monument Road, and paved in 1891.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|20}}\n\nSome of the farm buildings were converted into residences in the early 20th century.<ref name=\"Massey\"/>{{rp|19}} By the time of T. Williams Roberts's death in 1962, the size of the farm was down to about {{convert|20|acre|ha|abbr=off}}.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|60}}\n\n==Church of Saint Asaph==\n[[File:St Asaph's Hotchkin Rural Pennsylvania 1897.jpg|thumb|Church of Saint Asaph, 1888 perspective drawing by architect Theophilus P. Chandler.]]\n[[File:Pennsylvania Route 23 eastern terminus.jpg|thumb|Entrance to St. Asaph's Church from Conshohocken State Road (left), in 2019]]\nGeorge Brooke Roberts had been born a Quaker, but became an Episcopalian prior to his marriage to Sarah Lapsley Brinton in 1868.<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|45}} She died the following year, at age 23, after giving birth to their only child, George Brinton Roberts. He married Miriam Williams in 1874, and they had five children together. Roberts was the driving force behind building the Church of Saint Asaph.\n\nRoberts obtained permission to create a new Episcopal parish, organized its Board of Trustees, and hosted its first vestry meeting, at Pencoyd on November 16, 1887.<ref name=\"JCR\">Joan Church Roberts, ''Our First One Hundred Years, 1888\u20131988: The Church of Saint Asaph'' (Church of Saint Asaph, 1992).</ref>{{rp|2\u20133}} At the second vestry meeting, December 12, 1887, several sites along City Avenue were discussed, and the name \"[[Saint Asaph]]\" was chosen.{{efn|Saint Asaph had been a 6th century Welsh bishop, but the name also had a Philadelphia connection: Dr. [[Jonathan Shipley]], Bishop of the Diocese of Saint Asaph, Wales, 1769\u201388, was a close friend of Benjamin Franklin. Franklin began writing his famous ''[[Autobiography of Benjamin Franklin|Autobiography]]'' while Shipley's houseguest. page 7.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>}} At the third vestry meeting, January 30, 1888, architect [[Theophilus P. Chandler, Jr.]] was a guest.{{efn|Chandler had already designed investment properties for George Brooke Roberts.<ref name=\"JCR\"/> His presence at the vestry meeting with plans already in hand was no coincidence.}} He submitted a general plan for a church, which was accepted, and he was elected to the vestry that night.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|4}} At the same meeting, Roberts announced that he and his sisters wished to donate land at the west end of Pencoyd Farm, along Conshohocken State Road, as the site for the church, which the vestry also accepted.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|4}}\n\nChandler may have based his design on [[Saint Asaph Cathedral]], a small 14th-century cathedral in [[St. Asaph|Saint Asaph]], [[Denbighshire]], Wales.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|5}} Superficially, both churches share a squat, flat-roofed tower at the [[Crossing (architecture)|crossing]]. Excavation was to begin in mid-March, but was interrupted by the [[Great Blizzard of 1888]].<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|7}} The church's cornerstone was laid, May 8, 1888.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|8}} Chandler also designed the church's rectory, which Roberts donated in thanksgiving for the birth of his daughter Miriam that summer.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|10}} The opening service in the nearly-completed church was held on March 24, 1889.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|14}} The following Sunday, Chandler placed the signed bill for his services in the [[collection plate]], indicating that he regarded it as paid in full, along with a monetary contribution.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|4}}\n\nRoberts was the church's first rector's warden, serving until his death in 1897.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|109}} He was initially buried at [[Laurel Hill Cemetery]], but was later reinterred in the church's cemetery. His son, T. Williams Roberts, served as a vestryman for 42 years, and accounting warden for 29 years.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|109}} Architect Louis Carter Baker, Jr. designed alterations to the church and rectory, and served on the vestry from 1908 to his death in 1915.<ref name=\"JCR\"/>{{rp|36\u201337}}\n\n==Pencoyd Iron Works==\nIn 1852, Algernon Sidney Roberts (who would later inherit the eastern half of Pencoyd farm) and his cousin Percival Roberts founded the A. & P. Roberts Company, a specialty iron foundry located along the Schuylkill River, opposite [[Manayunk, Philadelphia|Manayunk]].<ref name=\"PIW\"/> The company initially made railroad equipment, but soon began manufacturing iron bridge members.<ref name=\"PIW\">[http://www.pennrealestategroup.com/pencoyd_ironworks_history.htm The History of the Pencoyd Iron Works,] from Penn Real Estate Group.</ref> It won the contract to manufacture all the structural elements for the cast-iron-and-glass Main Exhibition Building and Machinery Hall at the [[1876 Centennial Exposition]]. The Main Exhibition Building was to be the largest building in the world. Designed by [[Wilson Brothers & Company]], it was {{convert|1,880|ft|m|abbr=on}} in length, {{convert|464|ft|m|abbr=on}} in width, and enclosed {{convert|21.5|acre|ha|abbr=off}} of space. Machinery Hall, also designed by the Wilson Brothers, was {{convert|1402|ft|m|abbr=on}} in length, {{convert|360|ft|m|abbr=on}} in width, and enclosed {{convert|12.8|acre|ha|abbr=off}}. After the World's Fair, the buildings were auctioned off, disassembled, and their structural elements were reused in other buildings.{{efn|The Main Exhibition Building sold at auction for $250,000.<ref>Sandy Hingston, [http://www.phillymag.com/news/2016/05/10/centennial-exhibition-history/ \"10 Things You Might Not Know About the 1876 Centennial Exhibition,\"] ''Philadelphia Magazine'', May 10, 2016.</ref>}}\n\nPencoyd Iron Works became a major bridge producer, manufacturing and constructing hundreds of bridges in the United States.<ref name=\"PIW\"/> The company built Pencoyd Village \u2013 a community of 70 worker houses,{{efn|Most of the worker houses, which once lined Righters Ferry Road,<ref name=\"1937 atlas\"/> have been demolished.}} a public school and a public library \u2013 all squeezed between Pencoyd Farm and [[West Laurel Hill Cemetery]].<ref name=\"Loth\"/>{{rp|43}} The company was purchased by [[J. P. Morgan]] in 1900, [[List of companies consolidated into American Bridge Company|one of 28 companies consolidated into the American Bridge Company]].<ref name=\"PIW\"/> The [[American Bridge Company]] became part of [[United States Steel]] in 1902.<ref name=\"PIW\"/> Pencoyd Iron Works closed in the 1940s, and most of the steel mill was demolished in the 1950s for construction of the [[Schuylkill Expressway]].<ref name=\"PIW\"/> \n\nThe \"Pencoyd Bridge over Schuylkill River,\" a two-span, 1899 iron [[Truss bridge#Parker (camelback) truss|Parker truss bridge]] that connected the foundry to Manayunk, is now part of the Pencoyd Trail and open to pedestrians and bikes. The Schuylkill Expressway's 1950s Pencoyd [[Viaduct]], between the Belmont Avenue and City Avenue exits, is also (inaccurately) called the \"Pencoyd Bridge.\"\n<gallery>\nFile:AmCyc Philadelphia - Main Exhibition Building.jpg|Main Exhibition Building, 1876 Centennial Exposition, Philadelphia\nFile:Construction of the Netherlands department in the main exhibition building of the Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia in 1876.jpg|Interior of Main Exhibition Building, 1876 Centennial Exposition, Philadelphia\nFile:Pencoyd Iron Works Port of Philadelphia 1914 p.58.jpg|Pencoyd Iron Works, in 1914, at background left. Pencoyd Bridge is visible in the background center.\nFile:Manayunk, Philadelphia (2015).jpg|Site of Pencoyd Iron Works, in 2015. Righters Ferry Road passes under the railroad line at bottom left.\nFile:View from Manayunk Bridge, October 2014.jpg|Schuylkill Expressway Pencoyd Viaduct, in 2014, at far right. Manayunk is left.\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n*[http://www.saintasaphs.org/ Church of Saint Asaph website]\n\n{{coord|40.006444|-75.216741|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-PA|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1690]]\n[[Category:Frank Furness buildings]]\n[[Category:Houses in Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Lower Merion Township, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Welsh-American culture in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "BoringHistoryGuy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChurch of Saint Asaph", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pencoyd_(Bala_Cynwyd,_Pennsylvania)"}
{"title_page": "Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox official post\n|post            = Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering\n|insignia        = Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering logo.png\n|insigniasize    = 150\n|insigniacaption = Logo of the Office of the Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering\n|department      = [[Office of the Secretary of Defense]]\n|reports_to      = [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]]<br>[[United States Deputy Secretary of Defense|Deputy Secretary of Defense]]\n|image           = Michael D. Griffin (cropped).jpg\n|incumbent       = [[Michael D. Griffin]]\n|incumbentsince  = 19 February 2018\n|nominator       = The [[President of the United States|President]]<br>with the [[advice and consent]] of the [[United States Senate|Senate]]\n|termlength      = No fixed term\n|website         = {{url|https://www.cto.mil/|Office of the Under Secretary}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering''', abbreviated '''USD(R&E)''' is a senior official of the [[United States Department of Defense]]. The USD(R&E) and the office s/he heads are charged with the development and oversight of DoD technology strategy for the DoD.  The post (or effectively the same post) has at various times had the titles '''Assistant Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering''' ('''ASD(R&E)'''), or '''Director of Defense Research and Engineering''' ('''DDR&E''').  The latter title has itself historically varied between the rank of under secretary and that of assistant secretary.\n\nUSD(R&E) is the principal staff advisor for research and engineering matters to the [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary]] and Deputy Secretary of Defense. In this capacity, USD(R&E) serves as the [[Chief Technology Officer]] (CTO) for the Department of Defense charged with the development and oversight of DoD technology strategy in concert with the department\u2019s current and future requirements. The goal of USD(R&E) is to extend the capabilities of current war fighting systems, develop breakthrough capabilities, hedge against an uncertain future through a set of scientific and engineering options and counter strategic surprise.  USD(R&E) also provides advice and assistance in developing policies for rapid technology transition.\n\nFrom 1987 until 1 February 2018, ASD(R&E) was subordinate to the Under Secretary of Defense for Acquisition, Technology and Logistics.  On 1 February 2018, the research and engineering were split into an independent office, with the head position being elevated from an assistant secretary to an under secretary level.  The remaining acquisition office became the Office of the [[Under Secretary of Defense for Acquisition and Sustainment]] (A&S).<ref name=\":1\" />  The current under secretary is [[Michael D. Griffin]], who took office on 15 February 2018, following nomination by President [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news |title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Key Additions to his Administration |date=4 December 2017 |accessdate=22 February 2018 |website=[[whitehouse.gov]] |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/president-donald-j-trump-announces-key-additions-administration-21/}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Organization ==\nOrganizations included under the USD(R&E) include the following.  As of February 2018, organizational relationships remained to be finalized as the organization was being formed.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.acq.osd.mil/fo/docs/Section-901-FY-2017-NDAA-Report.pdf|title=Report to Congress: Restructuring the Department of Defense Acquisition, Technology and Logistics Organization and Chief Management Officer Organization|date=1 August 2017|website=|access-date=22 February 2018}}</ref>  The organizational structure was finalized in July 2018.  Agencies marked with an asterisk (*) are not part of the [[Office of the Secretary of Defense]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defensenews.com/pentagon/2018/07/17/revealed-the-new-structure-for-the-pentagons-tech-and-acquisition-offices/|title=Revealed: The new structure for the Pentagon\u2019s tech and acquisition offices|last=Mehta|first=Aaron|date=2018-07-17|website=Defense News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref>\n\n* [[Deputy Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fcw.com/articles/2018/03/05/dod-research-engineering-deputy-porter.aspx|title=White House names deputy undersecretary for DOD R&E|last=Johnnson|first=Derek B.|date=5 March 2018|website=FCW||access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n**Technical Director of Defense Research and Engineering for AI\n**Technical Director of Defense Research and Engineering for 5G\n* Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Research and Technology\n** Deputy Director for Strategic Technology Protection and Exploitation\n***[[Defense Microelectronics Activity]]*\n** Deputy Director for Research, Technology, and Laboratories\n**[[Defense Technical Information Center]]*\n* Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Advanced Capabilities\n** Deputy Director for Mission Engineering and Integration\n** Deputy Director for Developmental Test and Evaluation\n***[[Test Resource Management Center]]*\n*Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Modernization\n**Assistant Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Biotechnology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/johncumbers/2019/09/24/with-great-power-comes-great-responsibility--meet-alexander-titus-the-department-of-defenses-head-of-biotechnology/|title=\u201cWith Great Power Comes Great Responsibility\u201d \u2014 Meet Alexander Titus The Department Of Defense\u2019s Head Of Biotechnology|last=Cumbers|first=John|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/Our-Story/Biographies/Biography/Article/1845752/dr-alexander-titus/|title=Dr. Alexander Titus > U.S. DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE > Biography|website=www.defense.gov|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n**Assistant Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Autonomy\n**Assistant Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Cyber<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/Our-Story/Biographies/Biography/Article/1845739/dr-daniel-j-ragsdale/|title=Dr. Daniel J. Ragsdale > U.S. DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE > Biography|website=www.defense.gov|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n**Assistant Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Directed Energy<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/Our-Story/Biographies/Biography/Article/1808202/dr-thomas-j-karr/|title=Dr. Thomas J. Karr > U.S. DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE > Biography|website=www.defense.gov|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n**Assistant Director of Defense Research and Engineering for FNC3\n**Assistant Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Hypersonics<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Transcripts/Transcript/Article/2101062/department-of-defense-press-briefing-on-hypersonics/|title=Department of Defense Press Briefing on Hypersonics|website=U.S. DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n**Assistant Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Microelectronics<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/Our-Story/Biographies/Biography/Article/1848311/ms-nicole-m-petta/|title=Ms. Nicole M. Petta > U.S. DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE > Biography|website=www.defense.gov|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n**Assistant Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Quantum Science<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/Our-Story/Biographies/Biography/Article/1890149/dr-paul-lopata/|title=Dr. Paul Lopata > U.S. DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE > Biography|website=www.defense.gov|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n**Assistant Director of Defense Research and Engineering for Space\n*[[Strategic Intelligence Analysis Cell]]\n*[[Strategic Capabilities Office]]\n*[[Defense Innovation Unit]]\n* [[Missile Defense Agency]]*\n* [[DARPA]]*\n\nUpon the February 2018 reorganization, the USD(R&E) assumed responsibility for administering the [[Small Business Innovation Research]] and Rapid Innovation Fund programs.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==History==\n\nThe National Security Act of 1947 and its 1949 amendments established the Department of Defense, including the establishment of two statutory boards: a Munitions Board, and a Research and Development Board.  In June 1953, President Eisenhower\u2019s Reorganization Plan No. 6 abolished the boards as such, and created six new Assistant Secretaries of Defense. Two of these assistant secretary positions\u2014Applications Engineering, and Research and Development\u2014were combined in March 1957 to become the Assistant Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering (ASD(R&E)).\n\nUnder the DoD Reorganization Act of 1958 (PL 85-599, effective 6 August 1958), the position of ASD(R&E) was abolished and replaced by a Director of Defense Research and Engineering (DDR&E).\n\nFrom 19 May 1961, until 15 July 1965, a Deputy Director of Defense Research and Engineering held the additional title of ASD(R&E), on the theory that this position reported to, in rank, an under secretary\u2014the DDR&E.  On 21 October 1977, PL 95-140 made the rank of the DDR&E unambiguous by renaming it to the Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering (USD(R&E)).\n\nThe history of Department of Defense management of science and technology up to the 1980s is described at greater length in a report available from the Defense Technical Information Center (DTIC).<ref>O'Neil, William D. and Gene H. Porter, \u201cWhat to Buy? The Role of Director of Defense Research and Engineering (DDR&E): Lessons from the 1970s,\u201d IDA Paper P-4675 (Alexandria, Virginia: Institute for Defense Analyses, Jan 2011) http://handle.dtic.mil/100.2/ADA549549.</ref>\n\nThe Military Retirement Reform Act of 1986 expanded the scope of USD(R&E) position to encompass acquisition and logistics, as well as technology, and it was renamed USD(AT&L).  A subordinate position at the assistant secretary level was reestablished with the previous title DDR&E.  However, budget control of the technology portfolio was kept by USD(AT&L), diminishing the importance of the DDR&E position subsequently.\n\nOn 7 January 2011, President Obama signed the National Defense Authorization Act with several redesignated titles within the Department of Defense. These changes included renaming the DDR&E as, once again, ASD(R&E).<ref name=\"asd_re\">[http://www.acq.osd.mil/ddre/index.html Assistant Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126215523/http://www.acq.osd.mil/ddre/index.html |date=26 November 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2018, the Office of the [[Under Secretary of Defense for Acquisition, Technology and Logistics]] was split into two new offices: the Office of the Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering (R&E) and the Office of the Undersecretary of Defense for Acquisition and Sustainment (A&S), as a result of the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2017]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.defensenews.com/pentagon/2018/02/01/the-pentagons-acquisition-office-is-gone-heres-what-the-next-120-days-bring/|title=The Pentagon\u2019s acquisition office is gone. Here\u2019s what the next 120 days bring. |last=Mehta|first=Aaron|date=2 February 2018|work=Defense News|access-date=22 February 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Office holders==\n\nThe table below includes both the various names which this position has been named over time, as well as all the holders of those various offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dod.mil/ddre/ddre_history.htm|title=A History of the Office of the Director of Defense Research and Engineering|publisher=DoD|year=2009|accessdate=11 April 2010}}</ref>  Acting officers have a beige background.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"200\" | Name\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"280\" | Tenure\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"215\" | SecDef(s) Served Under\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"215\" | President(s) Served Under\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"  | '''Chairman, Research and Development Board'''\n|-\n| [[Vannevar Bush]] || 30 September 1947 \u2013 14 October 1948 || [[James V. Forrestal]] || [[Harry Truman]]\n|-\n| [[Karl Taylor Compton|Karl T. Compton]] || 15 October 1948 \u2013 14 March 1950 || [[James V. Forrestal]] <br/> [[Louis A. Johnson]] || [[Harry Truman]]\n|-\n| William Webster || 15 March 1950 \u2013 31 July 1951 || [[Louis A. Johnson]] <br/> [[George C. Marshall]] || [[Harry Truman]]\n|-\n| Walter G. Whitman || 1 August 1951 \u2013 29 June 1953 || [[George C. Marshall]] <br/> [[Robert A. Lovett]] <br/> [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charles E. Wilson]] || [[Harry Truman]] <br/> [[Dwight Eisenhower]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | '''Assistant Secretary of Defense (Research and Development)'''\n|-\n| [[Donald A. Quarles]] || 1 September 1953 \u2013 14 August 1955 || [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charles E. Wilson]] || [[Dwight Eisenhower]]\n|-\n| [[Clifford C. Furnas]] || 1 December 1955 \u2013 15 February 1957 || [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charles E. Wilson]] || [[Dwight Eisenhower]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | '''Assistant Secretary of Defense (Applications Engineering)'''\n|-\n| Frank D. Newbury || 18 August 1953 \u2013 17 March 1957 || [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charles E. Wilson]] || [[Dwight Eisenhower]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"  | '''Assistant Secretary of Defense (Research and Engineering)'''\n|-\n| Frank D. Newbury || 18 March 1957 \u2013 17 May 1957 || [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charles E. Wilson]] || [[Dwight Eisenhower]]\n|-\n| Paul D. Foote || 10 September 1957 \u2013 31 October 1958 || [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charles E. Wilson]] <br/> [[Neil H. Mc