{"title_page": "Ganesh Shankar Vidyarthi Puraskar", "text_new": "'''Ganesh Shankar Vidyarthi Puraskar''' is an award  given to renowned journalists by honourable President of India every year from 1989.<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ganesh_Shankar_Vidyarthi#Life</ref>\nThe award was instituted in the memory of Sri [[Ganesh Shankar Vidyarthi]] who fell into an orgy of communal rioting at Kanpur, while he was about to proceed to Karachi to attend the Congress Session. Ganesh Shankar Vidyarthi threw himself in the midst of furious mobs and saved the lives of thousands of innocent persons belonging to both the Hindu and Muslim communities and it was on this mission of mercy that he was butchered to by rioting mob only to be found few days later near litter where it took some time to identify him due to multiple wounds by knife<ref>Gandhi, Rajmohan (2006). Gandhi: The Man, His People, and the Empire. University of California Press. p. 327. ISBN 978-0520255708.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n'''Ganesh Shankar Vidyarthi Puraskar''' is an award  given to renowned journalists by honourable President of India every year from 1989.<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ganesh_Shankar_Vidyarthi#Life</ref>\nThe award was instituted in the memory of Sri [[Ganesh Shankar Vidyarthi]] who fell into an orgy of communal rioting at Kanpur, while he was about to proceed to Karachi to attend the Congress Session. Ganesh Shankar Vidyarthi threw himself in the midst of furious mobs and saved the lives of thousands of innocent persons belonging to both the Hindu and Muslim communities and it was on this mission of mercy that he was butchered to by rioting mob only to be found few days later near litter where it took some time to identify him due to multiple wounds by knife<ref>Gandhi, Rajmohan (2006). Gandhi: The Man, His People, and the Empire. University of California Press. p. 327. ISBN 978-0520255708.</ref>\n", "name_user":