{"title_page": "Cit\u00e9 Frug\u00e8s de Pessac", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name       = Cit\u00e9 Frug\u00e8s de Pessac\n| native_name= \n| image               = \n| location            = \n| address             = [[Pessac]], [[France]]\n| owner               = \n| coordinates         = \n| completion_date     = 1926\n| architect           = [[Le Corbusier]]\n| awards              = \n| references          = \n{{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site\n  |child         = yes\n  |Official_name = [[Cit\u00e9 Frug\u00e8s de Pessac]]\n  |ID            = 1321rev\n  |Criteria      = Cultural: i, ii, vi\n  |Year          = 2016\n  |Area          = \n  |Buffer_zone   = \n}}\n}}\nThe '''Cit\u00e9 Frug\u00e8s de Pessac''' is a housing development located in [[Pessac]], [[France]]. It was designed by noted architect [[Le Corbusier]] as both an architect and a town planner.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1981/03/15/arts/architecture-view-le-corbusier-s-housing-project-flexible-enough-endure-ada.html?pagewanted=all Architecture View - LE CORBUSIER'S HOUSING PROJECT- FLEXIBLE ENOUGH TO ENDURE - by Ada Louise Huxtable - NYTimes.com]</ref> It contained some 70 housing units.\n\nThe district is a part of the works of Le Corbusier listed as [[UNESCO Heritage site|UNESCO heritage]] since 2016<ref>https://whc.unesco.org/fr/list/1321/</ref>.\n\n==History==\nThe building was built as experimental housing for workers.\n\n==Design and construction==\nLe Corbusier took into account prevailing social and economic factors, and was determined to build the plan to provide people with low-cost, predetermined, homogeneous cubist structures.\n\nThe project originated in 1920 with 10 houses built at Lege, near Pessac, for the father of Henry Fruges. Following this initial phase, the project was extended to 200 houses. Only a quarter of this number were built by 1926. \nL-C painted panels of brown, blue, yellow and jade green in response to the clients request for 'decoration'.<ref>Le Corbusier edited by Willy Boesiger, p.26.</ref>\n\nThe layout consists of:\n\nA terrace of about 8 three storey houses with roof gardens.\nBehind them is a terrace of houses connected to each other with a concrete arch which provides a sheltered garden.\nIn the middle of the development are the interlocking houses.<ref> personal visit to Pessac in 1970s</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Lived-In Architecture: Le Corbusier's Pessac Revisited'' by Philippe Boudon\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|44.7990|N|0.6477|W|source:wikidata-and-enwiki-cat-tree_region:FR|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quartiers Modernes Fruges}}\n[[Category:Le Corbusier buildings in France]]\n[[Category:Pessac]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name       = Cit\u00e9 Frug\u00e8s de Pessac\n| native_name= \n| image               = \n| location            = \n| address             = [[Pessac]], [[France]]\n| owner               = \n| coordinates         = \n| completion_date     = 1926\n| architect           = [[Le Corbusier]]\n| awards              = \n| references          = \n{{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site\n  |child         = yes\n  |Official_name = [[Cit\u00e9 Frug\u00e8s de Pessac]]\n  |ID            = 1321rev\n  |Criteria      = Cultural: i, ii, vi\n  |Year          = 2016\n  |Area          = \n  |Buffer_zone   = \n}}\n}}\nThe '''Cit\u00e9 Frug\u00e8s de Pessac''' is a housing development located in [[Pessac]], [[France]]. It was designed by noted architect [[Le Corbusier]] as both an architect and a town planner.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1981/03/15/arts/architecture-view-le-corbusier-s-housing-project-flexible-enough-endure-ada.html?pagewanted=all Architecture View - LE CORBUSIER'S HOUSING PROJECT- FLEXIBLE ENOUGH TO ENDURE - by Ada Louise Huxtable - NYTimes.com]</ref> It contained some 70 housing units.\n\nThe district is a part of the works of Le Corbusier listed as UNESCO heritage since 2016<ref>https://whc.unesco.org/fr/list/1321/</ref>.\n\n==History==\nThe building was built as experimental housing for workers.\n\n==Design and construction==\nLe Corbusier took into account prevailing social and economic factors, and was determined to build the plan to provide people with low-cost, predetermined, homogeneous cubist structures.\n\nThe project originated in 1920 with 10 houses built at Lege, near Pessac, for the father of Henry Fruges. Following this initial phase, the project was extended to 200 houses. Only a quarter of this number were built by 1926. \nL-C painted panels of brown, blue, yellow and jade green in response to the clients request for 'decoration'.<ref>Le Corbusier edited by Willy Boesiger, p.26.</ref>\n\nThe layout consists of:\n\nA terrace of about 8 three storey houses with roof gardens.\nBehind them is a terrace of houses connected to each other with a concrete arch which provides a sheltered garden.\nIn the middle of the development are the interlocking houses.<ref> personal visit to Pessac in 1970s</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Lived-In Architecture: Le Corbusier's Pessac Revisited'' by Philippe Boudon\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|44.7990|N|0.6477|W|source:wikidata-and-enwiki-cat-tree_region:FR|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quartiers Modernes Fruges}}\n[[Category:Le Corbusier buildings in France]]\n[[Category:Pessac]]\n", "name_user": "Jefunky", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cit%C3%A9_Frug%C3%A8s_de_Pessac"}
{"title_page": "Eric Vila", "text_new": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Eric Vila\n| image = \n| caption =\n| number = \n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6 \n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lb = 221\n| league = [[Conference USA]]\n| team = UTEP Miners\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|5|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Girona]], Spain\n| nationality = Spanish\n| high_school = \n| college = \n* [[Texas A&M Aggies men's basketball|Texas A&M]] (2016\u20132017)\n* [[Northwest Florida State College|Northwest Florida State]] (2018\u20132019)\n* [[UTEP Miners men's basketball|UTEP]] (2019\u2013present)\n| career_start =\n| years1 = 2014\u20132016\n| team1 = [[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet|FC Barcelona]]\n| years2 = 2014\u20132016\n| team2 = \u2192[[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet B|FC Barcelona B]]\n| highlights =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Men's basketball}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{bk|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA U16 European Championship]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2014 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|2014 France]]|[[Spain men's national under-16 basketball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Eric Mart\u00ednez Vila''' (born 15 May 1998) is a Spanish [[college basketball]] player for the [[UTEP Miners men's basketball|UTEP Miners]] of the [[Conference USA]].\n\n==Career==\nA native of [[Girona]], he played for [[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet|FC Barcelona]] at the youth level since he was 12 years old. Vila received regular playing time for its [[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet B|reserve team]]. In December 2014, at age 16, he became the youngest player in club history to play in the [[Liga ACB]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Eric Vila and Stefan Peno youngest league debutants in FC Barcelona history |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/1115993/eric-vila-and-stefan-peno-youngest-league-debutants-in-fc-barcelona-history# |publisher=[[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet|FC Barcelona]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nVila started playing college basketball in the United States with [[Texas A&M Aggies men's basketball|Texas A&M]]. After one season, he transferred to [[Fresno State Bulldogs men's basketball|Fresno State]], sitting out his following year, but did not play for the team.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Scott |title=Fresno State lands Texas A&M transfer Eric Vila |url=https://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2017/08/03/fresno-state-lands-texas-am-transfer-eric-vila/ |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=3 August 2017}}</ref> Vila played for [[Northwest Florida State College]] in 2018\u201319 before moving to [[UTEP Miners men's basketball|UTEP]] as a [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] junior.<ref name=\"stringer\">{{cite web |last1=Stringer |first1=Seth |title=Vila\u2019s versatility shining for Raiders |url=https://www.nwfdailynews.com/sports/20181207/vilas-versatility-shining-for-raiders |website=[[Northwest Florida Daily News]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=7 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Chavez |first1=Felix F. |title=UTEP basketball signee Eric Vila having big season on junior college level |url=https://www.elpasotimes.com/story/sports/college/utep/2019/03/15/utep-basketball-signee-eric-vila-stars-northwest-florida-state/3153218002/ |website=[[El Paso Times]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nVila has represented Spain in several international tournaments. In 2014, he helped his team win a bronze medal at the [[2014 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship]] in Latvia. In the [[2017 FIBA Under-19 Basketball World Cup|2017 FIBA Under-19 World Cup]] in [[Cairo]], Vila averaged 13 points, 10.9 rebounds and 2.7 assists per game. At the quarterfinals of the tournament, he recorded 24 points, 11 rebounds and three assists in a 70\u201358 win over [[Argentina men's national under-19 basketball team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Eric Vila with 24 points and 11 rebounds against Argentina |url=http://www.fiba.basketball/world/u19/2017/news/eric-vila-s-double-double-sends-spain-into-semi-finals |publisher=[[FIBA]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=7 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://utepminers.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/eric-vila/6893 UTEP Miners bio]\n*[https://12thman.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/eric-vila/4471 Texas A&M Aggies bio]\n\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet B players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet players]]\n[[Category:Texas A&M Aggies men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Northwest Florida State Raiders men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:UTEP Miners men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Eric Vila\n| image = \n| caption =\n| number = \n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6 \n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lb = 221\n| league = [[Conference USA]]\n| team = UTEP Miners\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|5|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Girona]], Spain\n| nationality = Spanish\n| high_school = \n| college = \n* [[Texas A&M Aggies men's basketball|Texas A&M]] (2016\u20132017)\n* [[Northwest Florida State College|Northwest Florida State]] (2018\u20132019)\n* [[UTEP Miners men's basketball|UTEP]] (2019\u2013present)\n| career_start =\n| years1 = 2014\u20132016\n| team1 = [[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet|FC Barcelona]]\n| years2 = 2014\u20132016\n| team2 = \u2192[[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet B|FC Barcelona B]]\n| highlights =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Men's basketball}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{bk|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA U16 European Championship]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2014 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|2014 France]]|[[Spain men's national under-16 basketball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Eric Mart\u00ednez Vila''' (born 15 May 1998) is a Spanish [[college basketball]] player for the [[UTEP Miners men's basketball|UTEP Miners]] of the [[Conference USA]].\n\n==Career==\nA native of [[Girona]], he played for [[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet|FC Barcelona]] at the youth level since he was 12 years old. Vila received regular playing time for its [[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet B|reserve team]]. In December 2014, at age 16, he became the youngest player in club history to play in the [[Liga ACB]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Eric Vila and Stefan Peno youngest league debutants in FC Barcelona history |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/1115993/eric-vila-and-stefan-peno-youngest-league-debutants-in-fc-barcelona-history# |publisher=[[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet|FC Barcelona]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nVila started playing college basketball in the United States with [[Texas A&M Aggies men's basketball|Texas A&M]]. After one season, he transferred to [[Fresno State Bulldogs men's basketball|Fresno State]], sitting out his following year, but did not play for the team.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Scott |title=Fresno State lands Texas A&M transfer Eric Vila |url=https://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2017/08/03/fresno-state-lands-texas-am-transfer-eric-vila/ |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=3 August 2017}}</ref> Vila played for [[Northwest Florida State College]] in 2018\u201319 before moving to [[UTEP Miners men's basketball|UTEP]] as a [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] junior.<ref name=\"stringer\">{{cite web |last1=Stringer |first1=Seth |title=Vila\u2019s versatility shining for Raiders |url=https://www.nwfdailynews.com/sports/20181207/vilas-versatility-shining-for-raiders |website=[[Northwest Florida Daily News]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=7 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Chavez |first1=Felix F. |title=UTEP basketball signee Eric Vila having big season on junior college level |url=https://www.elpasotimes.com/story/sports/college/utep/2019/03/15/utep-basketball-signee-eric-vila-stars-northwest-florida-state/3153218002/ |website=[[El Paso Times]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nVila has represented Spain in several international tournaments. In 2014, he helped his team win a bronze medal at the [[2014 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship]] in Latvia. In the [[2017 FIBA Under-19 Basketball World Cup|2017 FIBA Under-19 World Cup]] in [[Cairo]], Vila averaged 13 points, 10.9 rebounds and 2.7 assists per game. At the quarterfinals of the tournament, he recorded 24 points, 11 rebounds and three assists in a 70\u201358 win over [[Argentina men's national under-19 basketball team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Eric Vila with 24 points and 11 rebounds against Argentina |url=http://www.fiba.basketball/world/u19/2017/news/eric-vila-s-double-double-sends-spain-into-semi-finals |publisher=[[FIBA]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=7July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://utepminers.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/eric-vila/6893 UTEP Miners bio]\n*[https://12thman.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/eric-vila/4471 Texas A&M Aggies bio]\n\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet B players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet players]]\n[[Category:Texas A&M Aggies men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Northwest Florida State Raiders men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:UTEP Miners men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Vila"}
{"title_page": "Society of the Helpers of the Holy Souls", "text_new": "The '''Society of Helpers''', formerly known as the '''Society of the Helpers of the Holy Souls''', is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[religious congregation]] of women founded in [[Paris]], [[France]] in 1856, with the objective of assisting the [[souls]] in [[Purgatory]] through their service to the needy of the world. The Sisters use the [[postnominal]] initials of \"A.P.\" ({{lang-fr|Auxiliatrices des \u00e2mes du purgatoire}}) in Europe, or, alternately, \"H.H.S\" in English-speaking countries.\n\n==History==\n===Eug\u00e9nie Smet=== \n{{Infobox saint\n|honorific_prefix=Blessed\n|name= Eug\u00e9nie Smet\n|birth_date=25 March 1825\n|death_date=7 February 1871\n|feast_day=February 7\n|venerated_in=[[Roman Catholic Church]]\n|image=\n|imagesize=\n|caption=\n|birth_place=[[Lille]], [[France]] \n|death_place=[[Paris]], [[France]]\n|titles=Foundress\n|beatified_date=26 May 1957\n|beatified_place=[[Rome]], [[Italy]]\n|beatified_by=[[Pope Pius XII]]\n|canonized_date=\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=\n|attributes=\n|patronage=\n|major_shrine=\n|suppressed_date=\n|issues=\n}}\nEug\u00e9nie Smet (25 March 1825 in [[Lille]] &ndash; 7 February 1871), also known as '''s\u0153ur Marie de la Providence''', was a French nun who founded the [[Society of the Helpers|Society of the Helpers of the Holy Souls]] in 1856. Her [[Calendar of saints|feast day]] is 7 February.\n\nShe was born in Lille on 25 March 1825, the daughter of Henri \u00c9douard Joseph and Marie Pauline Joseph Taverne Smet. Her father was a trader from Lille. From 1836 to 1843 she was educated at the Convent of the Sacred Heart in [[Lille]], where she demonstrated a particular devotion to the [[Guardian Angels]].<ref name=Garside/>\n\nIn November 1853, she discovered her mission in the Church. In 1855, the [[John Vianney|Cur\u00e9 d'Ars]] confirmed her in her mission. She went to Paris on 19 January 1856 (the society dates its foundation from this day); three days later, Smet obtained permission of [[Marie-Dominique-Auguste Sibour|Archbishop Sibour]] to establish her congregation in Paris. The community Mademoiselle Smet had gathered round her took possession of No. 16, Rue de la Barouill\u00e8re, on 1 July, 1856.<ref name=society>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/07213a.htm \"Society of the Helpers of the Holy Souls.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 7. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1910. 27 June 2019{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 December 1857, Smet, with five of her first companions, pronounced her first [[religious vows]]. A [[Jesuit]] was appointed [[chaplain]], and the Rule of [[Ignatius of Loyola|St. Ignatius]] was adapted.<ref name=shuk>[http://www.societyofhelpersgb.org/en-us/ourstory.aspx \"Our Story\", Society of Helpers -UK]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AyGv46tnsj8C&pg=PA301 ''Vida de santos'' (Editorial San Pablo), p. 301] {{ISBN|9789978061022}}</ref> The congregation was dedicated to Our Lady of Providence.<ref name=Garside>[https://archive.org/details/TheHelpersOfTheHolySouls/page/n43 Garside, Charles Brierly. ''The Helpers of the Holy Souls'', London: Burns & Oates, 1874]{{PD-notice}}</ref> \n\nEug\u00e9nie Smet died on 7 February 1871,<ref>[https://catholicsaints.info/the-holiness-of-the-church-in-the-nineteenth-century-eugenia-de-smet/ Kempf, SJ. Constantine. \u201cEugenia de Smet\u201d. ''The Holiness of the Church in the Nineteenth Century: Saintly Men and Women of Our Own Times'', 1916. CatholicSaints.Info. 18 March 2018]{{PD-notice}}</ref> of breast cancer, at the age of 45. She is buried in the Montparnasse cemetery. \nEug\u00e9nie Smet, was [[beatified]] in [[Rome]] on May 26, 1957 by [[Pope Pius XII]]. Her feast is kept on February 7, the anniversary of her death.<ref name=society/>\n \n[[Georgiana Fullerton|Lady Georgiana Fullerton]] wrote a biography of Eug\u00e9nie Smet, ''Mere Marie de la Providence''.<ref name=shr>[https://newspapers.bc.edu/?a=d&d=BOSTONSH18930415-01.2.37 \"The society of Helpers of the Holy souls\", ''The Sacred Heart Review'', Volume 9, Number 21, 15 April 1893]</ref> \n\n===Foundation===\nThe first branch house was established at Nantes, July, 1864. In 1867 six nuns were conducted by [[Adrien Languillat|Bishop Adrien Languillat]] to Shanghai to take charge of an orphanage. In December, 1869, a house was established in Brussels. The Helpers did good work in the ambulances for the wounded of both nations during the [[Franco-Prussian War]]. On 25 June, 1878, the constitutions of the order were approved by [[Pope Leo XIII]]. From 1874 to 1880 communities were established at Cannes, Orl\u00e9ans, Tourcoing, and Montmartre.<ref name=society/>\n\n==Present day==\nThe Helpers profess vows of poverty, chastity and obedience, and follow an Ignation spirituality. They have worked with the poor and the marginal of their societies since their founding. They work in a variety of ministries, based in [[Ignatian spirituality]], with the goal of working  for peace and justice in a lifestyle based in [[contemplation]]. Rather than focus on a particular ministry, Smet decided to respond to such needs as presented themselves.<ref name=shuk/> As of 2015 they numbered some 500 Sisters in twenty four countries.\n\n===In the UK===\nThe first foundation in the UK was in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Westminster|Archdiocese of Westminster]], at 23 Queen Anne Street, Cavendish Square. They removed to Gloucester Avenue, Regent's Park, in 1882.<ref name=society/> As of 2019 sisters serve in London, Edinburgh, Glasgow, Liverpool and Burnley.\n\n===US Province===\nIn May, 1892, seven \u201cHelpers\u201d sailed to [[New York City]], and were heartily welcomed by Archbishop [[Michael Corrigan]]. The first convent was a very small house in Seventh Avenue; there they laboured for nearly three years, when they removed to 114 East 86th Street. During 1905 a course of lectures on hygiene and first aid to the injured was given. In 1906, they had five houses in the same neighbourhood. Children from the public schools came to the convents for religious instruction and preparation for First Communion and Confirmation.<ref name=shr/>\nThere were sewing classes for girls. \n\nIn May 1903, some Helpers were sent to St. Louis, Missouri led by Mother Mary St. Bernard. Archbishop [[John J. Glennon]] asked them to work among the African-American community. Home visitation was a major part of the Sisters\u2019 work in North St. Louis.<ref>[https://www.stlmag.com/history/sister-patricia-hottinger-st-louis-last-member-of-the-holy-souls/ Naffziger, Chris. \"The last member of the Helpers of the Holy Souls is leaving St. Louis\", ''St. Louis'', April 5, 2017]</ref>\n\nIn 1905, the Sisters went to San Francisco, where they settled in a house in Howard Street, which was destroyed in the earthquake of 1906.<ref name=society/>  \n\nThe leadership team of the U.S. Province is located in Chicago. The province produces an annual publication, ''Voices of Hope''.<ref>[http://helpers.org/ The Society of Helpers -US Province]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.helpers.org Society of Helpers]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060303003402/http://www.catholic-forum.com/saints/sainte1e.htm Eugenia at Patron Saints Index]\n*[http://www.katolsk.no/biografi/esmet.htm Norse article on Eugenia]\n*[http://www.ewtn.com/library/FAMILY/NAMEINDX.TXT name day index] \n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Saints |portal2= Biography |portal3= Catholicism |portal4= France}}\n{{Catholic religious institutes}}\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1856]]\n[[Category:Catholic religious institutes established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Catholic female orders and societies]]\n[[Category:Women's congregations following Ignatian spirituality]]\n[[Category:1856 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:French beatified people]]\n[[Category:Founders of Catholic religious communities]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Society of Helpers''', formerly known as the '''Society of the Helpers of the Holy Souls''', is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[religious congregation]] of women founded in [[Paris]], [[France]] in 1856, with the objective of assisting the [[souls]] in [[Purgatory]] through their service to the needy of the world. The Sisters use the [[postnominal]] initials of \"A.P.\" ({{lang-fr|Auxiliatrices des \u00e2mes du purgatoire}}) in Europe, or, alternately, \"H.H.S\" in English-speaking countries.\n\n==History==\n===Eug\u00e9nie Smet=== \n{{Infobox saint\n|honorific_prefix=Blessed\n|name= Eug\u00e9nie Smet\n|birth_date=25 March 1825\n|death_date=7 February 1871\n|feast_day=February 7\n|venerated_in=[[Roman Catholic Church]]\n|image=\n|imagesize=\n|caption=\n|birth_place=[[Lille]], [[France]] \n|death_place=[[Paris]], [[France]]\n|titles=Foundress\n|beatified_date=26 May 1957\n|beatified_place=[[Rome]], [[Italy]]\n|beatified_by=[[Pope Pius XII]]\n|canonized_date=\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=\n|attributes=\n|patronage=\n|major_shrine=\n|suppressed_date=\n|issues=\n}}\nEug\u00e9nie Smet (25 March 1825 in [[Lille]] &ndash; 7 February 1871), also known as '''s\u0153ur Marie de la Providence''', was a French nun who founded the [[Society of the Helpers|Society of the Helpers of the Holy Souls]] in 1856. Her [[Calendar of saints|feast day]] is 7 February.\n\nShe was born in Lille on 25 March 1825, the daughter of Henri \u00c9douard Joseph and Marie Pauline Joseph Taverne Smet. Her father was a trader from Lille. From 1836 to 1843 she was educated at the Convent of the Sacred Heart in [[Lille]], where she demonstrated a particular devotion to the [[Guardian Angels]].<ref name=Garside/>\n\nIn November 1853, she discovered her mission in the Church. In 1855, the [[John Vianney|Cur\u00e9 d'Ars]] confirmed her in her mission. She went to Paris on 19 January 1856 (the society dates its foundation from this day); three days later, Smet obtained permission of [[Marie-Dominique-Auguste Sibour|Archbishop Sibour]] to establish her congregation in Paris. The community Mademoiselle Smet had gathered round her took possession of No. 16, Rue de la Barouill\u00e8re, on 1 July, 1856.<ref name=society>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/07213a.htm \"Society of the Helpers of the Holy Souls.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 7. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1910. 27 June 2019{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 December 1857, Smet, with five of her first companions, pronounced her first [[religious vows]]. A [[Jesuit]] was appointed [[chaplain]], and the Rule of [[Ignatius of Loyola|St. Ignatius]] was adapted.<ref name=shuk>[http://www.societyofhelpersgb.org/en-us/ourstory.aspx \"Our Story\", Society of Helpers -UK]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AyGv46tnsj8C&pg=PA301 ''Vida de santos'' (Editorial San Pablo), p. 301] {{ISBN|9789978061022}}</ref> The congregation was dedicated to Our Lady of Providence.<ref name=Garside>[https://archive.org/details/TheHelpersOfTheHolySouls/page/n43 Garside, Charles Brierly. ''The Helpers of the Holy Souls'', London: Burns & Oates, 1874]{{PD-notice}}</ref> \n\nEug\u00e9nie Smet died on 7 February 1871,<ref>[https://catholicsaints.info/the-holiness-of-the-church-in-the-nineteenth-century-eugenia-de-smet/ Kempf, SJ. Constantine. \u201cEugenia de Smet\u201d. ''The Holiness of the Church in the Nineteenth Century: Saintly Men and Women of Our Own Times'', 1916. CatholicSaints.Info. 18 March 2018]{{PD-notice}}</ref> of breast cancer, at the age of 45. She is buried in the Montparnasse cemetery. \nEug\u00e9nie Smet, was [[beatified]] in [[Rome]] on May 26, 1957 by [[Pope Pius XII]]. Her feast is kept on February 7, the anniversary of her death.<ref name=society/>\n \n[[Georgiana Fullerton|Lady Georgiana Fullerton]] wrote a biography of Eug\u00e9nie Smet, ''Mere Marie de la Providence''.<ref name=shr>[https://newspapers.bc.edu/?a=d&d=BOSTONSH18930415-01.2.37 \"The society of Helpers of the Holy souls\", ''The Sacred Heart Review'', Volume 9, Number 21, 15 April 1893]</ref> \n\n===Foundation===\nThe first branch house was established at Nantes, July, 1864. In 1867 six nuns were conducted by [[Adrien Languillat|Bishop Adrien Languillat]] to Shanghai to take charge of an orphanage. In December, 1869, a house was established in Brussels. The Helpers did good work in the ambulances for the wounded of both nations during the [[Franco-Prussian War]]. On 25 June, 1878, the constitutions of the order were approved by [[Pope Leo XIII]]. From 1874 to 1880 communities were established at Cannes, Orl\u00e9ans, Tourcoing, and Montmartre.<ref name=society/>\n\n==Present day==\nThe Helpers have worked with the poor and the marginal of their societies since their founding. They work in a variety of ministries, based in [[Ignatian spirituality]], with the goal of working  for peace and justice in a lifestyle based in [[contemplation]]. Rather than focus on a particular ministry, Smet decided to respond to such needs as presented themselves.<ref name=shuk/> As of 2015 they numbered some 500 Sisters in twenty four countries.\n\n===In the UK===\nThe first foundation in the UK was in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Westminster|Archdiocese of Westminster]], at 23 Queen Anne Street, Cavendish Square. They removed to Gloucester Avenue, Regent's Park, in 1882.<ref name=society/> As of 2019 sisters serve in London, Edinburgh, Glasgow, Liverpool and Burnley.\n\n===US Province===\nIn May, 1892, seven \u201cHelpers\u201d sailed to [[New York City]], and were heartily welcomed by Archbishop [[Michael Corrigan]]. The first convent was a very small house in Seventh Avenue; there they laboured for nearly three years, when they removed to 114 East 86th Street. During 1905 a course of lectures on hygiene and first aid to the injured was given. In 1906, they had five houses in the same neighbourhood. Children from the public schools came to the convents for religious instruction and preparation for First Communion and Confirmation.<ref name=shr/>\nThere were sewing classes for girls. \n\nIn May 1903, some Helpers were sent to St. Louis, Missouri led by Mother Mary St. Bernard. Archbishop [[John J. Glennon]] asked them to work among the African-American community. Home visitation was a major part of the Sisters\u2019 work in North St. Louis.<ref>[https://www.stlmag.com/history/sister-patricia-hottinger-st-louis-last-member-of-the-holy-souls/ Naffziger, Chris. \"The last member of the Helpers of the Holy Souls is leaving St. Louis\", ''St. Louis'', April 5, 2017]</ref>\n\nIn 1905, the Sisters went to San Francisco, where they settled in a house in Howard Street, which was destroyed in the earthquake of 1906.<ref name=society/>  \n\nThe leadership team of the U.S. Province is located in Chicago. The province produces an annual publication, ''Voices of Hope''.<ref>[http://helpers.org/ The Society of Helpers -US Province]</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.helpers.org Society of Helpers]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060303003402/http://www.catholic-forum.com/saints/sainte1e.htm Eugenia at Patron Saints Index]\n*[http://www.katolsk.no/biografi/esmet.htm Norse article on Eugenia]\n*[http://www.ewtn.com/library/FAMILY/NAMEINDX.TXT name day index] \n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Saints |portal2= Biography |portal3= Catholicism |portal4= France}}\n{{Catholic religious institutes}}\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1856]]\n[[Category:Catholic religious institutes established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Catholic female orders and societies]]\n[[Category:Women's congregations following Ignatian spirituality]]\n[[Category:1856 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:French beatified people]]\n[[Category:Founders of Catholic religious communities]]\n", "name_user": "Manannan67", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePresent day", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Society_of_the_Helpers_of_the_Holy_Souls"}
{"title_page": "Homoscedasticity", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=October 2011}}\n\n[[File:Homoscedasticity.png|thumb|right|Plot with random data showing homoscedasticity: at each value of ''x'', the ''y''-value of the dots has about the same [[variance]].]]\nIn [[statistics]], a [[sequence]] (or a vector) of [[random variable]]s is '''homoscedastic''' {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|h|o\u028a|m|o\u028a|s|k|\u0259|\u02c8|d|\u00e6|s|t|\u026a|k}} if all its random variables have the same finite [[variance]]. This is also known as '''homogeneity of variance'''. The complementary notion is called [[heteroscedasticity]]. The spellings ''homos'''k'''edasticity'' and ''heteros'''k'''edasticity'' are also frequently used.<ref>For the Greek etymology of the term, see {{cite journal |first=J. Huston |last=McCulloch |year=1985 |title=On Heteros*edasticity |journal=[[Econometrica]] |volume=53 |issue=2 |page=483 |jstor=1911250 }}</ref>\n\nAssuming a  variable is homoscedastic when in reality it is heteroscedastic {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|h|\u025b|t|\u0259r|o\u028a|s|k|\u0259|\u02c8|d|\u00e6|s|t|\u026a|k}}) results in unbiased but inefficient point estimates and in biased estimates of standard errors, and may result in overestimating the [[goodness of fit]] as measured by the [[Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient|Pearson coefficient]].\n\n==Assumptions of a regression model==\nA standard assumption in a [[simple linear regression|linear regression]], <math> y_i= X_i \\beta + \\epsilon_i, i =  1,\\ldots, N,  </math> is that  the variance of the disturbance term <math>  \\epsilon_i </math> is the same across observations, and in particular does not depend on the values of the explanatory variables <math> X_i.</math><ref>Peter Kennedy, ''A Guide to Econometrics'', 5th edition, p. 137.</ref>  This is one of the assumptions under which the [[Gauss\u2013Markov theorem]] applies and  ordinary least squares (OLS) gives the   [[best linear unbiased estimator]] (\"BLUE\"). Homoscedasticity is not required for the coefficient estimates to be unbiased, consistent, and asymptotically normal, but it is required for OLS to be efficient.<ref>{{citation|title=Cross-Level Inference|first1=Christopher H.|last1=Achen|first2=W. Phillips|last2=Shively|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1995|isbn=9780226002194|pages=47\u201348|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AEXUlWus4K4C&pg=PA47}}.</ref> It is also required for the   standard errors of the estimates to be unbiased and consistent, so it is required for accurate hypothesis testing, e.g. for a [[Student's t-test|t-test]] of whether a coefficient  is significantly different from zero. \n\nA more formal way to state the assumption of homoskedasticity is that the diagonals of the variance-covariance matrix of <math>  \\epsilon  </math> must all be the same number: <math> E \\epsilon_i\\epsilon_i= \\sigma^2 </math>, where  <math>     \\sigma^2 </math> is the same for all ''i''.<ref>Peter Kennedy, ''A Guide to Econometrics'', 5th edition, p. 136.</ref> Note that this still allows for the off-diagonals, the covariances <math> E \\epsilon_i\\epsilon_j   </math>, to be nonzero, which is a separate violation of the Gauss-Markov assumptions known as serial correlation. The matrices below are covariances when there are just three observations across time. The disturbance in matrix A is homoskedastic; this is the simple case where OLS is the best linear unbiased estimator. The disturbances in matrices B and C are heteroskedastic. In matrix B, the variance is time-varying, increasing steadily across time; in   matrix C, the variance depends on the value of x. The disturbance in matrix D is homoskedastic because the diagonal variances are constant, even though the off-diagonal covariances are non-zero and ordinary least squares is inefficient  for a different reason: serial correlation. \n:<math>\nA = \\sigma^2\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n 1 & 0 & 0   \\\\  \n0 & 1 & 0   \\\\  \n0 & 0 & 1   \\\\  \n\\end{bmatrix}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\nB = \\sigma^2\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n 1 & 0 & 0   \\\\  \n0 & 2 & 0   \\\\  \n0 & 0 & 3   \\\\  \n\\end{bmatrix}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\nC = \\sigma^2\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n  x_1 & 0 & 0   \\\\ \n0 & x_2 & 0   \\\\  \n0 & 0 & x_3   \\\\  \n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\nD = \\sigma^2\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n 1 & \\rho & \\rho^2    \\\\  \n\\rho & 1 & \\rho    \\\\  \n\\rho^2 &\\rho  & 1   \\\\ \n\\end{bmatrix}\n</math>\n\n==Example of Lack of Homoskedasticity==\n\nA common reason for the homoskedasticity assumption to be violated is if the disturbance term rises with the value of one of the exogenous variables ''x''.  If ''y'' is consumption, ''x'' is income, and <math>\\epsilon </math> is whims of the consumer, for example, and we are estimating  <math>y_i  = \\beta x_i + \\epsilon_i,</math> then if richer consumers' whims affect their spending more in absolute dollars, we might have  <math>Var(\\epsilon_i) = x_i \\sigma^2,</math> rising with income. Homoskedasticity would require that  <math>Var(\\epsilon_i) =   \\sigma^2,</math> independent of  <math>x_i.</math><ref>Peter Kennedy, ''A Guide to Econometrics'', 5th edition, p. 136.</ref>\n\n==Testing==\nResiduals can be tested for homoscedasticity using the [[Breusch\u2013Pagan test]], which performs an auxiliary regression of the squared residuals on the independent variables. From this auxiliary regression, the explained sum of squares is retained, divided by two, and then becomes the test statistic for a chi-squared distribution with the degrees of freedom equal to the number of independent variables. The null hypothesis of this chi-squared test is homoscedasticity, and the alternative hypothesis would indicate heteroscedasticity. Since the Breusch\u2013Pagan test is sensitive to departures from normality or small sample sizes, the Koenker\u2013Bassett or 'generalized Breusch\u2013Pagan' test is commonly used instead. From the auxiliary regression, it retains the R-squared value which is then multiplied by the sample size, and then becomes the test statistic for a chi-squared distribution (and uses the same degrees of freedom). Although it is not necessary for the Koenker\u2013Bassett test, the Breusch\u2013Pagan test requires that the squared residuals also be divided by the residual sum of squares divided by the sample size.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pryce|first1=Gwilym|title=Heteroscedasticity: Testing and Correcting in SPSS|url=http://reocities.com/Heartland/4205/SPSS/HeteroscedasticityTestingAndCorrectingInSPSS1.pdf|pages=12\u201318|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref> Testing for groupwise heteroscedasticity requires the [[Goldfeld\u2013Quandt test]].\n\n==Homoscedastic distributions==\n\nTwo or more [[normal distribution]]s, <math>N(\\mu_i,\\Sigma_i)</math>, are homoscedastic if they share a common [[covariance matrix|covariance]] (or [[correlation matrix|correlation]]) matrix, <math>\\Sigma_i = \\Sigma_j,\\ \\forall i,j</math>. Homoscedastic distributions are especially useful to derive statistical [[pattern recognition]] and [[machine learning]] algorithms. One popular example is Fisher's [[linear discriminant analysis]].\n\nThe concept of homoscedasticity can be applied to distributions on spheres.<ref>Hamsici, Onur C.; Martinez, Aleix M. (2007) [http://jmlr.csail.mit.edu/papers/volume8/hamsici07a/hamsici07a.pdf \"Spherical-Homoscedastic Distributions: The Equivalency of Spherical and Normal Distributions in Classification\"], ''Journal of Machine Learning Research'', 8, 1583-1623</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bartlett's test]]\n*[[Homogeneity (statistics)]]\n*[[Heterogeneous#Statistics|Heterogeneity]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{statistics}}\n\n[[Category:Statistical deviation and dispersion]]\n\n[[de:Homoskedastizit\u00e4t]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=October 2011}}\n\n[[File:Homoscedasticity.png|thumb|right|Plot with random data showing homoscedasticity: at each value of ''x'', the ''y''-value of the dots has about the same [[variance]].]]\nIn [[statistics]], a [[sequence]] (or a vector) of [[random variable]]s is '''homoscedastic''' {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|h|o\u028a|m|o\u028a|s|k|\u0259|\u02c8|d|\u00e6|s|t|\u026a|k}} if all its random variables have the same finite [[variance]]. This is also known as '''homogeneity of variance'''. The complementary notion is called [[heteroscedasticity]]. The spellings ''homos'''k'''edasticity'' and ''heteros'''k'''edasticity'' are also frequently used.<ref>For the Greek etymology of the term, see {{cite journal |first=J. Huston |last=McCulloch |year=1985 |title=On Heteros*edasticity |journal=[[Econometrica]] |volume=53 |issue=2 |page=483 |jstor=1911250 }}</ref>\n\nAssuming a  variable is homoscedastic when in reality it is heteroscedastic {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|h|\u025b|t|\u0259r|o\u028a|s|k|\u0259|\u02c8|d|\u00e6|s|t|\u026a|k}}) results in unbiased but inefficient point estimates and in biased estimates of standard errors, and may result in overestimating the [[goodness of fit]] as measured by the [[Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient|Pearson coefficient]].\n\n==Assumptions of a regression model==\nA standard assumption in a [[simple linear regression|linear regression]], <math> y_i= X_i \\beta + \\epsilon_i, i =  1,\\ldots, N,  </math> is that  the variance of the disturbance term <math>  \\epsilon_i </math> is the same across observations, and in particular does not depend on the values of the explanatory variables <math> X_i.</math><ref>Peter Kennedy, ''A Guide to Econometrics'', 5th edition, p. 137.</ref>  This is one of the assumptions under which the [[Gauss\u2013Markov theorem]] applies and  ordinary least squares (OLS) gives the   [[best linear unbiased estimator]] (\"BLUE\"). Homoscedasticity is not required for the coefficient estimates to be unbiased, consistent, and asymptotically normal, but it is required for OLS to be efficient.<ref>{{citation|title=Cross-Level Inference|first1=Christopher H.|last1=Achen|first2=W. Phillips|last2=Shively|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1995|isbn=9780226002194|pages=47\u201348|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AEXUlWus4K4C&pg=PA47}}.</ref> It is also required for the   standard errors of the estimates to be unbiased and consistent, so it is required for accurate hypothesis testing, e.g. for a [[Student's t-test|t-test]] of whether a coefficient  is significantly different from zero. \n\nA more formal way to state the assumption of homoskedasticity is that the diagonals of the variance-covariance matrix of y must all be equal: <math> E \\epsilon_i\\epsilon_i= \\sigma^2 </math>, where  <math>     \\sigma^2 </math> is the same for all ''i''.<ref>Peter Kennedy, ''A Guide to Econometrics'', 5th edition, p. 136.</ref> Note that this still allows for the off-diagonals, the covariances <math> E \\epsilon_i\\epsilon_j   </math>, to be nonzero, which is a separate violation of the Gauss-Markov assumptions known as serial correlation. The matrices below are covariances when there are just three observations across time. The disturbance in matrix A is homoskedastic; this is the simple case where OLS is the best linear unbiased estimator. The disturbances in matrices B and C are heteroskedastic. In matrix B, the variance is time-varying, increasing steadily across time; in   matrix C, the variance depends on the value of x. The disturbance in matrix D is homoskedastic because the diagonal variances are constant, even though the off-diagonal covariances are non-zero and ordinary least squares is inefficient  for a different reason: serial correlation. \n:<math>\nA = \\sigma^2\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n 1 & 0 & 0   \\\\  \n0 & 1 & 0   \\\\  \n0 & 0 & 1   \\\\  \n\\end{bmatrix}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\nB = \\sigma^2\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n 1 & 0 & 0   \\\\  \n0 & 2 & 0   \\\\  \n0 & 0 & 3   \\\\  \n\\end{bmatrix}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\nC = \\sigma^2\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n  x_1 & 0 & 0   \\\\ \n0 & x_2 & 0   \\\\  \n0 & 0 & x_3   \\\\  \n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\nD = \\sigma^2\n\\begin{bmatrix}\n 1 & \\rho & \\rho^2    \\\\  \n\\rho & 1 & \\rho    \\\\  \n\\rho^2 &\\rho  & 1   \\\\ \n\\end{bmatrix}\n</math>\n\n==Example of Lack of Homoskedasticity==\n\nA common reason for the homoskedasticity assumption to be violated is if the disturbance term rises with the value of one of the exogenous variables ''x''.  If ''y'' is consumption, ''x'' is income, and <math>\\epsilon </math> is whims of the consumer, for example, and we are estimating  <math>y_i  = \\beta x_i + \\epsilon_i,</math> then if richer consumers' whims affect their spending more in absolute dollars, we might have  <math>Var(\\epsilon_i) = x_i \\sigma^2,</math> rising with income. Homoskedasticity would require that  <math>Var(\\epsilon_i) =   \\sigma^2,</math> independent of  <math>x_i.</math><ref>Peter Kennedy, ''A Guide to Econometrics'', 5th edition, p. 136.</ref>\n\n==Testing==\nResiduals can be tested for homoscedasticity using the [[Breusch\u2013Pagan test]], which performs an auxiliary regression of the squared residuals on the independent variables. From this auxiliary regression, the explained sum of squares is retained, divided by two, and then becomes the test statistic for a chi-squared distribution with the degrees of freedom equal to the number of independent variables. The null hypothesis of this chi-squared test is homoscedasticity, and the alternative hypothesis would indicate heteroscedasticity. Since the Breusch\u2013Pagan test is sensitive to departures from normality or small sample sizes, the Koenker\u2013Bassett or 'generalized Breusch\u2013Pagan' test is commonly used instead. From the auxiliary regression, it retains the R-squared value which is then multiplied by the sample size, and then becomes the test statistic for a chi-squared distribution (and uses the same degrees of freedom). Although it is not necessary for the Koenker\u2013Bassett test, the Breusch\u2013Pagan test requires that the squared residuals also be divided by the residual sum of squares divided by the sample size.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pryce|first1=Gwilym|title=Heteroscedasticity: Testing and Correcting in SPSS|url=http://reocities.com/Heartland/4205/SPSS/HeteroscedasticityTestingAndCorrectingInSPSS1.pdf|pages=12\u201318|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref> Testing for groupwise heteroscedasticity requires the [[Goldfeld\u2013Quandt test]].\n\n==Homoscedastic distributions==\n\nTwo or more [[normal distribution]]s, <math>N(\\mu_i,\\Sigma_i)</math>, are homoscedastic if they share a common [[covariance matrix|covariance]] (or [[correlation matrix|correlation]]) matrix, <math>\\Sigma_i = \\Sigma_j,\\ \\forall i,j</math>. Homoscedastic distributions are especially useful to derive statistical [[pattern recognition]] and [[machine learning]] algorithms. One popular example is Fisher's [[linear discriminant analysis]].\n\nThe concept of homoscedasticity can be applied to distributions on spheres.<ref>Hamsici, Onur C.; Martinez, Aleix M. (2007) [http://jmlr.csail.mit.edu/papers/volume8/hamsici07a/hamsici07a.pdf \"Spherical-Homoscedastic Distributions: The Equivalency of Spherical and Normal Distributions in Classification\"], ''Journal of Machine Learning Research'', 8, 1583-1623</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bartlett's test]]\n*[[Homogeneity (statistics)]]\n*[[Heterogeneous#Statistics|Heterogeneity]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{statistics}}\n\n[[Category:Statistical deviation and dispersion]]\n\n[[de:Homoskedastizit\u00e4t]]\n", "name_user": "Editeur24", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAssumptions of a regression model", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homoscedasticity"}
{"title_page": "Wahidullah Waissi", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox ambassador \n| honorific-prefix = [[His Excellency]] \n|image = Wahidullah Waissi (2012).jpg\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   = Waissi at the Bled Strategic Forum, Slovenia, September 2012\n|name = Wahidullah Waissi<br>{{small|{{lang|ps|\u0648\u062d\u06cc\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0648\u06cc\u0633\u06cc}}}}\n|country = Australia | term_start = February 22, 2017 \n|president    = [[Ashraf Ghani]]\n|predecessor =  Dr. Nasir Ahmad Andisha\n|office1 =     [http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547 Director-General for Economic Cooperation]\n|term_start1  = August 5, 2012\n|term_end1    = February 21, 2017\n|predecessor2 = Dr. Daud Yar\n|successor2   = Hassan Soroosh {{small|(Acting)}}\n|birth_name    = Wahidullah Waissi\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1975|04|18}}\n|birth_place = [[Kabul]], [[Afghanistan]] [[Image:Flag of Afghanistan.svg|25px]] \n|nationality   = [[Afghan]]\n|alma_mater = [[Williams College]], [[United States]]<br>[[Kabul University]]\n|website = [http://www.afghanembassy.net Embassy of I. R. of Afghanistan in Canberra, Australia]\n|footnotes = |office = [http://www.afghanembassy.net/ambassador/ambassadors-message Afghanistan's Ambassador to Australia]}}\n\n'''Wahidullah Waissi''' (born April 18, 1975) is an Afghan diplomat. He is now serving as an Ambassador of [[Afghanistan|Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] to the [[Australia|Commonwealth of Australia]], the [[New Zealand]] and [[Fiji|Republic of Fiji]]. He worked as [http://www.mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547 Director-General for Economic Cooperation]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547|title=Economic Cooperations - Ministry of Foreign Affairs - Islamic Republic of Afghanistan|website=www.mfa.gov.af|access-date=2016-11-08}}</ref> at the [http://www.mfa.gov.af/en Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Islamic Republic of Afghanistan] from 2012 to 2016 overseeing regional economic cooperation and multilateral development partnerships, chaired economic diplomacy committee, coordinated [http://www.recca.af Regional Economic Cooperation Conference for Afghanistan] process and projects and served as a Focal Point for economic [[Confidence-building measures|Confidence Building Measures (CBMs)]] of the [http://www.hoa.gov.af Heart of Asia] Istanbul Process.\n\nWaissi is Co-founder and Chair of the [http://greeningafghanistan.com Green Club], a voluntarily association on environment and green activities. He used to teach economic development at the University of Afghanistan and writes on development, region, [[geoeconomics]] and socio-development issues.\n\n== Early life and education ==\n[[File:CACI CAMCA.jpg|left|thumb|[https://www.flickr.com/photos/rumsfeldfoundation/33472356742/in/photostream/ Waissi at the 2016 CAMCA Regional Forum - Tbilisi, Georgia.]]]\nWahidullah Waissi was born on April 18, 1975 in [[Kabul]]. He has studied in the [[United States]] and holds MA in [[Development economics|Development Economics]] from [https://cde.williams.edu Center for Development Economics] of [[Williams College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cde.williams.edu/people/alumni/|title=Selected Alumni Profiles: Wahidullah Waissi, CDE, Williams College}}</ref> Waissi was one of the [https://cde.williams.edu/people/alumni/ first Afghan students] studied at the CDE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://williamsrecord.com/2004/10/19/rashid-and-waissi-are-first-afghan-students-at-cde/|title=Rashid and Waissi are first Afghan students at CDE|date=2004-10-19|website=The Williams Record|access-date=2016-11-08}}</ref> Among them were fellows from countries near [[Afghanistan]]\u2014the [[Kyrgyzstan|Kyrgyz Republic]], [[Uzbekistan]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://magazine.williams.edu/files/archive/2017-spring.pdf|title=Williams Magazine|date=Spring 2017|publisher=The Williams College}}</ref>\n\nHe is a [[visiting scholar]] of the [[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute]] of the [[Paul H. Nitze School of Advanced International Studies|SAIS/Johns Hopkins University in Washington DC]], a fellowship program for raising regional leaders in government, commerce, and academia from [[Central Asia]], [[Mongolia]], the [[Caucasus]] and [[Afghanistan]] ([https://www.rumsfeldfoundation.org/greater_central_asia/camca CAMCA]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rumsfeldfoundation.org/doclib/201607111_forumreportonlineversion.pdf|title=CAMCA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.silkroadstudies.org/fellowship/item/13057-fall-2014-rumsfeld-fellowship.html|title=CACI, Johns Hopkins University, Washington DC|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nWaissi had also studied [[Results-based management|Results Based Management]] at the [[Shanghai]] based [http://www.afdc.org.cn/default.aspx?l=english&Type=ShipDet Asia-Pacific Finance and Development Institute (AFDI)] in 2007 under a fellowship granted from [http://www.afdc.org.cn/SAG_Index.aspx?Type=ShipDet&l=english Shanghai International Program for Development Evaluation Training (SHIPDET)] program.\n\n== Diplomatic career ==\n[[File:Wahidullah Waissi submits his letter of credential to Peter Cosgrove.png|thumb|[https://www.gg.gov.au/diplomatic-representatives/islamic-republic-afghanistan Waissi submits his letter of credential to Sir Peter Cosgrove, Governor-General of Commonwealth of Australia as the fifth Ambassador of Islamic Republic of Afghanistan to Australia on 1 March 2017, Canberra.]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gg.gov.au/diplomatic-representatives/islamic-republic-afghanistan|title=The Governor-General received from His Excellency Mr Wahidullah Waissi, Letters of Credence accrediting him as the Ambassador of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan. 1 March 2017, Canberra.}}</ref>|left]]\nWaissi joins [http://mfa.gov.af Ministry of Foreign Affairs] in 2012 as Senior Advisor on regional cooperation. Later, he was appointed as [http://www.mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547 Director-General for Economic Cooperation]<ref name=\":2\" /> at the [http://www.mfa.gov.af/en Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Islamic Republic of Afghanistan] (2012 to 2016). In this position he was overseeing regional economic cooperation and multilateral development partnerships, chairing Economic Diplomacy Committee, coordinates [http://www.recca.af Regional Economic Cooperation Conference for Afghanistan] and serving as a national Focal Point for economic Confidence Building Measures of [http://www.hoa.gov.af Heart of Asia] Istanbul Process. \n\nWaissi was coordinating infrastructure project negotiation phases for [[Turkmenistan\u2013Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan\u2013India Pipeline|TAPI]], [http://www.casa-1000.org CASA-1000], TAT Railway, regional transit and transport agreements and projects and [http://recca.af/?page_id=2108 Special Economic Zones/Dry Ports].\n\n=== Ambassador accredited to Australia, New Zealand and Fiji ===\n[[File:Credential's submission ceremony of Wahidullah Waissi to Australia.jpg|thumb|Waissi at the ceremony of credential's submission to the Governor-General of Australia, 1 March 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gg.gov.au/diplomatic-representatives/islamic-republic-afghanistan|title=Ceremony of Credentials Submission}}</ref>]]\n\nWaissi was appointed as the [[Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary]] of the [[Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] to the [[Commonwealth of Australia]] in February 2017 and as a non-resident Ambassador to [[New Zealand]] and [[Fiji]] on 12 August 2017 and 24 April 2018 respectively. As an ambassador, this is his first mission abroad. Waissi has submitted his letter of credentials to [[Peter Cosgrove|Sir Peter Cosgrove]], [[Governor-General of Australia|Governor-General of Commonwealth of Australia]] on 1 March 2017 and to [[Patsy Reddy|Dame Patsy Reddy]], [[Governor-General of New Zealand]] on 6 September 2017 as the fifth Ambassador of Afghanistan to both [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gg.gov.au/diplomatic-representatives/islamic-republic-afghanistan|title=The Governor-General received from His Excellency Mr Wahidullah Waissi, Letters of Credence accrediting him as the Ambassador of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan.|archive-date=1 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gg.govt.nz/governor-general/blog/2017/09/credentials-ceremony-6-september-2017|title=Credentials Ceremony 6 September 2017|website=gg.govt.nz }}</ref>\n[[File:Wahidullah Waissi and Dame Patsy Reddy after Waissi's credentials ceremony to New Zealand.jpg|thumb|HE the Rt Hon Dame Patsy Reddy with HE Mr Wahidullah Waissi, the Ambassador of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gg.govt.nz/image-galleries/7241/media?page=11|title=Credentials Ceremony 6 September 2017 {{!}} The Governor-General of New Zealand|website=gg.govt.nz|language=en|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Wahidullah Waissi's credential ceremony to Fiji.jpg|thumb|President [[Jioji Konrote|Major-General (Ret\u2019d) Jioji Konrote]] (left), with the non-resident Ambassador of the [[Afghanistan|Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] to the [[Fiji|Republic of Fiji]], HE Wahidullah Waissi (right), at Borron House on April 24, 2018. Photo: DEPTFO News]]\n[[File:Ambassador Waissi with Prime Minister Turnbull.jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull greets the Ambassador to Australia, Wahidullah Waissi, before a statement from the leaders remembering the victims of the bombing in Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/live/2017/jun/01/pauline-hanson-received-donations-to-personal-bank-account-politics-live|title=Australian Politics|last=Photograph: Mike Bowers for the Guardian|date=1 June 2017|website=www.theguardian.com/australia-news/live/2017/jun/01/pauline-hanson-received-donations-to-personal-bank-account-politics-live}}</ref>]]\nAs the first Afghan President visiting Australia, [[Ashraf Ghani|Dr. Mohammad Ashraf Ghani]] arrived to [[Canberra]] on 2 April 2017 for an almost 3 days visit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/foreign-affairs/first-visit-to-australia-by-afghan-president/news-story/28d7ddd65098e31412aec7b6827f3de7|title=First visit to Australia by Afghan president|date=3 April 2017}}</ref> Marking the visit, Prime Minister [[Malcolm Turnbull]] said Afghanistan and Australia had forged a \u201csolid connection\u201d for more than a century. From [[Afghan (Australia)|Afghan cameleers]] in the 1860s, through to the Australian military effort to free Afghanistan of [[terrorism]], the two nations have long maintained a healthy partnership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/2017-04-02/president-afghanistans-visit-australia|title=President of Afghanistan Visit's to Australia}}</ref> Discussions were mainly focused on security and development co-operation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/2017-04-04/outcomes-president-ghanis-visit-australia|title=Outcome of President Ghani's Visit to Australia|website=pm.gov.au}}</ref>\n\n=== Regional Economic Cooperation Conference on Afghanistan (RECCA) ===\n[[File:RECCA VI Doc.png|thumb|The Silk Road through Afghanistan strategy presented at the [http://recca.af/?page_id=490 Sixth Regional Economic Cooperation Conference] in Kabul, 2015.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Towards Regional Economic Growth & Stability: The Silk Road through Afghanistan|last=|first=|publisher=Directorate-General for Economic Cooperation, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Afghanistan|year=2015|isbn=|location=Kabul|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://recca.af/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/main-document1.pdf|title=The Silk Road through Afghanistan}}</ref>]]\nOne of the efforts that have been striving to have regional economic cooperation in South and Central Asia so as to assist Afghanistan is [http://www.recca.af Regional Economic Cooperation Conference on Afghanistan (RECCA)]. RECCA is a forum that has been managed to promote stabilization in Afghanistan and [[South Asia|South]] and [[Central Asia]]n regional economic integration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://recca.af/?page_id=578|title=Regional Economic Cooperation Conference on Afghanistan (RECCA)}}</ref>\n\nWaissi have been engaged on developing the first Regional Cooperation Strategy for the ANDS since 2005. This strategy made the platform for broader regional cooperation discussion among immediate neighbors and far neighboring countries of Afghanistan. The first regional economic cooperation conference under the title of [http://recca.af/?page_id=578 RECCA has been inaugurated in Kabul in 2005]. More annual RECCA meetings were hosted in [http://recca.af/?page_id=572 New Delhi in 2006], [http://recca.af/?page_id=569 Islamabad in 2007], [http://recca.af/?page_id=560 Istanbul in 2009], [http://recca.af/?page_id=549 Dushanbe in 2012] and back in [http://recca.af/?page_id=490 Kabul in 2015]. Waissi played a major role in organization and coordination of the last two RECCA events in Dushanbe and Kabul.\n\nThe [http://recca.af/?page_id=490 RECCA process in 2015] covers a broader range of economic activities in forms of energy cooperation, connectivity, and business to business opportunities in the region. Waissi and his team at the [http://www.mfa.af Ministry of Foreign Affairs] have launched a new website ([http://www.recca.af www.recca.af])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.recca.af|title=RECCA Website}}</ref> to include necessary information about status of projects under the RECCA process for a wider outreach. He also initiated identifying [http://recca.af/?page_id=1722 RECCA Focal Points] from 16 countries for better coordination of regional project's implementation. The first meeting of the [http://recca.af/?page_id=1722 RECCA Focal Points] took place on 26 August 2017 in Kabul.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://recca.af/?p=2440|title=The First RECCA National Focal Points Meeting was held on August 26, 2017 at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Afghanistan with the participation of the National Focal Points from RECCA regional countries.|website=recca.af }}</ref> The Seventh RECCA meeting will be hosted by the [[Turkmenistan]] Government in [[Ashgabat]] in November 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://recca.af/?p=2431|title=Seventh Meeting of the Regional Economic Cooperation Conference on Afghanistan (RECCA VII) scheduled to take place from 14-15 November 2017 in Ashgabat, Turkmenistan.|website=recca.af }}</ref>\n\n=== Chabahar Agreement ===\n[[File:Chabahar Agreement.png|thumb|[http://afghanembassy.in/en/media-menu/news/687-afghanistan-india-and-iran-initial-momentous-agreement-on-chabahar Afghanistan, India and Iran completed text of the Chabahar Agreement, New Delhi, 11 May 2016]|left]]\nWaissi was a lead-negotiator for the [http://recca.af/?page_id=2083 International Transport and Transit Corridor] (also known as the 'Chabahar Agreement') on behalf of the Afghan Government since 2012, when the primary discussion over this agreement started in 2012 in Tehran between [[Afghanistan]], [[Iran]] and [[India]] and to its signing ceremony. On 23 May 2016, the Agreement was signed in Tehran, Iran, by the Afghan [[Ministry of Transport and Civil Aviation (Afghanistan)|Minister of Transport and Civil Aviation]], the Indian [[Ministry of Shipping (India)|Minister of Shipping, Road Transport, and Highways]] and the Iranian [[Ministry of Roads and Urban Development (Iran)|Ministry of Road and Urban Development]], while the three heads of states, President Mohammad Ashraf Ghani, President [[Hassan Rouhani]] and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] were present. The agreement later approved by the Cabinet of the Afghan Government on 3 August 2016 and ratified by the Afghan National Assembly (Parliament).\n\nThe Agreement aims to: 1) Facilitate access to international markets by using land, sea, and/or air transportation through [[Chabahar Port]]; and 2) Simplify, harmonize, and standardize procedures governing the international transport and transit of goods and passengers, in accordance with the international agreements and conventions in which the three signatory governments are members.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://recca.af/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/RECCA-Annual-Review-2016-light-version.pdf|title=From Negotiation to Investment, Construction, & Trade: A New Decade of Progress - RECCA Annual Review 2016|date=15 September 2016|website=www.recca.af}}</ref>\n\nThe Chabahar Agreement is the first multilateral transit and transport agreement of its kind that [[Afghanistan]] signs with other countries. It basically connects [[South Asia]] with [[Central Asia]], and [[Gulf Region|Gulf region]] with [[Central Asia]] and [[Caucasus]] markets. [[Chabahar Port|The ports in Chabahar]] will considerably cut transportation costs and time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://afghanembassy.in/en/news/687-afghanistan-india-and-iran-initial-momentous-agreement-on-chabahar|title=Finalization of the text of the Chabahar Agreement, New Delhi.|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== The Lapis Lazuli Route ===\n{{main|Lapis Lazuli corridor}}\n[[File:Lapis Lazuli Route Agreement text finalized.jpg|thumb|[http://afghanembassyturkmenistan.com/text-of-the-lapis-lazuli-route-agreement-finalized/ Text of the Lapis Lazuli Route Agreement was finalized in Baku between Afghanistan, Georgia, Azerbaijan, Turkey and Turkmenistan in its fourth technical meeting on 16 November 2016]]]\nAfghanistan as a landlocked country needs more diversified transit policy. Alternative routes and corridors are always helpful for the domestic economy as well as regional connectivity. This was the biggest motivation for Waissi to initiate an alternative transit route, later called the Lapis Lazuli Transit and Transport Route. His ideas was accepted by [[Jawed Ludin]], former Deputy Foreign Minister of [[Afghanistan]] and later by Zarar Ahmad Osmani, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Afghanistan)|former Minister of Foreign Affairs of Afghanistan]]. Waissi was being appointed immediately by Minister Osmani to follow with the concerned counties and coordinate to become a party to this initiative. Turkmenistan, [[Azerbaijan]] and Georgia immediately joined and [[Turkey]] was the last country to become as a party to this initiative. In early 2014 Waissi and a team of experts from the Afghan Government started the negotiation from [[Ashgabat]] in Turkmenistan. Waissi was leading the negotiation for the agreement on behalf of the Afghan Government.\n\nThe [[Lapis Lazuli corridor]] was opened for business in December 2018.\n\n=== Multilateralism & Multilateral Diplomacy ===\n[[File:Wahidullah Waissi UNGA 2013.jpg|alt= Wahidullah Waissi is delivering his statement on behalf of Afghan Government at the side of United Nations General Assembly in 2013 at a special event on efforts made towards achieving MDGs.|thumb|Wahidullah Waissi is delivering his statement on behalf of Afghan Government at the side of [[United Nations General Assembly]] in 2013 at a special event on efforts made towards achieving [[Millennium Development Goals|MDGs]].]]\nWorking for the Afghanistan's Aid Coordination Authority (AACA) in 2003, Waissi's main work focuses were on multilateral cooperation. He was appointed as Aid Coordination Officer at the Ministry of Finance when the AACA moved to this ministry and his areas of focus were on International Financial Institutions (IFIs) i.e. the World Bank, Asian Development Bank (ADB) and European Commission (EC) between years 2003 and 2004. In early 2004, Waissi was manager for a newly established department focussing on IFI's portfolio monitoring.\n\nLater in 2012, as Director-General for Economic Cooperation, Waissi was mainly working on multilateral diplomatic activities throughout Afghanistan's Foreign Policy principles. Waissi represented the Afghan Government at the United Nation's General Assembly debates on G7+, G77, Land-Locked Development Countries (LLDC), Least-Development Countries (LDC), special events on Sustainable Development Goals (SDG) and Millennium Development Goals (MDG) and many other events in years 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015 and 2016.\n\n=== Sustainable Development Goals ===\n[[File:Afghan media interviewing Wahidullah Waissi on regional cooperation.jpg|thumb|[http://www.ucentralasia.org/Media/Item/438 Afghan media interviewing Wahidullah Waissi after a symposium on \u201cTrade and Cooperation between Central Asia and Afghanistan\u201d organized by the University of Central Asia and Afghanistan Ministry of Foreign Affairs, 2012]]]\nWaissi has initiated the Sustainable Development Goals & Green Economy Desk at the [http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547 department of economic cooperation] of [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] of [[Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] to promote and increase focus on Afghanistan\u2019s green diplomacy at the regional and international level. This has enabled more cooperation between Afghanistan and its partners when Afghanistan's [[Sustainable Development Goals]] (SDGs) are developed.\n\nWaissi participate at the [[United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development|Rio+20 of United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development]] took place in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]] on 20\u201322 June 2012 as part of the Afghan delegation. The Government of Afghanistan has presented its position paper in support of the SDGs.\n\nIn 2013 and 2014, Waissi and his team at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs have inaugurated a first series of consultations on SDGs and adopting the goals to national level policies and plans. The first review of [[Sustainable Development Goals|SDGs]] for Afghanistan has been developed in 2014 and submitted to the [[United Nations]]. The [[Government of Afghanistan]] endorsed the [[Sustainable Development Goals|SDGs]] and presented its adoption policy of the [[Post-2015 Development Agenda|post-2015 development agenda]] at the [https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/post2015/summit United Nations Sustainable Development Summit 2015] held on 25\u201327 September 2015, in [[New York City]].\n\n== Development career ==\nWaissi's professional work focuses on economic development since 1998. He has worked for many national and international non-governmental organizations, UN agencies, and government in Kabul and provinces. Waissi has started his first government engagement in the field of aid management and budget policy. He has been responsible for most of the development partnership activities for Afghanistan since 2003 and has been directly involved in coordination and organizing of 22 national and international conferences for Afghanistan from 2004 to 2015 in Kabul, Berlin, Paris, Tokyo, Rome, London, Bonn, Brussels and in number of neighboring countries.\n\n=== Afghanistan National Development Strategy ===\n\nIn June 2006, Waissi has been appointed as the Coordinator and Formulation Manager for the [https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2006/cr06194.pdf Interim-Afghanistan National Development Strategy (I-ANDS)] at the Office of the Senior Economic Advisor to the President of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, Professor [[M. Ishaq Nadiri|Ishaq Nadiri]] (Former President [[Hamid Karzai]]). The [https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2006/cr06194.pdf I-ANDS] was served as the interim [[Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper]] (I-PRSP) based on the [[Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper|World Bank development modules]].\n\nThe ANDS was a five-year national development plan outlined the government strategy for achieving its long term development vision. It was based on the [http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547/afghanistan-millennium-development-goals-mdgs Afghanistan Millennium Development Goals] and the benchmarks of the [http://www.nato.int/isaf/docu/epub/pdf/afghanistan_compact.pdf Afghanistan Compact]. Both the [[Millennium Development Goals|MDGs]] and ANDS/PRSP meant to help the government and policy makers at the national and ministry levels to plan activities for reaching the priority development results required to address people\u2019s priority needs. The [https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2006/cr06194.pdf I-ANDS/I-PRSP] was presented at the [[International Conference on Afghanistan, London (2010)|International Donor Conference in London in 2006]].\n\nThe [http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547/afghanistan-national-development-strategy/afghanistan-national-development-strategy-ands Afghanistan National Development Strategy (ANDS)], 2008-2013 served as [http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547/afghanistan-national-development-strategy/afghanistan-national-development-strategy-ands Afghanistan\u2019s Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper (PRSP)] and used the pillars, principles and benchmarks of the [[International Conference on Afghanistan, London (2006)|Afghanistan Compact]] (2006) as a foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547/afghanistan-national-development-strategy/afghanistan-national-development-strategy-ands|title=The Afghanistan National Development Strategy (ANDS)|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The ANDS document was instrumental for absorbing more foreign aid for the development process of Afghanistan and presented at the Paris Conference on Afghanistan in July 2008.\n\nIn July 2007, the Boards of Executive Directors of the [[International Development Association|International Development Association (IDA)]] and the [[International Monetary Fund|International Monetary Fund (IMF)]] agreed that the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan had met the requirements for reaching the decision point under the enhanced [[Heavily indebted poor countries|Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) Initiative]]. The amount of debt relief determined at the decision point was US$571.4 million in March 20, 2006 net present value (NPV) terms, calculated to reduce the NPV of eligible external debt to 150 percent of exports at March 20, 2006. This relief implied a common reduction factor of 51.0 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2015/09/14/01/49/pr1015|title=Debt Relief for Afghanistan|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Paris Conference and approval of the ANDS by the [[World Bank|boards of the World Bank]] and IMF in 2008, Waissi has been appointed as Director for Coordination of ANDS Implementation and Budget Policy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.af/Content/files/ANDS%20Annual%20Report%201387%20-%20English.pdf|title=First ANDS Annual Report (2008/09): Making a Difference: Transition from Planning to Practice}}</ref> overseeing implementation of the ANDS and its activities underlined in its National Action Plan.\n\n=== Millennium Development Goals (MDG) ===\n\n=== Results Based Budgeting ===\nIn 2008 Waissi has been appointed as the Director for ANDS Coordination of Implementation and Budget Policy at the Ministry of Finance. In late 2008 Waissi and his team at the [[Ministry of Finance (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Finance]] have introduced [[Results-based management|Results Based Management (RBM)]] mechanism and [[Performance-based budgeting|performance budgeting]] into [http://www.budgetmof.gov.af/index.php/en/2012-12-06-22-51-13/national-budget National Budget of Afghanistan] for the first time between 2009 and 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wpqr4.adb.org/lotusquickr/cop-mfdr/pagelibrary482571ae00516aa5.nsf/0/6D44BE2708C3C461482574F60029CFAA/$file/Afghanistan%20Results%20Based%20Management%20-%20Wahid%20Waissi%20-%2030Oct08.doc.pdf|title=Afghanistan\u2019s Experience On Results Based Management: Moving Toward Program Budgeting, Written by Wahidullah Waissi, ANDS/PRSP Development Manager, Ministry of Finance|last=Waissi|first=Wahidullah|date=2008}}</ref> The RBM later introduced as the [[Performance-based budgeting|Performance Budgeting]] at the Ministry of Finance and still continues as a budget policy tool for measuring results at the [[Ministry of Finance (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Finance]] of Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Waissi|first=Wahidullah|year=2008|title=Afghanistan's Experience on Results Based Management: Moving toward program budgeting|url=https://wpqr4.adb.org/LotusQuickr/cop-mfdr/PageLibrary482571AE00516AA5.nsf/0/6D44BE2708C3C461482574F60029CFAA/$file/Afghanistan%20Results%20Based%20Management%20-%20Wahid%20Waissi%20-%2030Oct08.doc.pdf|journal=Asia Pacific CoP-MfDR|volume=|pages=4|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Environmentalism ==\n\n=== The Green Club ===\n\nWahid Waissi has had a long-standing concern with environmentalism as a national and global issue. Waissi has co-founded the [http://greeningafghanistan.com Green Club] in 2009 together with [https://www.facebook.com/jawid.omar Jawid Omar] and a team of young Afghans on voluntary basis. Waissi is the Chairman and co-founder of [http://greeningafghanistan.com Green Club, Afghanistan] on voluntary basis. The [http://greeningafghanistan.com Green Club] soon found its way to the heart and minds of youth activists focused its objectives to encourage environment protection and green knowledge by volunteerism, advocacy and awareness rising. In June 2012, Waissi participated at the [[United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development|Rio+20]] [[United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development|United Nation Conference on Sustainable Development]] as member of the Government of Islamic Republic of Afghanistan delegation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.af/Content/files/Afghanistan's%20Position%20Paper%20.pdf|title=Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, COUNTRY POSITION PAPER FOR RIO+20|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n[[File:Green Club Planting .png|thumb|The Green Club volunteers planted over thousands trees after the first \"[https://www.plant-for-the-planet.org/billiontreecampaign/show/15207/1 A tree for me is a tree for Afghanistan]\" planting campaign at the outskirts of Kabul city. 19 April 2010]]\n[http://greeningafghanistan.com The Green Club] became the first registered civil society organizations on environment protection and [[sustainable development]]. The Green Club engaged active citizens who are concerned about environmental degradation and volunteer to make the communities green.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://greeningafghanistan.com|title=The Green Club|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Green Club made its path towards [http://www.earthday.org Earth Day Network] and owned the 2013 Earth Day International Recognition Award for its green activities. Waissi also registered a petition on [[Afghan Independent Human Rights Commission|Afghanistan\u2019s Independent Human Rights Commission]] and submitted the Right for Environment as future Human Rights Commission consideration for their annual analysis and reports.\n\nThe Green Club volunteers organized several campaigns namely: [https://www.plant-for-the-planet.org/billiontreecampaign/show/15207/1 A Tree for Me is a Tree for Afghanistan],<ref name=\":3\" /> [http://unama.unmissions.org/international-day-afghan-children-paint-and-athletes-run-message-protect-earth Earth Day Festivals],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unama.unmissions.org/international-day-afghan-children-paint-and-athletes-run-message-protect-earth|title=ON INTERNATIONAL DAY, AFGHAN CHILDREN PAINT AND ATHLETES RUN WITH MESSAGE TO PROTECT EARTH|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Green Club Environment Week, Green Caravans Awareness Campaigns for schools, Run for Green Cycling Contest, Green Policy, media awareness campaigns, drawing competition at selected schools, and photography competition and exhibitions in support of the [[Earth Day]] and environment protection. More than 100 youth were engaged directly in all these campaigns all at the same time.\n\n==== A Tree for Me is a Tree for Afghanistan ====\nWaissi and the Green Club volunteers have initiated the first national tree planting campaigns using the Facebook application under the title of [https://www.plant-for-the-planet.org/billiontreecampaign/show/15207/1 A Tree for Me is a Tree for Afghanistan].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.plant-for-the-planet.org/billiontreecampaign/show/15207/1|title=A Tree for Me is a Tree for Afghanistan National Sapling Campaign|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The Green Club volunteers planted more than ten thousand trees in Kabul, [[Mazar-i-Sharif|Mazar-e-Sharif]] and [[Herat]] for five consecutive years. [[File:Environment Week.png|thumb|The Green Club volunteers organized the first Environment Week in 2011 with a social activity for a day for seven days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/greenclub-af/with/5827444825/|title=The Green Club Environment Week}}</ref>]]\n\n==== National Environment Week ====\n\nIn 2015, Waissi and [https://web.facebook.com/jawid.omar Omar] have submitted a proposal to the [[Ashraf Ghani|President of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, Mohammad Ashraf Ghani]], to localize the [[World Environment Day]] to National Environment Week based on its successful model practiced by the [https://www.flickr.com/photos/greenclub-af/albums Green Club between years of 2010 to 2014]. The [[Islamic Republic of Afghanistan|Cabinet of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] has approved this idea and included it into national calendar for annual celebration. Since 2015, the national environment week are being celebrated officially.\n\n==== Green Policy ====\nThe Green Club has partnered with the [http://www.cw4wafghan.ca CW4WAfghan] to make its Green Policy a public document in the hopes that other organizations, agencies and companies operating in Afghanistan will also adopt similar policies.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cw4wafghan.ca/about-us/governance/green-policy|title=Initiating the Green Policy|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Afghanistan, and its capital city in particular, are facing an environmental crisis that puts millions of lives at risk, and significantly lowers the quality of life of Afghans. Despite the gravity of this crisis\u2014which is estimated to claim far more lives than the current conflict\u2014little is being done.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Memberships ==\n[[File:Market Place Award.png|thumb|The [[Afghan National Solidarity Programme|National Solidarity Program]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfdr.org/Marketplace/Posters-pdf/Afghanistan_MfDR_Marketplace_Poster_Final_07.pdf|title=National Solidarity Program (NSP)}}</ref> presented by the Afghan delegation at the [http://www.mfdr.org/RT3/ Third International Roundtable on Managing for Development Results] and won the favorite Marketplace poster by the participants' votes, 9 February 2007, Hanoi, Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfdr.org/Marketplace/index.html|title=Third International Roundtable on MfDR, Hanoi, February 2007}}</ref>\n]]\nWaissi is member of Afghanistan Policy Group (APG)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=|title=Envisioning Afghanistan Post 2014, Perspectives and Strategies for Constructive Con ict Resolution from the Neighbourhood|url=http://www.fes-asia.org/media/Peace%20and%20Security/Policy_group_members_page/May_21_-_FES-Envisioning-Afghanistan-Brochuere-13.05.2014.pdf|journal=Afghanistan Policy Group|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> focusing on regional peace and stability envisioning post 2014 with other policy groups of 10 member countries. APG is part of the network of policy groups in Afghanistan, Central Asia, India and Pakistan for a regional project entitled \"Envisioning a Secure and Independent Afghanistan Post 2014. Perspectives and Strategies for Constructive Conflict Resolution from the Neighborhood\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fesdc.org/news-list/e/peace-and-stability-in-afghanistan-post-2014-what-role-for-regional-actors/|title=Peace and Stability in Afghanistan Post-2014: What Role for Regional Actors?|access-date=2016-11-08}}</ref>\n\nWaissi is member of [http://www.managingfordevelopmentresults.org/CoP/index.html Asia-Pacific Community of Practice (APCoP)] on [https://wpqr4.adb.org/LotusQuickr/cop-mfdr/PageLibrary48257336001AF1FE.nsf/51CD559CD941B15C48257377001E02CD/3DF6D6C3CEF42C1B48257386000C2C01/?OpenDocument Managing for Development Results]. Through APCoP, he has participated as Afghan Government representative at the Third High Level Forum on Managing for Development Results in Hanoi, Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfdr.org/rt3/participants/RT3ParticipantsList-CD.pdf|title=Wahidullah Waissi has participated as Afghan delegation at the 3rd HLF Meeting on MfDR in Hanoi.|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> He was also supporting for preparation of [http://www.oecd.org/dac/effectiveness/fourthhighlevelforumonaideffectiveness.htm Fourth High Level Forum on New Deal Aid Effectiveness], which was held in Busan in 2011.\n\nWaissi was a fellow member and program coordinator (2012) of [http://asiasociety.org/asia21-young-leaders/2011-ayli-forum Afghanistan 21 Young Leaders Initiative] a non-partisan and non-political group of young Afghans who shared common values and beliefs to address social, economic and political issues in Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ayli.blog.af/?page_id=2|title=Afghanistan 21 Young Leaders Initiative - Who we are?}}</ref> The AYLI fellows<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=|title=AYLI|url=http://asiasociety.org/files/2012-AYLI-Participants-Profiles.pdf|journal=AYLI Class Profiles|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> have managed to reflect their views and considerations about current and international affairs of Afghanistan. The AYLI fellows developed many position papers ahead of the key strategic events linked to Afghanistan i.e. [http://ayli.blog.af/?p=19 Tokyo Conference on Afghanistan], 2012; [http://ayli.blog.af/?p=15 Position Paper on NATO Summit in Chicago], 2012; and [http://ayli.blog.af/?p=9 International Afghanistan Conference in Bonn], 2012. AYLI is being supported by [[Asia Society]] 21 Young Leaders program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://asiasociety.org/asia21-young-leaders|title=Asia 21 Young Leaders Initiative|website=Asia Society|language=en|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nWaissi is married and has two daughters and a son.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[RECCA]]\n[[CoP MfDR]]\n\n[[Category:Afghan politicians]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Williams College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox ambassador \n| honorific-prefix = [[His Excellency]] \n|image = Wahidullah Waissi (2012).jpg\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   = Waissi at the Bled Strategic Forum, Slovenia, September 2012\n|name = Wahidullah Waissi<br>{{small|{{lang|ps|\u0648\u062d\u06cc\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0648\u06cc\u0633\u06cc}}}}\n|country = Australia | term_start = February 22, 2017 \n|president    = [[Ashraf Ghani]]\n|predecessor =  Dr. Nasir Ahmad Andisha\n|office1 =     [http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547 Director-General for Economic Cooperation]\n|term_start1  = August 5, 2012\n|term_end1    = February 21, 2017\n|predecessor2 = Dr. Daud Yar\n|successor2   = Hassan Soroosh {{small|(Acting)}}\n|birth_name    = Wahidullah Waissi\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1975|04|18}}\n|birth_place = [[Kabul]], [[Afghanistan]] [[Image:Flag of Afghanistan.svg|25px]] \n|nationality   = [[Afghan]]\n|alma_mater = [[Williams College]], [[United States]]<br>[[Kabul University]]\n|website = [http://www.afghanembassy.net Embassy of I. R. of Afghanistan in Canberra, Australia]\n|footnotes = |office = [http://www.afghanembassy.net/ambassador/ambassadors-message Afghanistan's Ambassador to Australia]}}\n\n'''Wahidullah Waissi''' (born April 18, 1975) is an Afghan diplomat. He is now serving as an Ambassador of [[Afghanistan|Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] to the [[Australia|Commonwealth of Australia]], the [[New Zealand]] and [[Fiji|Republic of Fiji]]. He worked as [http://www.mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547 Director-General for Economic Cooperation]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547|title=Economic Cooperations - Ministry of Foreign Affairs - Islamic Republic of Afghanistan|website=www.mfa.gov.af|access-date=2016-11-08}}</ref> at the [http://www.mfa.gov.af/en Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Islamic Republic of Afghanistan] from 2012 to 2016 overseeing regional economic cooperation and multilateral development partnerships, chaired economic diplomacy committee, coordinated [http://www.recca.af Regional Economic Cooperation Conference for Afghanistan] process and projects and served as a Focal Point for economic [[Confidence-building measures|Confidence Building Measures (CBMs)]] of the [http://www.hoa.gov.af Heart of Asia] Istanbul Process.\n\nWaissi is Co-founder and Chair of the [http://greeningafghanistan.com Green Club], a voluntarily association on environment and green activities. He used to teach economic development at the University of Afghanistan and writes on development, region, [[geoeconomics]] and socio-development issues.\n\n== Early life and education ==\n[[File:CACI CAMCA.jpg|left|thumb|[https://www.flickr.com/photos/rumsfeldfoundation/33472356742/in/photostream/ Waissi at the 2016 CAMCA Regional Forum - Tbilisi, Georgia.]]]\nWahidullah Waissi was born on April 18, 1975 in [[Kabul]]. He has studied in the [[United States]] and holds MA in [[Development economics|Development Economics]] from [https://cde.williams.edu Center for Development Economics] of [[Williams College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cde.williams.edu/people/alumni/|title=Selected Alumni Profiles: Wahidullah Waissi, CDE, Williams College}}</ref> Waissi was one of the [https://cde.williams.edu/people/alumni/ first Afghan students] studied at the CDE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://williamsrecord.com/2004/10/19/rashid-and-waissi-are-first-afghan-students-at-cde/|title=Rashid and Waissi are first Afghan students at CDE|date=2004-10-19|website=The Williams Record|access-date=2016-11-08}}</ref> Among them were fellows from countries near [[Afghanistan]]\u2014the [[Kyrgyzstan|Kyrgyz Republic]], [[Uzbekistan]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://magazine.williams.edu/files/archive/2017-spring.pdf|title=Williams Magazine|date=Spring 2017|publisher=The Williams College}}</ref>\n\nHe is a [[visiting scholar]] of the [[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute]] of the [[Paul H. Nitze School of Advanced International Studies|SAIS/Johns Hopkins University in Washington DC]], a fellowship program for raising regional leaders in government, commerce, and academia from [[Central Asia]], [[Mongolia]], the [[Caucasus]] and [[Afghanistan]] ([https://www.rumsfeldfoundation.org/greater_central_asia/camca CAMCA]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rumsfeldfoundation.org/doclib/201607111_forumreportonlineversion.pdf|title=CAMCA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.silkroadstudies.org/fellowship/item/13057-fall-2014-rumsfeld-fellowship.html|title=CACI, Johns Hopkins University, Washington DC|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nWaissi had also studied [[Results-based management|Results Based Management]] at the [[Shanghai]] based [http://www.afdc.org.cn/default.aspx?l=english&Type=ShipDet Asia-Pacific Finance and Development Institute (AFDI)] in 2007 under a fellowship granted from [http://www.afdc.org.cn/SAG_Index.aspx?Type=ShipDet&l=english Shanghai International Program for Development Evaluation Training (SHIPDET)] program.\n\n== Diplomatic career ==\n[[File:Wahidullah Waissi submits his letter of credential to Peter Cosgrove.png|thumb|[https://www.gg.gov.au/diplomatic-representatives/islamic-republic-afghanistan Waissi submits his letter of credential to Sir Peter Cosgrove, Governor-General of Commonwealth of Australia as the fifth Ambassador of Islamic Republic of Afghanistan to Australia on 1 March 2017, Canberra.]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gg.gov.au/diplomatic-representatives/islamic-republic-afghanistan|title=The Governor-General received from His Excellency Mr Wahidullah Waissi, Letters of Credence accrediting him as the Ambassador of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan. 1 March 2017, Canberra.}}</ref>|left]]\nWaissi joins [http://mfa.gov.af Ministry of Foreign Affairs] in 2012 as Senior Advisor on regional cooperation. Later, he was appointed as [http://www.mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547 Director-General for Economic Cooperation]<ref name=\":2\" /> at the [http://www.mfa.gov.af/en Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Islamic Republic of Afghanistan] (2012 to 2016). In this position he was overseeing regional economic cooperation and multilateral development partnerships, chairing Economic Diplomacy Committee, coordinates [http://www.recca.af Regional Economic Cooperation Conference for Afghanistan] and serving as a national Focal Point for economic Confidence Building Measures of [http://www.hoa.gov.af Heart of Asia] Istanbul Process. \n\nWaissi was coordinating infrastructure project negotiation phases for [[Turkmenistan\u2013Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan\u2013India Pipeline|TAPI]], [http://www.casa-1000.org CASA-1000], TAT Railway, regional transit and transport agreements and projects and [http://recca.af/?page_id=2108 Special Economic Zones/Dry Ports].\n\n=== Ambassador accredited to Australia, New Zealand and Fiji ===\n[[File:Submission of Credentials .jpg|thumb|Waissi at the ceremony of credential's submission to the Governor-General of Australia, 1 March 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gg.gov.au/diplomatic-representatives/islamic-republic-afghanistan|title=Ceremony of Credentials Submission}}</ref>]]\n\nWaissi was appointed as the [[Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary]] of the [[Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] to the [[Commonwealth of Australia]] in February 2017 and as a non-resident Ambassador to [[New Zealand]] and [[Fiji]] on 12 August 2017 and 24 April 2018 respectively. As an ambassador, this is his first mission abroad. Waissi has submitted his letter of credentials to [[Peter Cosgrove|Sir Peter Cosgrove]], [[Governor-General of Australia|Governor-General of Commonwealth of Australia]] on 1 March 2017 and to [[Patsy Reddy|Dame Patsy Reddy]], [[Governor-General of New Zealand]] on 6 September 2017 as the fifth Ambassador of Afghanistan to both [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gg.gov.au/diplomatic-representatives/islamic-republic-afghanistan|title=The Governor-General received from His Excellency Mr Wahidullah Waissi, Letters of Credence accrediting him as the Ambassador of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan.|archive-date=1 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gg.govt.nz/governor-general/blog/2017/09/credentials-ceremony-6-september-2017|title=Credentials Ceremony 6 September 2017|website=gg.govt.nz }}</ref>\n[[File:Wahidullah Waissi and Dame Patsy Reddy after Waissi's credentials ceremony to New Zealand.jpg|thumb|HE the Rt Hon Dame Patsy Reddy with HE Mr Wahidullah Waissi, the Ambassador of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gg.govt.nz/image-galleries/7241/media?page=11|title=Credentials Ceremony 6 September 2017 {{!}} The Governor-General of New Zealand|website=gg.govt.nz|language=en|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Wahidullah Waissi's credential ceremony to Fiji.jpg|thumb|President [[Jioji Konrote|Major-General (Ret\u2019d) Jioji Konrote]] (left), with the non-resident Ambassador of the [[Afghanistan|Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] to the [[Fiji|Republic of Fiji]], HE Wahidullah Waissi (right), at Borron House on April 24, 2018. Photo: DEPTFO News]]\n[[File:Ambassador Waissi with Prime Minister Turnbull.jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull greets the Ambassador to Australia, Wahidullah Waissi, before a statement from the leaders remembering the victims of the bombing in Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/live/2017/jun/01/pauline-hanson-received-donations-to-personal-bank-account-politics-live|title=Australian Politics|last=Photograph: Mike Bowers for the Guardian|date=1 June 2017|website=www.theguardian.com/australia-news/live/2017/jun/01/pauline-hanson-received-donations-to-personal-bank-account-politics-live}}</ref>]]\nAs the first Afghan President visiting Australia, [[Ashraf Ghani|Dr. Mohammad Ashraf Ghani]] arrived to [[Canberra]] on 2 April 2017 for an almost 3 days visit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/foreign-affairs/first-visit-to-australia-by-afghan-president/news-story/28d7ddd65098e31412aec7b6827f3de7|title=First visit to Australia by Afghan president|date=3 April 2017}}</ref> Marking the visit, Prime Minister [[Malcolm Turnbull]] said Afghanistan and Australia had forged a \u201csolid connection\u201d for more than a century. From [[Afghan (Australia)|Afghan cameleers]] in the 1860s, through to the Australian military effort to free Afghanistan of [[terrorism]], the two nations have long maintained a healthy partnership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/2017-04-02/president-afghanistans-visit-australia|title=President of Afghanistan Visit's to Australia}}</ref> Discussions were mainly focused on security and development co-operation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/2017-04-04/outcomes-president-ghanis-visit-australia|title=Outcome of President Ghani's Visit to Australia|website=pm.gov.au}}</ref>\n\n=== Regional Economic Cooperation Conference on Afghanistan (RECCA) ===\n[[File:RECCA VI Doc.png|thumb|The Silk Road through Afghanistan strategy presented at the [http://recca.af/?page_id=490 Sixth Regional Economic Cooperation Conference] in Kabul, 2015.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Towards Regional Economic Growth & Stability: The Silk Road through Afghanistan|last=|first=|publisher=Directorate-General for Economic Cooperation, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Afghanistan|year=2015|isbn=|location=Kabul|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://recca.af/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/main-document1.pdf|title=The Silk Road through Afghanistan}}</ref>]]\nOne of the efforts that have been striving to have regional economic cooperation in South and Central Asia so as to assist Afghanistan is [http://www.recca.af Regional Economic Cooperation Conference on Afghanistan (RECCA)]. RECCA is a forum that has been managed to promote stabilization in Afghanistan and [[South Asia|South]] and [[Central Asia]]n regional economic integration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://recca.af/?page_id=578|title=Regional Economic Cooperation Conference on Afghanistan (RECCA)}}</ref>\n\nWaissi have been engaged on developing the first Regional Cooperation Strategy for the ANDS since 2005. This strategy made the platform for broader regional cooperation discussion among immediate neighbors and far neighboring countries of Afghanistan. The first regional economic cooperation conference under the title of [http://recca.af/?page_id=578 RECCA has been inaugurated in Kabul in 2005]. More annual RECCA meetings were hosted in [http://recca.af/?page_id=572 New Delhi in 2006], [http://recca.af/?page_id=569 Islamabad in 2007], [http://recca.af/?page_id=560 Istanbul in 2009], [http://recca.af/?page_id=549 Dushanbe in 2012] and back in [http://recca.af/?page_id=490 Kabul in 2015]. Waissi played a major role in organization and coordination of the last two RECCA events in Dushanbe and Kabul.\n\nThe [http://recca.af/?page_id=490 RECCA process in 2015] covers a broader range of economic activities in forms of energy cooperation, connectivity, and business to business opportunities in the region. Waissi and his team at the [http://www.mfa.af Ministry of Foreign Affairs] have launched a new website ([http://www.recca.af www.recca.af])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.recca.af|title=RECCA Website}}</ref> to include necessary information about status of projects under the RECCA process for a wider outreach. He also initiated identifying [http://recca.af/?page_id=1722 RECCA Focal Points] from 16 countries for better coordination of regional project's implementation. The first meeting of the [http://recca.af/?page_id=1722 RECCA Focal Points] took place on 26 August 2017 in Kabul.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://recca.af/?p=2440|title=The First RECCA National Focal Points Meeting was held on August 26, 2017 at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Afghanistan with the participation of the National Focal Points from RECCA regional countries.|website=recca.af }}</ref> The Seventh RECCA meeting will be hosted by the [[Turkmenistan]] Government in [[Ashgabat]] in November 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://recca.af/?p=2431|title=Seventh Meeting of the Regional Economic Cooperation Conference on Afghanistan (RECCA VII) scheduled to take place from 14-15 November 2017 in Ashgabat, Turkmenistan.|website=recca.af }}</ref>\n\n=== Chabahar Agreement ===\n[[File:Chabahar Agreement.png|thumb|[http://afghanembassy.in/en/media-menu/news/687-afghanistan-india-and-iran-initial-momentous-agreement-on-chabahar Afghanistan, India and Iran completed text of the Chabahar Agreement, New Delhi, 11 May 2016]|left]]\nWaissi was a lead-negotiator for the [http://recca.af/?page_id=2083 International Transport and Transit Corridor] (also known as the 'Chabahar Agreement') on behalf of the Afghan Government since 2012, when the primary discussion over this agreement started in 2012 in Tehran between [[Afghanistan]], [[Iran]] and [[India]] and to its signing ceremony. On 23 May 2016, the Agreement was signed in Tehran, Iran, by the Afghan [[Ministry of Transport and Civil Aviation (Afghanistan)|Minister of Transport and Civil Aviation]], the Indian [[Ministry of Shipping (India)|Minister of Shipping, Road Transport, and Highways]] and the Iranian [[Ministry of Roads and Urban Development (Iran)|Ministry of Road and Urban Development]], while the three heads of states, President Mohammad Ashraf Ghani, President [[Hassan Rouhani]] and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] were present. The agreement later approved by the Cabinet of the Afghan Government on 3 August 2016 and ratified by the Afghan National Assembly (Parliament).\n\nThe Agreement aims to: 1) Facilitate access to international markets by using land, sea, and/or air transportation through [[Chabahar Port]]; and 2) Simplify, harmonize, and standardize procedures governing the international transport and transit of goods and passengers, in accordance with the international agreements and conventions in which the three signatory governments are members.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://recca.af/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/RECCA-Annual-Review-2016-light-version.pdf|title=From Negotiation to Investment, Construction, & Trade: A New Decade of Progress - RECCA Annual Review 2016|date=15 September 2016|website=www.recca.af}}</ref>\n\nThe Chabahar Agreement is the first multilateral transit and transport agreement of its kind that [[Afghanistan]] signs with other countries. It basically connects [[South Asia]] with [[Central Asia]], and [[Gulf Region|Gulf region]] with [[Central Asia]] and [[Caucasus]] markets. [[Chabahar Port|The ports in Chabahar]] will considerably cut transportation costs and time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://afghanembassy.in/en/news/687-afghanistan-india-and-iran-initial-momentous-agreement-on-chabahar|title=Finalization of the text of the Chabahar Agreement, New Delhi.|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== The Lapis Lazuli Route ===\n{{main|Lapis Lazuli corridor}}\n[[File:Lapis Lazuli Route Agreement text finalized.jpg|thumb|[http://afghanembassyturkmenistan.com/text-of-the-lapis-lazuli-route-agreement-finalized/ Text of the Lapis Lazuli Route Agreement was finalized in Baku between Afghanistan, Georgia, Azerbaijan, Turkey and Turkmenistan in its fourth technical meeting on 16 November 2016]]]\nAfghanistan as a landlocked country needs more diversified transit policy. Alternative routes and corridors are always helpful for the domestic economy as well as regional connectivity. This was the biggest motivation for Waissi to initiate an alternative transit route, later called the Lapis Lazuli Transit and Transport Route. His ideas was accepted by [[Jawed Ludin]], former Deputy Foreign Minister of [[Afghanistan]] and later by Zarar Ahmad Osmani, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Afghanistan)|former Minister of Foreign Affairs of Afghanistan]]. Waissi was being appointed immediately by Minister Osmani to follow with the concerned counties and coordinate to become a party to this initiative. Turkmenistan, [[Azerbaijan]] and Georgia immediately joined and [[Turkey]] was the last country to become as a party to this initiative. In early 2014 Waissi and a team of experts from the Afghan Government started the negotiation from [[Ashgabat]] in Turkmenistan. Waissi was leading the negotiation for the agreement on behalf of the Afghan Government.\n\nThe [[Lapis Lazuli corridor]] was opened for business in December 2018.\n\n=== Multilateralism & Multilateral Diplomacy ===\n[[File:Wahidullah Waissi UNGA 2013.jpg|alt= Wahidullah Waissi is delivering his statement on behalf of Afghan Government at the side of United Nations General Assembly in 2013 at a special event on efforts made towards achieving MDGs.|thumb|Wahidullah Waissi is delivering his statement on behalf of Afghan Government at the side of [[United Nations General Assembly]] in 2013 at a special event on efforts made towards achieving [[Millennium Development Goals|MDGs]].]]\nWorking for the Afghanistan's Aid Coordination Authority (AACA) in 2003, Waissi's main work focuses were on multilateral cooperation. He was appointed as Aid Coordination Officer at the Ministry of Finance when the AACA moved to this ministry and his areas of focus were on International Financial Institutions (IFIs) i.e. the World Bank, Asian Development Bank (ADB) and European Commission (EC) between years 2003 and 2004. In early 2004, Waissi was manager for a newly established department focussing on IFI's portfolio monitoring.\n\nLater in 2012, as Director-General for Economic Cooperation, Waissi was mainly working on multilateral diplomatic activities throughout Afghanistan's Foreign Policy principles. Waissi represented the Afghan Government at the United Nation's General Assembly debates on G7+, G77, Land-Locked Development Countries (LLDC), Least-Development Countries (LDC), special events on Sustainable Development Goals (SDG) and Millennium Development Goals (MDG) and many other events in years 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015 and 2016.\n\n=== Sustainable Development Goals ===\n[[File:Afghan media interviewing Wahidullah Waissi on regional cooperation.jpg|thumb|[http://www.ucentralasia.org/Media/Item/438 Afghan media interviewing Wahidullah Waissi after a symposium on \u201cTrade and Cooperation between Central Asia and Afghanistan\u201d organized by the University of Central Asia and Afghanistan Ministry of Foreign Affairs, 2012]]]\nWaissi has initiated the Sustainable Development Goals & Green Economy Desk at the [http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547 department of economic cooperation] of [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] of [[Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] to promote and increase focus on Afghanistan\u2019s green diplomacy at the regional and international level. This has enabled more cooperation between Afghanistan and its partners when Afghanistan's [[Sustainable Development Goals]] (SDGs) are developed.\n\nWaissi participate at the [[United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development|Rio+20 of United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development]] took place in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]] on 20\u201322 June 2012 as part of the Afghan delegation. The Government of Afghanistan has presented its position paper in support of the SDGs.\n\nIn 2013 and 2014, Waissi and his team at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs have inaugurated a first series of consultations on SDGs and adopting the goals to national level policies and plans. The first review of [[Sustainable Development Goals|SDGs]] for Afghanistan has been developed in 2014 and submitted to the [[United Nations]]. The [[Government of Afghanistan]] endorsed the [[Sustainable Development Goals|SDGs]] and presented its adoption policy of the [[Post-2015 Development Agenda|post-2015 development agenda]] at the [https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/post2015/summit United Nations Sustainable Development Summit 2015] held on 25\u201327 September 2015, in [[New York City]].\n\n== Development career ==\nWaissi's professional work focuses on economic development since 1998. He has worked for many national and international non-governmental organizations, UN agencies, and government in Kabul and provinces. Waissi has started his first government engagement in the field of aid management and budget policy. He has been responsible for most of the development partnership activities for Afghanistan since 2003 and has been directly involved in coordination and organizing of 22 national and international conferences for Afghanistan from 2004 to 2015 in Kabul, Berlin, Paris, Tokyo, Rome, London, Bonn, Brussels and in number of neighboring countries.\n\n=== Afghanistan National Development Strategy ===\n\nIn June 2006, Waissi has been appointed as the Coordinator and Formulation Manager for the [https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2006/cr06194.pdf Interim-Afghanistan National Development Strategy (I-ANDS)] at the Office of the Senior Economic Advisor to the President of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, Professor [[M. Ishaq Nadiri|Ishaq Nadiri]] (Former President [[Hamid Karzai]]). The [https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2006/cr06194.pdf I-ANDS] was served as the interim [[Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper]] (I-PRSP) based on the [[Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper|World Bank development modules]].\n\nThe ANDS was a five-year national development plan outlined the government strategy for achieving its long term development vision. It was based on the [http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547/afghanistan-millennium-development-goals-mdgs Afghanistan Millennium Development Goals] and the benchmarks of the [http://www.nato.int/isaf/docu/epub/pdf/afghanistan_compact.pdf Afghanistan Compact]. Both the [[Millennium Development Goals|MDGs]] and ANDS/PRSP meant to help the government and policy makers at the national and ministry levels to plan activities for reaching the priority development results required to address people\u2019s priority needs. The [https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2006/cr06194.pdf I-ANDS/I-PRSP] was presented at the [[International Conference on Afghanistan, London (2010)|International Donor Conference in London in 2006]].\n\nThe [http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547/afghanistan-national-development-strategy/afghanistan-national-development-strategy-ands Afghanistan National Development Strategy (ANDS)], 2008-2013 served as [http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547/afghanistan-national-development-strategy/afghanistan-national-development-strategy-ands Afghanistan\u2019s Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper (PRSP)] and used the pillars, principles and benchmarks of the [[International Conference on Afghanistan, London (2006)|Afghanistan Compact]] (2006) as a foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.af/en/page/6547/afghanistan-national-development-strategy/afghanistan-national-development-strategy-ands|title=The Afghanistan National Development Strategy (ANDS)|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The ANDS document was instrumental for absorbing more foreign aid for the development process of Afghanistan and presented at the Paris Conference on Afghanistan in July 2008.\n\nIn July 2007, the Boards of Executive Directors of the [[International Development Association|International Development Association (IDA)]] and the [[International Monetary Fund|International Monetary Fund (IMF)]] agreed that the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan had met the requirements for reaching the decision point under the enhanced [[Heavily indebted poor countries|Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) Initiative]]. The amount of debt relief determined at the decision point was US$571.4 million in March 20, 2006 net present value (NPV) terms, calculated to reduce the NPV of eligible external debt to 150 percent of exports at March 20, 2006. This relief implied a common reduction factor of 51.0 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2015/09/14/01/49/pr1015|title=Debt Relief for Afghanistan|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Paris Conference and approval of the ANDS by the [[World Bank|boards of the World Bank]] and IMF in 2008, Waissi has been appointed as Director for Coordination of ANDS Implementation and Budget Policy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.af/Content/files/ANDS%20Annual%20Report%201387%20-%20English.pdf|title=First ANDS Annual Report (2008/09): Making a Difference: Transition from Planning to Practice}}</ref> overseeing implementation of the ANDS and its activities underlined in its National Action Plan.\n\n=== Millennium Development Goals (MDG) ===\n\n=== Results Based Budgeting ===\nIn 2008 Waissi has been appointed as the Director for ANDS Coordination of Implementation and Budget Policy at the Ministry of Finance. In late 2008 Waissi and his team at the [[Ministry of Finance (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Finance]] have introduced [[Results-based management|Results Based Management (RBM)]] mechanism and [[Performance-based budgeting|performance budgeting]] into [http://www.budgetmof.gov.af/index.php/en/2012-12-06-22-51-13/national-budget National Budget of Afghanistan] for the first time between 2009 and 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wpqr4.adb.org/lotusquickr/cop-mfdr/pagelibrary482571ae00516aa5.nsf/0/6D44BE2708C3C461482574F60029CFAA/$file/Afghanistan%20Results%20Based%20Management%20-%20Wahid%20Waissi%20-%2030Oct08.doc.pdf|title=Afghanistan\u2019s Experience On Results Based Management: Moving Toward Program Budgeting, Written by Wahidullah Waissi, ANDS/PRSP Development Manager, Ministry of Finance|last=Waissi|first=Wahidullah|date=2008}}</ref> The RBM later introduced as the [[Performance-based budgeting|Performance Budgeting]] at the Ministry of Finance and still continues as a budget policy tool for measuring results at the [[Ministry of Finance (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Finance]] of Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Waissi|first=Wahidullah|year=2008|title=Afghanistan's Experience on Results Based Management: Moving toward program budgeting|url=https://wpqr4.adb.org/LotusQuickr/cop-mfdr/PageLibrary482571AE00516AA5.nsf/0/6D44BE2708C3C461482574F60029CFAA/$file/Afghanistan%20Results%20Based%20Management%20-%20Wahid%20Waissi%20-%2030Oct08.doc.pdf|journal=Asia Pacific CoP-MfDR|volume=|pages=4|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Environmentalism ==\n\n=== The Green Club ===\n\nWahid Waissi has had a long-standing concern with environmentalism as a national and global issue. Waissi has co-founded the [http://greeningafghanistan.com Green Club] in 2009 together with [https://www.facebook.com/jawid.omar Jawid Omar] and a team of young Afghans on voluntary basis. Waissi is the Chairman and co-founder of [http://greeningafghanistan.com Green Club, Afghanistan] on voluntary basis. The [http://greeningafghanistan.com Green Club] soon found its way to the heart and minds of youth activists focused its objectives to encourage environment protection and green knowledge by volunteerism, advocacy and awareness rising. In June 2012, Waissi participated at the [[United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development|Rio+20]] [[United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development|United Nation Conference on Sustainable Development]] as member of the Government of Islamic Republic of Afghanistan delegation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.af/Content/files/Afghanistan's%20Position%20Paper%20.pdf|title=Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, COUNTRY POSITION PAPER FOR RIO+20|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n[[File:Green Club Planting .png|thumb|The Green Club volunteers planted over thousands trees after the first \"[https://www.plant-for-the-planet.org/billiontreecampaign/show/15207/1 A tree for me is a tree for Afghanistan]\" planting campaign at the outskirts of Kabul city. 19 April 2010]]\n[http://greeningafghanistan.com The Green Club] became the first registered civil society organizations on environment protection and [[sustainable development]]. The Green Club engaged active citizens who are concerned about environmental degradation and volunteer to make the communities green.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://greeningafghanistan.com|title=The Green Club|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Green Club made its path towards [http://www.earthday.org Earth Day Network] and owned the 2013 Earth Day International Recognition Award for its green activities. Waissi also registered a petition on [[Afghan Independent Human Rights Commission|Afghanistan\u2019s Independent Human Rights Commission]] and submitted the Right for Environment as future Human Rights Commission consideration for their annual analysis and reports.\n\nThe Green Club volunteers organized several campaigns namely: [https://www.plant-for-the-planet.org/billiontreecampaign/show/15207/1 A Tree for Me is a Tree for Afghanistan],<ref name=\":3\" /> [http://unama.unmissions.org/international-day-afghan-children-paint-and-athletes-run-message-protect-earth Earth Day Festivals],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unama.unmissions.org/international-day-afghan-children-paint-and-athletes-run-message-protect-earth|title=ON INTERNATIONAL DAY, AFGHAN CHILDREN PAINT AND ATHLETES RUN WITH MESSAGE TO PROTECT EARTH|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Green Club Environment Week, Green Caravans Awareness Campaigns for schools, Run for Green Cycling Contest, Green Policy, media awareness campaigns, drawing competition at selected schools, and photography competition and exhibitions in support of the [[Earth Day]] and environment protection. More than 100 youth were engaged directly in all these campaigns all at the same time.\n\n==== A Tree for Me is a Tree for Afghanistan ====\nWaissi and the Green Club volunteers have initiated the first national tree planting campaigns using the Facebook application under the title of [https://www.plant-for-the-planet.org/billiontreecampaign/show/15207/1 A Tree for Me is a Tree for Afghanistan].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.plant-for-the-planet.org/billiontreecampaign/show/15207/1|title=A Tree for Me is a Tree for Afghanistan National Sapling Campaign|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The Green Club volunteers planted more than ten thousand trees in Kabul, [[Mazar-i-Sharif|Mazar-e-Sharif]] and [[Herat]] for five consecutive years. [[File:Environment Week.png|thumb|The Green Club volunteers organized the first Environment Week in 2011 with a social activity for a day for seven days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/greenclub-af/with/5827444825/|title=The Green Club Environment Week}}</ref>]]\n\n==== National Environment Week ====\n\nIn 2015, Waissi and [https://web.facebook.com/jawid.omar Omar] have submitted a proposal to the [[Ashraf Ghani|President of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, Mohammad Ashraf Ghani]], to localize the [[World Environment Day]] to National Environment Week based on its successful model practiced by the [https://www.flickr.com/photos/greenclub-af/albums Green Club between years of 2010 to 2014]. The [[Islamic Republic of Afghanistan|Cabinet of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] has approved this idea and included it into national calendar for annual celebration. Since 2015, the national environment week are being celebrated officially.\n\n==== Green Policy ====\nThe Green Club has partnered with the [http://www.cw4wafghan.ca CW4WAfghan] to make its Green Policy a public document in the hopes that other organizations, agencies and companies operating in Afghanistan will also adopt similar policies.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cw4wafghan.ca/about-us/governance/green-policy|title=Initiating the Green Policy|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Afghanistan, and its capital city in particular, are facing an environmental crisis that puts millions of lives at risk, and significantly lowers the quality of life of Afghans. Despite the gravity of this crisis\u2014which is estimated to claim far more lives than the current conflict\u2014little is being done.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Memberships ==\n[[File:Market Place Award.png|thumb|The [[Afghan National Solidarity Programme|National Solidarity Program]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfdr.org/Marketplace/Posters-pdf/Afghanistan_MfDR_Marketplace_Poster_Final_07.pdf|title=National Solidarity Program (NSP)}}</ref> presented by the Afghan delegation at the [http://www.mfdr.org/RT3/ Third International Roundtable on Managing for Development Results] and won the favorite Marketplace poster by the participants' votes, 9 February 2007, Hanoi, Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfdr.org/Marketplace/index.html|title=Third International Roundtable on MfDR, Hanoi, February 2007}}</ref>\n]]\nWaissi is member of Afghanistan Policy Group (APG)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=|title=Envisioning Afghanistan Post 2014, Perspectives and Strategies for Constructive Con ict Resolution from the Neighbourhood|url=http://www.fes-asia.org/media/Peace%20and%20Security/Policy_group_members_page/May_21_-_FES-Envisioning-Afghanistan-Brochuere-13.05.2014.pdf|journal=Afghanistan Policy Group|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> focusing on regional peace and stability envisioning post 2014 with other policy groups of 10 member countries. APG is part of the network of policy groups in Afghanistan, Central Asia, India and Pakistan for a regional project entitled \"Envisioning a Secure and Independent Afghanistan Post 2014. Perspectives and Strategies for Constructive Conflict Resolution from the Neighborhood\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fesdc.org/news-list/e/peace-and-stability-in-afghanistan-post-2014-what-role-for-regional-actors/|title=Peace and Stability in Afghanistan Post-2014: What Role for Regional Actors?|access-date=2016-11-08}}</ref>\n\nWaissi is member of [http://www.managingfordevelopmentresults.org/CoP/index.html Asia-Pacific Community of Practice (APCoP)] on [https://wpqr4.adb.org/LotusQuickr/cop-mfdr/PageLibrary48257336001AF1FE.nsf/51CD559CD941B15C48257377001E02CD/3DF6D6C3CEF42C1B48257386000C2C01/?OpenDocument Managing for Development Results]. Through APCoP, he has participated as Afghan Government representative at the Third High Level Forum on Managing for Development Results in Hanoi, Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfdr.org/rt3/participants/RT3ParticipantsList-CD.pdf|title=Wahidullah Waissi has participated as Afghan delegation at the 3rd HLF Meeting on MfDR in Hanoi.|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> He was also supporting for preparation of [http://www.oecd.org/dac/effectiveness/fourthhighlevelforumonaideffectiveness.htm Fourth High Level Forum on New Deal Aid Effectiveness], which was held in Busan in 2011.\n\nWaissi was a fellow member and program coordinator (2012) of [http://asiasociety.org/asia21-young-leaders/2011-ayli-forum Afghanistan 21 Young Leaders Initiative] a non-partisan and non-political group of young Afghans who shared common values and beliefs to address social, economic and political issues in Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ayli.blog.af/?page_id=2|title=Afghanistan 21 Young Leaders Initiative - Who we are?}}</ref> The AYLI fellows<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=|title=AYLI|url=http://asiasociety.org/files/2012-AYLI-Participants-Profiles.pdf|journal=AYLI Class Profiles|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> have managed to reflect their views and considerations about current and international affairs of Afghanistan. The AYLI fellows developed many position papers ahead of the key strategic events linked to Afghanistan i.e. [http://ayli.blog.af/?p=19 Tokyo Conference on Afghanistan], 2012; [http://ayli.blog.af/?p=15 Position Paper on NATO Summit in Chicago], 2012; and [http://ayli.blog.af/?p=9 International Afghanistan Conference in Bonn], 2012. AYLI is being supported by [[Asia Society]] 21 Young Leaders program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://asiasociety.org/asia21-young-leaders|title=Asia 21 Young Leaders Initiative|website=Asia Society|language=en|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nWaissi is married and has two daughters and a son.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[RECCA]]\n[[CoP MfDR]]\n\n[[Category:Afghan politicians]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Williams College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Mazbel", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Submission of Credentials .jpg\u2192File:Credential's submission ceremony of Wahidullah Waissi to Australia.jpgCriterion 2(meaningless or ambiguous name)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wahidullah_Waissi"}
